{"title_page": "Liz Sheridan", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Liz Sheridan\n| image         =\n| imagesize     =\n| birth_name       = Elizabeth Ann Sheridan\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1929|4|10}}\n| birth_place   = [[Rye, New York]], U.S.\n| occupation    = Actress\n| spouse        = {{marriage|William Dale Wales<br/>|1985|2003|end=d.}}\n| yearsactive   = 1976\u20132010\n| children       = 1\n}}\n\n'''Elizabeth Ann Sheridan''' (born April 10, 1929) is an American actress. She was born and raised in [[Rye, New York]], the daughter of concert singer Elizabeth Poole-Jones and classical pianist, Frank Sheridan. While best known for her role as Jerry's mother in ''[[Seinfeld]]'', her decades-long career is extensive and includes work as a dancer, singer, and actress of stage and screen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/60/Liz-Sheridan.html|title=Liz Sheridan Biography (1929-)|author=|date=|work=filmreference.com|accessdate=16 March 2016}} While best known for her role in Seinfeld, her decades-long career is extensive and includes work as a dancer, singer, and actress of stage and screen.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSheridan began her professional life in New York City as a nightclub dancer, moving on to stage work. She was cast in Broadway productions throughout the 1970s, both in musicals and plays.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/liz-sheridan-80515|title=Liz Sheridan|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Broadway Database|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Sheridan co-starred with [[Meryl Streep]] and [[Christopher Lloyd]] in the 1977's musical, ''[[Happy End (musical)|Happy End]]'', before moving to Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/happy-end-4000#OpeningNightCast|title=Happy End|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Broadway Database|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Working in Hollywood, she came to prominence in supporting roles in over a dozen feature films and 60 [[prime time]] network television movies, mini-series, and series including ''[[Kojak]]'', ''[[Archie Bunker's Place]]'', ''[[St. Elsewhere]]'', ''[[Newhart]]'', ''[[Moonlighting (TV series)|Moonlighting]]'', ''[[The A-Team]]'', ''[[Who's the Boss?|Who's the Boss]]'', ''[[Hill Street Blues|Hill St. Blues,]]'' ''[[Cagney & Lacey]]'', ''[[Family Ties]]'', and ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''. Her first major role was playing nosy neighbor Raquel Ochmonek on the NBC TV series ''[[ALF (TV series)|ALF]]'', from 1986 to 1990. Following that she secured her most renowned and long-lived role, as [[Jerry Seinfeld (character)|Jerry Seinfeld]]'s mother, Helen, in the long-running and highly rated series, ''Seinfeld''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/the-20-best-tv-sitcoms-of-all-time-2013-6#1-seinfeld-20|title=The 20 Best TV Sitcoms Of All Time|last=Driscoll|first=Molly|date=June 8, 2013|website=Business Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> She appeared in all nine seasons, from 1990 to 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/filmoseries#tt0098904|title=Filmography by TV series for Liz Sheridan (I)|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=April 29, 2013}}</ref>  \n\nIn the 1950s and 1960s, she lived and worked in the Caribbean, \"singing and playing the piano in almost every bar and saloon in the West Indies.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> In the 1960s, she performed in one of Julius Monk's annual cabaret reviews at Plaza 9, located in the [[Plaza Hotel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.quora.com/Was-there-a-club-in-New-York-City-in-the-1970s-called-Plaza-9-all-that-Jazz|title=Was there a club in New York City in the 1970s called \"Plaza 9 & all that Jazz?\"|last=Rose|first=David S.|date=2018|website=Quora|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nIn 2009, with [[Andy Griffith]] and [[Doris Roberts]], Sheridan co-starred in the feature film, ''[[Play the Game (2009 film)|Play the Game]]'', a romantic comedy about a lonely, [[Widow|widowed]] [[grandfather]] who, after a 60-year hiatus, learns dating tricks from his serial romancer of a grandson. The film stirred up [[controversy]] due to its [[Ageing|octogenarian]] [[Sex in film|sex scene]] between Sheridan and Griffith.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/play-the-game-2009|title=Andy Griffith and Seinfeld's mom: I would really rather not know|last=Ebert|first=Roger|date=August 26, 2009|website=Roger Ebert|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Saslow|first=Rachel|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/08/17/AR2009081702067.html|title=Media Scan: A Movie About Aging, a DVD for Exercise, a Book About Dieting|date=18 August 2009|work=Washington Post|accessdate=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWhile working as a dancer in New York City nightclubs, Sheridan met the then-unknown [[James Dean]]. She wrote a book, ''Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: A Love Story'', chronicling their time together in the early 1950s. In it, she describes them as each other's first romantic love. Dean pursued work on the stage in New York, then film roles in Hollywood. Without sure footing or a serious plan, Sheridan was not interested in following him around on both coasts, thus bringing about the end of their relationship.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Spoto|first=Donald|title=Rebel: The Life and Legend of James Dean|publisher=Harper Collins|year=1996|isbn=978-0060176563|location=New York, New York|pages=95-122}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/an-affair-to-remember-vol-45-no-25/|title=An Affair to Remember|last=Lipton|first=Michael A.|date=June 24, 1996|website=People magazine|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://people.com/archive/an-affair-to-remember-vol-45-no-25/|archive-date=June 24, 1996|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bcf165OjUms|title=Liz Sheridan Interview on The Paul Leslie Hour|last=Leslie|first=Paul|date=March 2, 2012|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nEarly in 1953, Sheridan departed New York for the Virgin Islands.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Sheridan|first=Liz|title=Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: a Love Story|publisher=Harper Entertainment|year=2000|isbn=978-0060393830|location=New York, NY|pages=298}}</ref> She lived for years in the Caribbean, settling in St. Thomas and later Puerto Rico. She earned a living as a dancer, dance instructor, and also by singing and playing piano. She, with a neighbor who had a dance troupe, won a dance contest she choreographed for the first Carnival in St. Thomas. She also won a six hundred dollar purse finishing first in a horse race, atop her mare, General\u00e9. After a brief engagement to a man, Justus Villa (aka Pancho), she realized realized she didn't want to be married to him, broke it off and returned, for a time, to New York City. There she met up again with Dean, at a party. Afterwards, in a cab, he told her, \"Nothing's lost between us. It never will be. You're a part of me and I'm a part of you. I take you with me wherever I go.\" That was the last time she saw him.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sheridan|first=Liz|title=Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: a Love Story|publisher=Harper Entertainment|year=2000|isbn=978-0060393830|location=New York, NY|pages=306-319}}</ref>  Back in the Caribbean, she met jazz musician<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.myheritage.com/research/record-10182-2227934/william-dale-wales-in-biographical-summaries-of-notable-people|title=William Dale Wales|last=|first=|date=|website=My Heritage|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Kelley|first=Robin|title=Thelonious Monk: The Life and Times of an American Original|publisher=Free Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0684831909|location=New York, NY|pages=pp. 227, 229}}</ref> William \"Dale\" Wales (1917\u20132003) in Puerto Rico. They shared a life from 1960 until his death; they wed in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|last=|first= |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm|title=Biography: Spouse|publisher=imdb.com|date= |accessdate=2016-06-12}}</ref> Their daughter is a photographer living in New York City's [[Greenwich Village]]. \n\nLiz Sheridan and actress Elizabeth Montgomery were best friends: \"Lizzie and Dizzie.\" Montgomery only took on the nickname \"Lizzie\" following her performance in the Emmy Award winning TV movie, ''[[The Legend of Lizzie Borden]]''; Dizzie, more commonly Dizzy, was a shortened version of \"Dizabeth,\" which is how her sister managed to pronounce her name when young.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pilato|first=Herbie J.|title=Twitch Upon a Star: The Bewitched Life and Career of Elizabeth Montgomery|publisher=Taylor Trade|year=2012|isbn=978-1589797499|location=Lanham, MD|pages=pp. 6, 358, 366}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/bio|title=Liz Sheridan Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bcf165OjUms|title=Liz Sheridan Interview on The Paul Leslie Hour|last=Leslie|first=Paul|date=March 2, 2012|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> They each adored horses and together they frequented the Santa Anita race track.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pilato|first=Herbie J.|title=The Essential Elizabeth Montgomery: A Guide to Her Magical Performances|publisher=Taylor Trade|year=2013|isbn=978-1589798243|location=Lanham, MD|pages=17-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Pilato|first=Herbie J.|title=Twitch Upon a Star: The Bewitched Life and Career of Elizabeth Montgomery|publisher=Taylor Trade|year=2012|isbn=978-1589797499|location=Lanham, MD|pages=pp. 291, 293}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0792210}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sheridan, Liz}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American female dancers]]\n[[Category:American dancers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Westchester County, New York]]\n[[Category:Dancers from New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Liz Sheridan\n| image         =\n| imagesize     =\n| birth_name       = Elizabeth Ann Sheridan\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1929|4|10}}\n| birth_place   = [[Rye, New York]], U.S.\n| occupation    = Actress\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Dale Wales<br/>|1985|2003|end=d.}}\n| yearsactive   = 1976\u20132010\n| children       = 1\n}}\n\n'''Elizabeth Ann Sheridan''' (born April 10, 1929) is an American actress. She was born and raised in [[Rye, New York]], the daughter of concert singer Elizabeth Poole-Jones and classical pianist, Frank Sheridan. While best known for her role as Jerry's mother in ''[[Seinfeld]]'', her decades-long career is extensive and includes work as a dancer, singer, and actress of stage and screen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/60/Liz-Sheridan.html|title=Liz Sheridan Biography (1929-)|author=|date=|work=filmreference.com|accessdate=16 March 2016}} While best known for her role in Seinfeld, her decades-long career is extensive and includes work as a dancer, singer, and actress of stage and screen.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSheridan began her professional life in New York City as a nightclub dancer, moving on to stage work. She was cast in Broadway productions throughout the 1970s, both in musicals and plays.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/liz-sheridan-80515|title=Liz Sheridan|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Broadway Database|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Sheridan co-starred with [[Meryl Streep]] and [[Christopher Lloyd]] in the 1977's musical, ''[[Happy End (musical)|Happy End]]'', before moving to Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/happy-end-4000#OpeningNightCast|title=Happy End|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Broadway Database|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Working in Hollywood, she came to prominence in supporting roles in over a dozen feature films and 60 [[prime time]] network television movies, mini-series, and series including ''[[Kojak]]'', ''[[Archie Bunker's Place]]'', ''[[St. Elsewhere]]'', ''[[Newhart]]'', ''[[Moonlighting (TV series)|Moonlighting]]'', ''[[The A-Team]]'', ''[[Who's the Boss?|Who's the Boss]]'', ''[[Hill Street Blues|Hill St. Blues,]]'' ''[[Cagney & Lacey]]'', ''[[Family Ties]]'', and ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''. Her first major role was playing nosy neighbor Raquel Ochmonek on the NBC TV series ''[[ALF (TV series)|ALF]]'', from 1986 to 1990. Following that she secured her most renowned and long-lived role, as [[Jerry Seinfeld (character)|Jerry Seinfeld]]'s mother, Helen, in the long-running and highly rated series, ''Seinfeld''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/the-20-best-tv-sitcoms-of-all-time-2013-6#1-seinfeld-20|title=The 20 Best TV Sitcoms Of All Time|last=Driscoll|first=Molly|date=June 8, 2013|website=Business Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> She appeared in all nine seasons, from 1990 to 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/filmoseries#tt0098904|title=Filmography by TV series for Liz Sheridan (I)|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=April 29, 2013}}</ref>  \n\nIn the 1950s and 1960s, she lived and worked in the Caribbean, \"singing and playing the piano in almost every bar and saloon in the West Indies.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> In the 1960s, she performed in one of Julius Monk's annual cabaret reviews at Plaza 9, located in the [[Plaza Hotel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.quora.com/Was-there-a-club-in-New-York-City-in-the-1970s-called-Plaza-9-all-that-Jazz|title=Was there a club in New York City in the 1970s called \"Plaza 9 & all that Jazz?\"|last=Rose|first=David S.|date=2018|website=Quora|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nIn 2009, with [[Andy Griffith]] and [[Doris Roberts]], Sheridan co-starred in the feature film, ''[[Play the Game (2009 film)|Play the Game]]'', a romantic comedy about a lonely, [[Widow|widowed]] [[grandfather]] who, after a 60-year hiatus, learns dating tricks from his serial romancer of a grandson. The film stirred up [[controversy]] due to its [[Ageing|octogenarian]] [[Sex in film|sex scene]] between Sheridan and Griffith.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/play-the-game-2009|title=Andy Griffith and Seinfeld's mom: I would really rather not know|last=Ebert|first=Roger|date=August 26, 2009|website=Roger Ebert|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Saslow|first=Rachel|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/08/17/AR2009081702067.html|title=Media Scan: A Movie About Aging, a DVD for Exercise, a Book About Dieting|date=18 August 2009|work=Washington Post|accessdate=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWhile working as a dancer in New York City nightclubs, Sheridan met the then-unknown [[James Dean]]. She wrote a book, ''Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: A Love Story'', chronicling their time together in the early 1950s. In it, she describes them as each other's first romantic love. Dean pursued work on the stage in New York, then film roles in Hollywood. Without sure footing or a serious plan, Sheridan was not interested in following him around on both coasts, thus bringing about the end of their relationship.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Spoto|first=Donald|title=Rebel: The Life and Legend of James Dean|publisher=Harper Collins|year=1996|isbn=978-0060176563|location=New York, New York|pages=95-122}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/an-affair-to-remember-vol-45-no-25/|title=An Affair to Remember|last=Lipton|first=Michael A.|date=June 24, 1996|website=People magazine|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://people.com/archive/an-affair-to-remember-vol-45-no-25/|archive-date=June 24, 1996|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bcf165OjUms|title=Liz Sheridan Interview on The Paul Leslie Hour|last=Leslie|first=Paul|date=March 2, 2012|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nEarly in 1953, Sheridan departed New York for the Virgin Islands.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Sheridan|first=Liz|title=Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: a Love Story|publisher=Harper Entertainment|year=2000|isbn=978-0060393830|location=New York, NY|pages=298}}</ref> She lived for years in the Caribbean, settling in St. Thomas and later Puerto Rico. She earned a living as a dancer, dance instructor, and also by singing and playing piano. She, with a neighbor who had a dance troupe, won a dance contest she choreographed for the first Carnival in St. Thomas. She also won a six hundred dollar purse finishing first in a horse race, atop her mare, General\u00e9. After a brief engagement to a man, Justus Villa (aka Pancho), she realized realized she didn't want to be married to him, broke it off and returned, for a time, to New York City. There she met up again with Dean, at a party. Afterwards, in a cab, he told her, \"Nothing's lost between us. It never will be. You're a part of me and I'm a part of you. I take you with me wherever I go.\" That was the last time she saw him.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sheridan|first=Liz|title=Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: a Love Story|publisher=Harper Entertainment|year=2000|isbn=978-0060393830|location=New York, NY|pages=306-319}}</ref>  Back in the Caribbean, she met jazz musician<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.myheritage.com/research/record-10182-2227934/william-dale-wales-in-biographical-summaries-of-notable-people|title=William Dale Wales|last=|first=|date=|website=My Heritage|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Kelley|first=Robin|title=Thelonious Monk: The Life and Times of an American Original|publisher=Free Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0684831909|location=New York, NY|pages=pp. 227, 229}}</ref> William \"Dale\" Wales (1917\u20132003) in Puerto Rico. They shared a life from 1960 until his death; they wed in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|last=|first= |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm|title=Biography: Spouse|publisher=imdb.com|date= |accessdate=2016-06-12}}</ref> Their daughter is a photographer living in New York City's [[Greenwich Village]]. \n\nLiz Sheridan and actress Elizabeth Montgomery were best friends: \"Lizzie and Dizzie.\" Montgomery only took on the nickname \"Lizzie\" following her performance in the Emmy Award winning TV movie, ''[[The Legend of Lizzie Borden]]''; Dizzie, more commonly Dizzy, was a shortened version of \"Dizabeth,\" which is how her sister managed to pronounce her name when young.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pilato|first=Herbie J.|title=Twitch Upon a Star: The Bewitched Life and Career of Elizabeth Montgomery|publisher=Taylor Trade|year=2012|isbn=978-1589797499|location=Lanham, MD|pages=pp. 6, 358, 366}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/bio|title=Liz Sheridan Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bcf165OjUms|title=Liz Sheridan Interview on The Paul Leslie Hour|last=Leslie|first=Paul|date=March 2, 2012|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> They each adored horses and together they frequented the Santa Anita race track.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pilato|first=Herbie J.|title=The Essential Elizabeth Montgomery: A Guide to Her Magical Performances|publisher=Taylor Trade|year=2013|isbn=978-1589798243|location=Lanham, MD|pages=17-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Pilato|first=Herbie J.|title=Twitch Upon a Star: The Bewitched Life and Career of Elizabeth Montgomery|publisher=Taylor Trade|year=2012|isbn=978-1589797499|location=Lanham, MD|pages=pp. 291, 293}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0792210}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sheridan, Liz}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American female dancers]]\n[[Category:American dancers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Westchester County, New York]]\n[[Category:Dancers from New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "PaulThePony", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added spouses born first name in infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liz_Sheridan"}
{"title_page": "The California Raisins", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = The California Raisins\n| image              = California Raisin claymation.jpg\n| image_size         = 200px\n| first              = June 19, 1986\n| last               = 1998\n| creator            = [[California Raisin Advisory Board]]\n| nickname           = The Vine-Yls (''[[Meet the Raisins!]]'')\n| alias              = The Singin' Dancin' California Raisins\n| nationality        = American\n}}\n\n'''The California Raisins''' were a [[fictional]] [[rhythm and blues]] [[virtual band|animated musical group]] as well as [[advertising character|advertising]] and merchandising characters composed of  [[anthropomorphism|anthropomorphized]] [[raisins]]. Lead vocals were sung by musician [[Buddy Miles]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/28/arts/music/28cnd-miles.html?hp |title= Buddy Miles, Hendrix Drummer, Dies |first= Jon |last= Pareles |author-link=Jon Pareles |work= [[The New York Times]] |date= February 28, 2008}}</ref> The California Raisins were popular in the mid-to-late 1980s through [[clay animation|claymation]] [[Television advertisement|TV commercials]] and [[animation|animated]] [[television special|specials]], winning an [[Emmy Award]] and one nomination.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/12/21/arts/tv-review-claymation-christmas-on-cbs.html |title=TV Review; 'Claymation Christmas,' On CBS |work= The New York Times |date=December 21, 1987 |accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-04-12/news/tv-509_1_california-raisins |title=On View: A Feat of Clay: The Creator of California Raisins Molds an Animated Easter Special |work= [[Los Angeles Times]] |date=April 12, 1992 |accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Origin and success==\nThe concept was originally created for a 1986 [[Sun-Maid]] commercial on behalf of the [[California Raisin Advisory Board]] when one of the writers, Seth Werner (at the time with the advertising firm Foote, Cone & Belding SF, and now with big) came up with an idea for the new raisin commercial, saying, \"We have tried everything but dancing raisins singing '[[I Heard It Through the Grapevine]]'\" (the 1968 song popularized by [[Marvin Gaye]]).<ref>{{cite news|title= Stardom Is Feat Of Clay For California Raisins|work= [[Orlando Sentinel]]|date= January 25, 1988 |url= http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1988-01-25/lifestyle/0010260008_1_california-raisins-stardom-critical-acclaim|accessdate=October 6, 2010}}</ref> To their surprise, the commercial became wildly popular, paving the way for several future commercials and opportunities through other media. The commercials were produced by [[Will Vinton|Vinton Studios]] using their [[claymation]] technique, with character designs by Michael Brunsfeld.<ref>{{cite news |last= Corliss |first= Richard |url= http://entertainment.time.com/2012/10/18/bad-25-spike-lee-brings-michael-jackson-back-to-thrilling-life/ |title= Bad 25: Spike Lee Brings Michael Jackson Back to Thrilling Life |work= [[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date= September 22, 2016}}</ref> The following year, the Raisins appeared in the [[Emmy Award]]-winning ''[[A Claymation Christmas Celebration]]'', singing the [[Christmas carol]] \"[[Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer (song)|Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer]]\".\n\nThe California Raisins released four [[studio album]]s on [[Priority Records]] between 1987 and 1988, and their signature song, \"I Heard It Through the Grapevine\", landed on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. However, the Raisins would continue to make their strongest impression through animated endeavors, and the characters proved popular enough that they were used to endorse [[Post Consumer Brands|Post]] [[Raisin Bran]] cereal.\n\nOn November 4, 1988, [[CBS]] aired a primetime television special called ''[[Meet the Raisins!]]'' The musical [[mockumentary]] was again created by Vinton Studios, and was nominated for a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program (for Programming Less Than One Hour)|Primetime Emmy Award]]. It also provided the band members with more personality and individual names: A.C., Beebop (drums), Stretch (bass), and Red (guitar/piano). \n\nA [[Saturday morning cartoons|Saturday morning cartoon]] series, ''[[The California Raisin Show]]'', debuted the following year, but lasted only 13 episodes.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |page=104 }}</ref> While [[Cel animation|cel animated]] by [[Murakami-Wolf-Swenson]], it maintained Will Vinton's creative direction. A sequel to the original CBS special aired in 1990 under the title ''The Raisins: Sold Out! - The California Raisins II''. This special saw the Raisins hiring a new manager with the goal of making a comeback.\n\n==Merchandise==\nMany of the items created for the campaign have become part of the permanent collection of the [[Smithsonian Institution]]. Merchandise sales included toys and Raisins images on nearly every conceivable medium: [[lunch box]]es, notebooks, clothing, [[posters]], bedsheets, and even a [[Halloween costume]], just to name a few. A California Raisins Fan Club began in 1987, which included a ''Grapevine Gazette'' newsletter and various memorabilia.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://wharble.com/California_Raisins_Collectibles.htm |title= California Raisins Collectibles |work= Wharble.com |access-date= May 15, 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110216065812/http://wharble.com/California_Raisins_Collectibles.htm |archive-date= February 16, 2011 |url-status= dead }}</ref> [[Blackthorne Publishing]] also released a six-issue [[comic book]] series entitled ''The California Raisins 3-D'' which included [[Stereoscopy#3D viewers|3D glasses]]; these would later be re-released in the ''Ultimate Collection'' [[Trade paperback (comics)|trade paperback]].\n\nSeveral California Raisins music albums were also released, featuring classic [[Motown]] and rock standards. These albums were included in the Smithsonian collection and were illustrated and art-directed by [[Helane Freeman]], who later became famous for her work on ''[[Hannah Montana]]'' and ''[[The Suite Life of Zack & Cody]]'', among other [[Disney]] programs.\n\nPerhaps the most memorable piece of California Raisins merchandise, however, came in the form of small, non-poseable California Raisins figures. The [[Hardee's]] restaurant chain offered these as part of a promotion for their Cinnamon 'N' Raisin biscuits.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.hardees.com/company/story/ |title= The Hardee's Story |publisher= Hardees |access-date= June 22, 2010}}</ref> Different collections were produced in 1987, 1988, 1991, and finally in 2001 (the latter adding [[Carls Jr.]] due to their late '90s acquisition of Hardee's) for their new stylization. This latest incarnation can still be seen on the California Raisin Marketing Board website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.calraisins.org/raisins_home/|title=CalRaisins.org}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s, [[Capcom]] produced a [[video game]] for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] titled ''[[The California Raisins: The Grape Escape]]'',<ref name=\"NP-9\">{{cite journal| journal = [[Nintendo Power]]| publisher = [[Nintendo]]| title = Pak Watch| page = 95| author = Nintendo Power Staff|date=November\u2013December 1989| issue = #9}}</ref> in which the player controlled a California Raisin through five [[side-scrolling]] levels battling various evil fruit and vegetable characters that have stolen the Raisins' music. The game was completed and several video game critics reviewed it, but it was never released on the open market.\n\nBox Office Software produced a different, unrelated California Raisins computer game in 1988 for the [[Apple II]], [[Commodore 64]], and [[PC compatible]]s. The plot of the game involved Tiny Goodbite having to rescue his friends who have been kidnapped and held in a cereal factory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mobygames.com/game/c64/california-raisins|title=The California Raisins for Commodore 64 (1988)|website=MobyGames}}</ref>\n\n==Decline==\nAlthough popular with the public, the California Raisin campaign eventually failed because its production cost the raisin growers almost twice their earnings. [[California Raisin Advisory Board|CALRAB]], the organization who made the campaign, was also closed on July 31, 1994, due to disagreements with raisin producers over the fairness of required payments to the organization.<ref name=\"The New York Times 2019\">{{cite web | title=The Raisin Situation | website=The New York Times | date=2019-04-27 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/27/style/sun-maid-raisin-industry.html | access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref>{{Additional citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n==Post-popularity and legacy==\nOn March 28, 1997 ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' published \"The 50 Best Commercials of All Time\" as its [[article (publishing)|cover story]]. The article ranked The California Raisins' premiere advertisement, \"Lunchbox\", at #15 with comments by ad agency executive Claude Jacques and described the Raisins as \"The coolest wrinkled musicians this side of the [[The Rolling Stones|Stones]].\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,287305_2,00.html |title= The 50 Best Commercials of All Time |work = [[Entertainment Weekly]] |date= March 28, 1997 |access-date= May 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe vast amount of California Raisins merchandise has made for a substantial collectors' market. It even led to an unauthorized collectibles guide published in 1998, cataloging the many items based on the clay characters.<ref>{{cite book |title= Collectible California Raisins: An Unauthorized Guide With Values |isbn = 076430433X|last1 = Curran|first1 = Pamela Duvall|last2 = Curran|first2 = George|date = December 23, 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, the [[Food Network]] program ''[[Unwrapped]]'' featured a segment on The California Raisins featuring interviews with [[Will Vinton]], David Altschul, and Mark Gustafson of Vinton Studios. Concept illustrations of the Raisins were also featured as interviewees discussed the characters' creation.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qDN_C70xpZ8 |work= Unwrapped |title= The California Raisins |via= YouTube |access-date= June 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[['Tis the Fifteenth Season]]\", The California Raisins were spoofed as ''The California Prunes'', on a special entitled ''Christmas with the California Prunes''. [[Lisa Simpson|Lisa]] dismisses it as \"offensive to both [[Christians]] ''and'' prunes.\"\n\nAn article published by AnimateClay.com in the late 2000s details the whereabouts of the original claymation sculptures used by Vinton Studios. The figures were kept in a box for several years and headed for the trash before being obtained by Webster Colcord, a former employee of Vinton. Several photos were taken providing a close look at the Raisins' internal armatures and detailing their extremely poor condition, including the absence of the A.C. puppet's head.<ref>{{cite web |last= Spess |first= Marc |url= http://www.animateclay.com/index.php/articles/69-behind-the-scenes/119-california-raisin-raisin-puppets-late-80s-early-90s |title= California Raisin Raisin Puppets: Late 80s - Early 90s |work= AnimateClay.com |date= April 18, 2010 |access-date= May 15, 2011 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110707143703/http://www.animateclay.com/index.php/articles/69-behind-the-scenes/119-california-raisin-raisin-puppets-late-80s-early-90s |archivedate= July 7, 2011 |df= mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nAs of the 2010s, packages of [[Sun-Maid]] Natural California Raisins still feature an updated California Raisin character. This figure is also included on [http://www.calraisins.org/ CalRaisins.org].\n\nIn 2010, [[Clay animation|claymation]] versions of the California Raisins were featured in the special [[Christmas]] episode of ''[[It's Always Sunny in Philadelphia]]'', \"A Very Sunny Christmas\".<ref>{{cite news |last= Zingale |first= Jason |url= http://www.premiumhollywood.com/2009/11/21/its-always-sunny-in-philadelphia-a-very-sunny-christmas/ |title= It's Always Sunny in Philadelphia: A Very Sunny Christmas |work= Premium Hollywood |date= November 21, 2009 |access-date= September 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the California Raisins made a cameo appearance in the [[RadioShack]] [[Super Bowl XLVIII]] commercial \"[[The '80s Called]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://people.com/tv/radioshack-super-bowl-commercial-every-80s-reference-in-the-ad-spot/ |title=Celebrating Every '80s Reference in That RadioShack Super Bowl Commercial |author=Jones, Nate |publisher=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=2 February 2014 |accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, an episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]'' called \"[[The Cad and the Hat]]\" included a couch gag segment featuring the California Raisins being killed by Homer.<ref>{{cite AV media |last=Animation on FOX|title=Robot Chicken Couch Gag, Season 28 Ep. 14, ''The Simpsons'' |date=February 16, 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wXzLju-4Su8|accessdate=February 23, 2017 |via= YouTube}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, an episode of ''[[The Americans]]'' called \"[[Rififi (The Americans)|Rififi]]\" feature a cereal box featuring the California Raisins on the back.\n\n===Planned film===\nIn 2015, it was announced that a live-action/CGI reboot of the California Raisins would be produced, with president of The Actors Hall of Fame Foundation, Rusty Citron, as one of the people behind the project.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.cartoonbrew.com/feature-film/california-raisins-set-for-comeback-in-live-actioncg-feature-exclusive-110510.html |title= California Raisins Set for Comeback in Live-Action Feature |work= Cartoon Brew.com |access-date= July 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*''The California Raisins Sing the Hit Songs'' - 1987, [[Priority Records]]\n*\"What Does It Take (To Win Your Love)\" b/w \"I Got You (I Feel Good)\" - 1988, Purple Vinyl 7\"\n*\"I Heard it Through the Grapevine\" - 1988 (single, peaked at #84 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]])\n*''Sweet, Delicious, & Marvelous'' - 1988, [[Priority Records]]\n*''Meet the Raisins!'' - 1988, [[Atlantic Records]]\n*''Christmas with The California Raisins'' - 1988, [[Priority Records]]\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n*''A Claymation Christmas Celebration'' - [[Primetime Emmy]]\n*''Meet the Raisins!'' - Primetime Emmy nominee\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0284709|title=\"California Raisins\" TV series}}\n*{{IMDb title|id=0261220|title=\"Raisins Sold Out: The California Raisins II\"}}\n*[https://archive.is/20060327125729/http://www.nesplayer.com/features/californiaraisins/proto.htm California Raisins NES Game]\n*[http://www.willvinton.net Official Will Vinton (LAIKA) Studios Site]\n*[http://laika.com New Laika Studio Site (Will Vinton)]\n*[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p3819|pure_url=yes}} All Music Entry]\n*[http://www.calraisins.org California Raisins Marketing Board] official website\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110707143703/http://www.animateclay.com/index.php/articles/69-behind-the-scenes/119-california-raisin-raisin-puppets-late-80s-early-90s The Clay and Stop-Motion Animation How-To Page: \"California Raisin Raisin Puppets: Late 80s - Early 90s\"]\n\n{{The California Raisins}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:California Raisins, The}}\n[[Category:Mascots introduced in 1986]]\n[[Category:Food advertising characters]]\n[[Category:Animated musical groups]]\n[[Category:Fruit and vegetable characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional food characters]]\n[[Category:Clay animation]]\n[[Category:Priority Records artists]]\n[[Category:Motown]]\n[[Category:Blackthorne Publishing titles]]\n[[Category:1988 in comics]]\n[[Category:Comics featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Raisins]]\n[[Category:1980s fads and trends]]\n[[Category:Fictional musical groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = The California Raisins\n| image              = California Raisin claymation.jpg\n| image_size         = 200px\n| first              = June 19, 1986\n| last               = 1998\n| creator            = [[California Raisin Advisory Board]]\n| nickname           = The Vine-Yls (''[[Meet the Raisins!]]'')\n| alias              = The Singin' Dancin' California Raisins\n| nationality        = American\n}}\n\n'''The California Raisins''' were a [[fictional]] [[rhythm and blues]] [[virtual band|animated musical group]] as well as [[advertising character|advertising]] and merchandising characters composed of  [[anthropomorphism|anthropomorphized]] [[raisins]]. Lead vocals were sung by musician [[Buddy Miles]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/28/arts/music/28cnd-miles.html?hp |title= Buddy Miles, Hendrix Drummer, Dies |first= Jon |last= Pareles |author-link=Jon Pareles |work= [[The New York Times]] |date= February 28, 2008}}</ref> The California Raisins were popular in the mid-to-late 1980s through [[clay animation|claymation]] [[Television advertisement|TV commercials]] and [[animation|animated]] [[television special|specials]], winning an [[Emmy Award]] and one nomination.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/12/21/arts/tv-review-claymation-christmas-on-cbs.html |title=TV Review; 'Claymation Christmas,' On CBS |work= The New York Times |date=December 21, 1987 |accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-04-12/news/tv-509_1_california-raisins |title=On View: A Feat of Clay: The Creator of California Raisins Molds an Animated Easter Special |work= [[Los Angeles Times]] |date=April 12, 1992 |accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Origin and success==\nThe concept was originally created for a 1986 [[Sun-Maid]] commercial on behalf of the [[California Raisin Advisory Board]] when one of the writers, Seth Werner (at the time with the advertising firm Foote, Cone & Belding SF, and now with big) came up with an idea for the new raisin commercial, saying, \"We have tried everything but dancing raisins singing '[[I Heard It Through the Grapevine]]'\" (the 1968 song popularized by [[Marvin Gaye]]).<ref>{{cite news|title= Stardom Is Feat Of Clay For California Raisins|work= [[Orlando Sentinel]]|date= January 25, 1988 |url= http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1988-01-25/lifestyle/0010260008_1_california-raisins-stardom-critical-acclaim|accessdate=October 6, 2010}}</ref> To their surprise, the commercial became wildly popular, paving the way for several future commercials and opportunities through other media. The commercials were produced by [[Will Vinton|Vinton Studios]] using their [[claymation]] technique, with character designs by Michael Brunsfeld.<ref>{{cite news |last= Corliss |first= Richard |url= http://entertainment.time.com/2012/10/18/bad-25-spike-lee-brings-michael-jackson-back-to-thrilling-life/ |title= Bad 25: Spike Lee Brings Michael Jackson Back to Thrilling Life |work= [[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date= September 22, 2016}}</ref> The following year, the Raisins appeared in the [[Emmy Award]]-winning ''[[A Claymation Christmas Celebration]]'', singing the [[Christmas carol]] \"[[Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer (song)|Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer]]\".\n\nThe California Raisins released four [[studio album]]s on [[Priority Records]] between 1987 and 1988, and their signature song, \"I Heard It Through the Grapevine\", landed on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. However, the Raisins would continue to make their strongest impression through animated endeavors, and the characters proved popular enough that they were used to endorse [[Post Consumer Brands|Post]] [[Raisin Bran]] cereal.\n\nOn November 4, 1988, [[CBS]] aired a primetime television special called ''[[Meet the Raisins!]]'' The musical [[mockumentary]] was again created by Vinton Studios, and was nominated for a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program (for Programming Less Than One Hour)|Primetime Emmy Award]]. It also provided the band members with more personality and individual names: A.C., Beebop (drums), Stretch (bass), and Red (guitar/piano). \n\nA [[Saturday morning cartoons|Saturday morning cartoon]] series, ''[[The California Raisin Show]]'', debuted the following year, but lasted only 13 episodes.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |page=104 }}</ref> While [[Cel animation|cel animated]] by [[Murakami-Wolf-Swenson]], it maintained Will Vinton's creative direction. A sequel to the original CBS special aired in 1990 under the title ''The Raisins: Sold Out! - The California Raisins II''. This special saw the Raisins hiring a new manager with the goal of making a comeback.\n\n==Merchandise==\nMany of the items created for the campaign have become part of the permanent collection of the [[Smithsonian Institution]]. Merchandise sales included toys and Raisins images on nearly every conceivable medium: [[lunch box]]es, notebooks, clothing, [[posters]], bedsheets, and even a [[Halloween costume]], just to name a few. A California Raisins Fan Club began in 1987, which included a ''Grapevine Gazette'' newsletter and various memorabilia.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://wharble.com/California_Raisins_Collectibles.htm |title= California Raisins Collectibles |work= Wharble.com |access-date= May 15, 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110216065812/http://wharble.com/California_Raisins_Collectibles.htm |archive-date= February 16, 2011 |url-status= dead }}</ref> [[Blackthorne Publishing]] also released a six-issue [[comic book]] series entitled ''The California Raisins 3-D'' which included [[Stereoscopy#3D viewers|3D glasses]]; these would later be re-released in the ''Ultimate Collection'' [[Trade paperback (comics)|trade paperback]].\n\nSeveral California Raisins music albums were also released, featuring classic [[Motown]] and rock standards. These albums were included in the Smithsonian collection and were illustrated and art-directed by [[Helane Freeman]], who later became famous for her work on ''[[Hannah Montana]]'' and ''[[The Suite Life of Zack & Cody]]'', among other [[Disney]] programs.\n\nPerhaps the most memorable piece of California Raisins merchandise, however, came in the form of small, non-poseable California Raisins figures. The [[Hardee's]] restaurant chain offered these as part of a promotion for their Cinnamon 'N' Raisin biscuits.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.hardees.com/company/story/ |title= The Hardee's Story |publisher= Hardees |access-date= June 22, 2010}}</ref> Different collections were produced in 1987, 1988, 1991, and finally in 2001 (the latter adding [[Carls Jr.]] due to their late '90s acquisition of Hardee's) for their new stylization. This latest incarnation can still be seen on the California Raisin Marketing Board website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.calraisins.org/raisins_home/|title=CalRaisins.org}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s, [[Capcom]] produced a [[video game]] for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] titled ''[[The California Raisins: The Grape Escape]]'',<ref name=\"NP-9\">{{cite journal| journal = [[Nintendo Power]]| publisher = [[Nintendo]]| title = Pak Watch| page = 95| author = Nintendo Power Staff|date=November\u2013December 1989| issue = #9}}</ref> in which the player controlled a California Raisin through five [[side-scrolling]] levels battling various evil fruit and vegetable characters that have stolen the Raisins' music. The game was completed and several video game critics reviewed it, but it was never released on the open market.\n\nBox Office Software produced a different, unrelated California Raisins computer game in 1988 for the [[Apple II]], [[Commodore 64]], and [[PC compatible]]s. The plot of the game involved Tiny Goodbite having to rescue his friends who have been kidnapped and held in a cereal factory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mobygames.com/game/c64/california-raisins|title=The California Raisins for Commodore 64 (1988)|website=MobyGames}}</ref>\n\n==Decline==\nAlthough popular with the public, the California Raisin campaign eventually failed because its production cost the raisin growers almost twice their earnings. [[California Raisin Advisory Board|CALRAB]], the organization who made the campaign, was also closed on July 31, 1994, due to disagreements with raisin producers over the fairness of required payments to the organization.<ref name=\"The New York Times 2019\">{{cite web | title=The Raisin Situation | website=The New York Times | date=2019-04-27 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/27/style/sun-maid-raisin-industry.html | access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref>{{Additional citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n==Post-popularity and legacy==\nOn March 28, 1997 ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' published \"The 50 Best Commercials of All Time\" as its [[article (publishing)|cover story]]. The article ranked The California Raisins' premiere advertisement, \"Lunchbox\", at #15 with comments by ad agency executive Claude Jacques and described the Raisins as \"The coolest wrinkled musicians this side of the [[The Rolling Stones|Stones]].\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,287305_2,00.html |title= The 50 Best Commercials of All Time |work = [[Entertainment Weekly]] |date= March 28, 1997 |access-date= May 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe vast amount of California Raisins merchandise has made for a substantial collectors' market. It even led to an unauthorized collectibles guide published in 1998, cataloging the many items based on the clay characters.<ref>{{cite book |title= Collectible California Raisins: An Unauthorized Guide With Values |isbn = 076430433X|last1 = Curran|first1 = Pamela Duvall|last2 = Curran|first2 = George|date = December 23, 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, the [[Food Network]] program ''[[Unwrapped]]'' featured a segment on The California Raisins featuring interviews with [[Will Vinton]], David Altschul, and Mark Gustafson of Vinton Studios. Concept illustrations of the Raisins were also featured as interviewees discussed the characters' creation.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qDN_C70xpZ8 |work= Unwrapped |title= The California Raisins |via= YouTube |access-date= June 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[['Tis the Fifteenth Season]]\", The California Raisins were spoofed as ''The California Prunes'', on a special entitled ''Christmas with the California Prunes''. [[Lisa Simpson|Lisa]] dismisses it as \"offensive to both [[Christians]] ''and'' prunes.\"\n\nAn article published by AnimateClay.com in the late 2000s details the whereabouts of the original claymation sculptures used by Vinton Studios. The figures were kept in a box for several years and headed for the trash before being obtained by Webster Colcord, a former employee of Vinton. Several photos were taken providing a close look at the Raisins' internal armatures and detailing their extremely poor condition, including the absence of the A.C. puppet's head.<ref>{{cite web |last= Spess |first= Marc |url= http://www.animateclay.com/index.php/articles/69-behind-the-scenes/119-california-raisin-raisin-puppets-late-80s-early-90s |title= California Raisin Raisin Puppets: Late 80's - Early 90's |work= AnimateClay.com |date= April 18, 2010 |access-date= May 15, 2011 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110707143703/http://www.animateclay.com/index.php/articles/69-behind-the-scenes/119-california-raisin-raisin-puppets-late-80s-early-90s |archivedate= July 7, 2011 |df= mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nAs of the 2010s, packages of [[Sun-Maid]] Natural California Raisins still feature an updated California Raisin character. This figure is also included on [http://www.calraisins.org/ CalRaisins.org].\n\nIn 2010, [[Clay animation|claymation]] versions of the California Raisins were featured in the special [[Christmas]] episode of ''[[It's Always Sunny in Philadelphia]]'', \"A Very Sunny Christmas\".<ref>{{cite news |last= Zingale |first= Jason |url= http://www.premiumhollywood.com/2009/11/21/its-always-sunny-in-philadelphia-a-very-sunny-christmas/ |title= It's Always Sunny in Philadelphia: A Very Sunny Christmas |work= Premium Hollywood |date= November 21, 2009 |access-date= September 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the California Raisins made a cameo appearance in the [[RadioShack]] [[Super Bowl XLVIII]] commercial \"[[The '80s Called]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://people.com/tv/radioshack-super-bowl-commercial-every-80s-reference-in-the-ad-spot/ |title=Celebrating Every '80s Reference in That RadioShack Super Bowl Commercial |author=Jones, Nate |publisher=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=2 February 2014 |accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, an episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]'' called \"[[The Cad and the Hat]]\" included a couch gag segment featuring the California Raisins being killed by Homer.<ref>{{cite AV media |last=Animation on FOX|title=Robot Chicken Couch Gag, Season 28 Ep. 14, ''The Simpsons'' |date=February 16, 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wXzLju-4Su8|accessdate=February 23, 2017 |via= YouTube}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, an episode of ''[[The Americans]]'' called \"[[Rififi (The Americans)|Rififi]]\" feature a cereal box featuring the California Raisins on the back.\n\n===Planned film===\nIn 2015, it was announced that a live-action/CGI reboot of the California Raisins would be produced, with president of The Actors Hall of Fame Foundation, Rusty Citron, as one of the people behind the project.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.cartoonbrew.com/feature-film/california-raisins-set-for-comeback-in-live-actioncg-feature-exclusive-110510.html |title= California Raisins Set for Comeback in Live-Action Feature |work= Cartoon Brew.com |access-date= July 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*''The California Raisins Sing the Hit Songs'' - 1987, [[Priority Records]]\n*\"What Does It Take (To Win Your Love)\" b/w \"I Got You (I Feel Good)\" - 1988, Purple Vinyl 7\"\n*\"I Heard it Through the Grapevine\" - 1988 (single, peaked at #84 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]])\n*''Sweet, Delicious, & Marvelous'' - 1988, [[Priority Records]]\n*''Meet the Raisins!'' - 1988, [[Atlantic Records]]\n*''Christmas with The California Raisins'' - 1988, [[Priority Records]]\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n*''A Claymation Christmas Celebration'' - [[Primetime Emmy]]\n*''Meet the Raisins!'' - Primetime Emmy nominee\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0284709|title=\"California Raisins\" TV series}}\n*{{IMDb title|id=0261220|title=\"Raisins Sold Out: The California Raisins II\"}}\n*[https://archive.is/20060327125729/http://www.nesplayer.com/features/californiaraisins/proto.htm California Raisins NES Game]\n*[http://www.willvinton.net Official Will Vinton (LAIKA) Studios Site]\n*[http://laika.com New Laika Studio Site (Will Vinton)]\n*[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p3819|pure_url=yes}} All Music Entry]\n*[http://www.calraisins.org California Raisins Marketing Board] official website\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110707143703/http://www.animateclay.com/index.php/articles/69-behind-the-scenes/119-california-raisin-raisin-puppets-late-80s-early-90s The Clay and Stop-Motion Animation How-To Page: \"California Raisin Raisin Puppets: Late 80s - Early 90s\"]\n\n{{The California Raisins}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:California Raisins, The}}\n[[Category:Mascots introduced in 1986]]\n[[Category:Food advertising characters]]\n[[Category:Animated musical groups]]\n[[Category:Fruit and vegetable characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional food characters]]\n[[Category:Clay animation]]\n[[Category:Priority Records artists]]\n[[Category:Motown]]\n[[Category:Blackthorne Publishing titles]]\n[[Category:1988 in comics]]\n[[Category:Comics featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Raisins]]\n[[Category:1980s fads and trends]]\n[[Category:Fictional musical groups]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_California_Raisins"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Washington, D.C.", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Washington, D.C., United States}}\n{{Current event|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Washington, D.C.\n| width           = \n| image           = National Gallery of Art (49656625722).jpg\n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = Visitors wearing masks in the [[National Gallery of Art]], the day before it closed as a precaution against COVID-19\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n| first_case      = March 7, 2020\n| arrival_date    = \n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 902\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| deaths          = 21\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://coronavirus.dc.gov/}}\n}}\n\nThe first cases of [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the global pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in [[Washington, D.C.]] were reported on March 7, 2020. {{As of|2020|04|02|df=US}}, there are 902 confirmed cases and 21 deaths in Washington, D.C. alone, with other cases in the surrounding counties of the [[Washington metropolitan area]].<ref name=\"dcgovdata\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Data |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/page/coronavirus-data |website=DC.Gov |publisher=Government of the District of Columbia |accessdate=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323134324/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/page/coronavirus-data |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Washington, D.C. medical cases chart}}\n\n==Timeline==\n\n=== February ===\nMayor [[Muriel Bowser]] signed an executive order that began to prepare Washington D.C. for coronavirus impacts on February 28. It was announced in the executive order that the District's Emergency Operations Center (EOC) would be activated on March 2, 2020 at 9:00&nbsp;a.m. to begin to \"coordinate inter-agency information sharing and identify logistical needs for critical incident responses.\" It was also announced that the Washington D.C. Department of Health and the Homeland Security and Emergency Management Agency would be responsible for the response planning for COVID-19.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayors-order-district-government-preparations-coronavirus|title=Mayor's Order: District Government Preparations for the Coronavirus {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329193351/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayors-order-district-government-preparations-coronavirus|archive-date=2020-03-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n\n==== March 1\u20134 ====\nOn March 2 at 9:00&nbsp;a.m., the D.C. Emergency Operations Center was activated at an Enhanced Watch status, as per the executive order signed on February 28.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn March 3, Mayor Bowser, the D.C. Department of Health, and the D.C. Homeland Security and Emergency Management Agency held a public briefing on the coronavirus and the District's \"monitoring, preparation, and response\" to it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-hold-briefing-district%E2%80%99s-coronavirus-monitoring-preparation-and-response|title=Mayor Bowser to Hold Briefing on the District's Coronavirus Monitoring, Preparation, and Response {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308004155/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-hold-briefing-district%E2%80%99s-coronavirus-monitoring-preparation-and-response|archive-date=2020-03-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====March 5\u20137====\nOn March 7, the first two cases of COVID-19 in Washington, D.C. were confirmed. The first case was a [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|rector]] at [[Christ Church (Georgetown, Washington, D.C.)|Christ Church Georgetown]] who had not traveled outside the United States recently or had contact with another infected coronavirus patient. He participated in church services on February 23 and March 1. The rector felt better initially, but his condition deteriorated to the point of hospitalization, when it was confirmed he had coronavirus. After it was confirmed the rector contracted the virus, the church cancelled services indefinitely. The second case was a [[Nigeria]]n national who traveled to D.C. and went to a hospital in [[Maryland]] for treatment. Although the second man was being treated at a Maryland hospital, he was counted as the District's second case by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC).<ref>{{cite news |title=Georgetown Church Rector, Traveler Diagnosed as DC's First 2 Coronavirus Cases |url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-has-first-presumptive-coronavirus-case/2234068/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=NBC4 Washington |date=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316154326/https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-has-first-presumptive-coronavirus-case/2234068/ |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|user=MayorBowser|number=1236422174958895104|title=Late this afternoon, testing at the Public Health Lab at the DC Department of Forensic Sciences yielded its first presumptive positive coronavirus (COVID-19) case. Join me live at 7:30 p.m. for a briefing at the John A. Wilson Building.|date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====March 8\u201310====\nOn March 9, [[School Without Walls (Washington, D.C.)|School Without Walls]], a public school in [[Foggy Bottom]], was closed by [[District of Columbia Public Schools]] (DCPS) for a full-day deep cleaning and disinfecting by a third-party contractor after an employee was exposed to COVID-19 the week before. The employee tested negative and entered a two-week quarantine. DCPS chancellor Lewis Ferebee announced the closing over Twitter the previous day.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1236819215920832513|date=8 Mar 2020|title=Tomorrow - 3/9 - School Without Walls High School will be closed. DCPS is conducting a deep cleaning and disinfecting of the building following an employee being exposed to COVID-19. Test results were negative, and there is no immediate risk to students and staff. cc: @SWWHSA}}</ref>\n\nThree more coronavirus cases in D.C. were confirmed the night of March 9, including an attendee of Christ Church Georgetown. D.C. officials recommended a two-week self-quarantine per CDC guidelines for anyone who attended Christ Church on February 24 or between February 28 and March 3. At that time, $1.5 million had been allocated to the pandemic response by the D.C. government.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gelman |first1=Scott |last2=Alvarez |first2=Alejandro |title=16 coronavirus cases confirmed in DC, Md. and Va. |url=https://wtop.com/local/2020/03/bowser-hogan-to-deliver-update-on-coronavirus-as-dc-area-officials-investigate-9-cases/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=WTOP |date=9 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313023822/https://wtop.com/local/2020/03/bowser-hogan-to-deliver-update-on-coronavirus-as-dc-area-officials-investigate-9-cases/ |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, [[George Washington University]] announced classes will be moved online after spring break, starting on March 23 and continuing until at least April 5. In addition, all residential students were expected to no longer be living on campus beginning March 21. It was stated that an opening date would not be announced until the end of the instructional continuity period when a decision for the rest of the semester would be made.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fox5dc.com/news/george-washington-university-moving-to-online-classes-after-spring-break|title=George Washington University moving to online classes after spring break|date=2020-03-10|website=Fox 5 DC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311103004/https://www.fox5dc.com/news/george-washington-university-moving-to-online-classes-after-spring-break|archive-date=2020-03-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.georgetown.edu/coronavirus/|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) Resource Center|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312130006/https://www.georgetown.edu/coronavirus/|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAlso on March 10, [[Georgetown Day School]], a private school, closed indefinitely and began a deep clean citing concerns about community members affiliated with [[Christ Church (Georgetown, Washington, D.C.)|Christ Church Georgetown]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Volou |first1=Khalida |title=DC school closed due to coronavirus exposure linked to Christ Church Georgetown |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-day-school-closed-tuesday-due-to-coronavirus/65-e374b3e9-a496-42ed-9043-d4bd0b9c45c9 |agency=WUSA9 |date=10 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311195837/https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-day-school-closed-tuesday-due-to-coronavirus/65-e374b3e9-a496-42ed-9043-d4bd0b9c45c9 |archive-date=11 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====March 11\u201314====\nOn March 11, [[Maria Cantwell]], a U.S. senator from Washington state, closed her D.C. office due to one of her aides testing positive for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/politics-government/article241118946.html|title=Aide to Maria Cantwell tests positive for coronavirus. Senator closes her D.C. office|last=Lightman|first=David|website=thenewstribune|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313030257/https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/politics-government/article241118946.html|archive-date=2020-03-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Georgetown University]] announced that it would be moving to virtual learning entirely beginning on March 16, and while campus would remain open and key services would remain accessible the university strongly suggested that students return to their homes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khan |first1=Saliqa |title=Georgetown University moves to virtual learning amid coronavirus concerns |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-university-moves-to-virtual-learning-amid-coronavirus-concerns/65-60c60f1b-9838-4090-80e9-dffa49d92737 |work=WUSA9 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318192012/https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-university-moves-to-virtual-learning-amid-coronavirus-concerns/65-60c60f1b-9838-4090-80e9-dffa49d92737 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, the [[United States Capitol]], the [[White House]], and the [[United States Supreme Court Building]] closed to most of the public until April after several offices closed and multiple lawmakers went into precautionary quarantines.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zengerle |first1=Patricia |last2=Heavey |first2=Susan |title=UPDATE 5-U.S. federal buildings put away the welcome mat as coronavirus hits |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-usa-capitol/update-5-us-federal-buildings-put-away-the-welcome-mat-as-coronavirus-hits-idUSL1N2B50S4 |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, [[District of Columbia Public Schools|DCPS]] announced that they will cancel classes until April 1, implementing online distance learning.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1238430012417748993|date=13 March 2020|title=DCPS will modify operations from Monday, March 16 through Tuesday, March 31 to help limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19) in our region. For more info about the closure schedule, meal locations for students & distance learning details, please visit: https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus}}</ref> Also on March 13, the [[Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]] (WMATA) escalated its operations to level 3 of its pandemic flu plan, announcing that service on the [[Washington Metro]] would be reduced to one train every 12 minutes from Monday to Saturday and one train every 15 minutes on Sunday beginning on March 17. In addition, [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]] service would change to a Saturday supplemental schedule on weekdays beginning on March 17.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmata.com/service/status/details/COVID-19.cfm#main-content|title=Metro takes additional steps, coordinates with public health authorities on COVID-19 {{!}} WMATA|website=wmata.com|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314155101/https://wmata.com/service/status/details/COVID-19.cfm#main-content|archive-date=2020-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/transportation/2020/03/13/metro-reduces-transit-service-response-coronavirus/|title=Metro to reduce transit service in response to the coronavirus outbreak|last=George|first=Justin|date=13 March 2020|website=Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314134151/https://www.washingtonpost.com/transportation/2020/03/13/metro-reduces-transit-service-response-coronavirus/|archive-date=14 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMayor [[Muriel Bowser]] held a press conference, announcing that gatherings of people over 60 years of age or with preexisting health issues would be limited to 10 people. The restriction would not apply to residences, schools, or places of work. For populations not at-risk the government promoted [[social distancing]] measures to limit the spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vitka |first1=Will |last2=Bonk |first2=Valerie |title=Trump declares national emergency; DC bans mass gatherings |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-dc-area/ |work=WTOP |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314183154/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-dc-area/ |archive-date=14 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, Mayor Bowser issued a statement confirming 6 more positive cases in Washington, D.C., bringing the total number of cases up to 16.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-14|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 14 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316100728/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-14|archive-date=2020-03-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====March 15\u201316====\nOn March 15, Bowser's office announced one more positive case in Washington D.C., bringing the total cumulative number of cases to 17. The patient in this case is a 38-year-old woman who came into contact with another case.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-15|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 15|work=Government of the District of Columbia|accessdate=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324170918/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-15|archive-date=2020-03-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Hill Restaurant Group (HRG) said on March 16 they would comply would restrictions on bars and restaurants ordered by Mayor Bowser on March 15. Tom Johnson, the managing director of the group, had earlier said he would ignore the order, saying it would force his company into bankruptcy.<ref>[https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/487826-dc-restaurant-group-says-it-will-comply-with-restrictions-after-mayor DC restaurant group says it will comply with restrictions after mayor's warning] The Hill, 16 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nOn the evening of March 16, Mayor Bowser's office released an update that confirmed five more positive cases of coronavirus in the District. The patients involved were a 23-year-old man, a 42-year-old woman with a history of travel to Europe, a 54-year-old woman, a 54-year-old man, and a 56-year-old man. These five cases brought the cumulative number of cases in D.C. to 22.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-16|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 16 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317204518/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-16|archive-date=2020-03-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== March 17\u201318 ====\nLate on March 17, Mayor Bowser's office announced the confirmation of nine more positive cases in the District, bringing the total number of positive cases to 31. The patients were all male and between the ages of 23 and 61. The 23-year-old patient was confirmed to have attended the [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC) in [[National Harbor, Maryland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-17|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 17 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319072119/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-17|archive-date=2020-03-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, at least 8 more cases were found, including a [[District of Columbia Fire and Emergency Medical Services Department|DC FEMS]] employee (leading to a quarantine of 73 firefighters), a [[U.S. marshal]] at the [[Superior Court of the District of Columbia]], and an undergraduate student at the George Washington University who lives off-campus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moore |first1=Jack |title=Coronavirus: Jump in new cases around region; DC first responder, US Marshal test positive |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-updates-dc-maryland-virginia/ |work=WTOP |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319002447/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-updates-dc-maryland-virginia/ |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Metropolitan Police Department of the District of Columbia]] announced new [[social distancing]] precautions in dealing with callers reporting flu-like symptoms as well as changes to police protocol for citations and warning notices in light of the restriction of certain services in the D.C. government.<ref>{{cite web |title=Metropolitan Police Department Operational Adjustments During COVID-19 |url=https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/metropolitan-police-department-operational-adjustments-during-covid-19 |website=Metropolitan Police Department |publisher=DC.Gov |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319002500/https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/metropolitan-police-department-operational-adjustments-during-covid-19 |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== March 19\u201320 ====\nAs of March 19, the number of confirmed cases sharply jumped to 71 as the supply of tests was expanded, an increase of 32 over one day.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1240791217647976448|user=MayorBowser|title=As of 8:00 p.m. on Thursday, March 19, the District\u2019s coronavirus (COVID-19) data includes 32 new positive cases, bringing the District\u2019s overall positive case total to 71 individuals. For more information visit:|date=19 March 2020}}</ref> This includes two more DC FEMS members and an eight-year-old.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Massimo |first1=Rick |title=Coronavirus: As more tests become available, DC sees jump in coronavirus cases |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-all-md-malls-entertainment-venues-to-close-at-5-p-m-thursday/ |work=WTOP |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320014753/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-all-md-malls-entertainment-venues-to-close-at-5-p-m-thursday/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe same day, [[Washington Metro]] closed the [[Smithsonian station|Smithsonian]] and [[Arlington Cemetery station|Arlington Cemetery]] stations until further notice. Metro ridership reduced by 85% due to the pandemic, leading to general manager Paul Wiedefeld submitting a request to Congress for emergency funding.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Augenstein |first1=Neal |title=Coronavirus: Metro asks Congress for emergency funding after ridership drops 85% |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-metro-asks-congress-for-emergency-funding-after-ridership-drops-85/ |work=WTOP |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320014754/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-metro-asks-congress-for-emergency-funding-after-ridership-drops-85/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Mayor Bowser announced the first death related to COVID-19 in the District, a 59-year-old male, Deacon Brother John-Sebastian Laird-Hammond, [[Order of Friars Minor|OFM]], a [[Franciscan]] [[friar]] and [[permanent deacon]], a native of [[Minonk, Illinois]], with underlying medical conditions, specifically a multi-year battle with a type of [[leukemia]] who had been undergoing cancer treatments and was therefore more vulnerable to the virus.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/a-franciscan-friar-is-dcs-first-known-coronavirus-fatality-32938 | title=A Franciscan friar and deacon is DC's first known coronavirus fatality | access-date=2020-03-26 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329041046/https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/a-franciscan-friar-is-dcs-first-known-coronavirus-fatality-32938 | archive-date=2020-03-29 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Bowser tweet first death\">{{cite tweet|last=Bowser |first=Muriel |author-link=Muriel Bowser |user=MayorBowser |number=1241051533631946752 |date=2020-03-20 |title=It is with great sadness that we announce a tragic death and, on behalf of our residents, I share our love and condolences with the patient\u2019s family and friends. |access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> The number of cases rose to 77.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\nDCPS extended the school shutdown to April 24, meaning classes would be scheduled to resume on Monday, April 27. In preparation for the beginning of distance learning on March 24, the DCPS Distance Learning platform was released, publicly accessible at {{URL|https://dcps.instructure.com/courses/179580}}. Certain schools would continue to provide lunch on weekdays.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1241081893656956931|title=\ud83d\udea8UPDATE\ud83d\udea8 DCPS will be closed to all staff and students through Friday, April 24 to help mitigate the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19) in our region. Classes will resume for all students on Monday, April 27. For more info please visit: http://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus.|date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== March 21\u201322 ====\n\nOn March 21, the D.C. government, operating through the Metropolitan Police Department and the [[National Park Service]] announced several road closures around beginning on March 22, 7:00 AM to 8:00 PM, in an effort to reduce congregation of tourists around monuments during the [[National Cherry Blossom Festival]]. These crowds had not been conforming to social distancing guidelines and thus presented a possible vector for the transmission of coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Corse |first1=Alexa |title=Washington, D.C., Closes Streets to Prevent Coronavirus Transmission |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/washington-d-c-closes-streets-to-prevent-coronavirus-transmission-11584850717 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=22 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322213549/https://www.wsj.com/articles/washington-d-c-closes-streets-to-prevent-coronavirus-transmission-11584850717 |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=TRAFFIC ADVISORY: Street Closures |url=https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/traffic-advisory-street-closures?mod=article_inline |website=Metropolitan Police Department |publisher=DC.Gov |date=21 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322213607/https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/traffic-advisory-street-closures?mod=article_inline |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[District of Columbia Department of Parks and Recreation|DC Department of Parks and Recreation]] closed all of its facilities including parks, playgrounds, and athletic fields. Only dog parks remained open.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1241457230349811712|user=DCDPR|title=!!ALERT - All DPR facilities including Playgrounds + Gated Parks and Athletic Fields are CLOSED. Dog parks remain open. Stay informed http://coronavirus.dc.gov.|date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe same day, [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]] announced reduced operation from 325 routes to only 20 high-use corridors. Real-time bus data would no longer be available and drivers may bypass stops in order to observe social distancing guidelines on buses. [[WMATA]] said it hoped to restore some routes with limited operation hours soon.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Delaney |first1=Matthew |title=Coronavirus: 2nd death in DC; cases surge throughout region with more testing |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-positive-cases-continue-to-surge-transit-changes-enforce-social-distancing/ |work=WTOP |date=22 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322235143/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-positive-cases-continue-to-surge-transit-changes-enforce-social-distancing/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe number of cases as of 7:30 PM that day was 98.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\nOn March 22, the second death due to COVID-19 was reported in the District, a 65-year-old woman with underlying medical conditions.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=MayorBowser|number=1241783602830020615|title=1/ I am saddened to announce a second death related to COVID-19 in our community. The hearts and prayers of our entire city are with her family and loved ones.|date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe number of cases as of 7:00 PM that day was 116.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\n==== March 23\u201324 ====\nOn March 23, Mayor Bowser and Chief Financial Officer [[Jeffrey DeWitt]] announced that the 2019 tax filing deadlines would be pushed to July 15, instead of the upcoming April 15.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Bowser and Chief Financial Officer DeWitt Announce 2019 Tax Filings and Payment Deadline Extended to July 15, 2020 |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-and-chief-financial-officer-dewitt-announce-2019-tax-filings-and-payment |website=coronavirus.dc.gov |publisher=DC.Gov |date=23 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323215938/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-and-chief-financial-officer-dewitt-announce-2019-tax-filings-and-payment |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Mayor also urged D.C. residents to remain at home except for \"essential activities,\" clarifying that she would not be issuing a [[shelter-in-place order]] as of now.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Katz |first1=Jeffrey |last2=Austermuhle |first2=Martin |last3=Pascale |first3=Jordan |last4=Chamberlin |first4=Victoria |title=UPDATED: D.C.-Area Residents Are Being Asked To Stay In Their Homes If They Can. How Is That Going To Work? |url=https://wamu.org/story/20/03/22/what-happens-if-d-c-declares-a-shelter-in-place-your-questions-answered/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=WAMU |date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323234638/https://wamu.org/story/20/03/22/what-happens-if-d-c-declares-a-shelter-in-place-your-questions-answered/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn that day, Mayor Bowser also commissioned [[Republic Restoratives Distillery]] and [[Compass Coffee]], two locally owned companies, for the production of {{convert|2000|gal}} of [[hand sanitizer]] ({{convert|1000|gal}} each) for use by D.C. government workers and emergency responders.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1242193836014796806|user=MayorBowser|title=1/ DC Government has commissioned 2,000 gallons of hand sanitizer from @RepublicRestore and @CompassCoffeeDC (1,000 each) as part of our response to the coronavirus (COVID-19).|date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 7:00 PM that day, the number of cases was 137.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\n==== March 25 ====\nOn March 25, the third death in Washington, D.C. was a 75-year-old female with underlying health conditions.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1242969615283740673|user=mayorbowser|date=25 March 2020|title=There's a third death in DC due to coronavirus (COVID-19). The patient, a 75-year-old female, was admitted to a hospital with underlying health conditions and passed away on March 25. She tested positive for COVID-19 and was included among the District\u2019s reporting data.}}</ref>\n\n==== March 30 ====\nOn March 30, Mayor Bowser announced a [[stay-at-home order]] that would go into effect on April 1. The order stated that residents may only leave their residences to engage in essential activities, including obtaining medical care that cannot be provided through telehealth and obtaining food and essential household goods, to perform or access essential governmental functions, to work at essential businesses, to engage in essential travel and to \nengage in specific recreational activities that the order defined.<ref name=\"stay at home\">(1) {{cite web|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-issues-stay-home-order|title=Mayor Bowser Issues Stay-At-Home Order|work=News Release|date=March 30, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}<br>(2) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/coronavirus/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-054%20Stay%20at%20Home.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-054: Stay At Home Order|work=Administrative Issuance System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> \n\nAnyone found to be violating the order would be charged with a [[misdemeanor]] and subject to a $5,000 fine and/or 90 days in prison. Bowser said, \"Staying at home is the best way to flatten the curve and protect yourself, your family, and our entire community from COVID-19.\"<ref name=Franklin>{{cite news |last1=Franklin |first1=Jonathan |title=DC issues Stay-At-Home order: Here's what you can leave your house for |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/dc-stay-at-home-order-why-and-what-you-can-leave-your-house-for/65-7f0f0bf1-1cb6-4921-a4a5-bbf7ddbaa88b |work=[[WUSA (TV)|WUSA9]]|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn the same day, [[Maryland]]'s Governor [[Larry Hogan]] and [[Virginia]]'s Governor [[Ralph Northam]] issued similar stay-at-home orders (see [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maryland]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Virginia|in Virginia]]). However, the penalties for violating those orders were different from those in the District.<ref name=\"Post March 30\">{{cite web|first1=Antonio|last=Olivo|first2=Ovetta|last2=Wiggins|first3=Gregory S.|last3=Schneider|date=March 30, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/hogan-northam-coronavirus-stay-home-orders/2020/03/30/5f36e146-722f-11ea-85cb-8670579b863d_story.html|title=Hogan, Northam, Bowser order residents in Maryland, Virginia, D.C. to stay at home|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== April ===\n\n==== April 6 ====\nMayor Bowser announced a governmentwide hiring and pay freeze to ensure the District's funds are conserved.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Massimo |first1=Rick |last2=Moore |first2=Jack |last3=Constantino |first3=Abigail |title=Coronavirus update: As area cases top 8,000, DC to take more emergency action |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/04/coronavirus-update-dc-maryland-virginia-april-6/ |work=WTOP |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n==Projections==\nA number of organizations have produced models that project the trajectory of the coronavirus outbreak.A number of organizations have produced models that project the trajectory of the coronavirus outbreak.<ref>{{cite news|first1=William|last1=Wan|first2=Carolyn Y.|last2=Johnson|date=April 7, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2020/04/06/americas-most-influential-coronavirus-model-just-revised-its-estimates-downward-not-every-model-agrees/|title=America\u2019s most influential coronavirus model just revised its estimates downward. But not every model agrees.|work=Health|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020}} {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407034032/https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2020/04/06/americas-most-influential-coronavirus-model-just-revised-its-estimates-downward-not-every-model-agrees/|date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The [[Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation]] at the [[University of Washington]] in [[Seattle]] has constructed one of these (the IHME).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.healthdata.org/research-article/forecasting-covid-19-impact-hospital-bed-days-icu-days-ventilator-days-and-deaths|title=Forecasting COVID-19 impact on hospital bed-days, ICU-days, ventilator days and deaths by US state in the next 4 months|date=April 7, 2020|location=[[Seattle]], [[Washington]]|publisher=[[Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407002253/http://www.healthdata.org/research-article/forecasting-covid-19-impact-hospital-bed-days-icu-days-ventilator-days-and-deaths|archive-date=April 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Penn Medicine, a [[consortium]] of the [[Perelman School of Medicine]] and the [[University of Pennsylvania Health System]] in [[Philadelphia]], has constructed another, the COVID-19 Hospital Impact Model for Epidemics (CHIME).<ref>(1) {{cite web|first=Mackenzie|last=Bean|date=March 16, 2020|url=https://www.beckershospitalreview.com/patient-flow/penn-medicine-shares-tool-for-covid-19-capacity-planning.html|title=Penn Medicine shares tool for COVID-19 capacity planning|work=Becker's Hospital Review|publisher=Becker's Healthcare|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}<br>(2) {{cite web|url=https://penn-chime.phl.io|title=COVID-19 Hospital Impact Model for Epidemics (CHIME)|year=2020|location=[[Philadelphia]]|publisher=The Trustees of the [[University of Pennsylvania]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406135147/https://penn-chime.phl.io/|archive-date=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Among other things, the two models differ in the methods by which they calculate the effectiveness of [[social distancing]] in reducing the number of new COVID-19 infections.<ref>{{cite news|first=Fenit|last=Nirappil|date=April 3, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-peak-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/04/03/0636bc6c-75cf-11ea-87da-77a8136c1a6d_story.html|title=Coronavirus peak in D.C., Maryland, Virginia: FAQ on why models differ|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407055223/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-peak-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/04/03/0636bc6c-75cf-11ea-87da-77a8136c1a6d_story.html|archive-date=April 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation]] at the [[University of Washington]] in [[Seattle]] has constructed one of these (the IHME).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.healthdata.org/research-article/forecasting-covid-19-impact-hospital-bed-days-icu-days-ventilator-days-and-deaths|title=Forecasting COVID-19 impact on hospital bed-days, ICU-days, ventilator days and deaths by US state in the next 4 months|date=April 7, 2020|location=[[Seattle]], [[Washington]]|publisher=[[Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407002253/http://www.healthdata.org/research-article/forecasting-covid-19-impact-hospital-bed-days-icu-days-ventilator-days-and-deaths|archive-date=April 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Penn Medicine, a [[consortium]] of the [[Perelman School of Medicine]] and the [[University of Pennsylvania Health System]] in [[Philadelphia]], has constructed another, the COVID-19 Hospital Impact Model for Epidemics (CHIME).<ref>(1) {{cite web|first=Mackenzie|last=Bean|date=March 16, 2020|url=https://www.beckershospitalreview.com/patient-flow/penn-medicine-shares-tool-for-covid-19-capacity-planning.html|title=Penn Medicine shares tool for COVID-19 capacity planning|work=Becker's Hospital Review|publisher=Becker's Healthcare|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}<br>(2) {{cite web|url=https://penn-chime.phl.io|title=COVID-19 Hospital Impact Model for Epidemics (CHIME)|year=2020|location=[[Philadelphia]]|publisher=The Trustees of the [[University of Pennsylvania]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406135147/https://penn-chime.phl.io/|archive-date=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Among other things, the two models differ in the methods by which they calculate the effectiveness of [[social distancing]] in reducing the number of new COVID-19 infections.<ref name=Nirappil>{{cite news|first=Fenit|last=Nirappil|date=April 3, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-peak-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/04/03/0636bc6c-75cf-11ea-87da-77a8136c1a6d_story.html|title=Coronavirus peak in D.C., Maryland, Virginia: FAQ on why models differ|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407055223/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-peak-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/04/03/0636bc6c-75cf-11ea-87da-77a8136c1a6d_story.html|archive-date=April 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 3, the CHIME was projecting that the peak hospital impact of the COVID-19 outbreak would occur in the District at the end of June.<ref name=Nirappil/> As of April 7, the IHME was projecting that the hospital resource use due to COVID-19 had peaked in the District on April 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://covid19.healthdata.org/united-states-of-america/district-of-columbia|title=Hospital Resource Use|work=COVID-19 Projections: District of Columbia|date=April 7, 2020|location=[[Seattle]]|publisher=[[University of Washington]]: [[Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government response==\nOn March 11, Mayor Muriel Bowser declared a state of emergency for the District of Columbia. The declaration allowed Bowser to request federal disaster funds and to address price gouging. The order also gave her additional authorities, including the ordering of quarantines without court approval.<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-declares-public-health-emergency|title=Mayor Bowser Declares Public Health Emergency|work=News Release|date=March 11, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331050450/https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-declares-public-health-emergency|archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(2) {{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/politics/washington-dc-state-of-emergency-coronavirus/index.html|title=DC mayor declares state of emergency due to coronavirus|first1=Jamiel|last1=Lynch|first2=Paul|last2=LeBlanc|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311230011/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/politics/washington-dc-state-of-emergency-coronavirus/index.html|archive-date=2020-03-11|url-status=live}}<br>(3) {{Cite news|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/487112-washington-dc-declares-state-of-emergency-over-coronavirus|title=Washington, DC, declares state of emergency over coronavirus|last=Moreno|first=J. Edward|date=2020-03-11|website=TheHill|language=en|accessdate=2020-03-12}}<br>(4) {{cite news|first1=Jenna|last1=Portnoy|first2=Fenit|last2=Nirappil|first3=Darran|last3=Simon|date=March 12, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-dc-maryland-coronavirus-news-wednesday/2020/03/11/50a0d822-6342-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html|title=D.C. declares state of emergency as concerts, parades, church services are canceled|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327105804/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-dc-maryland-coronavirus-news-wednesday/2020/03/11/50a0d822-6342-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(5) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicEmergency03.11.20.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-045: Declaration of Public Emergency: Coronavirus (COVID-19)|date=March 20, 2020|work=Administrative Infomation System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329201523/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicEmergency03.11.20.pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(6) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicHealthEmergency03.11.20.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-046: Declaration of Public Emergency: Coronavirus (COVID-19)|date=March 20, 2020|work=Administrative Infomation System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329201521/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicHealthEmergency03.11.20.pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, [[District of Columbia Public Schools]] (DCPS) shut down schools from March 16 to March 31. March 16 was reserved for professional development for teachers in preparation for the implementation of [[distance learning]]. The April Spring Break period was moved to March 17 to March 23, after which classes were set to resume online. DCPS-sponsored out-of-state travel for students was suspended until May 1 and staff travel was restricted. During the closure, several schools were set to offer meals to students from 10 am to 2 pm on weekdays.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) Updates |url=https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus |website=District of Columbia Public Schools |publisher=DC.Gov |accessdate=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313221000/https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, the District government suspended on-site bar and restaurant service and shut down movie theaters and gyms. Restaurants could still offer food for carryout and delivery, but customers could not dine in.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/03/16/2362519a-6777-11ea-abef-020f086a3fab_story.html |title=Second Va. man dies, D.C., Maryland restaurants, bars close as toll passes 100 |work=[[Washington Post]] |date=2020-03-16 |accessdate=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316234751/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/03/16/2362519a-6777-11ea-abef-020f086a3fab_story.html |archive-date=2020-03-16 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Mayor Bowser issued an order that prohibited mass gatherings of 50 or more people. The order also prohibited table service and service to standing customers at restaurants, bars and multi-purpose facilities, including seated, fast food and fast casual restaurants. Those businesses could only operate for take-out, \"grab-and-go\" and delivery operations.<ref name=\"March 20 order\">(1) {{cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor\u2019s-order-2020-051-prohibition-mass-gatherings-during-public-health-emergency|title=Prohibition on Mass Gatherings During Public Health Emergency - Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=News Release|date=March 20, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330150520/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor%E2%80%99s-order-2020-051-prohibition-mass-gatherings-during-public-health-emergency|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(2) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/u23/Mayor%60s%20Order%202020-51.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-051: Prohibition on Mass Gatherings During Public Health Emergency - Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 20, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330201113/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/u23/Mayor%60s%20Order%202020-51.pdf|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThe Mayor's March 20 order also required nightclubs, health clubs, health spas, massage parlors and theaters to continue their suspension of operations, which the District's government had initially ordered on March 17. The order further closed to the public all facilities that the District's Department of Recreation operated, including playgrounds, parks and athletic fields.<ref name=\"March 20 order\"/>\n\nThe District of Columbia Medical Reserve Corps (DC MRC), a volunteer organization under the [[District of Columbia Department of Health]], was mobilized to aid emergency workers in responding to the coronavirus pandemic throughout D.C. On March 21, Mayor Bowser called for more volunteers to join the task force.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Bowser Encourages Volunteers to Join the DC Medical Reserve Corps |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-encourages-volunteers-join-dc-medical-reserve-corps |website=coronavirus.dc.gov |publisher=DC.Gov |date=21 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323215101/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-encourages-volunteers-join-dc-medical-reserve-corps |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, Mayor Bowser issued an order \"to temporarily cease all non-essential business activities, including tour guides and touring services; gyms, health clubs, spas, and massage establishments; theaters, auditoriums, and other places of large gatherings; nightclubs; hair, nail, and tanning salons and barbershops; tattoo parlors; sales not involved in essential services; retail clothing stores; and professional services not devoted to assisting essential business operations.\"<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-orders-closure-non-essential-businesses|title=New Mayor\u2019s Order Requires Temporary Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibits Gatherings of Ten or More People|work=News Release|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330200918/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-orders-closure-non-essential-businesses|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}} <br>(2) {{cite news|last=Barnes|first=Sophia|url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-closes-nonessential-businesses-dmv-latest-tuesday-march-23-whats-closed-washington/2252010/|title=DC Closes Nonessential Businesses, DMV Centers to Stop Coronavirus|date=March 25, 2020|work=Coronavirus|publisher=[[WRC-TV|NBC4 Washington]]|accessdate=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327133947/https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-closes-nonessential-businesses-dmv-latest-tuesday-march-23-whats-closed-washington/2252010/|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(3) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|title=Mayor\u2019s Order 2020-053: Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibition on Large Gatherings During Public Health Emergency for the 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329184808/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBowser's March 24 order defined \"Construction and Building Trades\" as \"essential businesses\", but did not define private construction projects themselves as being \"essential\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|title=Mayor\u2019s Order 2020-053: Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibition on Large Gatherings During Public Health Emergency for the 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329184808/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> However, [[The Washington Post]] reported on March 28 that the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia had designated construction as \"essential,\" along with hospitals, grocery stores, banks and several other types of businesses. The ''Post'' reported that each of these jurisdictions had allowed private construction, including home building and commercial developments, to continue.<ref name=Lazo>{{cite news|first1=Luz|last1=Lazo|first2=Katherine|last2=Shaver|date=March 28, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/work-on-regions-big-projects-continues-amid-coronavirus-with-construction-an-essential-business/2020/03/28/e4af8b38-6dfd-11ea-a3ec-70d7479d83f0_story.html|title=Work on region\u2019s big projects continues amid coronavirus, with construction an \u2018essential\u2019 business|work=Transportation|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401022830/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/work-on-regions-big-projects-continues-amid-coronavirus-with-construction-an-essential-business/2020/03/28/e4af8b38-6dfd-11ea-a3ec-70d7479d83f0_story.html|archive-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  \n\nThe ''Post'' reported that John Falcicchio, Bowser's chief of staff, had stated that the District, Maryland and Virginia had agreed to follow the federal guidance declaring construction to be essential work. However, the ''Post'' reported that several states, including Pennsylvania and Vermont, had suspended or prohibited all construction work (except for emergencies) as unnecessary during a public health crisis. The Post further reported that the State of Washington's transportation department had suspended work on nearly all of its projects and that Washington's governor had clarified his [[Stay-at-home order|stay-at-home]] order to state that commercial and residential construction were generally prohibited \"because construction is not considered to be an essential activity.\"<ref name=Lazo/>\n\nThe [[United States Department of Homeland Security]]'s March 28 guidance on essential critical infrastructure lists as \"essential\" the construction of residential/shelter facilities and services, energy-related facilities, communications and information technology, public works including the  construction of critical or strategic infrastructure and infrastructure that is temporarily required to support COVID-19 response, is for certain other types of community- or government-based operations, or is otherwise critical, strategic, or essential. The guidance does not contain any such listings for other types of construction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cisa.gov/sites/default/files/publications/CISA_Guidance_on_the_Essential_Critical_Infrastructure_Workforce_Version_2.0_Updated.pdf|title=Guidance on the Essential Critical Infrastructure Workforce: Ensuring Community and National Resilience in COVID-19 Response|date=March 28, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[United States Department of Homeland Security]]: [[Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency]]: Office of the Director|accessdate=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402033910/https://www.cisa.gov/sites/default/files/publications/CISA_Guidance_on_the_Essential_Critical_Infrastructure_Workforce_Version_2.0_Updated.pdf|archive-date=April 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, Bowser announced a stay-at-home order that would go into effect on April 1. The order stated that residents may only leave their residences to engage in essential activities, including obtaining medical care that cannot be provided through telehealth and obtaining food and essential household goods, to perform or access essential governmental functions, to work at essential businesses, to engage in essential travel and to engage in specific recreational activities that the order defined.<ref name=\"stay at home\"/><ref name=\"Post March 30\"/> Anyone found to be violating the order would be charged with a [[misdemeanor]] and subject to a $5,000 fine and/or 90 days in prison.<ref name=Franklin/>\n\n==Impact on sports==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nThe pandemic affected several sports in the district. On March 12, [[Major League Baseball]] cancelled the remainder of [[spring training]], and on March 16, they announced that the season will be postponed indefinitely, after the recommendations from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] to restrict events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, affecting the [[2020 Washington Nationals season|Washington Nationals]].<ref name=\"mlb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |title=Opening of regular season to be pushed back |first=Mark |last=Feinsand |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317025811/https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Washington Wizards season|Washington Wizards]].<ref name=nba>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=March 13, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313004850/https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the [[National Hockey League]], the season was suspended for an indefinite amount of time, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Washington Capitals season|Washington Capitals]].<ref name=nhl>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314025848/https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 |date=2020-03-14 }} NHL, March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities districtwide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312213051/http://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships |date=2020-03-12 }} NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318182102/https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html |date=2020-03-18 }} MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maryland]] \u2013 for impact on Maryland counties in the Washington metropolitan area\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Virginia]] \u2013 for impact on Virginia counties in the Washington metropolitan area\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://coronavirus.dc.gov/ Coronavirus information] from the [[Government of the District of Columbia]]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by city|Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:2020 in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Washington, D.C., United States}}\n{{Current event|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Washington, D.C.\n| width           = \n| image           = National Gallery of Art (49656625722).jpg\n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = Visitors wearing masks in the [[National Gallery of Art]], the day before it closed as a precaution against COVID-19\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n| first_case      = March 7, 2020\n| arrival_date    = \n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 902\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| deaths          = 21\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://coronavirus.dc.gov/}}\n}}\n\nThe first cases of [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the global pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in [[Washington, D.C.]] were reported on March 7, 2020. {{As of|2020|04|02|df=US}}, there are 902 confirmed cases and 21 deaths in Washington, D.C. alone, with other cases in the surrounding counties of the [[Washington metropolitan area]].<ref name=\"dcgovdata\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Data |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/page/coronavirus-data |website=DC.Gov |publisher=Government of the District of Columbia |accessdate=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323134324/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/page/coronavirus-data |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Washington, D.C. medical cases chart}}\n\n==Timeline==\n\n=== February ===\nMayor [[Muriel Bowser]] signed an executive order that began to prepare Washington D.C. for coronavirus impacts on February 28. It was announced in the executive order that the District's Emergency Operations Center (EOC) would be activated on March 2, 2020 at 9:00&nbsp;a.m. to begin to \"coordinate inter-agency information sharing and identify logistical needs for critical incident responses.\" It was also announced that the Washington D.C. Department of Health and the Homeland Security and Emergency Management Agency would be responsible for the response planning for COVID-19.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayors-order-district-government-preparations-coronavirus|title=Mayor's Order: District Government Preparations for the Coronavirus {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329193351/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayors-order-district-government-preparations-coronavirus|archive-date=2020-03-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n\n==== March 1\u20134 ====\nOn March 2 at 9:00&nbsp;a.m., the D.C. Emergency Operations Center was activated at an Enhanced Watch status, as per the executive order signed on February 28.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn March 3, Mayor Bowser, the D.C. Department of Health, and the D.C. Homeland Security and Emergency Management Agency held a public briefing on the coronavirus and the District's \"monitoring, preparation, and response\" to it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-hold-briefing-district%E2%80%99s-coronavirus-monitoring-preparation-and-response|title=Mayor Bowser to Hold Briefing on the District's Coronavirus Monitoring, Preparation, and Response {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308004155/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-hold-briefing-district%E2%80%99s-coronavirus-monitoring-preparation-and-response|archive-date=2020-03-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====March 5\u20137====\nOn March 7, the first two cases of COVID-19 in Washington, D.C. were confirmed. The first case was a [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|rector]] at [[Christ Church (Georgetown, Washington, D.C.)|Christ Church Georgetown]] who had not traveled outside the United States recently or had contact with another infected coronavirus patient. He participated in church services on February 23 and March 1. The rector felt better initially, but his condition deteriorated to the point of hospitalization, when it was confirmed he had coronavirus. After it was confirmed the rector contracted the virus, the church cancelled services indefinitely. The second case was a [[Nigeria]]n national who traveled to D.C. and went to a hospital in [[Maryland]] for treatment. Although the second man was being treated at a Maryland hospital, he was counted as the District's second case by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC).<ref>{{cite news |title=Georgetown Church Rector, Traveler Diagnosed as DC's First 2 Coronavirus Cases |url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-has-first-presumptive-coronavirus-case/2234068/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=NBC4 Washington |date=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316154326/https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-has-first-presumptive-coronavirus-case/2234068/ |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|user=MayorBowser|number=1236422174958895104|title=Late this afternoon, testing at the Public Health Lab at the DC Department of Forensic Sciences yielded its first presumptive positive coronavirus (COVID-19) case. Join me live at 7:30 p.m. for a briefing at the John A. Wilson Building.|date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====March 8\u201310====\nOn March 9, [[School Without Walls (Washington, D.C.)|School Without Walls]], a public school in [[Foggy Bottom]], was closed by [[District of Columbia Public Schools]] (DCPS) for a full-day deep cleaning and disinfecting by a third-party contractor after an employee was exposed to COVID-19 the week before. The employee tested negative and entered a two-week quarantine. DCPS chancellor Lewis Ferebee announced the closing over Twitter the previous day.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1236819215920832513|date=8 Mar 2020|title=Tomorrow - 3/9 - School Without Walls High School will be closed. DCPS is conducting a deep cleaning and disinfecting of the building following an employee being exposed to COVID-19. Test results were negative, and there is no immediate risk to students and staff. cc: @SWWHSA}}</ref>\n\nThree more coronavirus cases in D.C. were confirmed the night of March 9, including an attendee of Christ Church Georgetown. D.C. officials recommended a two-week self-quarantine per CDC guidelines for anyone who attended Christ Church on February 24 or between February 28 and March 3. At that time, $1.5 million had been allocated to the pandemic response by the D.C. government.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gelman |first1=Scott |last2=Alvarez |first2=Alejandro |title=16 coronavirus cases confirmed in DC, Md. and Va. |url=https://wtop.com/local/2020/03/bowser-hogan-to-deliver-update-on-coronavirus-as-dc-area-officials-investigate-9-cases/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=WTOP |date=9 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313023822/https://wtop.com/local/2020/03/bowser-hogan-to-deliver-update-on-coronavirus-as-dc-area-officials-investigate-9-cases/ |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, [[George Washington University]] announced classes will be moved online after spring break, starting on March 23 and continuing until at least April 5. In addition, all residential students were expected to no longer be living on campus beginning March 21. It was stated that an opening date would not be announced until the end of the instructional continuity period when a decision for the rest of the semester would be made.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fox5dc.com/news/george-washington-university-moving-to-online-classes-after-spring-break|title=George Washington University moving to online classes after spring break|date=2020-03-10|website=Fox 5 DC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311103004/https://www.fox5dc.com/news/george-washington-university-moving-to-online-classes-after-spring-break|archive-date=2020-03-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.georgetown.edu/coronavirus/|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) Resource Center|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312130006/https://www.georgetown.edu/coronavirus/|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAlso on March 10, [[Georgetown Day School]], a private school, closed indefinitely and began a deep clean citing concerns about community members affiliated with [[Christ Church (Georgetown, Washington, D.C.)|Christ Church Georgetown]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Volou |first1=Khalida |title=DC school closed due to coronavirus exposure linked to Christ Church Georgetown |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-day-school-closed-tuesday-due-to-coronavirus/65-e374b3e9-a496-42ed-9043-d4bd0b9c45c9 |agency=WUSA9 |date=10 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311195837/https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-day-school-closed-tuesday-due-to-coronavirus/65-e374b3e9-a496-42ed-9043-d4bd0b9c45c9 |archive-date=11 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====March 11\u201314====\nOn March 11, [[Maria Cantwell]], a U.S. senator from Washington state, closed her D.C. office due to one of her aides testing positive for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/politics-government/article241118946.html|title=Aide to Maria Cantwell tests positive for coronavirus. Senator closes her D.C. office|last=Lightman|first=David|website=thenewstribune|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313030257/https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/politics-government/article241118946.html|archive-date=2020-03-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Georgetown University]] announced that it would be moving to virtual learning entirely beginning on March 16, and while campus would remain open and key services would remain accessible the university strongly suggested that students return to their homes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khan |first1=Saliqa |title=Georgetown University moves to virtual learning amid coronavirus concerns |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-university-moves-to-virtual-learning-amid-coronavirus-concerns/65-60c60f1b-9838-4090-80e9-dffa49d92737 |work=WUSA9 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318192012/https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-university-moves-to-virtual-learning-amid-coronavirus-concerns/65-60c60f1b-9838-4090-80e9-dffa49d92737 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, the [[United States Capitol]], the [[White House]], and the [[United States Supreme Court Building]] closed to most of the public until April after several offices closed and multiple lawmakers went into precautionary quarantines.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zengerle |first1=Patricia |last2=Heavey |first2=Susan |title=UPDATE 5-U.S. federal buildings put away the welcome mat as coronavirus hits |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-usa-capitol/update-5-us-federal-buildings-put-away-the-welcome-mat-as-coronavirus-hits-idUSL1N2B50S4 |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, [[District of Columbia Public Schools|DCPS]] announced that they will cancel classes until April 1, implementing online distance learning.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1238430012417748993|date=13 March 2020|title=DCPS will modify operations from Monday, March 16 through Tuesday, March 31 to help limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19) in our region. For more info about the closure schedule, meal locations for students & distance learning details, please visit: https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus}}</ref> Also on March 13, the [[Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]] (WMATA) escalated its operations to level 3 of its pandemic flu plan, announcing that service on the [[Washington Metro]] would be reduced to one train every 12 minutes from Monday to Saturday and one train every 15 minutes on Sunday beginning on March 17. In addition, [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]] service would change to a Saturday supplemental schedule on weekdays beginning on March 17.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmata.com/service/status/details/COVID-19.cfm#main-content|title=Metro takes additional steps, coordinates with public health authorities on COVID-19 {{!}} WMATA|website=wmata.com|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314155101/https://wmata.com/service/status/details/COVID-19.cfm#main-content|archive-date=2020-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/transportation/2020/03/13/metro-reduces-transit-service-response-coronavirus/|title=Metro to reduce transit service in response to the coronavirus outbreak|last=George|first=Justin|date=13 March 2020|website=Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314134151/https://www.washingtonpost.com/transportation/2020/03/13/metro-reduces-transit-service-response-coronavirus/|archive-date=14 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMayor [[Muriel Bowser]] held a press conference, announcing that gatherings of people over 60 years of age or with preexisting health issues would be limited to 10 people. The restriction would not apply to residences, schools, or places of work. For populations not at-risk the government promoted [[social distancing]] measures to limit the spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vitka |first1=Will |last2=Bonk |first2=Valerie |title=Trump declares national emergency; DC bans mass gatherings |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-dc-area/ |work=WTOP |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314183154/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-dc-area/ |archive-date=14 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, Mayor Bowser issued a statement confirming 6 more positive cases in Washington, D.C., bringing the total number of cases up to 16.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-14|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 14 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316100728/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-14|archive-date=2020-03-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====March 15\u201316====\nOn March 15, Bowser's office announced one more positive case in Washington D.C., bringing the total cumulative number of cases to 17. The patient in this case is a 38-year-old woman who came into contact with another case.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-15|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 15|work=Government of the District of Columbia|accessdate=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324170918/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-15|archive-date=2020-03-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Hill Restaurant Group (HRG) said on March 16 they would comply would restrictions on bars and restaurants ordered by Mayor Bowser on March 15. Tom Johnson, the managing director of the group, had earlier said he would ignore the order, saying it would force his company into bankruptcy.<ref>[https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/487826-dc-restaurant-group-says-it-will-comply-with-restrictions-after-mayor DC restaurant group says it will comply with restrictions after mayor's warning] The Hill, 16 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nOn the evening of March 16, Mayor Bowser's office released an update that confirmed five more positive cases of coronavirus in the District. The patients involved were a 23-year-old man, a 42-year-old woman with a history of travel to Europe, a 54-year-old woman, a 54-year-old man, and a 56-year-old man. These five cases brought the cumulative number of cases in D.C. to 22.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-16|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 16 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317204518/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-16|archive-date=2020-03-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== March 17\u201318 ====\nLate on March 17, Mayor Bowser's office announced the confirmation of nine more positive cases in the District, bringing the total number of positive cases to 31. The patients were all male and between the ages of 23 and 61. The 23-year-old patient was confirmed to have attended the [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC) in [[National Harbor, Maryland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-17|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 17 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319072119/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-17|archive-date=2020-03-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, at least 8 more cases were found, including a [[District of Columbia Fire and Emergency Medical Services Department|DC FEMS]] employee (leading to a quarantine of 73 firefighters), a [[U.S. marshal]] at the [[Superior Court of the District of Columbia]], and an undergraduate student at the George Washington University who lives off-campus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moore |first1=Jack |title=Coronavirus: Jump in new cases around region; DC first responder, US Marshal test positive |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-updates-dc-maryland-virginia/ |work=WTOP |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319002447/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-updates-dc-maryland-virginia/ |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Metropolitan Police Department of the District of Columbia]] announced new [[social distancing]] precautions in dealing with callers reporting flu-like symptoms as well as changes to police protocol for citations and warning notices in light of the restriction of certain services in the D.C. government.<ref>{{cite web |title=Metropolitan Police Department Operational Adjustments During COVID-19 |url=https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/metropolitan-police-department-operational-adjustments-during-covid-19 |website=Metropolitan Police Department |publisher=DC.Gov |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319002500/https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/metropolitan-police-department-operational-adjustments-during-covid-19 |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== March 19\u201320 ====\nAs of March 19, the number of confirmed cases sharply jumped to 71 as the supply of tests was expanded, an increase of 32 over one day.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1240791217647976448|user=MayorBowser|title=As of 8:00 p.m. on Thursday, March 19, the District\u2019s coronavirus (COVID-19) data includes 32 new positive cases, bringing the District\u2019s overall positive case total to 71 individuals. For more information visit:|date=19 March 2020}}</ref> This includes two more DC FEMS members and an eight-year-old.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Massimo |first1=Rick |title=Coronavirus: As more tests become available, DC sees jump in coronavirus cases |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-all-md-malls-entertainment-venues-to-close-at-5-p-m-thursday/ |work=WTOP |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320014753/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-all-md-malls-entertainment-venues-to-close-at-5-p-m-thursday/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe same day, [[Washington Metro]] closed the [[Smithsonian station|Smithsonian]] and [[Arlington Cemetery station|Arlington Cemetery]] stations until further notice. Metro ridership reduced by 85% due to the pandemic, leading to general manager Paul Wiedefeld submitting a request to Congress for emergency funding.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Augenstein |first1=Neal |title=Coronavirus: Metro asks Congress for emergency funding after ridership drops 85% |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-metro-asks-congress-for-emergency-funding-after-ridership-drops-85/ |work=WTOP |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320014754/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-metro-asks-congress-for-emergency-funding-after-ridership-drops-85/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Mayor Bowser announced the first death related to COVID-19 in the District, a 59-year-old male, Deacon Brother John-Sebastian Laird-Hammond, [[Order of Friars Minor|OFM]], a [[Franciscan]] [[friar]] and [[permanent deacon]], a native of [[Minonk, Illinois]], with underlying medical conditions, specifically a multi-year battle with a type of [[leukemia]] who had been undergoing cancer treatments and was therefore more vulnerable to the virus.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/a-franciscan-friar-is-dcs-first-known-coronavirus-fatality-32938 | title=A Franciscan friar and deacon is DC's first known coronavirus fatality | access-date=2020-03-26 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329041046/https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/a-franciscan-friar-is-dcs-first-known-coronavirus-fatality-32938 | archive-date=2020-03-29 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Bowser tweet first death\">{{cite tweet|last=Bowser |first=Muriel |author-link=Muriel Bowser |user=MayorBowser |number=1241051533631946752 |date=2020-03-20 |title=It is with great sadness that we announce a tragic death and, on behalf of our residents, I share our love and condolences with the patient\u2019s family and friends. |access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> The number of cases rose to 77.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\nDCPS extended the school shutdown to April 24, meaning classes would be scheduled to resume on Monday, April 27. In preparation for the beginning of distance learning on March 24, the DCPS Distance Learning platform was released, publicly accessible at {{URL|https://dcps.instructure.com/courses/179580}}. Certain schools would continue to provide lunch on weekdays.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1241081893656956931|title=\ud83d\udea8UPDATE\ud83d\udea8 DCPS will be closed to all staff and students through Friday, April 24 to help mitigate the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19) in our region. Classes will resume for all students on Monday, April 27. For more info please visit: http://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus.|date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== March 21\u201322 ====\n\nOn March 21, the D.C. government, operating through the Metropolitan Police Department and the [[National Park Service]] announced several road closures around beginning on March 22, 7:00 AM to 8:00 PM, in an effort to reduce congregation of tourists around monuments during the [[National Cherry Blossom Festival]]. These crowds had not been conforming to social distancing guidelines and thus presented a possible vector for the transmission of coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Corse |first1=Alexa |title=Washington, D.C., Closes Streets to Prevent Coronavirus Transmission |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/washington-d-c-closes-streets-to-prevent-coronavirus-transmission-11584850717 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=22 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322213549/https://www.wsj.com/articles/washington-d-c-closes-streets-to-prevent-coronavirus-transmission-11584850717 |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=TRAFFIC ADVISORY: Street Closures |url=https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/traffic-advisory-street-closures?mod=article_inline |website=Metropolitan Police Department |publisher=DC.Gov |date=21 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322213607/https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/traffic-advisory-street-closures?mod=article_inline |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[District of Columbia Department of Parks and Recreation|DC Department of Parks and Recreation]] closed all of its facilities including parks, playgrounds, and athletic fields. Only dog parks remained open.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1241457230349811712|user=DCDPR|title=!!ALERT - All DPR facilities including Playgrounds + Gated Parks and Athletic Fields are CLOSED. Dog parks remain open. Stay informed http://coronavirus.dc.gov.|date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe same day, [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]] announced reduced operation from 325 routes to only 20 high-use corridors. Real-time bus data would no longer be available and drivers may bypass stops in order to observe social distancing guidelines on buses. [[WMATA]] said it hoped to restore some routes with limited operation hours soon.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Delaney |first1=Matthew |title=Coronavirus: 2nd death in DC; cases surge throughout region with more testing |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-positive-cases-continue-to-surge-transit-changes-enforce-social-distancing/ |work=WTOP |date=22 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322235143/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-positive-cases-continue-to-surge-transit-changes-enforce-social-distancing/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe number of cases as of 7:30 PM that day was 98.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\nOn March 22, the second death due to COVID-19 was reported in the District, a 65-year-old woman with underlying medical conditions.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=MayorBowser|number=1241783602830020615|title=1/ I am saddened to announce a second death related to COVID-19 in our community. The hearts and prayers of our entire city are with her family and loved ones.|date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe number of cases as of 7:00 PM that day was 116.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\n==== March 23\u201324 ====\nOn March 23, Mayor Bowser and Chief Financial Officer [[Jeffrey DeWitt]] announced that the 2019 tax filing deadlines would be pushed to July 15, instead of the upcoming April 15.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Bowser and Chief Financial Officer DeWitt Announce 2019 Tax Filings and Payment Deadline Extended to July 15, 2020 |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-and-chief-financial-officer-dewitt-announce-2019-tax-filings-and-payment |website=coronavirus.dc.gov |publisher=DC.Gov |date=23 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323215938/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-and-chief-financial-officer-dewitt-announce-2019-tax-filings-and-payment |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Mayor also urged D.C. residents to remain at home except for \"essential activities,\" clarifying that she would not be issuing a [[shelter-in-place order]] as of now.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Katz |first1=Jeffrey |last2=Austermuhle |first2=Martin |last3=Pascale |first3=Jordan |last4=Chamberlin |first4=Victoria |title=UPDATED: D.C.-Area Residents Are Being Asked To Stay In Their Homes If They Can. How Is That Going To Work? |url=https://wamu.org/story/20/03/22/what-happens-if-d-c-declares-a-shelter-in-place-your-questions-answered/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=WAMU |date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323234638/https://wamu.org/story/20/03/22/what-happens-if-d-c-declares-a-shelter-in-place-your-questions-answered/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn that day, Mayor Bowser also commissioned [[Republic Restoratives Distillery]] and [[Compass Coffee]], two locally owned companies, for the production of {{convert|2000|gal}} of [[hand sanitizer]] ({{convert|1000|gal}} each) for use by D.C. government workers and emergency responders.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1242193836014796806|user=MayorBowser|title=1/ DC Government has commissioned 2,000 gallons of hand sanitizer from @RepublicRestore and @CompassCoffeeDC (1,000 each) as part of our response to the coronavirus (COVID-19).|date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 7:00 PM that day, the number of cases was 137.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\n==== March 25 ====\nOn March 25, the third death in Washington, D.C. was a 75-year-old female with underlying health conditions.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1242969615283740673|user=mayorbowser|date=25 March 2020|title=There's a third death in DC due to coronavirus (COVID-19). The patient, a 75-year-old female, was admitted to a hospital with underlying health conditions and passed away on March 25. She tested positive for COVID-19 and was included among the District\u2019s reporting data.}}</ref>\n\n==== March 30 ====\nOn March 30, Mayor Bowser announced a [[stay-at-home order]] that would go into effect on April 1. The order stated that residents may only leave their residences to engage in essential activities, including obtaining medical care that cannot be provided through telehealth and obtaining food and essential household goods, to perform or access essential governmental functions, to work at essential businesses, to engage in essential travel and to \nengage in specific recreational activities that the order defined.<ref name=\"stay at home\">(1) {{cite web|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-issues-stay-home-order|title=Mayor Bowser Issues Stay-At-Home Order|work=News Release|date=March 30, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}<br>(2) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/coronavirus/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-054%20Stay%20at%20Home.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-054: Stay At Home Order|work=Administrative Issuance System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> \n\nAnyone found to be violating the order would be charged with a [[misdemeanor]] and subject to a $5,000 fine and/or 90 days in prison. Bowser said, \"Staying at home is the best way to flatten the curve and protect yourself, your family, and our entire community from COVID-19.\"<ref name=Franklin>{{cite news |last1=Franklin |first1=Jonathan |title=DC issues Stay-At-Home order: Here's what you can leave your house for |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/dc-stay-at-home-order-why-and-what-you-can-leave-your-house-for/65-7f0f0bf1-1cb6-4921-a4a5-bbf7ddbaa88b |work=[[WUSA (TV)|WUSA9]]|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn the same day, [[Maryland]]'s Governor [[Larry Hogan]] and [[Virginia]]'s Governor [[Ralph Northam]] issued similar stay-at-home orders (see [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maryland]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Virginia|in Virginia]]). However, the penalties for violating those orders were different from those in the District.<ref name=\"Post March 30\">{{cite web|first1=Antonio|last=Olivo|first2=Ovetta|last2=Wiggins|first3=Gregory S.|last3=Schneider|date=March 30, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/hogan-northam-coronavirus-stay-home-orders/2020/03/30/5f36e146-722f-11ea-85cb-8670579b863d_story.html|title=Hogan, Northam, Bowser order residents in Maryland, Virginia, D.C. to stay at home|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== April ===\n\n==== April 6 ====\nMayor Bowser announced a governmentwide hiring and pay freeze to ensure the District's funds are conserved.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Massimo |first1=Rick |last2=Moore |first2=Jack |last3=Constantino |first3=Abigail |title=Coronavirus update: As area cases top 8,000, DC to take more emergency action |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/04/coronavirus-update-dc-maryland-virginia-april-6/ |work=WTOP |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n==Projections==\nA number of organizations have produced models that project the trajectory of the coronavirus outbreak.A number of organizations have produced models that project the trajectory of the coronavirus outbreak.<ref>{{cite news|first1=William|last1=Wan|first2=Carolyn Y.|last2=Johnson|date=April 7, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2020/04/06/americas-most-influential-coronavirus-model-just-revised-its-estimates-downward-not-every-model-agrees/|title=America\u2019s most influential coronavirus model just revised its estimates downward. But not every model agrees.|work=Health|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020}} {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407034032/https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2020/04/06/americas-most-influential-coronavirus-model-just-revised-its-estimates-downward-not-every-model-agrees/|date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The [[Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation]] at the [[University of Washington]] in [[Seattle]] has constructed one of these (the IHME).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.healthdata.org/research-article/forecasting-covid-19-impact-hospital-bed-days-icu-days-ventilator-days-and-deaths|title=Forecasting COVID-19 impact on hospital bed-days, ICU-days, ventilator days and deaths by US state in the next 4 months|date=April 7, 2020|location=[[Seattle]], [[Washington]]|publisher=[[Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407002253/http://www.healthdata.org/research-article/forecasting-covid-19-impact-hospital-bed-days-icu-days-ventilator-days-and-deaths|archive-date=April 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Penn Medicine, a [[consortium]] of the [[Perelman School of Medicine]] and the [[University of Pennsylvania Health System]] in [[Philadelphia]], has constructed another, the COVID-19 Hospital Impact Model for Epidemics (CHIME).<ref>(1) {{cite web|first=Mackenzie|last=Bean|date=March 16, 2020|url=https://www.beckershospitalreview.com/patient-flow/penn-medicine-shares-tool-for-covid-19-capacity-planning.html|title=Penn Medicine shares tool for COVID-19 capacity planning|work=Becker's Hospital Review|publisher=Becker's Healthcare|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}<br>(2) {{cite web|url=https://penn-chime.phl.io|title=COVID-19 Hospital Impact Model for Epidemics (CHIME)|year=2020|location=[[Philadelphia]]|publisher=The Trustees of the [[University of Pennsylvania]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406135147/https://penn-chime.phl.io/|archive-date=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Among other things, the two models differ in the methods by which they calculate the effectiveness of [[social distancing]] in reducing the number of new COVID-19 infections.<ref>{{cite news|first=Fenit|last=Nirappil|date=April 3, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-peak-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/04/03/0636bc6c-75cf-11ea-87da-77a8136c1a6d_story.html|title=Coronavirus peak in D.C., Maryland, Virginia: FAQ on why models differ|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407055223/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-peak-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/04/03/0636bc6c-75cf-11ea-87da-77a8136c1a6d_story.html|archive-date=April 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n The [[Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation]] at the [[University of Washington]] in [[Seattle]] has constructed one of these (the IHME).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.healthdata.org/research-article/forecasting-covid-19-impact-hospital-bed-days-icu-days-ventilator-days-and-deaths|title=Forecasting COVID-19 impact on hospital bed-days, ICU-days, ventilator days and deaths by US state in the next 4 months|date=April 7, 2020|location=[[Seattle]], [[Washington]]|publisher=[[Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407002253/http://www.healthdata.org/research-article/forecasting-covid-19-impact-hospital-bed-days-icu-days-ventilator-days-and-deaths|archive-date=April 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Penn Medicine, a [[consortium]] of the [[Perelman School of Medicine]] and the [[University of Pennsylvania Health System]] in [[Philadelphia]], has constructed another, the COVID-19 Hospital Impact Model for Epidemics (CHIME).<ref>(1) {{cite web|first=Mackenzie|last=Bean|date=March 16, 2020|url=https://www.beckershospitalreview.com/patient-flow/penn-medicine-shares-tool-for-covid-19-capacity-planning.html|title=Penn Medicine shares tool for COVID-19 capacity planning|work=Becker's Hospital Review|publisher=Becker's Healthcare|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}<br>(2) {{cite web|url=https://penn-chime.phl.io|title=COVID-19 Hospital Impact Model for Epidemics (CHIME)|year=2020|location=[[Philadelphia]]|publisher=The Trustees of the [[University of Pennsylvania]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406135147/https://penn-chime.phl.io/|archive-date=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Among other things, the two models differ in the methods by which they calculate the effectiveness of [[social distancing]] in reducing the number of new COVID-19 infections.<ref name=Nirappil>{{cite news|first=Fenit|last=Nirappil|date=April 3, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-peak-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/04/03/0636bc6c-75cf-11ea-87da-77a8136c1a6d_story.html|title=Coronavirus peak in D.C., Maryland, Virginia: FAQ on why models differ|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407055223/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-peak-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/04/03/0636bc6c-75cf-11ea-87da-77a8136c1a6d_story.html|archive-date=April 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 3, the CHIME was projecting that the peak hospital impact of the COVID-19 outbreak would occur in the District at the end of June.<ref name=Nirappil/> As of April 7, the IHME was projecting that the hospital resource use due to COVID-19 had peaked in the District on April 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://covid19.healthdata.org/united-states-of-america/district-of-columbia|title=Hospital Resource Use|work=COVID-19 Projections: District of Columbia|date=April 7, 2020|location=[[Seattle]]|publisher=[[University of Washington]]: [[Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government response==\nOn March 11, Mayor Muriel Bowser declared a state of emergency for the District of Columbia. The declaration allowed Bowser to request federal disaster funds and to address price gouging. The order also gave her additional authorities, including the ordering of quarantines without court approval.<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-declares-public-health-emergency|title=Mayor Bowser Declares Public Health Emergency|work=News Release|date=March 11, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331050450/https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-declares-public-health-emergency|archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(2) {{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/politics/washington-dc-state-of-emergency-coronavirus/index.html|title=DC mayor declares state of emergency due to coronavirus|first1=Jamiel|last1=Lynch|first2=Paul|last2=LeBlanc|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311230011/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/politics/washington-dc-state-of-emergency-coronavirus/index.html|archive-date=2020-03-11|url-status=live}}<br>(3) {{Cite news|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/487112-washington-dc-declares-state-of-emergency-over-coronavirus|title=Washington, DC, declares state of emergency over coronavirus|last=Moreno|first=J. Edward|date=2020-03-11|website=TheHill|language=en|accessdate=2020-03-12}}<br>(4) {{cite news|first1=Jenna|last1=Portnoy|first2=Fenit|last2=Nirappil|first3=Darran|last3=Simon|date=March 12, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-dc-maryland-coronavirus-news-wednesday/2020/03/11/50a0d822-6342-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html|title=D.C. declares state of emergency as concerts, parades, church services are canceled|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327105804/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-dc-maryland-coronavirus-news-wednesday/2020/03/11/50a0d822-6342-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(5) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicEmergency03.11.20.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-045: Declaration of Public Emergency: Coronavirus (COVID-19)|date=March 20, 2020|work=Administrative Infomation System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329201523/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicEmergency03.11.20.pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(6) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicHealthEmergency03.11.20.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-046: Declaration of Public Emergency: Coronavirus (COVID-19)|date=March 20, 2020|work=Administrative Infomation System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329201521/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicHealthEmergency03.11.20.pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, [[District of Columbia Public Schools]] (DCPS) shut down schools from March 16 to March 31. March 16 was reserved for professional development for teachers in preparation for the implementation of [[distance learning]]. The April Spring Break period was moved to March 17 to March 23, after which classes were set to resume online. DCPS-sponsored out-of-state travel for students was suspended until May 1 and staff travel was restricted. During the closure, several schools were set to offer meals to students from 10 am to 2 pm on weekdays.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) Updates |url=https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus |website=District of Columbia Public Schools |publisher=DC.Gov |accessdate=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313221000/https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, the District government suspended on-site bar and restaurant service and shut down movie theaters and gyms. Restaurants could still offer food for carryout and delivery, but customers could not dine in.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/03/16/2362519a-6777-11ea-abef-020f086a3fab_story.html |title=Second Va. man dies, D.C., Maryland restaurants, bars close as toll passes 100 |work=[[Washington Post]] |date=2020-03-16 |accessdate=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316234751/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/03/16/2362519a-6777-11ea-abef-020f086a3fab_story.html |archive-date=2020-03-16 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Mayor Bowser issued an order that prohibited mass gatherings of 50 or more people. The order also prohibited table service and service to standing customers at restaurants, bars and multi-purpose facilities, including seated, fast food and fast casual restaurants. Those businesses could only operate for take-out, \"grab-and-go\" and delivery operations.<ref name=\"March 20 order\">(1) {{cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor\u2019s-order-2020-051-prohibition-mass-gatherings-during-public-health-emergency|title=Prohibition on Mass Gatherings During Public Health Emergency - Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=News Release|date=March 20, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330150520/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor%E2%80%99s-order-2020-051-prohibition-mass-gatherings-during-public-health-emergency|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(2) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/u23/Mayor%60s%20Order%202020-51.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-051: Prohibition on Mass Gatherings During Public Health Emergency - Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 20, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330201113/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/u23/Mayor%60s%20Order%202020-51.pdf|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThe Mayor's March 20 order also required nightclubs, health clubs, health spas, massage parlors and theaters to continue their suspension of operations, which the District's government had initially ordered on March 17. The order further closed to the public all facilities that the District's Department of Recreation operated, including playgrounds, parks and athletic fields.<ref name=\"March 20 order\"/>\n\nThe District of Columbia Medical Reserve Corps (DC MRC), a volunteer organization under the [[District of Columbia Department of Health]], was mobilized to aid emergency workers in responding to the coronavirus pandemic throughout D.C. On March 21, Mayor Bowser called for more volunteers to join the task force.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Bowser Encourages Volunteers to Join the DC Medical Reserve Corps |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-encourages-volunteers-join-dc-medical-reserve-corps |website=coronavirus.dc.gov |publisher=DC.Gov |date=21 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323215101/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-encourages-volunteers-join-dc-medical-reserve-corps |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, Mayor Bowser issued an order \"to temporarily cease all non-essential business activities, including tour guides and touring services; gyms, health clubs, spas, and massage establishments; theaters, auditoriums, and other places of large gatherings; nightclubs; hair, nail, and tanning salons and barbershops; tattoo parlors; sales not involved in essential services; retail clothing stores; and professional services not devoted to assisting essential business operations.\"<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-orders-closure-non-essential-businesses|title=New Mayor\u2019s Order Requires Temporary Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibits Gatherings of Ten or More People|work=News Release|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330200918/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-orders-closure-non-essential-businesses|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}} <br>(2) {{cite news|last=Barnes|first=Sophia|url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-closes-nonessential-businesses-dmv-latest-tuesday-march-23-whats-closed-washington/2252010/|title=DC Closes Nonessential Businesses, DMV Centers to Stop Coronavirus|date=March 25, 2020|work=Coronavirus|publisher=[[WRC-TV|NBC4 Washington]]|accessdate=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327133947/https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-closes-nonessential-businesses-dmv-latest-tuesday-march-23-whats-closed-washington/2252010/|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(3) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|title=Mayor\u2019s Order 2020-053: Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibition on Large Gatherings During Public Health Emergency for the 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329184808/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBowser's March 24 order defined \"Construction and Building Trades\" as \"essential businesses\", but did not define private construction projects themselves as being \"essential\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|title=Mayor\u2019s Order 2020-053: Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibition on Large Gatherings During Public Health Emergency for the 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329184808/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> However, [[The Washington Post]] reported on March 28 that the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia had designated construction as \"essential,\" along with hospitals, grocery stores, banks and several other types of businesses. The ''Post'' reported that each of these jurisdictions had allowed private construction, including home building and commercial developments, to continue.<ref name=Lazo>{{cite news|first1=Luz|last1=Lazo|first2=Katherine|last2=Shaver|date=March 28, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/work-on-regions-big-projects-continues-amid-coronavirus-with-construction-an-essential-business/2020/03/28/e4af8b38-6dfd-11ea-a3ec-70d7479d83f0_story.html|title=Work on region\u2019s big projects continues amid coronavirus, with construction an \u2018essential\u2019 business|work=Transportation|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401022830/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/work-on-regions-big-projects-continues-amid-coronavirus-with-construction-an-essential-business/2020/03/28/e4af8b38-6dfd-11ea-a3ec-70d7479d83f0_story.html|archive-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  \n\nThe ''Post'' reported that John Falcicchio, Bowser's chief of staff, had stated that the District, Maryland and Virginia had agreed to follow the federal guidance declaring construction to be essential work. However, the ''Post'' reported that several states, including Pennsylvania and Vermont, had suspended or prohibited all construction work (except for emergencies) as unnecessary during a public health crisis. The Post further reported that the State of Washington's transportation department had suspended work on nearly all of its projects and that Washington's governor had clarified his [[Stay-at-home order|stay-at-home]] order to state that commercial and residential construction were generally prohibited \"because construction is not considered to be an essential activity.\"<ref name=Lazo/>\n\nThe [[United States Department of Homeland Security]]'s March 28 guidance on essential critical infrastructure lists as \"essential\" the construction of residential/shelter facilities and services, energy-related facilities, communications and information technology, public works including the  construction of critical or strategic infrastructure and infrastructure that is temporarily required to support COVID-19 response, is for certain other types of community- or government-based operations, or is otherwise critical, strategic, or essential. The guidance does not contain any such listings for other types of construction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cisa.gov/sites/default/files/publications/CISA_Guidance_on_the_Essential_Critical_Infrastructure_Workforce_Version_2.0_Updated.pdf|title=Guidance on the Essential Critical Infrastructure Workforce: Ensuring Community and National Resilience in COVID-19 Response|date=March 28, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[United States Department of Homeland Security]]: [[Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency]]: Office of the Director|accessdate=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402033910/https://www.cisa.gov/sites/default/files/publications/CISA_Guidance_on_the_Essential_Critical_Infrastructure_Workforce_Version_2.0_Updated.pdf|archive-date=April 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, Bowser announced a stay-at-home order that would go into effect on April 1. The order stated that residents may only leave their residences to engage in essential activities, including obtaining medical care that cannot be provided through telehealth and obtaining food and essential household goods, to perform or access essential governmental functions, to work at essential businesses, to engage in essential travel and to engage in specific recreational activities that the order defined.<ref name=\"stay at home\"/><ref name=\"Post March 30\"/> Anyone found to be violating the order would be charged with a [[misdemeanor]] and subject to a $5,000 fine and/or 90 days in prison.<ref name=Franklin/>\n\n==Impact on sports==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nThe pandemic affected several sports in the district. On March 12, [[Major League Baseball]] cancelled the remainder of [[spring training]], and on March 16, they announced that the season will be postponed indefinitely, after the recommendations from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] to restrict events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, affecting the [[2020 Washington Nationals season|Washington Nationals]].<ref name=\"mlb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |title=Opening of regular season to be pushed back |first=Mark |last=Feinsand |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317025811/https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Washington Wizards season|Washington Wizards]].<ref name=nba>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=March 13, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313004850/https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the [[National Hockey League]], the season was suspended for an indefinite amount of time, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Washington Capitals season|Washington Capitals]].<ref name=nhl>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314025848/https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 |date=2020-03-14 }} NHL, March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities districtwide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312213051/http://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships |date=2020-03-12 }} NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318182102/https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html |date=2020-03-18 }} MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maryland]] \u2013 for impact on Maryland counties in the Washington metropolitan area\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Virginia]] \u2013 for impact on Virginia counties in the Washington metropolitan area\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://coronavirus.dc.gov/ Coronavirus information] from the [[Government of the District of Columbia]]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by city|Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:2020 in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "name_user": "Corker1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProjections:editorial change", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Washington,_D.C."}
{"title_page": "Essential amino acid", "text_new": "{{See also|Protein (nutrient)|Protein quality}}\n<!-- Please ensure you note the difference between **Essential** amino acids and **common** or proteinogenic amino acids before editing this article -->\nAn '''essential amino acid''', or '''indispensable amino acid''', is an [[amino acid]] that cannot be [[de novo synthesis|synthesized ''de novo'']] (from scratch) by the organism at a rate commensurate with its demand, and thus must be supplied in its diet. Of the 21 amino acids common to all life forms, the nine amino acids humans cannot synthesize are [[phenylalanine]], [[valine]], [[threonine]], [[tryptophan]], [[methionine]], [[leucine]], [[isoleucine]], [[lysine]], and [[histidine]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Young VR |title=Adult amino acid requirements: the case for a major revision in current recommendations |journal=J. Nutr. |volume=124 |issue=8 Suppl |pages=1517S\u20131523S |year=1994 |pmid=8064412 |url=http://jn.nutrition.org/cgi/reprint/124/8_Suppl/1517S.pdf |doi=10.1093/jn/124.suppl_8.1517S}}</ref><ref name=\"DRI\">[http://fnic.nal.usda.gov/dietary-guidance/dietary-reference-intakes/dri-reports Dietary Reference Intakes: The Essential Guide to Nutrient Requirements] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140705140516/http://fnic.nal.usda.gov/dietary-guidance/dietary-reference-intakes/dri-reports |date=5 July 2014 }}. Institute of Medicine's Food and Nutrition Board. usda.gov</ref>\n\nSix other amino acids are considered '''conditionally essential''' in the human diet, meaning their synthesis can be limited under special pathophysiological conditions, such as prematurity in the infant or individuals in severe catabolic distress.<ref name=\"DRI\" /> These six are [[arginine]], [[cysteine]], [[glycine]], [[glutamine]],<!-- Histidine is essential according to the Dietary Reference Intakes published by the USDA --> [[proline]], and [[tyrosine]]. Six amino acids are non-essential ('''dispensable''') in humans, meaning they can be synthesized in sufficient quantities in the body. These six are [[alanine]], [[aspartic acid]], [[asparagine]], [[glutamic acid]], [[serine]],<ref name=\"DRI\" /> and [[selenocysteine]] (considered the 21st amino acid). [[Pyrrolysine]] (considered the 22nd amino acid) is not used by humans; thus, it is non{{nbh}}essential.\n\nThe '''limiting amino acid''' is the essential amino acid found in the smallest quantity in the foodstuff, most plant-based foods have a limiting amino acid. This concept is important when calculating [[fodder|animal feeds]]. A [[complete protein]] contains all the essential amino acids in the right balance; meat, milk and eggs are complete protein sources for humans.\n\nCoronavirus\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Essential\n!Conditionally essential<ref name=\"FuerstStehle\">{{cite journal|vauthors=F\u00fcrst P, Stehle P|date=1 June 2004|title=What are the essential elements needed for the determination of amino acid requirements in humans?|journal=Journal of Nutrition|volume=134|issue=6 Suppl|pages=1558S\u20131565S|pmid=15173430|doi=10.1093/jn/134.6.1558S}}</ref><ref name=\"reeds\">{{cite journal|author=Reeds PJ|date=1 July 2000|title=Dispensable and indispensable amino acids for humans|journal=J. Nutr.|volume=130|issue=7|pages=1835S\u201340S|pmid=10867060|doi=10.1093/jn/130.7.1835S}}</ref>\n! Non-essential\n|-\n| [[Histidine]] (H)<!-- Histidine is essential, provide recent ref before modifying -->\n|[[Arginine]] (R)\n| [[Alanine]] (A)\n|-\n| [[Isoleucine]] (I)\n|[[Cysteine]] (C)\n| [[Aspartic acid]] (D)\n|-\n| [[Leucine]] (L)\n|[[Glutamine]] (Q)\n| [[Asparagine]] (N)\n|-\n| [[Lysine]] (K)\n|[[Glycine]] (G)\n| [[Glutamic acid]] (E)\n|-\n| [[Methionine]] (M)\n|[[Proline]] (P)\n| [[Serine]] (S)\n|-\n| [[Phenylalanine]] (F)\n|[[Tyrosine]] (Y)\n| [[Selenocysteine]] (U)\n|-\n| [[Threonine]] (T)\n|<br />\n|[[Pyrrolysine]]* (O)\n|-\n| [[Tryptophan]] (W)\n|\n|\n|-\n| [[Valine]] (V)\n|\n|\n|}\n\n(*) [[Pyrrolysine]], sometimes considered the \"22nd amino acid\", is not used by humans.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chem.qmul.ac.uk/iubmb/newsletter/2009.html#item3 |title=Newsletter 2009, Biochemical Nomenclature Committee of IUPAC and NC-IUBMB |author=Richard Cammack |access-date=16 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912194130/http://www.chem.qmul.ac.uk/iubmb/newsletter/2009.html#item3 |archive-date=12 September 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[Eukaryotes]] can synthesize some of the amino acids from other substrates. Consequently, only a subset of the amino acids used in protein synthesis are [[essential nutrient]]s.\n\n==Recommended daily intake==\n{{Main|Protein (nutrient)}}\nEstimating the daily requirement for the indispensable amino acids has proven to be difficult; these numbers have undergone considerable revision over the last 20 years. The following table lists the [[WHO]] and United States recommended daily amounts currently in use for essential amino acids in '''adult humans''', together with their standard one-letter abbreviations.<ref name=\"WHO\"/><ref name=\"DRItext\">{{cite book |last1=Institute of Medicine |title=Dietary Reference Intakes for Energy, Carbohydrates, Fiber, Fat, Fatty Acids, Cholesterol, Protein, and Amino Acids |chapter=Protein and Amino Acids |publisher=The National Academies Press |year=2002 |location=Washington, DC |pages=589\u2013768 |chapter-url=https://www.nap.edu/read/10490/chapter/12|author1-link=Institute of Medicine }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Amino acid(s)\n! WHO mg per kg body weight\n! WHO mg per 70&nbsp;kg\n! US mg per kg body weight\n|-\n| '''H''' [[Histidine]]\n| 10\n| 700\n| 14\n\n|-\n| '''I''' [[Isoleucine]]\n| 20\n| 1400\n| 19\n\n|-\n| '''L''' [[Leucine]]\n| 39\n| 2730\n| 42\n\n|-\n| '''K''' [[Lysine]]\n| 30\n| 2100\n| 38\n\n|-\n| '''M''' [[Methionine]]\n+ '''C''' [[Cysteine]]\n| 10.4 + 4.1 (15 total)\n| 1050 total\n| 19 total\n\n|-\n| '''F''' [[Phenylalanine]]\n+ '''Y''' [[Tyrosine]]\n| 25 (total)\n| 1750 total\n| 33 total\n\n|-\n| '''T''' [[Threonine]]\n| 15\n| 1050\n| 20\n\n|-\n| '''W''' [[Tryptophan]]\n| 4\n| 280\n| 5\n\n|-\n| '''V''' [[Valine]]\n| 26\n| 1820\n| 24\n|}\n\nThe recommended daily intakes for children aged three years and older is 10% to 20% higher than adult levels and those for infants can be as much as 150% higher in the first year of life. [[Cysteine]] (or sulfur-containing amino acids), [[tyrosine]] (or aromatic amino acids), and [[arginine]] are always required by infants and growing children.<ref name=\"WHO\">{{cite web |url=http://whqlibdoc.who.int/trs/WHO_TRS_935_eng.pdf |title=PROTEIN AND AMINO ACID REQUIREMENTS IN HUMAN NUTRITION |author=FAO/WHO/UNU |publisher=WHO Press |year=2007}}, page 150</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Imura K, Okada A |title=Amino acid metabolism in pediatric patients |journal=Nutrition |volume=14 |issue=1 |pages=143\u20138 |year=1998 |pmid=9437700 |url= |doi=10.1016/S0899-9007(97)00230-X}}</ref>\n\n==Relative amino acid composition of protein sources==\nFoodstuffs that lack essential amino acids are poor sources of [[protein]] equivalents, as the body tends to [[deamination|deaminate]] the amino acids obtained, converting proteins into [[fat]]s and [[carbohydrate]]s. Therefore, a balance of essential amino acids is necessary for a high degree of [[net protein utilization]], which is the mass ratio of amino acids converted to proteins to amino acids supplied.<ref name=McGilvery1979>McGilvery, Robert W. ''Biochemistry, a Functional Approach'' 1979. Chapter 41, esp Page 787</ref>\n\n[[Complete protein]]s contain a balanced set of essential amino acids for humans. Animal sources such as meat, poultry, eggs, fish, milk, and cheese provide all of the essential amino acids.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/nccdphp/dnpa/nutrition/nutrition_for_everyone/basics/protein.htm|title=Nutrition for Everyone: Basics: Protein|publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|accessdate=2008-05-15}}</ref> Near-complete proteins are also found in some plant sources such as [[quinoa]].<ref name=\"NASA\">http://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19940015664_1994015664.pdf</ref>\n\nThe net protein utilization is profoundly affected by the '''limiting amino acid''' content (the essential amino acid found in the smallest quantity in the foodstuff), and somewhat affected by salvage of essential amino acids in the body. It is therefore a good idea to mix foodstuffs that have different weaknesses in their essential amino acid distributions. This limits the loss of nitrogen through deamination and increases overall net protein utilization.<ref name=McGilvery1979/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! '''Protein source''' \n! '''Limiting amino acid''' \n|- \n| [[Wheat]] \n| [[lysine]] \n|- \n| [[Rice]] \n| [[lysine]] \n|- \n| [[Legumes]] \n| [[tryptophan]] \n|- \n| [[Maize]] \n| [[lysine]] and [[tryptophan]]\n|- \n| [[Pulses]] \n| [[methionine]] (or [[cysteine]])\n|- \n| [[egg (food)|Egg]], chicken, milk\n| none; egg is the reference for complete protein\n|}\n\nMany plant-based foods do not provide the correct protein profiles,<ref name=\"vProtein\">{{Cite journal |last1=Woolf |first1=P.J. |last2=Fu |first2=L.L. |last3=Basu |first3=A. | editor1-last=Haslam |editor1-first=Niall James |title=VProtein: Identifying Optimal Amino Acid Complements from Plant-Based Foods |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0018836 |journal=PLoS ONE |volume=6 |issue=4 |pages=e18836 |year=2011 |pmid=21526128 |pmc=3081312|bibcode=2011PLoSO...618836W }}</ref> but it is not necessary to consume plant foods containing complete proteins as long as a reasonably varied diet is maintained.<ref name=Vesanto2016>{{Cite journal|last=Melina|first=Vesanto |author-link=Vesanto Melina |last2=Craig |first2=Winston |last3=Levin |first3=Susan |date=2016-12-01 |title=Position of the Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics: Vegetarian Diets |url=http://jandonline.org/article/S2212-2672(16)31192-3/fulltext |journal=Journal of the Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics |language=English |volume=116 |issue=12 |pages=1971 |doi=10.1016/j.jand.2016.09.025 |issn=2212-2672 |pmid=27886704}}</ref> Numerous pairs of different plant foods can provide a complete protein profile. Some of the most efficient pairings include sweet corn/tomatoes, apple/coconut and sweet corn/cherry. Some algae such as [[wakame]] seaweed, or plant-based foods such as [[macadamia]]s and [[Flour#Degermed and heat-processed flour|degermed]] maize products, have a very imbalanced protein profile.<ref name=\"vProtein\"/> Certain traditional combinations of foods, such as corn and beans, or beans and rice, contain the essential amino acids necessary for humans in adequate amounts.<ref>[http://hyperphysics.phy-astr.gsu.edu/hbase/organic/essam.html Essential Amino Acids]. phy-astr.gsu.edu: \"a number of popular ethnic foods involve such a combination so that in a single dish, one might hope to get the ten essential amino acids. Mexican corn and beans, Japanese rice and soybeans, and Cajun red beans and rice are examples of such fortuitous combinations.\"</ref> The official position of the [[Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics]] is that protein from an appropriate planned combination of a variety of plant foods eaten during the course of a day can be nutritionally adequate when caloric requirements are met.<ref name=Vesanto2016/>\n\n===Protein quality===\n{{Main|Protein quality}}\n\nVarious attempts have been made to express the \"quality\" or \"value\" of various kinds of protein. Measures include the [[biological value]], [[net protein utilization]], [[protein efficiency ratio]], [[Protein Digestibility Corrected Amino Acid Score|protein digestibility-corrected amino acid score]] and [[Complete protein|complete proteins concept]]. These concepts are important in the [[animal husbandry|livestock industry]], because the relative lack of one or more of the essential amino acids in [[fodder|animal feeds]] would have a limiting effect on growth and thus on [[feed conversion ratio]]. Thus, various feedstuffs may be fed in combination to increase net protein utilization, or a [[Dietary supplement|supplement]] of an individual amino acid (methionine, lysine, threonine, or tryptophan) can be added to the feed.\n\n===Protein per calorie===\nProtein content in foods is often measured in protein per serving rather than protein per calorie. For instance, the USDA lists 6 grams of protein per large whole egg (a 50-gram serving) rather than 84&nbsp;mg of protein per calorie (71 calories total).<ref>{{cite book |title=SDA National Nutrient Database for Standard Reference |date=2008 |publisher=U.S. Department of Agriculture, Agricultural Research Service |edition=Release 21}}</ref> For comparison, there are 2.8 grams of protein in a serving of raw broccoli (100 grams) or 82&nbsp;mg of protein per calorie (34 calories total), or the [[Daily Value]] of 47.67g of protein after eating 1,690g of raw broccoli a day at 574 cal.<ref name=Broccoli>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nutritionvalue.org/Broccoli%2C_raw_nutritional_value.html |title=Broccoli, raw: nutritional value and analysis |last=Vanovschi |first=Vitalii |website=www.nutritionvalue.org |access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref> An egg contains 12.5g of protein per 100g, but 4&nbsp;mg more protein per calorie, or the protein DV after 381g of egg, which is 545 cal.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nutritionvalue.org/Egg%2C_poached%2C_cooked%2C_whole_nutritional_value.html |title=Egg, poached, cooked, whole: nutritional value and analysis |last=Vanovschi |first=Vitalii |website=www.nutritionvalue.org |access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref> The ratio of essential amino acids (the quality of protein) is not taken into account, one would actually need to eat more than 3&nbsp;kg of broccoli a day to have a healthy protein profile, and almost 6&nbsp;kg to get enough calories.<ref name=Broccoli/> It is recommended that adult humans obtain between 10\u201335% of their 2000 calories a day as protein.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.webmd.com/food-recipes/protein |title=Web MD Protein: Are You Getting Enough? |publisher=webmd.com |date=2014-09-05 |accessdate=2015-03-31}}</ref>\n\n==Complete proteins in non-human animals==\nScientists had known since the early 20th century that rats could not survive on a diet whose only protein source was [[zein]], which comes from [[maize]] (corn), but recovered if they were fed [[casein]] from cow's milk. This led [[William Cumming Rose]] to the discovery of the essential amino acid [[threonine]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Rose WC, Haines WJ, Warner DT, Johnson JE |title=The amino acid requirements of man. II. The role of threonine and histidine |journal=The Journal of Biological Chemistry |volume=188 |issue=1 |pages=49\u201358 |pmid=14814112 |year=1951}}</ref> Through manipulation of rodent diets, Rose was able to show that ten amino acids are essential for rats: [[lysine]], [[tryptophan]], [[histidine]], [[phenylalanine]], [[leucine]], [[isoleucine]], [[methionine]], [[valine]], and [[arginine]], in addition to threonine. Rose's later work showed that eight amino acids are essential for adult human beings, with histidine also being essential for infants. Longer-term studies established histidine as also essential for adult humans.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Kopple JD, Swendseid ME |date=May 1975 |title=Evidence that histidine is an essential amino acid in normal and chronically uremic man. |journal=J Clin Invest |volume=55 |issue=5 |pages=881\u2013891 |pmid=1123426 |pmc=301830 |doi=10.1172/JCI108016}}</ref>\n\n==Interchangeability==\nThe distinction between essential and non-essential amino acids is somewhat unclear, as some amino acids can be produced from others. The [[sulfur]]-containing amino acids, [[methionine]] and [[homocysteine]], can be converted into each other but neither can be synthesized ''de novo'' in humans. Likewise, cysteine can be made from homocysteine but cannot be synthesized on its own. So, for convenience, sulfur-containing amino acids are sometimes considered a single pool of nutritionally equivalent amino acids as are the [[aromatic]] amino acid pair, [[phenylalanine]] and [[tyrosine]]. Likewise [[arginine]], [[ornithine]], and [[citrulline]], which are interconvertible by the [[urea cycle]], are considered a single group.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n==Effects of deficiency==\n{{Main|Protein-energy malnutrition}}\nIf one of the essential amino acids is less than needed for an individual the utilization of other amino acids will be hindered and thus protein synthesis will be less than adequate.<ref name=\"DRI\" /> Protein deficiency has been shown to affect all of the body's organs and many of its systems, including the brain and brain function of infants and young children; the immune system, thus elevating risk of infection; gut [[mucosal]] function and permeability, which affects absorption and vulnerability to [[systemic disease]]; and kidney function.<ref name=\"DRI\" /> The physical signs of protein deficiency include edema, failure to thrive in infants and children, poor musculature, dull skin, and thin and fragile hair. Biochemical changes reflecting protein deficiency include low [[serum albumin]] and low [[serum transferrin]].<ref name=\"DRI\" />\n\nThe amino acids that are essential in the human diet were established in a series of experiments led by [[William Cumming Rose]]. The experiments involved elemental diets to healthy male graduate students. These diets consisted of [[Corn starch|cornstarch]], [[sucrose]], [[butterfat]] without protein, [[corn oil]], inorganic salts, the known [[vitamin]]s, a large brown \"candy\" made of liver extract flavored with [[peppermint oil]] (to supply any unknown vitamins), and mixtures of highly purified individual amino acids. The main outcome measure was [[nitrogen balance]]. Rose noted that the symptoms of nervousness, exhaustion, and dizziness were encountered to a greater or lesser extent whenever human subjects were deprived of an essential amino acid.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Rose |first1=WC |last2=Haines |first2=WJ |last3=Warner |first3=DT |title=The amino acid requirements of man. III. The role of isoleucine; additional evidence concerning histidine |journal=J Biol Chem |year=1951 |volume=193 |issue=2 |pages=605\u2013612 |url=http://www.jbc.org/content/193/2/605.full.pdf |accessdate=15 Dec 2012 |pmid=14907749}}</ref>\n\nEssential amino [[acid]] deficiency should be distinguished from [[protein-energy malnutrition]], which can manifest as [[marasmus]] or [[kwashiorkor]]. [[Kwashiorkor]] was once attributed to pure protein deficiency in individuals who were consuming enough [[calorie]]s (\"sugar baby syndrome\"). However, this theory has been challenged by the finding that there is no difference in the diets of children developing [[marasmus]] as opposed to kwashiorkor.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Ahmed T, Rahman S, Cravioto A |title=Oedematous malnutrition |journal=The Indian Journal of Medical Research |volume=130 |issue=5 |pages=651\u20134 |pmid=20090122 |year=2009}}</ref> Still, for instance in [[Dietary Reference Intake]]s (DRI) maintained by the [[USDA]], lack of one or more of the essential amino acids is described as [[protein-energy malnutrition]].<ref name=\"DRI\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Biological Value|Biological Value (BV)]]\n*[[Edible protein per unit area of land]]\n*[[Essential fatty acid]]\n*[[Essential genes]]\n*[[List of standard amino acids]]\n*[[Low-protein diet]]\n*[[Orthomolecular medicine]]\n*[[PDCAAS|Protein Digestibility Corrected Amino Acid Score]]\n*[[Ketogenic amino acid]]\n*[[Glucogenic amino acid]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Essential amino acids}}\n*[http://www.veganhealth.org/articles/protein Amino acid content of some vegetarian foods] at veganhealth.org.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050319163510/http://www.dasc.vt.edu/extension/nutritioncc/9729.html Amino Acid Profiles of Some Common Feeds] at [[Virginia Tech]].\n*[http://micro.magnet.fsu.edu/aminoacids/index.html Molecular Expressions: The Amino Acid Collection] at [[Florida State University]]. Features detailed information and crystal photographs of each amino acid.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120202075048/http://foodwiki.com/vprotein vProtein], an online software tool to analyze the essential amino acid profiles of single and pairs of plant based foods based on human requirements.\n\n{{Amino acids}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Essential Amino Acid}}\n[[Category:Amino acids]]\n[[Category:Essential amino acids| ]]\n[[Category:Nitrogen cycle]]\n[[Category:Nutrition]]\n", "text_old": "{{See also|Protein (nutrient)|Protein quality}}\n<!-- Please ensure you note the difference between **Essential** amino acids and **common** or proteinogenic amino acids before editing this article -->\nAn '''essential amino acid''', or '''indispensable amino acid''', is an [[amino acid]] that cannot be [[de novo synthesis|synthesized ''de novo'']] (from scratch) by the organism at a rate commensurate with its demand, and thus must be supplied in its diet. Of the 21 amino acids common to all life forms, the nine amino acids humans cannot synthesize are [[phenylalanine]], [[valine]], [[threonine]], [[tryptophan]], [[methionine]], [[leucine]], [[isoleucine]], [[lysine]], and [[histidine]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Young VR |title=Adult amino acid requirements: the case for a major revision in current recommendations |journal=J. Nutr. |volume=124 |issue=8 Suppl |pages=1517S\u20131523S |year=1994 |pmid=8064412 |url=http://jn.nutrition.org/cgi/reprint/124/8_Suppl/1517S.pdf |doi=10.1093/jn/124.suppl_8.1517S}}</ref><ref name=\"DRI\">[http://fnic.nal.usda.gov/dietary-guidance/dietary-reference-intakes/dri-reports Dietary Reference Intakes: The Essential Guide to Nutrient Requirements] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140705140516/http://fnic.nal.usda.gov/dietary-guidance/dietary-reference-intakes/dri-reports |date=5 July 2014 }}. Institute of Medicine's Food and Nutrition Board. usda.gov</ref>\n\nSix other amino acids are considered '''conditionally essential''' in the human diet, meaning their synthesis can be limited under special pathophysiological conditions, such as prematurity in the infant or individuals in severe catabolic distress.<ref name=\"DRI\" /> These six are [[arginine]], [[cysteine]], [[glycine]], [[glutamine]],<!-- Histidine is essential according to the Dietary Reference Intakes published by the USDA --> [[proline]], and [[tyrosine]]. Six amino acids are non-essential ('''dispensable''') in humans, meaning they can be synthesized in sufficient quantities in the body. These six are [[alanine]], [[aspartic acid]], [[asparagine]], [[glutamic acid]], [[serine]],<ref name=\"DRI\" /> and [[selenocysteine]] (considered the 21st amino acid). [[Pyrrolysine]] (considered the 22nd amino acid) is not used by humans; thus, it is non{{nbh}}essential.\n\nThe '''limiting amino acid''' is the essential amino acid found in the smallest quantity in the foodstuff, most plant-based foods have a limiting amino acid. This concept is important when calculating [[fodder|animal feeds]]. A [[complete protein]] contains all the essential amino acids in the right balance; meat, milk and eggs are complete protein sources for humans.\n\n==Essentiality in humans==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Essential\n!Conditionally essential<ref name=\"FuerstStehle\">{{cite journal|vauthors=F\u00fcrst P, Stehle P|date=1 June 2004|title=What are the essential elements needed for the determination of amino acid requirements in humans?|journal=Journal of Nutrition|volume=134|issue=6 Suppl|pages=1558S\u20131565S|pmid=15173430|doi=10.1093/jn/134.6.1558S}}</ref><ref name=\"reeds\">{{cite journal|author=Reeds PJ|date=1 July 2000|title=Dispensable and indispensable amino acids for humans|journal=J. Nutr.|volume=130|issue=7|pages=1835S\u201340S|pmid=10867060|doi=10.1093/jn/130.7.1835S}}</ref>\n! Non-essential\n|-\n| [[Histidine]] (H)<!-- Histidine is essential, provide recent ref before modifying -->\n|[[Arginine]] (R)\n| [[Alanine]] (A)\n|-\n| [[Isoleucine]] (I)\n|[[Cysteine]] (C)\n| [[Aspartic acid]] (D)\n|-\n| [[Leucine]] (L)\n|[[Glutamine]] (Q)\n| [[Asparagine]] (N)\n|-\n| [[Lysine]] (K)\n|[[Glycine]] (G)\n| [[Glutamic acid]] (E)\n|-\n| [[Methionine]] (M)\n|[[Proline]] (P)\n| [[Serine]] (S)\n|-\n| [[Phenylalanine]] (F)\n|[[Tyrosine]] (Y)\n| [[Selenocysteine]] (U)\n|-\n| [[Threonine]] (T)\n|<br />\n|[[Pyrrolysine]]* (O)\n|-\n| [[Tryptophan]] (W)\n|\n|\n|-\n| [[Valine]] (V)\n|\n|\n|}\n\n(*) [[Pyrrolysine]], sometimes considered the \"22nd amino acid\", is not used by humans.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chem.qmul.ac.uk/iubmb/newsletter/2009.html#item3 |title=Newsletter 2009, Biochemical Nomenclature Committee of IUPAC and NC-IUBMB |author=Richard Cammack |access-date=16 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912194130/http://www.chem.qmul.ac.uk/iubmb/newsletter/2009.html#item3 |archive-date=12 September 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[Eukaryotes]] can synthesize some of the amino acids from other substrates. Consequently, only a subset of the amino acids used in protein synthesis are [[essential nutrient]]s.\n\n==Recommended daily intake==\n{{Main|Protein (nutrient)}}\nEstimating the daily requirement for the indispensable amino acids has proven to be difficult; these numbers have undergone considerable revision over the last 20 years. The following table lists the [[WHO]] and United States recommended daily amounts currently in use for essential amino acids in '''adult humans''', together with their standard one-letter abbreviations.<ref name=\"WHO\"/><ref name=\"DRItext\">{{cite book |last1=Institute of Medicine |title=Dietary Reference Intakes for Energy, Carbohydrates, Fiber, Fat, Fatty Acids, Cholesterol, Protein, and Amino Acids |chapter=Protein and Amino Acids |publisher=The National Academies Press |year=2002 |location=Washington, DC |pages=589\u2013768 |chapter-url=https://www.nap.edu/read/10490/chapter/12|author1-link=Institute of Medicine }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Amino acid(s)\n! WHO mg per kg body weight\n! WHO mg per 70&nbsp;kg\n! US mg per kg body weight\n|-\n| '''H''' [[Histidine]]\n| 10\n| 700\n| 14\n\n|-\n| '''I''' [[Isoleucine]]\n| 20\n| 1400\n| 19\n\n|-\n| '''L''' [[Leucine]]\n| 39\n| 2730\n| 42\n\n|-\n| '''K''' [[Lysine]]\n| 30\n| 2100\n| 38\n\n|-\n| '''M''' [[Methionine]]\n+ '''C''' [[Cysteine]]\n| 10.4 + 4.1 (15 total)\n| 1050 total\n| 19 total\n\n|-\n| '''F''' [[Phenylalanine]]\n+ '''Y''' [[Tyrosine]]\n| 25 (total)\n| 1750 total\n| 33 total\n\n|-\n| '''T''' [[Threonine]]\n| 15\n| 1050\n| 20\n\n|-\n| '''W''' [[Tryptophan]]\n| 4\n| 280\n| 5\n\n|-\n| '''V''' [[Valine]]\n| 26\n| 1820\n| 24\n|}\n\nThe recommended daily intakes for children aged three years and older is 10% to 20% higher than adult levels and those for infants can be as much as 150% higher in the first year of life. [[Cysteine]] (or sulfur-containing amino acids), [[tyrosine]] (or aromatic amino acids), and [[arginine]] are always required by infants and growing children.<ref name=\"WHO\">{{cite web |url=http://whqlibdoc.who.int/trs/WHO_TRS_935_eng.pdf |title=PROTEIN AND AMINO ACID REQUIREMENTS IN HUMAN NUTRITION |author=FAO/WHO/UNU |publisher=WHO Press |year=2007}}, page 150</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Imura K, Okada A |title=Amino acid metabolism in pediatric patients |journal=Nutrition |volume=14 |issue=1 |pages=143\u20138 |year=1998 |pmid=9437700 |url= |doi=10.1016/S0899-9007(97)00230-X}}</ref>\n\n==Relative amino acid composition of protein sources==\nFoodstuffs that lack essential amino acids are poor sources of [[protein]] equivalents, as the body tends to [[deamination|deaminate]] the amino acids obtained, converting proteins into [[fat]]s and [[carbohydrate]]s. Therefore, a balance of essential amino acids is necessary for a high degree of [[net protein utilization]], which is the mass ratio of amino acids converted to proteins to amino acids supplied.<ref name=McGilvery1979>McGilvery, Robert W. ''Biochemistry, a Functional Approach'' 1979. Chapter 41, esp Page 787</ref>\n\n[[Complete protein]]s contain a balanced set of essential amino acids for humans. Animal sources such as meat, poultry, eggs, fish, milk, and cheese provide all of the essential amino acids.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/nccdphp/dnpa/nutrition/nutrition_for_everyone/basics/protein.htm|title=Nutrition for Everyone: Basics: Protein|publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|accessdate=2008-05-15}}</ref> Near-complete proteins are also found in some plant sources such as [[quinoa]].<ref name=\"NASA\">http://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19940015664_1994015664.pdf</ref>\n\nThe net protein utilization is profoundly affected by the '''limiting amino acid''' content (the essential amino acid found in the smallest quantity in the foodstuff), and somewhat affected by salvage of essential amino acids in the body. It is therefore a good idea to mix foodstuffs that have different weaknesses in their essential amino acid distributions. This limits the loss of nitrogen through deamination and increases overall net protein utilization.<ref name=McGilvery1979/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! '''Protein source''' \n! '''Limiting amino acid''' \n|- \n| [[Wheat]] \n| [[lysine]] \n|- \n| [[Rice]] \n| [[lysine]] \n|- \n| [[Legumes]] \n| [[tryptophan]] \n|- \n| [[Maize]] \n| [[lysine]] and [[tryptophan]]\n|- \n| [[Pulses]] \n| [[methionine]] (or [[cysteine]])\n|- \n| [[egg (food)|Egg]], chicken, milk\n| none; egg is the reference for complete protein\n|}\n\nMany plant-based foods do not provide the correct protein profiles,<ref name=\"vProtein\">{{Cite journal |last1=Woolf |first1=P.J. |last2=Fu |first2=L.L. |last3=Basu |first3=A. | editor1-last=Haslam |editor1-first=Niall James |title=VProtein: Identifying Optimal Amino Acid Complements from Plant-Based Foods |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0018836 |journal=PLoS ONE |volume=6 |issue=4 |pages=e18836 |year=2011 |pmid=21526128 |pmc=3081312|bibcode=2011PLoSO...618836W }}</ref> but it is not necessary to consume plant foods containing complete proteins as long as a reasonably varied diet is maintained.<ref name=Vesanto2016>{{Cite journal|last=Melina|first=Vesanto |author-link=Vesanto Melina |last2=Craig |first2=Winston |last3=Levin |first3=Susan |date=2016-12-01 |title=Position of the Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics: Vegetarian Diets |url=http://jandonline.org/article/S2212-2672(16)31192-3/fulltext |journal=Journal of the Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics |language=English |volume=116 |issue=12 |pages=1971 |doi=10.1016/j.jand.2016.09.025 |issn=2212-2672 |pmid=27886704}}</ref> Numerous pairs of different plant foods can provide a complete protein profile. Some of the most efficient pairings include sweet corn/tomatoes, apple/coconut and sweet corn/cherry. Some algae such as [[wakame]] seaweed, or plant-based foods such as [[macadamia]]s and [[Flour#Degermed and heat-processed flour|degermed]] maize products, have a very imbalanced protein profile.<ref name=\"vProtein\"/> Certain traditional combinations of foods, such as corn and beans, or beans and rice, contain the essential amino acids necessary for humans in adequate amounts.<ref>[http://hyperphysics.phy-astr.gsu.edu/hbase/organic/essam.html Essential Amino Acids]. phy-astr.gsu.edu: \"a number of popular ethnic foods involve such a combination so that in a single dish, one might hope to get the ten essential amino acids. Mexican corn and beans, Japanese rice and soybeans, and Cajun red beans and rice are examples of such fortuitous combinations.\"</ref> The official position of the [[Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics]] is that protein from an appropriate planned combination of a variety of plant foods eaten during the course of a day can be nutritionally adequate when caloric requirements are met.<ref name=Vesanto2016/>\n\n===Protein quality===\n{{Main|Protein quality}}\n\nVarious attempts have been made to express the \"quality\" or \"value\" of various kinds of protein. Measures include the [[biological value]], [[net protein utilization]], [[protein efficiency ratio]], [[Protein Digestibility Corrected Amino Acid Score|protein digestibility-corrected amino acid score]] and [[Complete protein|complete proteins concept]]. These concepts are important in the [[animal husbandry|livestock industry]], because the relative lack of one or more of the essential amino acids in [[fodder|animal feeds]] would have a limiting effect on growth and thus on [[feed conversion ratio]]. Thus, various feedstuffs may be fed in combination to increase net protein utilization, or a [[Dietary supplement|supplement]] of an individual amino acid (methionine, lysine, threonine, or tryptophan) can be added to the feed.\n\n===Protein per calorie===\nProtein content in foods is often measured in protein per serving rather than protein per calorie. For instance, the USDA lists 6 grams of protein per large whole egg (a 50-gram serving) rather than 84&nbsp;mg of protein per calorie (71 calories total).<ref>{{cite book |title=SDA National Nutrient Database for Standard Reference |date=2008 |publisher=U.S. Department of Agriculture, Agricultural Research Service |edition=Release 21}}</ref> For comparison, there are 2.8 grams of protein in a serving of raw broccoli (100 grams) or 82&nbsp;mg of protein per calorie (34 calories total), or the [[Daily Value]] of 47.67g of protein after eating 1,690g of raw broccoli a day at 574 cal.<ref name=Broccoli>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nutritionvalue.org/Broccoli%2C_raw_nutritional_value.html |title=Broccoli, raw: nutritional value and analysis |last=Vanovschi |first=Vitalii |website=www.nutritionvalue.org |access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref> An egg contains 12.5g of protein per 100g, but 4&nbsp;mg more protein per calorie, or the protein DV after 381g of egg, which is 545 cal.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nutritionvalue.org/Egg%2C_poached%2C_cooked%2C_whole_nutritional_value.html |title=Egg, poached, cooked, whole: nutritional value and analysis |last=Vanovschi |first=Vitalii |website=www.nutritionvalue.org |access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref> The ratio of essential amino acids (the quality of protein) is not taken into account, one would actually need to eat more than 3&nbsp;kg of broccoli a day to have a healthy protein profile, and almost 6&nbsp;kg to get enough calories.<ref name=Broccoli/> It is recommended that adult humans obtain between 10\u201335% of their 2000 calories a day as protein.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.webmd.com/food-recipes/protein |title=Web MD Protein: Are You Getting Enough? |publisher=webmd.com |date=2014-09-05 |accessdate=2015-03-31}}</ref>\n\n==Complete proteins in non-human animals==\nScientists had known since the early 20th century that rats could not survive on a diet whose only protein source was [[zein]], which comes from [[maize]] (corn), but recovered if they were fed [[casein]] from cow's milk. This led [[William Cumming Rose]] to the discovery of the essential amino acid [[threonine]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Rose WC, Haines WJ, Warner DT, Johnson JE |title=The amino acid requirements of man. II. The role of threonine and histidine |journal=The Journal of Biological Chemistry |volume=188 |issue=1 |pages=49\u201358 |pmid=14814112 |year=1951}}</ref> Through manipulation of rodent diets, Rose was able to show that ten amino acids are essential for rats: [[lysine]], [[tryptophan]], [[histidine]], [[phenylalanine]], [[leucine]], [[isoleucine]], [[methionine]], [[valine]], and [[arginine]], in addition to threonine. Rose's later work showed that eight amino acids are essential for adult human beings, with histidine also being essential for infants. Longer-term studies established histidine as also essential for adult humans.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Kopple JD, Swendseid ME |date=May 1975 |title=Evidence that histidine is an essential amino acid in normal and chronically uremic man. |journal=J Clin Invest |volume=55 |issue=5 |pages=881\u2013891 |pmid=1123426 |pmc=301830 |doi=10.1172/JCI108016}}</ref>\n\n==Interchangeability==\nThe distinction between essential and non-essential amino acids is somewhat unclear, as some amino acids can be produced from others. The [[sulfur]]-containing amino acids, [[methionine]] and [[homocysteine]], can be converted into each other but neither can be synthesized ''de novo'' in humans. Likewise, cysteine can be made from homocysteine but cannot be synthesized on its own. So, for convenience, sulfur-containing amino acids are sometimes considered a single pool of nutritionally equivalent amino acids as are the [[aromatic]] amino acid pair, [[phenylalanine]] and [[tyrosine]]. Likewise [[arginine]], [[ornithine]], and [[citrulline]], which are interconvertible by the [[urea cycle]], are considered a single group.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n==Effects of deficiency==\n{{Main|Protein-energy malnutrition}}\nIf one of the essential amino acids is less than needed for an individual the utilization of other amino acids will be hindered and thus protein synthesis will be less than adequate.<ref name=\"DRI\" /> Protein deficiency has been shown to affect all of the body's organs and many of its systems, including the brain and brain function of infants and young children; the immune system, thus elevating risk of infection; gut [[mucosal]] function and permeability, which affects absorption and vulnerability to [[systemic disease]]; and kidney function.<ref name=\"DRI\" /> The physical signs of protein deficiency include edema, failure to thrive in infants and children, poor musculature, dull skin, and thin and fragile hair. Biochemical changes reflecting protein deficiency include low [[serum albumin]] and low [[serum transferrin]].<ref name=\"DRI\" />\n\nThe amino acids that are essential in the human diet were established in a series of experiments led by [[William Cumming Rose]]. The experiments involved elemental diets to healthy male graduate students. These diets consisted of [[Corn starch|cornstarch]], [[sucrose]], [[butterfat]] without protein, [[corn oil]], inorganic salts, the known [[vitamin]]s, a large brown \"candy\" made of liver extract flavored with [[peppermint oil]] (to supply any unknown vitamins), and mixtures of highly purified individual amino acids. The main outcome measure was [[nitrogen balance]]. Rose noted that the symptoms of nervousness, exhaustion, and dizziness were encountered to a greater or lesser extent whenever human subjects were deprived of an essential amino acid.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Rose |first1=WC |last2=Haines |first2=WJ |last3=Warner |first3=DT |title=The amino acid requirements of man. III. The role of isoleucine; additional evidence concerning histidine |journal=J Biol Chem |year=1951 |volume=193 |issue=2 |pages=605\u2013612 |url=http://www.jbc.org/content/193/2/605.full.pdf |accessdate=15 Dec 2012 |pmid=14907749}}</ref>\n\nEssential amino [[acid]] deficiency should be distinguished from [[protein-energy malnutrition]], which can manifest as [[marasmus]] or [[kwashiorkor]]. [[Kwashiorkor]] was once attributed to pure protein deficiency in individuals who were consuming enough [[calorie]]s (\"sugar baby syndrome\"). However, this theory has been challenged by the finding that there is no difference in the diets of children developing [[marasmus]] as opposed to kwashiorkor.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Ahmed T, Rahman S, Cravioto A |title=Oedematous malnutrition |journal=The Indian Journal of Medical Research |volume=130 |issue=5 |pages=651\u20134 |pmid=20090122 |year=2009}}</ref> Still, for instance in [[Dietary Reference Intake]]s (DRI) maintained by the [[USDA]], lack of one or more of the essential amino acids is described as [[protein-energy malnutrition]].<ref name=\"DRI\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Biological Value|Biological Value (BV)]]\n*[[Edible protein per unit area of land]]\n*[[Essential fatty acid]]\n*[[Essential genes]]\n*[[List of standard amino acids]]\n*[[Low-protein diet]]\n*[[Orthomolecular medicine]]\n*[[PDCAAS|Protein Digestibility Corrected Amino Acid Score]]\n*[[Ketogenic amino acid]]\n*[[Glucogenic amino acid]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Essential amino acids}}\n*[http://www.veganhealth.org/articles/protein Amino acid content of some vegetarian foods] at veganhealth.org.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050319163510/http://www.dasc.vt.edu/extension/nutritioncc/9729.html Amino Acid Profiles of Some Common Feeds] at [[Virginia Tech]].\n*[http://micro.magnet.fsu.edu/aminoacids/index.html Molecular Expressions: The Amino Acid Collection] at [[Florida State University]]. Features detailed information and crystal photographs of each amino acid.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120202075048/http://foodwiki.com/vprotein vProtein], an online software tool to analyze the essential amino acid profiles of single and pairs of plant based foods based on human requirements.\n\n{{Amino acids}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Essential Amino Acid}}\n[[Category:Amino acids]]\n[[Category:Essential amino acids| ]]\n[[Category:Nitrogen cycle]]\n[[Category:Nutrition]]\n", "name_user": "2601:3c0:4304:9620:e9c7:b2dc:471e:2f0a", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEssentiality in humans)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Essential_amino_acid"}
{"title_page": "Chanell Stone", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name             = Chanell Stone\n| birth_date       = [[1992]]\n| birth_place      = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n| nationality      = American\n| field            = [[Photography]]\n| alma_mater       = [[California College of the Arts]]\n                   and [[Los Angeles Trade-Technical College]]\n| awards           = 2020 Artist in Residence, Real Time and Space\n2019-2020 Emerging Artist Award, [[Museum of the African Diaspora]], San Francisco\n2018-2019  Purchase Prize Award, [[Center for Photography at Woodstock]]\n| website          = {{URL|https://www.chanellstone.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Chanell Stone''' is an African American [[photographer]] living and working in [[Oakland, California]] known for her \"[https://www.chanellstone.com/natura-negra Natura Negra]\" series.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nStone\u00a0received a [[Bachelor of Fine Arts|B.F.A.]] in [[photography]] from [[California College of the Arts]] in 2019. She received an [[associate degree]] in [[English language|English]] from [[Los Angeles Trade-Technical College]] in 2017. \n\n== Work ==\nChanell Stone's work predominantly features black and white self-portraits. She first took an [[analog photography]] class in high school<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/young-photographers-to-follow-2020/|title=These Are the 8 Young Photographers to Follow in 2020|website=W Magazine {{!}} Women's Fashion & Celebrity News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> and continues to use film in her practice, primarily shooting with a Pentax.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nStone was a featured photographer in [[W (magazine)|W Magazine]]'s \"These Are the 8 Young Photographers to Follow in 2020\".<ref name=\":0\" />  She attributes her interest in representation and self-portraiture to growing up with social media, namely [[Myspace]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nHer series \"Natura Negra\" explores the connection of black bodies and nature, specifically the nature that can be found in dense cities<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/arts/13873630/the-faces-and-conversations-of-moads-winter-2020-opening-reception|title=The Faces and Conversations of MoAD's Winter Opening Reception|website=KQED|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> or what she refers to as \"urban nature\".<ref name=\":0\" /> This series sets out to reclaim and reconnect black bodies to nature, even if it is in an urban setting.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.moadsf.org/exhibition/moad-emerging-artists-presents-chanell-stone/|title=MoAD Emerging Artists presents Chanell Stone|website=MoAD Museum of African Diaspora|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> \"Natura Negra\" won her an emerging artist award from the [[Museum of the African Diaspora]] in San Francisco.\n\nStone has also worked as an editorial photographer for the [[The California Sunday Magazine|California Sunday Magazine]], documenting a family affected by the [[Camp Fire (2018)|Camp Fire]] in Paradise, California in 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://story.californiasunday.com/escape-paradise-fires|title=High School Students Escape the Paradise Fire|date=2019-10-03|website=The California Sunday Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>.\n\n== Awards and fellowships ==\nAmong the honors which Stone has earned are:\n\n2020 Artist in Residence, Real Time and Space<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.realtimeandspace.org/residency-2/|title=REAL TIME & SPACE {{!}} RESIDENCY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n2019-2020 Emerging Artist Award, [[Museum of the African Diaspora]] San Francisco<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moadsf.org/connect/emerging-artists-program/|title=Emerging Artists Program|website=MoAD Museum of African Diaspora|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n2018-2019\u00a0 Purchase Prize Award, [[Center for Photography at Woodstock]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cpw.org/news/about-photography-now-2018/|title=CPW \u2014 Photography Now 2018|website=www.cpw.org|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n2018-2019\u00a0 Kate V. and Harry W. Davies Memorial Scholarship, California College of the Arts\n\n2017-2019\u00a0 Diversity Scholarship, California College of the Arts\n\n2017-2019\u00a0 Faculty Honors Scholarship, California College of the Arts\n\n== Selected exhibitions ==\nStone\u2019s work has been featured in exhibitions at numerous galleries and institutions including:\n\n*[http://www.berkeleyartcenter.org/ Berkeley Art Center], Berkeley, CA \u201cExperiments in the Field: Creative Collaboration in the Age of Ecological Concern\u201d (2020)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mutualart.com/Exhibition/Experiments-in-the-Field--Creative-Colla/D74EE38665E0BFEA|title=MutualArt.com - The Web's Largest Art Information Service.|website=www.mutualart.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n*[[Museum of the African Diaspora]], San Francisco, CA, \u201cNatura Negra\u201d (2020)<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n* [[Aperture Foundation]], New York, NY, \u201cAperture Summer Open: Delirious Cities\u201d (2019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aperture.org/exhibition/2019-summer-open-delirious-cities/|title=2019 Summer Open: Delirious Cities, July 25 - August 29, 2019|website=Aperture Foundation NY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n* [[SF Camerawork]], San Francisco, CA, \u201cForecast\u201d (2019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sfcamerawork.org/forecast-2019|title=Forecast 2019|website=SF Camerawork|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n*[https://www.hitgallerysf.com/ Hit Gallery], San Francisco, CA, \u201cBrass Tacks\u201d (2019)\n\n*[http://www.kala.org/ Kala Art Institute], Berkeley, CA, \u201cPoetics of Conflict\u201d (2018)\n\n* [[Center for Photography at Woodstock]], Woodstock, NY, \u201cPhotography Now\u201d (2018)\n\n*[https://www.oygprojects.com/ Ortega y Gasset Projects], Brooklyn, NY, \u201cVice Versa\u201d (2018)\n\n== Collections ==\nStone's work is held in collections including:\n\n* [[Center for Photography at Woodstock]], Woodstock, NY\n\n* Meyer Library: Artist Book Collection, Oakland, CA\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Official site|https://www.chanellstone.com/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stone, Chanell}}\n[[Category:American contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:American photographers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women artists]]\n[[Category:Artists from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:California College of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name             = Chanell Stone\n| birth_date       = [[1992]]\n| birth_place      = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n| nationality      = American\n| field            = [[Photography]]\n| alma_mater       = [[California College of the Arts]]\n                   and [[Los Angeles Trade-Technical College]]\n| awards           = 2020 Artist in Residence, Real Time and Space\n2019-2020 Emerging Artist Award, [[Museum of the African Diaspora]], San Francisco\n2018-2019  Purchase Prize Award, [[Center for Photography at Woodstock]]\n| website          = {{URL|https://www.chanellstone.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Chanell Stone''' is an African American [[photographer]] living and working in [[Oakland, California]] known for her \"[https://www.chanellstone.com/natura-negra Natura Negra]\" series.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nStone\u00a0received a [[Bachelor of Fine Arts|B.F.A.]] in [[photography]] from [[California College of the Arts]] in 2019. She received an [[associate degree]] in [[English language|English]] from [[Los Angeles Trade-Technical College]] in 2017. \n\n== Work ==\nChanell Stone's work predominantly features black and white self-portraits. She first took an [[analog photography]] class in high school<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/young-photographers-to-follow-2020/|title=These Are the 8 Young Photographers to Follow in 2020|website=W Magazine {{!}} Women's Fashion & Celebrity News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> and continues to use film in her practice, primarily shooting with a Pentax.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nStone was a featured photographer in [[W (magazine)|W Magazine]]'s \"These Are the 8 Young Photographers to Follow in 2020\".<ref name=\":0\" />  She attributes her interest in representation and self-portraiture to growing up with social media, namely [[Myspace]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nHer series \"Natura Negra\" explores the connection of black bodies and nature, specifically the nature that can be found in dense cities<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/arts/13873630/the-faces-and-conversations-of-moads-winter-2020-opening-reception|title=The Faces and Conversations of MoAD's Winter Opening Reception|website=KQED|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> or what she refers to as \"urban nature\".<ref name=\":0\" /> This series sets out to reclaim and reconnect black bodies to nature, even if it is in an urban setting.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.moadsf.org/exhibition/moad-emerging-artists-presents-chanell-stone/|title=MoAD Emerging Artists presents Chanell Stone|website=MoAD Museum of African Diaspora|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> \"Natura Negra\" won her an emerging artist award from the [[Museum of the African Diaspora]] in San Francisco.\n\nStone has also worked as an editorial photographer for the [[The California Sunday Magazine|California Sunday Magazine]], documenting a family affected by the [[Camp Fire (2018)|Camp Fire]] in Paradise, California in 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://story.californiasunday.com/escape-paradise-fires|title=High School Students Escape the Paradise Fire|date=2019-10-03|website=The California Sunday Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>.\n\n== Awards and fellowships ==\nAmong the honors which Stone has earned are:\n\n2020 Artist in Residence, Real Time and Space<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.realtimeandspace.org/residency-2/|title=REAL TIME & SPACE {{!}} RESIDENCY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n2019-2020 Emerging Artist Award, [[Museum of the African Diaspora]] San Francisco<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moadsf.org/connect/emerging-artists-program/|title=Emerging Artists Program|website=MoAD Museum of African Diaspora|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n2018-2019\u00a0 Purchase Prize Award, [[Center for Photography at Woodstock]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cpw.org/news/about-photography-now-2018/|title=CPW \u2014 Photography Now 2018|website=www.cpw.org|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n2018-2019\u00a0 Kate V. and Harry W. Davies Memorial Scholarship, California College of the Arts\n\n2017-2019\u00a0 Diversity Scholarship, California College of the Arts\n\n2017-2019\u00a0 Faculty Honors Scholarship, California College of the Arts\n\n== Selected exhibitions ==\nStone\u2019s work has been featured in exhibitions at numerous galleries and institutions including:\n\n*[http://www.berkeleyartcenter.org/ Berkeley Art Center], Berkeley, CA \u201cExperiments in the Field: Creative Collaboration in the Age of Ecological Concern\u201d (2020)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mutualart.com/Exhibition/Experiments-in-the-Field--Creative-Colla/D74EE38665E0BFEA|title=MutualArt.com - The Web's Largest Art Information Service.|website=www.mutualart.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n*[[Museum of the African Diaspora]], San Francisco, CA, \u201cNatura Negra\u201d (2020)<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n* [[Aperture Foundation]], New York, NY, \u201cAperture Summer Open: Delirious Cities\u201d (2019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aperture.org/exhibition/2019-summer-open-delirious-cities/|title=2019 Summer Open: Delirious Cities, July 25 - August 29, 2019|website=Aperture Foundation NY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n* [[SF Camerawork]], San Francisco, CA, \u201cForecast\u201d (2019)\n\n*[https://www