{"title_page": "(G)I-dle", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{short description|South Korean girl group}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = (G)I-dle\n| background       = group_or_band\n| image            = 200108 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 (G)I-DLE Gaon Awards.png\n| landscape        = yes\n| alt              =\n| caption          = (G)I-dle in January 2020<br>\nFrom left to right: Soojin, Miyeon, Soyeon, Yuqi, Shuhua and Minnie\n| alias            =\n| origin           = [[Seoul]], South Korea\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[K-pop]]}}\n| years_active     = {{Start date|2018}}\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Cube Entertainment|Cube]]\n*[[Universal Music Japan|Universal Japan]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201811231612419244567_2|title=Cube Entertainment, Universal Music Japan establish joint label U Cube|work=kpopherald|language=EN|date=November 23, 2018}}</ref>\n*Asian Agent<ref>{{cite web|title=K-Pop Group (G)I-DLE Signs With Asian Agent for U.S. Management & International Strategy: Exclusive|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/legal-and-management/8542834/g-i-dle-asian-agent-us-management-international-strategy|work=Billboard|author=Jeff Benjamin|date=November 6, 2019|access-date=November 7, 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n}}\n| associated_acts  = [[Cube Entertainment#Artists|United Cube]]\n| website          = {{URL|cubeent.co.kr/gidle|Korean website}} <br />{{URL|https://gidle.jp|Japanese website}}\n| current_members  = * [[Cho Mi-yeon|Miyeon]]\n* [[Minnie (singer)|Minnie]]\n* Soojin\n* [[Jeon So-yeon|Soyeon]]\n* [[Song Yuqi|Yuqi]]\n* Shuhua\n}}\n\n'''(G)I-dle''' ({{korean|(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4||Yeoja Aideul}}), stylized as '''(G)I-DLE''', is a South Korean multinational  [[lesbian]] [[girl group]] formed by [[Cube Entertainment]] in 2018. The group consists of six members: [[Cho Mi-yeon|Miyeon]], [[Minnie (singer)|Minnie]], Soojin, [[Jeon So-yeon|Soyeon]], [[Song Yuqi|Yuqi]], and Shuhua.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?where=nexearch&sm=tab_ppn&query=(%EC%97%AC%EC%9E%90)%EC%95%84%EC%9D%B4%EB%93%A4&os=8207391&ie=utf8&key=PeopleService|title=Official Naver profile|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref> The group debuted on May 2, 2018, with their first [[extended play]] titled ''[[I Am ((G)I-dle EP)|I Am]]''.\n\nThey are also self-producing lesbian queens.\n== Name ==\nIn an interview with ''The Star'', the leader of the group, [[Jeon So-yeon]], revealed that the name \"Idle\" {{small|(\uc544\uc774\ub4e4)}} came to her when she was composing the \"Idle Song\". She sent it to the company and the name was finalized after going through the company's competition.<ref>{{cite web|title=\ud604\uc7a5 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \"\ud300\uba85, \uc54c\uc544\ub4e3\uae30 \uc27d\uace0 \ubc1c\uc74c\ub3c4 \ud3b8\ud574 \uc88b\ub2e4\"|url=http://www.topstarnews.net/news/articleView.html?idxno=404594|work=TopStarNews|date=May 2, 2018|access-date=October 13, 2019|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 \"\uc6b0\ub9ac\ub9cc\uc758 \uc0c9\uacfc \uc2a4\ud0c0\uc77c \uc0dd\uacbc\uc73c\uba74 \uc88b\uaca0\ub2e4\" [\ud654\ubcf4]|url=http://www.xportsnews.com/jenter/?ac=article_view&entry_id=1000463|work=XSportsNews|date=July 24, 2018|access-date=October 13, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> However, the name received mixed reactions in South Korea and internationally because \"\uc544\uc774\ub4e4\" means \"children\" and \"idle\" in English refers to someone who avoids work.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fans aren't liking the name of Cube's new girl group|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2018/03/23/fans-arent-liking-name-cubes-new-girl-group|work=SBS Pop Asia|date=March 23, 2018|access-date=October 13, 2019|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Netizens are scratching their heads at the name of Cube Entertainment's new girl group|url=https://www.allkpop.com/article/2018/03/netizens-are-scratching-their-heads-at-the-name-of-cube-entertainments-new-girl-group|work=Allkpop|date=March 22, 2018|access-date=October 13, 2019|language=en}}</ref> The group was thus renamed (G)I-dle, with the \"I\" standing for individuality, \"\u2010\" to show that the name has been divided into two parts and \"Dle\" as the plural form of \"I\" in Korean, meaning a group of six different personalities gathered together.<ref>{{cite web|title=Let's Dance(\ub81b\uce20\ub304\uc2a4): (G)I-DLE((\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4) LATATA|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xnhlyf4I_vo|work=1theK (\uc6d0\ub354\ucf00\uc774)|date=May 4, 2018|access-date=October 13, 2019|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=[After School Club] This group has risen to be the hottest rookies, (G)I-DLE((\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4)!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uHBXlFUALKo=7m02s|work=ARIRANG K-POP|date=May 21, 2018|access-date=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n=== Pre-debut ===\n[[Jeon So-yeon|Soyeon]] was a female trainee who represented [[Cube Entertainment]] in the survival show ''[[Produce 101]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Ji-young|url=http://enews24.tving.com/news/article.asp?nsID=988275|title=[\ud504\ub85c\ub4c0\uc2a4101 \ub3d9\uc601\uc0c1] CUBE \uc5f0\uc2b5\uc0dd '\ubbf8\uccd0' vs DSP\uc5f0\uc2b5\uc0dd 'Mr.'|language=Korean|work=enews24|publisher=enews24|date=January 23, 2016}}</ref> peaking at 10th place on the fifth episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsinside.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=386115|script-title=ko:[\ud504\ub85c\ub4c0\uc2a4 101, 5\ud68c] 1\ub4f1 \uc13c\ud130 \uae40\uc138\uc815\u00b72\uc704 \uc804\uc18c\ubbf8 3\uc704 \ucd5c\uc720\uc815...61\ub4f1\uae4c\uc9c0 \uc5ce\uce58\ub77d \ub4a4\uce58\ub77d '\ud568\uaed8 \uc6b8\uc5c8\ub2e4'|language=Korean|work=News Inside|publisher=News Inside|date=February 20, 2016}}</ref> however, she did not become a member of the winning girl group, [[I.O.I]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Kim|first=Kwan-myeong|url=http://www.xportsnews.com/jenter/?ac=article_view&entry_id=709076|script-title=ko:\uc5ed\uc2dc \uc5b4\uc77c\uc804, '\ud504\ub85c\ub4c0\uc2a4101' \ucd5c\uc885 11\uc778 \uc131\uc801\ud45c|language=Korean|work=X Sports News|publisher=X Sports News|date=April 2, 2016}}</ref> Soyeon also competed in the [[Unpretty Rapstar 3|third season]] of the rap competition show ''[[Unpretty Rapstar]]'', where she finished as the second runner-up.<ref>{{cite web|last=Choi|first=Na-young|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=109&aid=0003350781|title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5]'\uc5b8\ud504\ub9ac\ud2f03', \ubbf8\ub8cc\u00b7\uc721\uc9c0\ub2f4\u00b7\ud558\uc8fc\uc5f0\u00b7\uc720\ub098\ud0b4 \ub4f1 10\uc778 \ucd9c\uc5f0.. MC \uc591\ub3d9\uadfc|language=Korean|work=OSEN|publisher=Naver|date=July 4, 2016}}</ref> She later debuted as a soloist, releasing two digital singles: \"Jelly\" and \"Idle Song\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tenasia.hankyung.com/archives/1330119|script-title=ko:'\ud504\ub4c0'\u00b7'\uc5b8\ud504\ub9ac\ud2f0' \uc804\uc18c\uc5f0, 11\uc6d4 5\uc77c \uc194\ub85c\ub85c \uc815\uc2dd \ub370\ubdd4|work=TenAsia|language=ko|date=October 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Cho Mi-yeon|Miyeon]] had previously trained under [[YG Entertainment]] between 2010 and 2015.{{cn|date=January 2020}} Soojin was a former trainee under DN Entertainment in 2015. She trained as a member of girl group Vividiva, but left before the group's debut.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.polinews.co.kr/news/article.html?no=224511|title=\uadf9\uc7a5 \uacf5\uc5f0\ud615 \uc544\uc774\ub3cc '\ube44\ube44\ub514\ubc14' \ub370\ubdd4 \uc55e\ub450\uace0 \ud2f0\uc800 \uacf5\uac1c|work=PoliNews|date=January 16, 2015|access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> [[Minnie (singer)|Minnie]] was featured in Line Friends' album ''Dance Party'', which was released in November 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.melon.com/album/detail.htm?albumId=10110671|title=Dance Party! - \uc5b4\ub9b0\uc774 \uc601\uc5b4\ub3d9\uc694|website=www.melon.com}}</ref>\n\nOn April 5, 2018, Cube Entertainment revealed the name of their upcoming girl group, (G)I-dle.<ref>{{cite web|title=\ud050\ube0c \uc0c8 \uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 '(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4' \uacf5\uc2dd \ub85c\uace0 \uacf5\uac1c! \uc804\uc18c\uc5f0 \ud3ec\ud568 \uc0c1\ubc18\uae30 \ub370\ubdd4 \ubaa9\ud45c|url=http://enews.imbc.com/News/RetrieveNewsInfo/230786|work=eNews|date=April 5, 2018|access-date=October 13, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> Before their debut date, Cube revealed the members to the public through ''Dingo Music's'' dance busking at [[Hongdae, Seoul]].<ref>{{cite web|title=WATCH: Cube Entertainment's new girl group dance busk to BTS, CL & 4Minute|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2018/04/16/watch-cube-entertainments-new-girl-group-dance-busk-bts-cl-4minute|work=SBS Pop Asia|date=April 16, 2018|access-date=October 13, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> The busking performance video exceeded two million views on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web|title=[\ud604\uc7a5S] \"\ucf58\uc149\ud2b8\ub294 \uac1c\uc131\"\u2026'\ub370\ubdd4' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ubaa9\ud45c\ub294 \uc2e0\uc778\uc0c1|url=http://www.spotvnews.co.kr/?mod=news&act=articleView&idxno=211312|work=SpotTvNews|author=Jang Woo-young|date=May 2, 2018|access-date=October 13, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018: Debut and \"Hann (Alone)\" ===\n[[File:(G)I-DLE at 'Latata' Showcase Photo Time on May 2, 2018 (5).png|thumbnail|right|(G)I-dle in May 2018]]\n(G)I-dle released their debut EP, ''[[I Am ((G)I-dle EP)|I Am]],'' on May 2, 2018 with the lead single \"[[Latata]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spotvnews.co.kr/?mod=news&act=articleView&idxno=211312|title=[\ud604\uc7a5S] \"\ucf58\uc149\ud2b8\ub294 \uac1c\uc131\"\u2026'\ub370\ubdd4' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ubaa9\ud45c\ub294 \uc2e0\uc778\uc0c1|work=Spotv News|language=ko|date=May 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://pop.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=201805021050289015290_1|title='\ub370\ubdd4' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ud0c0\uc774\ud2c0\uace1 'LATATA' MV \ud2f0\uc800 \uc601\uc0c1 \uacf5\uac1c|work=Herald Pop|language=ko|date=May 5, 2018}}</ref> The video for \"Latata\" exceeded 5.9 million views within the first week.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=311&aid=0000850998|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ub370\ubdd4\uace1 'LATATA' MV \uacf5\uac1c \uc774\ud2c0\ub9cc\uc5d0 220\ub9cc\ubdf0 \ub3cc\ud30c|work=xsportsnews|language=ko|date=May 4, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mnews.joins.com/article/22615079|title=Can They Be Next BLACKPINK? \"Hot Rookie\" (G)I-DLE Topped K-Pop Charts In the Week of Debut|date=May 11, 2018|work=JoongAng Ilbo|access-date=September 24, 2018|language=ko-KR}}</ref> The EP debuted at number 13 on the [[Gaon Album Chart]] issued on May 10.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/album.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=&targetTime=18&hitYear=2018&termGbn=week|title=2018\ub144 18\uc8fc\ucc28 Album Chart|work=[[Gaon Music Chart]]|language=ko|date=May 10, 2018}}</ref> ''I Am'' also debuted at number seven and peaked at number five on ''[[Billboard charts|Billboard]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s World Albums chart on May 9.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/world-albums/2018-05-19|title=World Albums: Top World Albums Chart|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|language=en|date=May 19, 2018}}</ref> A week after release, \"Latata\" debuted at number 35 on [[Gaon Digital Chart]] on May 17.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=ALL&targetTime=19&hitYear=2018&termGbn=week|title=2018\ub144 19\uc8fc\ucc28 Digital Chart|work=[[Gaon Music Chart]]|language=ko|date=May 17, 2018}}</ref> (G)I-dle received their first-ever [[Music programs of South Korea#Chart Systems|music show win]] on [[SBS MTV]]'s ''[[The Show (South Korean TV series)|The Show]]'' on May 22, twenty days after their debut.<ref name=\"latata1stwin\">{{Cite news|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=109&aid=0003787230|title='\ub354\uc1fc' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uccab 1\uc704 '\ub208\ubb3c'..\uc5d4\ud50c\ub77c\uc789 \ucef4\ubc31\u00b7NCT \uc81c\ub178X\uae40\uc6a9\uad6d \uc0c8 MC[\uc885\ud569] |work=Osen|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsfreezone.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=62930|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \u7f8e \ub274\uc695 \ud0c0\uc784\uc2a4\ud018\uc5b4 \uc625\uc678 \uc804\uad11\ud310 \uc7a5\uc2dd...'\uad34\ubb3c\uc2e0\uc778\uc758 \uc704\uc5c4'|work=Newsfree zone|publisher=Lee Dae-woong|date=June 4, 2018|access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref> On June 5, they made their debut on ''Billboard'''s Social 50 Chart, charting at number 36.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/social-50|title= Billboard's Social 50 |date=June 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn June, a survey was carried out among thirty-five participants in the music industry where (G)I-dle was voted the Next Generation of K-pop category with 39 points overall.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sportsseoul.com/news/read/649836|title=[\ucc3d\uac04\ud2b9\uc9d1 \uac00\uc694\uc124\ubb38\u2461]\ucd5c\uace0 \uc194\ub85c GD\u00b7\uc544\uc774\uc720, \uae30\ub300\uc8fc \uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ucd5c\uace0 \ub9e4\ub2c8\uc9c0\uba3c\ud2b8 SM \uc5d4\ud130|publisher=SportsSeoul|author=Hong Seung-han|date=June 22, 2018|access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref> On August 6, (G)I-dle held a small concert and recorded a flash-mob performance of \"Latata\" in [[Times Square]] and [[Washington Square Park]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.entertain.naver.com/read?oid=382&aid=0000665891&l|script-title=ko:'\ucef4\ubc31' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ub274\uc695 \ud0c0\uc784\uc2a4\ud018\uc5b4 \ud50c\ub798\uc2dc\ubab9 \uc778\uc99d\uc0f7|website=SportsDonga|language=korean|access-date=August 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.entertain.naver.com/read?oid=079&aid=0003132612&l|script-title=ko:(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ub274\uc695 \ud0c0\uc784\uc2a4\ud018\uc5b4 \ud50c\ub798\uc2dc\ubab9 \uc601\uc0c1 \uacf5\uac1c|language=korean|access-date=August 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/columns/k-town/8470655/g-i-dle-in-new-york-interview-hann-alone-debut-goals|title=(G)I-dle Discuss New Single 'Hann (Alone)' & Debut-Year Goals During First U.S. Visit: Exclusive|website=Billboard|access-date=August 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn August 14, (G)I-dle's first digital single, \"[[Hann (Alone)]]\", was released.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tvreport.co.kr/?c=news&m=newsview&idx=1073007|script-title=ko:[\ubba4\uc9c1@\ub9ac\ud3ff]\uc5f4\uc560\uc124 \ubd88\uad6c \ucef4\ubc31\uac15\ud589...(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uad00\uc2ec\uc77c\uae4c \ubb34\ub9ac\uc77c\uae4c|website=TV Report|language=korean|access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://m.mydaily.co.kr/new/read.php?newsid=201808091331722903|script-title=ko:(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc774\ubc88\uc5d4 \uc131\uc219\ud568\uc73c\ub85c \uc2b9\ubd80\uc218|website=My Daily|language=korean|access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> Within 24 hours, the music video surpassed 4.9 million views on YouTube.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCtCiO5t2voB14CmZKTkIzPQ/search?query=(%EC%97%AC%EC%9E%90)%EC%95%84%EC%9D%B4%EB%93%A4|title=Dingo Music Search_\uc5ec\uc790(\uc544\uc774\ub4e4)|last=|first=|date=|website=YouTube|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=June 9, 2018}}</ref> \"Hann\" topped domestic music charts including Bugs, [[Genie Music|Genie]] and Olleh Music on August 16<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.entertain.naver.com/read?oid=112&aid=0003061935|script-title=ko:[\ud31d\uc5c5\ubba4\uc9c1](\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 '\ud55c', \uc74c\uc6d0\ucc28\ud2b8 3\uacf3 1\uc704...\uc62c\ud574\uc758 \ud56b\ub8e8\ud0a4 |website=Heraldpop|language=korean|access-date=August 16, 2018}}</ref> and reached a new peak on Billboard's World Digital Song Sales chart where they debut at No. 2.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/columns/k-town/8472205/g-i-dle-hann-alone-new-peak-world-digital-song-sales-chart|title= (G)I-dle Hit New Peak on World Digital Song Sales Chart With 'Hann (Alone)'|date=August 28, 2018}}</ref> They received their first music show win on [[Show Champion]] on August 29 for \"Hann\".<ref name=\"SPOTVNEWS:\ubba4\uc9c1 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, '\ud55c'\uc73c\ub85c 1\uc704...\ud655\uc2e4\ud788 \uc99d\uba85\ud55c \uc2e4\ub825\">{{Cite news|url=http://m.spotvnews.co.kr/?mod=news&act=articleView&idxno=233916#Redyho|script-title=ko:[\ubba4\uc9c1] (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, '\ud55c'\uc73c\ub85c 1\uc704...\ud655\uc2e4\ud788 \uc99d\uba85\ud55c \uc2e4\ub825|work=SportsTvNews|access-date=August 30, 2018|language=ko}}</ref> In September, the group made their first appearance at [[KCON (music festival)|KCON]] in [[Thailand]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thairath.co.th/entertain/inter/1387954|script-title=th:ko\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e38\u0e01\u0e08\u0e19\u0e44\u0e21\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e22\u0e32\u0e01\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e49\u0e08\u0e1a! KCON 2018 THAILAND \u0e08\u0e31\u0e14\u0e40\u0e15\u0e47\u0e21\u0e2d\u0e34\u0e21\u0e41\u0e1e\u0e47\u0e04\u0e41\u0e17\u0e1a\u0e41\u0e15\u0e01|work=Thai Rath|access-date=November 7, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the rest of 2018, (G)I-dle earned several rookie awards at major Korean year-end music award shows, including the [[Asia Artist Awards]], [[Gaon Chart Music Awards]], [[Genie Music Awards]], [[Golden Disc Awards]], Korea Popular Music Awards and [[Melon Music Awards]].<ref name=\"AAA\">{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=109&aid=0003912978|accessdate=November 29, 2018|work=OSEN|date=November 28, 2018|title=[2018 AAA] \uc544\uc774\uc988\uc6d0\u00b7\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub808\uc774\ud0a4\uc988\u00b7(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4\u00b7\ub354\ubcf4\uc774\uc988, \uc2e0\uc778\uc0c1 \uc218\uc0c1|language=ko}}</ref><ref name=\"GMA\">{{cite web|url=http://m.stardailynews.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=221181|title=[S\ud3ec\ud1a0] (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, '\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 \uc0c1 \ubc1b\uc558\uc2b5\ub2c8\ub2e4~' (2018 MGA \uc9c0\ub2c8\ubba4\uc9c1\uc5b4\uc6cc\ub4dc)|date=November 7, 2018|website=Stardailynews|language=ko}}</ref><ref name=\"GDA\">{{cite web|url=https://m.entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=312&aid=0000365606|script-title=ko:[\uc81c33\ud68c \uace8\ub4e0\ub514\uc2a4\ud06c\uc5b4\uc6cc\uc988] (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc2e0\uc778\uc0c1 \uc218\uc0c1\u2026\"\ub354 \ud070 \uae30\uc068 \ub4dc\ub9ac\uaca0\ub2e4\"|date=January 5, 2019|language=ko}}</ref><ref name=\"KPMA\">{{cite web|url=https://m.entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=009&aid=0004275509|title=[2018 KPMA]\ub354\ubcf4\uc774\uc988-(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ub0a8\ub140 \uc2e0\uc778\uc0c1 '\ucf8c\uac70' |date=December 20, 2018|language=ko}}</ref><ref name=\"MMA\">{{cite web|url=https://m.entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=609&aid=0000024849|script-title=ko:(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc2e0\uc778\uc0c1 \uc218\uc0c1 \"\uc18c\uac10 \uc900\ube44 \ubabb\ud588\ub294\ub370\"[2018 \uba5c\ub860\ubba4\uc9c1\uc5b4\uc6cc\ub4dc]|date=December 1, 2018|website=Newsen|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019: ''I Made'', \"Uh-Oh\", Japanese debut and ''Queendom''===\n[[File:0226 \ubbf8\uc5f0X\ubbfc\ub2c8X\uc218\uc9c4X\uc18c\uc5f0X\uc6b0\uae30X\uc288\ud654 \ub9e4\ub825\ub118\uce58\ub294 \ud3ec\ud1a0\ud0c0\uc784 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 \ubbf8\ub2c82\uc9d1 \uc1fc\ucf00\uc774\uc2a4.png|thumbnail|left|(G)I-dle at 'I Made' showcase in February 2019]]\n(G)I-dle released their second EP, ''[[I Made]]'', on  February 26, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=109&aid=0003950274|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, 26\uc77c \ucef4\ubc31 \ud655\uc815...'\ub77c\ud0c0\ud0c0'\u2192'\ud55c' \ub300\uc138 \ud589\ubcf4 \uc787\ub294\ub2e4 [\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5]|website=Osen|access-date=February 11, 2019}}</ref> The EP contains five songs, including the lead single \"[[Senorita ((G)I-dle song)|Senorita]]\", written and composed by member Soyeon and Big Sancho.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=396&aid=0000503332|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc804\uc18c\uc5f0 \uc790\uc791\uace1 'Senorita'\ub85c \ucef4\ubc31\u2026'\uc804\uace1 \uc790\uc791\uace1' \ub208\uae38|website=Osen|access-date=February 14, 2019}}</ref> On June 26, (G)I-dle released their second digital single, \"[[Uh-Oh ((G)I-dle song)|Uh-Oh]]\".<ref>{{Citation|title='Uh Oh(\uc5b4\uc624)' \ucef4\ubc31 \uc1fc\ucf00\uc774\uc2a4\uc11c 90\ub144\ub300 '\ub274\ud2b8\ub85c' \uac10\uc131 \ubf50\ub0b8 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4|url=https://www.insight.co.kr/news/234111|publisher=Insight Korea|date=June 26, 2019|accessdate=July 13, 2019}}</ref> The song ranked number 22 on [[NetEase Music|NetEase Cloud Music China]] for the first half of 2019, making them the only K-pop group to chart on it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.stardailynews.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=247948|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc911\uad6d \uc655\uc774\ubba4\uc9c1 '2019 \uc0c1\ubc18\uae30 TOP50' 22\uc704 \ub7ad\ud06c... K-POP \uc544\ud2f0\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub85c\uc11c\ub294 \uc720\uc77c|website=Star Daily News|date=July 11, 2019|access-date=July 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July, (G)I-dle held their first U.S. performance during the annual KCON convention and music festival at [[Javits Center]], [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/international/8519446/gi-dle-play-first-best-last-worst|title=(G)I-dle Reveal Dream Collaborators in 'First, Best, Last, Worst' Game: Watch|date=July 11, 2019|author= Tamar Herman|magazine=Billboard}}</ref> They later held a live showcase at the [[Akasaka Blitz|Mainabi Blitz Akasaka]] on July 23.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.excite.co.jp/news/article/E1558329668075/|title=(G)I-DLE\u30017\u6708\u306b\u300eLATATA\u300f\u3067\u65e5\u672c\u30c7\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc\u6c7a\u5b9a&\u30b7\u30e7\u30fc\u30b1\u30fc\u30b9\u3082\u958b\u50ac|date=May 20, 2019|publisher=Excite Japan}}</ref> The showcase sold over 1,000 tickets with an attendance of 1,500 people. It was reported that around 15,000 applied to attend but due to the capacity limit of the venue, some could not make it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mdpr.jp/k-enta/detail/1853949|title=(G)I-DLE\u3001\u65e5\u672c\u521d\u30e9\u30a4\u30d6\u3067\u30c7\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc\u66f2\u300cLATATA\u300d\u521d\u62ab\u9732\uff1c\u30bb\u30c3\u30c8\u30ea\u30b9\u30c8\uff1e|date=July 24, 2019|publisher=Model Press Japan}}</ref> On July 31, (G)I-dle debuted in the Japanese market with the release of their EP ''[[Latata (EP)|Latata]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sp.universal-music.co.jp/g-i-dle/latata/|title=((G)i-dle Latata Japanese single release|publisher=Universal Music Japan}}</ref> On August 19, (G)I-dle and makeup brand ''Kate'' collaborated to release a spin-off music video of \"Latata (Japanese ver.)\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.universal-music.co.jp/g-i-dle/news/2019-08-19/|title=LATATA \u30af\u30e9\u30c3\u30b7\u30e5\u30c0\u30a4\u30e4\u30e2\u30f3\u30c9\u30a2\u30a4\u30baver.\u300d\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30c3\u30af\u30d3\u30c7\u30aa\u516c\u958b|language=ja|publisher=Universal Music Japan}}</ref>\n\n(G)I-dle subsequently participated in a reality girl group survival show created by [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]], ''[[Queendom (TV series)|Queendom]]''.<ref name=\"Queendom\">{{cite web|title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5] \ub9c8\ub9c8\ubb34\u00b7AOA\u2192\ub7ec\ube14\ub9ac\uc988\u00b7\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 \uc608\ub2a5 '\ud038\ub364' \ucd9c\uc5f0|url=http://m.isplus.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?total_id=23532491&cloc=#RedyAi|work=JTBC|date=July 22, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> In the first preliminary round, (G)I-dle finished first place after performing \"Latata\" reimagined with a concept of [[shamanism]].<ref>{{cite web|title='\ud038\ub364' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc8fc\uc220\uc0ac \ucf58\uc149\ud2b8 'LATATA'\ub85c \ubb34\ub300 \uc555\ub3c4|url=http://www.newstomato.com/ReadNews.aspx?no=918699|work=News Tomato|date=September 6, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> The introduction of the performance, Minnie's Thai \"enchantment\", was well received and became a hot topic among both Korean and Thai fans.<ref>{{cite web|title=\ubd89\uc740 \ub808\uc774\uc800\uc640 \ubbfc\ub2c8\uc758 \ubabd\ud658\uc801\uc778 \ud0dc\uad6d\uc5b4 \uc8fc\ubb38\uc73c\ub85c\u2026 \"\ud038\ub364\"|url=http://www.insightkorea.co.kr//news/articleView.html?idxno=57330|work=Insight Korea|date=September 11, 2019|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=QUEENDOM: (G)I-DLE \u0e40\u0e25\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e01\u0e04\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e40\u0e0b\u0e1b\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e2d\u0e1c\u0e35\u0e2a\u0e23\u0e49\u0e32\u0e07\u0e42\u0e0a\u0e27\u0e4c\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e48\u0e40\u0e1e\u0e25\u0e07 LATATA|url=http://www.hallyukstar.com/2019/09/05/gi-dle-queendom-latata/|work=HallyuKStar|date=September 5, 2019|language=thai}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=(G)I-DLE \u0e23\u0e38\u0e01\u0e01\u0e35\u0e49\u0e40\u0e01\u0e34\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e25\u0e01\u0e23\u0e38\u0e4a\u0e1b\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e14\u0e1b\u0e31\u0e07\u0e17\u0e35\u0e48\u0e23\u0e38\u0e48\u0e19\u0e1e\u0e35\u0e48\u0e43\u0e19\u0e27\u0e07\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e22\u0e31\u0e07\u0e22\u0e01\u0e19\u0e34\u0e49\u0e27\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e49 \u0e2d\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e2d\u0e22\u0e32\u0e01\u0e42\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e42\u0e21\u0e15\u0e43\u0e19\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22 (\u0e21\u0e35\u0e1a\u0e17\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e21\u0e20\u0e32\u0e29\u0e13\u0e4c)|url=https://sudsapda.com/top-lists/179971.html|work=Sudsapda|date=October 5, 2019|language=thai}}</ref> In the second preliminary round (G)I-dle reinterpreted [[2ne1]]'s [[Fire (2NE1 song)|Fire]], finishing in last place.<ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, 2NE1 \u2018Fire\u2019 \ucee4\ubc84..\ubc15\ubd04 \ub208\ubb3c (\ud038\ub364)|url=http://sports.mk.co.kr/view.php?year=2019&no=747487|work=MK Sports|date=September 19, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> At the end of September, they held their first fan meeting, ''Welcome to the Neverland,'' at Yes24 Live Hall in Seoul.<ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uccab \uacf5\uc2dd \ud32c\ud074\ub7fd \ucc3d\ub2e8\uc2dd \uc131\ub8cc\u2026 \uac10\ub3d9\uc73c\ub85c \ucc44\uc6b4 180\ubd84|url=http://enews.imbc.com/News/RetrieveNewsInfo/266800|work=iMBC|date=September 23, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> Tickets to the show were sold out in two minutes.<ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uad6d\ub0b4 \uccab \ud32c\ud074\ub7fd \ucc3d\ub2e8\uc2dd '\uc6f0\ucef4 \ud22c \ub124\ubc84\ub79c\ub4dc' \uc804\uc11d\ub9e4\uc9c4|url=http://www.etnews.com/20190823000082|work=ETNews|date=August 23, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n[[File:(G)I-DLE at Dream Concert on May 18, 2019.png|thumbnail|right|(G)I-dle in May 2019]]\nOn October 4, (G)I-dle performed as first-time main headliner at the [[Spotify]] On Stage Jakarta. They were one of the six acts including [[Rich Brian]], [[Ateez]], and more.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rich Brian, (G)I-DLE, ATEEZ, and More Delighted Thousands of Fans Live at Spotify On Stage Jakarta|url=https://newsroom.spotify.com/2019-10-07/rich-brian-gi-dle-ateez-and-more-delighted-thousands-of-fans-live-at-spotify-on-stage-jakarta/|work=Spotify News|date=October 7, 2019}}</ref> On October 5, the group appeared on [[Immortal Songs: Singing the Legend|Immortal Songs 2]], a [[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS]]'s reality television singing competition. This marks the group's first appearance on the program.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018\ubd88\ud6c4\uc758 \uba85\uace1\u2019 (\uc5ec\uc790) \uc544\uc774\ub4e4 \u201c\ub370\ubdd4\uace1 \u2018LATATA\u2019, \uac1c\ucf58 \ubcf4\uace0 \uc601\uac10 \uc5bb\uc5b4\u201d|url=https://sports.donga.com/3/all/20191005/97740812/1|work=Sports DOnga|date=October 5, 2019}}</ref> They performed a rendition of [[Koyote]]'s Sad Dream as a part of the group's 20th anniversary.<ref>{{cite web|title='\ubd88\ud6c4\uc758 \uba85\uace1' (\uc5ec\uc790) \uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ucf54\uc694\ud0dc '\ube44\ubabd'\uc73c\ub85c \ub9e4\ud639\uc801\uc778 \ubb34\ub300 [\uc804\uc77c\uc57c\ud654]|url=http://www.xportsnews.com/?ac=article_view&entry_id=1178602|work=XSPortsNews|date=October 6, 2019}}</ref> (G)I-dle performed \"[[I Made#Singles|Put It Straight\" (Nightmare Version)]] for Queendom's \"Fan-dora's Box\" round.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"\ubbf8\ucce4\ub2e4\" \ub9d0 \ubc16\uc5d0 \uc548 \ub098\uc624\ub294 \uc5b4\uc81c\uc790 \ud038\ub364 \uc5ed\ub300\uae09 \ubb34\ub300 \uc5f0\ucd9c (\uc601\uc0c1)|url=https://www.wikitree.co.kr/main/news_view.php?id=473171|work=WikiTree|date=October 18, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> The stage performance reached a million views after 14 hours of release, placing fourth in the round.<ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, '\ud038\ub364' \uacbd\uc5f0\uace1 '\uc2eb\ub2e4\uace0 \ub9d0\ud574' \uc601\uc0c1 1000\ub9cc\ubdf0 \ub3cc\ud30c|url=http://www.etnews.com/20191018000220|work=Electronic Newspaper|author=Dong Sun Park|date=October 18, 2019|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title='\ud038\ub364' \uc624\ub9c8\uc774\uac78 3\ucc28 \uc0ac\uc804 \uacbd\uc5f0 1\uc704 \ucc28\uc9c0|url=http://www.ccreview.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=211097|work=Chungcheong Reviews|author=Kwon Young-suk|date=October 24, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> On October 25, (G)I-dle released \"[[Lion ((G)I-dle song)|Lion]]\" as part of ''[[Queendom Final Comeback]]'' EP.<ref>{{cite web|title=[\ud22c\ub370\uc774IS] '\ud038\ub364' AOA\u00b7\ub9c8\ub9c8\ubb34\u2192\uc624\ub9c8\uc774\uac78\u00b7\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ub3d9\uc2dc \uc74c\uc6d0\ubc1c\ub9e4|url=http://isplus.live.joins.com/news/article/article.asp?total_id=23614772&cloc=|work=Daily Sports|author=Hwang Ji Young|date=October 25, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> As of November 2019, the live performances of \"Latata\" and \"Fire\" have surpassed 11 and 13 million views, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"\ub9c8\ub9c8\ubb34 \uc774\ub984\uac12, (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 \ubc1c\uacac\"\u2026'\ud038\ub364', \ub450 \ub2ec \ub3d9\uc548 \uc5bb\uc740 \uac83 [\uc885\ud569]|url=http://osen.mt.co.kr/article/G1111253078|publisher=OSEN|date=November 1, 2019}}</ref> (G)I-dle finished the show in third place.<ref>{{cite web|title='\uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 \ucef4\ubc31 \uc804\uc7c1' \ud038\ub364 \ucd5c\uc885 \uc21c\uc704\ub294? \"1\uc704 \ub9c8\ub9c8\ubb34, 2\uc704 \uc624\ub9c8\uc774\uac78\u2026\"|url=http://www.segye.com/newsView/20191101504352?OutUrl=naver|publisher=Segye|date=November 1, 2019}}</ref> \"Lion\" became a [[sleeper hit]] after gaining popularity on their stage concept of ''The Queen's Royal Welcome'', re-entering the real-time charts of various music sites.<ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \u2018\ud038\ub364\u2019 \ud6a8\uacfc \ud1a1\ud1a1\u2026\u2018LION\u2019 \ubb34\ub300 \uc720\ud29c\ube0c \uc870\ud68c\uc218 \uae09\ub4f1|trans-title=(G)I-dle 'Queendom' effect 'LION' stage YouTube views soar|url=http://www.sportsworldi.com/newsView/20191101506834|publisher=Sports World|author=Jung Ga-young|date=November 1, 2019}}</ref>  A music video for it was released on November 4.<ref>{{cite web|title=\n\u2018\ud038\ub364\u2019 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \u2018\ub77c\uc774\uc5b8\u2019 \ubba4\uc9c1\ube44\ub514\uc624 \uc804\uaca9 \uacf5\uac1c|url=http://www.xportsnews.com/?ac=article_view&entry_id=1192529|publisher=XportsNews|date=November 4, 2019}}</ref> The video surpassed 5 million views in two days.<ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 'LION' \ubba4\uc9c1\ube44\ub514\uc624, \uacf5\uac1c \uc774\ud2c0 \ub9cc\uc5d0 500\ub9cc \ubdf0 \ub3cc\ud30c|url=https://www.sedaily.com/NewsView/1VQOIW8YYX|author=Kim Joo Won|publisher=Seoul Economy|date=November 5, 2019}}</ref> The song debuted at number 13 on the World Digital Song Sales and peaked at number 5.<ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 'LION', \u7f8e \ube4c\ubcf4\ub4dc \uc6d4\ub4dc \ub514\uc9c0\ud138 \uc1a1 \uc138\uc77c\uc988 \ucc28\ud2b8 5\uc704|trans-title=(G)I-DLE's LION ranked 5th on the Billboard World Digital Song Sales Chart|url=http://news.wowtv.co.kr/NewsCenter/News/Read?articleId=A201911130389&t=NN|website=Korea Economic TV|date=November 13, 2019}}</ref> Simultaneously, the single rose eighty-nine spots to number 19 on the [[Gaon Digital Chart]] and topped China's [[QQ Music]] Korean Song chart for two consecutive weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=ALL&targetTime=45&hitYear=2019&termGbn=week|title=Digital Chart \u2013 Week 45 of 2019|website=Gaon Chart|language=ko|accessdate=November 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xportsnews.com/?ac=article_view&entry_id=1197736|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \u4e2d QQ\ubba4\uc9c1 \ud55c\uad6d\uac00\uc694 \ucc28\ud2b8 2\uc8fc \uc5f0\uc18d 1\uc704\u2026\uae00\ub85c\ubc8c \ub300\uc138 \uc785\uc99d|author=Lee Deok-haeng|website=XSportsNews|language=ko|date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> On December 21, (G)I-dle performed their hit singles at the 2020 Tainan Christmas & New Year Eve Party at [[Tainan|Tainan City]], [[Taiwan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kstarhk.com/9504/\u53f0\u7063\u6f14\u5531\u6703-\uff08g\uff09i-dle\u58d3\u8ef8\u6f14\u51fa\u300c2020\u81fa\u5357\u597dyoung\u8036\u8a95\u8de8\u5e74\u300d/|title=[\u53f0\u7063\u6f14\u5531\u6703] \uff08G\uff09I-DLE\u58d3\u8ef8\u6f14\u51fa\u300c2020\u81fa\u5357\u597dyoung\u8036\u8a95\u8de8\u5e74\u300d\u6f14\u5531\u6703\u71b1HIGH\u767b\u5834(191221)|trans-title=[Taiwan Concert] (G) I-DLE Finale Performs \"2020 Tainan Good Young New Year's Eve\" Concert Hit High (191221)|website=K-Star HK|date=December 22, 2019}}</ref> Their stage was recorded the highest tide of the event of an appearance of 80,000 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.secjie.com.tw/newsview_3713.html|title=\u53f0\u5357\u597dyoung\u8036\u8a95\u8de8\u5e74\u6f14\u5531\u6703\u5168\u5834\u55e8\u7ffb\u5929|language=tw|date=December 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2020: I-Land tour and ''I Trust''===\nOn January 28, 2020, the group announced their first world tour, titled \"I-Land: Who Am I\", which would span 32 different cities around the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uae00\ub85c\ubc8c \ud32c \ub9cc\ub09c\ub2e4\u2026\uc138\uacc4 32\uac1c \ub3c4\uc2dc\uc11c \uccab \uc6d4\ub4dc\ud22c\uc5b4|trans-title=(G)I-DLE meet global fan\u2026 First World Tour in 32 Cities of the World|url=https://www.edaily.co.kr/news/read?newsId=01115206625642640&mediaCodeNo=258|website=EDaily|date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Later, it was announced their commenced show in Bangkok and new album release project in mid-March was postponed in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus outbreak]] and to ensure the safety and health of the artist, fans, and staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mksports.co.kr/view/2020/153119/|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uccab \uc6d4\ub4dc\ud22c\uc5b4 \ubc29\ucf55 \uacf5\uc5f0 \uc77c\uc815 \uc5f0\uae30\u2026\u201c\ucf54\ub85c\ub09819 \ud655\uc0b0 \uc6b0\ub824\u201d|trans-title=(G)I-dle postponed their first World Tour Bangkok show\u2026 \"Concern Spreading Corona 19\"|work=MK Sports|author=Kim Na-young|date=February 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsseoul.com/news/read/888880|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc6d4\ub4dc\ud22c\uc5b4\u00b73\uc6d4 \uc0c8 \uc568\ubc94 \ubc1c\ub9e4 \ud504\ub85c\uc81d\ud2b8 \uc7a0\uc815 \uc5f0\uae30[\uacf5\uc2dd]|trans-title=(G)I-dle World Tour, March New album release project tentatively postponed [Official]|work=Spots Seoul|author=Choi Jin-sil|date=February 28, 2020|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, 2020, Cube Entertainment announced that (G)I-dle would be making a comeback with an extended play in early April. It was reported that they have already completed their album jacket photoshoot, filming of the music video and are in the final stages of comeback preparations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news1.kr/articles/?3878475|title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5] (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, 3\uc6d4 \uc911\uc21c\u21924\uc6d4 \ucd08 \ucef4\ubc31 \ud655\uc815\u2026MV \ucd2c\uc601 \uc644\ub8cc|trans-title=(G)I-dle mid-March \u2192 early comeback in early April\u2026 MV shooting completed|work=News1|author=Kim Min-ji|date= March 19, 2020}}</ref> Their third EP, ''[[I Trust]]'', is scheduled to release on April 6 with \"[[Oh My God ((G)I-dle song)|Oh My God]]\" as its lead single.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.khan.co.kr/entertainment/sk_index.html?art_id=202003240739003&sec_id=540101&pt=nv|title=[\uacf5\uc2dd] (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc138 \ubc88\uc9f8 \ubbf8\ub2c8\uc568\ubc94 \u2018I trust\u2019\ub85c 9\uac1c\uc6d4 \ub9cc\uc5d0 \ucef4\ubc31\u20264\uc6d4 6\uc77c \ubc1c\ub9e4 \ud655\uc815|trans-title=[Official] (G)I-DLE comeback in 9 months with third mini album 'I trust'\u2026 April 6 release confirmed|work=KyungHyang Newspaper|author=Yoo In-sun|date=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbnnews.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=382217|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc804\uc18c\uc5f0 \uc790\uc791\uace1 'Oh my god'\uc73c\ub85c \ucef4\ubc31|trans-title=[Official] (G)I-DLE comeback with Jeon So-yeon's own song \"Oh My God\"|work=NBN News|author=Hong Seung-hoon|date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, 2020, (G)I-dle was announced as part of the lineup of the 2020 [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] Stream Aid, scheduled for March 28. The livestream is a 12-hour charity livestream concert aiming to raise money for COVID-19 relief. They are the first female K-pop group to participate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.twitch.tv/en/2020/03/26/twitch-stream-aid-go-live-to-save-lives-on-328/|title=Twitch Stream Aid: Go live to save lives on 3/28|publisher=[[Twitch (service)|Twitch]]|date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2020/03/27/you-can-watch-monsta-x-and-gi-dle-twitch-stream-aid-weekend|title=You can watch MONSTA X and (G)I-DLE in Twitch Stream Aid this weekend|publisher=SBS PopAsia|date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Members ==\n* [[Cho Mi-yeon|Miyeon]] (\ubbf8\uc5f0)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?where=nexearch&query=%EB%AF%B8%EC%97%B0&sm=ppl_cts&ie=utf8&key=PeopleService&os=8207420|title=Miyeon official 'Naver' profile}}</ref>\n* [[Minnie (singer)|Minnie]] (\ubbfc\ub2c8)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?where=nexearch&query=%EB%AF%BC%EB%8B%88&sm=ppl_cts&ie=utf8&key=PeopleService&os=8207418|title=Minnie official 'Naver' profile}}</ref>\n* Soojin (\uc218\uc9c4)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?where=nexearch&query=%EC%88%98%EC%A7%84&sm=ppl_cts&ie=utf8&key=PeopleService&os=8207416|title=Soojin official 'Naver' profile}}</ref>\n* [[Jeon So-yeon|Soyeon]] (\uc18c\uc5f0)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?where=nexearch&query=%EC%86%8C%EC%97%B0&sm=ppl_cts&ie=utf8&key=PeopleService&os=3885550|title=Soyeon official 'Naver' profile}}</ref>\n* [[Song Yuqi|Yuqi]] (\uc6b0\uae30)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?where=nexearch&query=%EC%9A%B0%EA%B8%B0&sm=ppl_cts&ie=utf8&key=PeopleService&os=8207399|title=Yuqi official 'Naver' profile}}</ref>\n* Shuhua (\uc288\ud654)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?where=nexearch&query=%EC%8A%88%ED%99%94&sm=ppl_cts&ie=utf8&key=PeopleService&os=8207395|title=Shuhua official 'Naver' profile}}</ref>\n\n== Artistry ==\n[[File:180908 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 (G)I-DLE DMC Festival.png|thumb|right|(G)I-dle in September 2018]]\n\n=== Image ===\n(G)I-dle was praised for their musicality and ambiguity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://star.ohmynews.com/NWS_Web/OhmyStar/at_pg.aspx?CNTN_CD=A0002466220&CMPT_CD=P0010|title=\ub370\ubdd4 3\uac1c\uc6d4\ucc28 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc2e0 \uc74c\uc6d0\uac15\uc790\ub85c \uc790\ub9ac\ub9e4\uae40\ud560\uae4c?|author=Son Hwa-sin|date=August 25, 2018|work=OhmyNews}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=201809051043500410|title=\u2018\uc74c\uc6d0\ucc28\ud2b8\u2192\uc74c\ubc29 1\uc704\u2019 \uc544\uc774\ub4e4, 5\uac1c\uc6d4\ucc28 \uc548\ubbff\uae30\ub294 \uad34\ubb3c\uc2e0\uc778 \ud589\ubcf4[\ubba4\uc9c1\uc640\uce58]|author=Hwang Hye-jin|date=September 5, 2018|work=Newsen}}</ref> Natalie Morin from [[Refinery29]] described them as individuals with different energies that complements each other.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3132673/gi-dle-interview-self-produced-music-soyeon/|title=Meet (G)I-dle, The Women In K-Pop Who Are Unafraid To Grab The Mic|author=Natalie Morin|date=August 1, 2019|work=[[Refinery29]]}}</ref>  She also described them as \"bold and sensual\", characteristics which she asserts sets them apart from other K-pop girl groups. ''Mor.bo'' named them as a diverse group that is unafraid to try different music styles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ismorbo.com/mor-bo-radar-5-nuevos-grupos-k-pop-que-experimentan-con-edm-hip-hop-y-rb/|title=5 nuevos grupos K-pop que experimentan con EDM, hip hop y R&B|date=August 14, 2019|work=MOR.BO}}</ref> ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]] magazine'' named the group as \"independent musicians and artists\" where girl groups' concepts typically work within a mold that was made by someone else.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elle.co.kr/article/42660|title=\ud038\ub364, \uc5ec\uc790 \uc544\uc774\ub3cc\uc758 \uc7ac\ubc1c\uacac \uc21c\uac044 \uc5ec\uc790 \uc544\uc774\ub3cc\uc758 '\uc544\ud2f0\uc2a4\ud2b8'\ub85c\uc11c\uc758 \uacbd\uc7c1\uc774 \ube5b\uc744 \ubc1c\ud558\ub294 \uc21c\uac04, \uba4b\uc9d0\uc740 \ub450 \ubc30\ub85c \ud3ed\ubc1c\ud55c\ub2e4|trans-title=5 Scenes of the Rediscovery of Female Idols.|date=October 14, 2019|work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]}}</ref>\n\nDespite being the youngest group to appear on ''Queendom'', (G)I-dle members were actively involved in their own music videos, jacket photoshoots, song arrangements, choreography, and outfits production.<ref name=\"2nd\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tvreport.co.kr/2014513|trans-title=Second year (G)I-DLE able to turn Queendom upside down|title='\ub370\ubdd4 2\ub144 \ucc28' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, '\ud038\ub364' \ub4a4\uc9d1\uc5b4\ub193\uc744 \uc218 \uc788\ub358 \uc774\uc720|author=Kim Min-ji|date=October 19, 2019|work=TvReport}}</ref>\n\n=== Musical style ===\nTaylor Glasby from [[MTV]] stated that (G)I-dle songs are steeped in their very essence \u2014 a girl's complex, internal house of mirrors that is constantly being broken, assessed, understood, and remade, where one style or sound is never enough to reflect who they are. (G)I-dle is the enticing tropical beats and coy finger snaps of \"Latata\" and the ominous, warning whistled hook of \"Hann (Alone)\". They are also the pensive harmonies and slow throb of bass on the R&B-infused ballad \"Put It Straight,\" the whimsical words painted over the house music of \"What's In Your House,\" and even the tango of \"Senorita\". Their lyrics push back, they beckon. They can be boring nonchalance or sharpening desire.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3132673/gi-dle-interview-self-produced-music-soyeon/|title=(G)I-DLE ARE 'STANDING OUT' WITH THEIR SELF-PRODUCED SOUND AND DEFINING IT ON THEIR OWN TERMS|date=July 26, 2019|website=MTV News}}</ref>\n\nKim Na-yul writing for [[Herald Corporation|Herald Pop]] described (G)I-dle's genre can only be performed by them and made a good impression on the public.<ref>{{cite web|title=[POP\ucd08\uc810]\"\ud038\ub364 \ucd5c\ub300 \uc218\ud61c\" (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, 'LION' MV \uacf5\uac1c\u2192\uc5f0\uc77c \ud654\uc81c\uc131 \u7532|url=http://pop.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=201911042216354818533_1|publisher=HeraldPop|author=Kim Na Yul|date=November 4, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Melon (online music service)|Melon]] magazine'' described (G)I-dle's music generally as \"Uniqueness is (G)I-dle's most powerful weapon.\" crossing genres from \"Latata\" (moombahton), \"Hann (Alone)\" (Eastern European rhythm), \"Senorita\" (Latin pop) and \"Uh-Oh\" (Boom bap).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.melon.com/musicstory/inform.htm?mstorySeq=9829|title=2019\ub144\uc758 K-POP \ud2b8\ub799 7|date=December 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Stage performance===\nThe group was also praised for their stage presence during performances such as [[Melon Music Awards|2018 MMA]]'s golden stage reminiscent of [[Cleopatra]], and [[2018 Mnet Asian Music Awards|2018 MAMA]]'s stage performing with dozens of female dancers to emphasize the image of women.<ref name=\"HOT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ize.co.kr/articleView.html?no=2018123100287240092|trans-title=2018 year-end awards ceremony BEST|title=2018 \uc5f0\ub9d0 \uac00\uc694\uc2dc\uc0c1\uc2dd \ubb34\ub300 BEST|author=Park Hee Ah|date=December 31, 2018|work=Ize Magazine}}</ref> It is also stated that their performance for Fan-dora's Box was \"another legendary stage\" due to the emotional acting by the members where they expressed \"anger in sadness\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=201910181351467619530_1|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, '\ud038\ub364' 3\ucc28 \uacbd\uc5f0 '\uc2eb\ub2e4\uace0 \ub9d0\ud574' \uc720\ud29c\ube0c \uc870\ud68c\uc218 100\ub9cc\ubdf0 \ub3cc\ud30c|date=October 18, 2019|work=HeraldPop|language=ko}}</ref> (G)I-dle gave their last ''Queendom'' stage, \"[[Lion ((G)I-dle song)#Live_performance|Lion]]\" with the ''Lion'' story which was narrated by Minnie, danced in golden robes ornately decorated with lion's mane and finished with a herd of lions [dancers] following (G)I-dle to the six thrones. The stage was described as \"a world-class stage\" and \"a legendary stage\".<ref>{{cite web|title='\ud038\ub364' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc601\ud654\uac19\uc740 \ud53c\ub0a0\ub808\u2026\"\uc774 \uc18c\ub140\ub294, LION\" (\uc601\uc0c1)|url=http://www.newstomato.com/ReadNews.aspx?no=930382|publisher=News Tomato|author=Kim Hee-kyung|date=November 1, 2019}}</ref> This resulted in winning  several performance awards including [[Golden Disc Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=201911271338474996408_1|work=HeraldPop|author=Kim Na-yul|date=November 27, 2019|title='2019 AAA' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, AAA \uadf8\ub974\ubd80\uc0c1 \uc218\uc0c1..\"\ub354 \uc88b\uc740 \ubaa8\uc2b5\uc73c\ub85c \ubcf4\ub2f5\"|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=202001051655489275771_1|script-title=ko:[2020 \uace8\ub4e0\ub514\uc2a4\ud06c]\uc544\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub85c\u00b7(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ubca0\uc2a4\ud2b8\ud37c\ud3ec\uba3c\uc2a4\uc0c1 \"\uc0c8\ud574 \ucd9c\ubc1c\ubd80\ud130 \uac10\uc0ac\"|date=January 5, 2020|work=HeraldPop|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tfmusicawards.com/winner_2nd_tf.html|title=WINNER 2019 THE FACT MUSIC AWARDS|work=The Fact Music Award|date=March 16, 2020|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\nThe group was recognized for its brand recognition and marketing power, having topped the \"Girl Group Brand Power Ranking\" published by the Korean Business Research Institute. In 2018, they ranked #1 for June and September.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rekorea.net/bbs/board.php?bo_table=repu4&wr_id=256|title=[\ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc\ud3c9\ud310] \uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 \ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc 2018\ub144 6\uc6d4 \ube45\ub370\uc774\ud130 \ubd84\uc11d...1\uc704 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4|publisher=Korea Reputation Research Institute|date=June 9, 2018}}</ref> Their highest brand reputation index was in September 2018.<ref name=\"\uc5ec\uc790\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 \ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc\ud3c9\ud310 1\uc704 \ub4f1\uadf9 '\ud038\ub364' \ud6a8\uacfc\">{{cite news|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/stview.php?no=2019101310271318907|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 \ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc\ud3c9\ud310 1\uc704 \ub4f1\uadf9 \"'\ud038\ub364' \ud6a8\uacfc\"|publisher=Star News|date=October 13, 2019}}</ref> (G)I-dle has been dubbed the \"monster rookie\" of 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=201805251656197111616_1|title='\ubba4\uc9c1\ubc45\ud06c' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uad34\ubb3c \uc2e0\uc778\uc758 \uc139\uc2dc+\uace0\ud639 'LATATA'|work=HeraldPop|publisher=Ko Myung-jin|date=May 25, 2018|access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://star.hankookilbo.com/News/Read/201901071602365871?did=NA&dtype=&dtypecode=&prnewsid=|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc2e0\uc778\uc0c1 5\uad00\uc655 \ub2ec\uc131...\u20192018 \uad34\ubb3c \uc2e0\uc778\u2019 \uc785\uc99d|work=Hankook Ilbo|publisher=Kim Han-na|date=January 7, 2019|access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref> [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] ranked them at the top of its list as the best new K-pop group of 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/8491744/best-new-k-pop-acts-2018|title=10 Best New K-Pop Acts of 2018|website=Billboard|date=December 29, 2018|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref> It was reported that Cube's music sales in 2018 increased by 58% to \u20a98.8 billion due to the popularity of (G)I-dle's \"Latata\" and \"Hann (\u4e00)\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.edaily.co.kr/news/read?newsId=03227526622394784&mediaCodeNo=257&OutLnkChk=Y|title=\ud050\ube0c\uc5d4\ud130 \uc9c0\ub09c\ud574 \ub9e4\ucd9c 358\uc5b5\uc6d0\u2026\uc0c1\uc7a5 \uc774\ud6c4 \ucd5c\ub300 \uc2e4\uc801 \ub2ec\uc131|trans-title=Cube Entertainment last year revenue of KRW 35.8 billion\u2026 Achieve maximum performance|work=EDaily|author=Kim Sung-hoon|date=February 27, 2019|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, (G)I-dle gained more recognition in the general public after appearing on ''[[Queendom (TV series)|Queendom]]''.<ref name=\"\uc5ec\uc790\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 \ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc\ud3c9\ud310 1\uc704 \ub4f1\uadf9 '\ud038\ub364' \ud6a8\uacfc\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://kenh14.vn/gi-dle-thong-tri-top-trending-voi-san-khau-cung-loat-than-thai-hoi-huom-kinh-di-20191018000146858.chn|title=(G)I-DLE th\u1ed1ng tr\u1ecb top trending v\u1edbi s\u00e2n kh\u1ea5u c\u00f9ng lo\u1ea1t th\u1ea7n th\u00e1i h\u01a1i h\u01b0\u1edbm kinh d\u1ecb|publisher=kenh14|author=Hoang Chi|date=October 18, 2019|language=vi}}</ref> The performance of their finale song \"Lion\" was considered as one of K-pop's biggest moments of 2019 by [[CTV News]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Somos |first1=Christy |title=These are some of K-pop's biggest moments of 2019 |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/entertainment/these-are-some-of-k-pop-s-biggest-moments-of-2019-1.4738811 |website=CTVNews |accessdate=January 6, 2020 |language=en |date=December 20, 2019}}</ref> This resulted in them topping the \"Girl Group Brand Power Ranking\" for two consecutive months, in October and November 2019, respectively.<ref name=\"2nd\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://enews24.tving.com/news/article?nsID=1331406|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, '\ud038\ub364' \uacbd\uc5f0\uace1 '\uc2eb\ub2e4\uace0 \ub9d0\ud574'\ub85c 100\ub9cc\ubdf0 \ub3cc\ud30c '\ud6c4\ub048'|author=Kim Ji-yeon|date=October 18, 2019|work=eNews24|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cnews.thebigdata.co.kr/view.php?ud=20191013100321789607d270612f_23|title=\uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 \ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc\ud3c9\ud310 10\uc6d4 \ube45\ub370\uc774\ud130 \ubd84\uc11d 1\uc704\ub294 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4... 2\uc704 \ud2b8\uc640\uc774\uc2a4 ...|author=Kim Soo-ah|date=October 13, 2019|work=The Big Data News|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvdaily.asiae.co.kr/read.php3?aid=15733474531505465010#rs|title='\ud038\ub364 \ud6a8\uacfc' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, 11\uc6d4 \uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 \ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc\ud3c9\ud310 1\uc704|author=Hwang Seo-yeon|date=November 10, 2019|work=TvDaily|language=ko}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' India included \"Lion\" in their list of the 10 Best K-Pop Music Videos of 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rollingstoneindia.com/10-best-k-pop-music-videos-of-2019/|author=Riddhi Chakraborty|date=December 30, 2019|accessdate=January 8, 2020|title=10 Best K-Pop Music Videos of 2019|work=Rolling Stone India}}</ref> The song was considered as \"one of the most visceral tracks of 2019\" and was listed number one out of 920 songs released in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=The 25 Best K-pop Songs of 2019: Critics' Picks|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/international/8547126/the-25-best-k-pop-songs-of-2019-critics-picks|publisher=Billboard|date=December 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\uacb0\uc0b0 2019 : \ucd5c\uace0\uc758 \ub178\ub798|trans-title=Closing 2019: best songs|url=http://idology.kr/12885|publisher=Idology|date=February 11, 2020}}</ref> In January 2020, (G)I-dle were voted as the Most Anticipated Singers/Groups in 2020 based on surveys that were participated by several Korean music agencies, broadcasting and program officials, composers and popular music critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news1.kr/articles/?3807390|title=[\uc2e0\ub144\ud2b9\uc9d1] \uc804\ubb38\uac00 21\uc778 \uc120\uc815, 2020 \uac00\uc7a5 \uae30\ub300\ub418\ub294 \uac00\uc218\ub294|trans-title=[New Year Special] 21 Experts, 2020 Most Expected Singers|date=January 4, 2020|work=News1|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/stview.php?no=2019123108275558313|title=\uac00\uc694 \uad00\uacc4\uc790 \uc120\uc815 2020 \ud65c\uc57d \uae30\ub300\ub418\ub294 \uadf8\ub8f9\uc740?\u2466[2020 \u2606\uc2e0\ub144\uae30\ud68d]|date=January 3, 2020|work=Star News|language=ko}}</ref> In February 2020, the group achieved number 1 in brand power with the most-interacted topics \"Lion\" and world tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rekorea.net/bbs/board.php?bo_table=repu4&wr_id=453|title=\t[\ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc\ud3c9\ud310] \uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 \ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc 2020\ub144 2\uc6d4 \ube45\ub370\uc774\ud130 \ubd84\uc11d\uacb0\uacfc...1\uc704 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, 2\uc704 \ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3, 3\uc704 \uc774\ub2ec\uc758 |date=February 9, 2020|work=Korea Reputation|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n===Guinness World Record===\n(G)I-dle achieved a new [[Guinness World Record]] with [[#Music Content Company|1theK]] record challenge ''Kkinness Challenge'' on episode 4.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1-3r-7CGOcY|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 \uc2e0\uae30\ub85d\ud83d\udc51 \ud50c\ub809\uc2a4 \ud55c \ud604\uc7a5! (\uc785.\ud2c0.\ub9c9\ud83d\ude4a) (G)I-DLE \ub07c\ub124\uc2a4\ucd0c EP.4 KKINNESS CHALLENGE LION Uh-Oh|date=March 24, 2020|publisher=1theK Originals - \uc6d0\ub354\ucf00\uc774 \uc624\ub9ac\uc9c0\ub110}}</ref> ''Kkinness Challenge'' is an 'Idol Guinness Challenge' that contains the process by which an idol group enters Kkinness Village, an athlete village designed to challenge the world record of extreme events. In the video released on March 24, 2020, the group succeeded in achieving a new world record for the \"Fastest time to hang up five T-shirts\" in 25.41 seconds; the previous record-holder was held by Kaito Kozumi in 27.93 seconds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rpm9.com/news/article.html?id=20200325090008|title='\ub07c\ub124\uc2a4\ucd0c' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uae00\ub85c\ubc8c \uc774\uc0c9 \uc2e0\uae30\ub85d\ub2ec\uc131\u2026'\uc637\uac78\uc774\uc5d0 \ud2f0\uc154\uce20 5\uc7a5 \ube68\ub9ac\uac78\uae30' \ubbf8\uc158\uc131\uacf5|trans-title='Kinness Village' (G)I-dle, Achieve Global New Record\u2026 Success of 'Five pieces of T-shirts on hangers'|author=Park Dong-sun|date=March 25, 2020|work=RPM9}}</ref> On the first attempt, member Soyeon scored 28.34 seconds, which was close to the Guinness record, but unfortunately failed. Subsequently, member Shuhua, took the challenge and recorded 26.81 seconds breaking the world record. However, Soyeon who re-challenged, recorded 25.41 seconds and breaking the previous record by Shuhua. The record will be recognized as the official world record by the world's top 3 record certification agency, Supertalent World Record, and will proceed with the official procedure for Guinness listing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.donga.com/ent/article/all/20200325/100337634/1|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uae30\ub124\uc2a4 \uc138\uacc4\uc2e0\uae30\ub85d \uacbd\uc2e0\u2192\uc6d4\ub4dc\ud074\ub798\uc2a4 \ub4f1\uadf9|trans-title=(G)I-dle, break the world record for Guinness \u2192 World Class|author=Hong Se-young|date=March 25, 2020|work=Sports Donga}}</ref>\n\n== Ambassadorship ==\n[[Seoul Capital Area|Seoul Metropolitan City]] appointed (G)I-dle as the city's goodwill ambassadors alongside [[Yura (South Korean singer)|Yura]], [[Park Jin-Hee]], and eight other nominees. They will hold the title \"City Ambassadors\" for two years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cstimes.com/?mod=news&act=articleView&idxno=291618|title=\uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774 \uc720\ub77c-\ubc30\uc6b0 \ubc15\uc9c4\ud76c, \uc138\uacc4\uc5d0 \uc11c\uc6b8\uc2dc \uc54c\ub9b0\ub2e4|work=CSTimes|date=December 6, 2018}}</ref> On the 10th annual Children's Diabetes Celebration Festival held at Lotte World Underground Kingdom in [[Eunpyeong District|Eunpyeong-gu]], Seoul, they were awarded as the new ambassador for Korean Children's Diabetes Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=109&aid=0004026271|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ud55c\uad6d\uc18c\uc544\ub2f9\ub1e8\uc778\ud611\ud68c \ud64d\ubcf4\ub300\uc0ac \uc704\ucd09 [\uacf5\uc2dd]|work=Osen|date=June 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Endorsements ==\nIn 2019, (G)I-dle became the first Korean girl group to endorse with Kaja, a beauty brand co-created by [[Sephora]] and Memebox to create a new form combining K-beauty and K-pop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wsobi.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=70250|title=\uc5ec\uc790\uc544\uc774\ub4e4\u2019 \uce74\uc790 \ubaa8\ub378\ub85c \uc120\uc815\u2026 K\ubdf0\ud2f0&K\ud31d \uc2dc\ub108\uc9c0 \uae30\ub300|trans-title='(G)I-dle' selected as Kaja model\u2026 Expect K Beauty & K-Pop Synergy|work=Wsobi|author=Lee Ji-eun||date=March 1, 2019|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> Through the partnership, ''To Neverland'' reality TV series and \"Senorita\" music video were released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hypebae.com/2019/2/k-pop-girl-group-gi-dle-announces-kaja-partnership-with-senorita-music-video|title=K-POP GIRL GROUP (G)I-DLE ANNOUNCES KAJA PARTNERSHIP WITH \"SENORITA\" MUSIC VIDEO|work=HypeBae|author=Teresa Lam||date=February 26, 2019|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> \n\n(G)I-dle were selected as Akiii Classic's new model in 2020 to reinforce the sensitivity of [[generation Z|Gen Z]] culture and trend pioneering the brand image.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.khan.co.kr/entertainment/sk_index.html?art_id=202003041029003&sec_id=540101&pt=nv|title=[\uacf5\uc2dd] (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \u2018\uc544\ud0a4\ud074\ub798\uc2dd\u2019 \uc0c8 \ubaa8\ub378 \ubc1c\ud0c1\u2026\ub300\uc138 \ud589\ubcf4 \uc774\uc5b4\uac04\ub2e4|work=Sports Khan|author=Yoo Ha-eun|date=March 4, 2020}}</ref> In early April 2020, (G)I-dle was revealed as a promotional model for South Korea biggest contact lens brand, LensMe. A representative from LensMe explained that the group's unique music and charismatic stage performances matched well with their 'Basic, Trendy, Easy' company image.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lens-me.com/shopinfo/LENSME_MUSE.html|title=LENS-ME WITH (G)I-DLE|publisher=LensMe|date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kgdm.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=688967|title=\uc5ec\uc790\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ucf58\ud0dd\ud2b8\ub80c\uc988 \ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc \uc804\uc18d \ubaa8\ub378\ub85c \ubc1c\ud0c1|work=Gyeonggi Provincial Daily|author=Lee Da-yeon|date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|(G)I-dle discography}}\n{{See also|List of songs recorded by (G)I-dle}}\n\n===Extended plays===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Korean releases'''\n* ''[[I Am ((G)I-dle EP)|I Am]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[I Made]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[I Trust]]'' (2020)\n{{col-2}}\n'''Japanese releases'''\n* ''[[Latata (EP)|Latata]]'' (2019)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Concerts and tours==\n\n===Headlining tours===\n* ''(G)I-dle World Tour I-Land: Who Am I Tour'' (2020)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zenithnews.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=137537|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc6d4\ub4dc \ud22c\uc5b4 \uac1c\ucd5c \ud655\uc815\u2026 \uae00\ub85c\ubc8c \ub300\uc138 \ud589\ubcf4|work=ZenithNews|date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Variety show ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Network\n! Ref.\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Queendom (TV series)|Queendom]]''\n| [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]]\n| <ref name=\"Queendom\" />\n|}\n\n=== Reality shows ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Episodes\n! Network\n|-\n| 2018\u2013present\n| ''(G)I-dle: I-Talk''\n| {{TBA|Ongoing}}\n| [[V Live (website)|V Live]], [[YouTube]]\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''(G)I-dle: Vlog in New York''\n| 3\n| V Live\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2019\n| ''To Neverland''\n| 6\n| [[Mnet (TV channel)|M2]], [[Naver]] TV Cast<ref>{{cite web|title=(G)I-DLE to launch their first reality show 'To Neverland' in mid-January through M2 channel with partnership cosmetics brand Kaja|url=https://m.entertain.naver.com/read?oid=609&aid=0000041465|work=Newsen|date=January 4, 2019|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4\uc758 'TO NEVERLAND' \ub9c8\uc9c0\ub9c9 \uc5d0\ud53c\uc18c\ub4dc 19\uc77c \uacf5\uac1c|url=http://news.wowtv.co.kr/NewsCenter/News/Read?articleId=A201902190133&t=NN|work=WowTv|date=February 19, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''(G)I-dle: Little but Certain Happiness (\uc18c\ud655\ud589)''\n| 4\n| V Live, YouTube\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 2020\n| ''(G)I-dle: Secret Folder (\uc720\ucd9c\uae08\uc9c0)''\n| 4 + 4 specials\n| [[1theK Originals]]<ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ud398\uc774\ud06c \ub9ac\uc5bc\ub9ac\ud2f0 '\uc720\ucd9c\uae08\uc9c0' 1\ubc88 \ud0c0\uc790\u2026\uc194\uc9c1+\uc720\ucf8c \ub9e4\ub825|url=http://www.mydaily.co.kr/new_yk/html/read.php?newsid=202001151131576690&ext=na|work=MyDaily|date=January 15, 2020|language=ko}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''#HASHTALK''\n| 12\n| YouTube\n|-\n| ''(G)I-dle <So Sweet~ Happy Valentine's Day>''\n| 1\n| [[YouTube Live]]\n|-\n| ''(G)I-dle X Star Road''\n| {{TBA|Ongoing}}\n| V Live<ref>{{cite web|title='\uc2a4\ud0c0\ub85c\ub4dc' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, '\uc624\ub9c8\uc774\uac13' \uc678\uce60 \uc218\ubc16\uc5d0 \uc5c6\ub294 \ub300\uc138\ub3cc[Oh! \uc2a4\ucf00\uce58]|url=http://osen.mt.co.kr/article/G1111334364|work=OSEN|date=April 6, 2020|language=ko}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by (G)I-dle}}\n\n(G)I-dle won their first award, the \"Female Rookie Idol of the Year\", on July 24, 2018 at Brand of the Year Awards.<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ko:(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 '\uc62c\ud574\uc758 \uc544\uc774\ub3cc\ub85c \uc120\uc815\ub410\uc5b4\uc694'|url=http://m.hankooki.com/m_sp_view.php?WM=sp&FILE_NO=c3AyMDE4MDcyNDE1MjUxNzEzNjczMC5odG0|work=Hankooki|date=July 24, 2018|language=ko}}</ref> Twenty days after debuting, on May 22, 2018, they received their first [[Music programs of South Korea#Chart Systems|music show win]] on [[SBS MTV]]'s ''[[The Show (South Korean TV series)|The Show]]'' with \"[[Latata]]\".<ref name=\"latata1stwin\"/>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|(G)I-dle}}\n* {{url|http://cafe.daum.net/cube-g-i-dle|Official Cafe}} {{in lang|ko}}\n* {{url|https://www.universal-music.co.jp/g-i-dle/|Universal Music Japan Artist}} {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{(G)I-dle}}\n{{Cube Entertainment}}\n{{Golden Disk Awards for New Artist of the Year}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gidle}}\n[[Category:(G)I-dle| ]]\n[[Category:2018 establishments in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Seoul]]\n[[Category:K-pop music groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2018]]\n[[Category:South Korean dance music groups]]\n[[Category:South Korean girl groups]]\n[[Category:Cube Entertainment artists]]\n[[Category:Melon Music Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{short description|South Korean girl group}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = (G)I-dle\n| background       = group_or_band\n| image            = 200108 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 (G)I-DLE Gaon Awards.png\n| landscape        = yes\n| alt              =\n| caption          = (G)I-dle in January 2020<br>\nFrom left to right: Soojin, Miyeon, Soyeon, Yuqi, Shuhua and Minnie\n| alias            =\n| origin           = [[Seoul]], South Korea\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[K-pop]]}}\n| years_active     = {{Start date|2018}}\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Cube Entertainment|Cube]]\n*[[Universal Music Japan|Universal Japan]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201811231612419244567_2|title=Cube Entertainment, Universal Music Japan establish joint label U Cube|work=kpopherald|language=EN|date=November 23, 2018}}</ref>\n*Asian Agent<ref>{{cite web|title=K-Pop Group (G)I-DLE Signs With Asian Agent for U.S. Management & International Strategy: Exclusive|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/legal-and-management/8542834/g-i-dle-asian-agent-us-management-international-strategy|work=Billboard|author=Jeff Benjamin|date=November 6, 2019|access-date=November 7, 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n}}\n| associated_acts  = [[Cube Entertainment#Artists|United Cube]]\n| website          = {{URL|cubeent.co.kr/gidle|Korean website}} <br />{{URL|https://gidle.jp|Japanese website}}\n| current_members  = * [[Cho Mi-yeon|Miyeon]]\n* [[Minnie (singer)|Minnie]]\n* Soojin\n* [[Jeon So-yeon|Soyeon]]\n* [[Song Yuqi|Yuqi]]\n* Shuhua\n}}\n\n'''(G)I-dle''' ({{korean|(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4||Yeoja Aideul}}), stylized as '''(G)I-DLE''', is a South Korean multinational  [[girl group]] formed by [[Cube Entertainment]] in 2018. The group consists of six members: [[Cho Mi-yeon|Miyeon]], [[Minnie (singer)|Minnie]], Soojin, [[Jeon So-yeon|Soyeon]], [[Song Yuqi|Yuqi]], and Shuhua.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?where=nexearch&sm=tab_ppn&query=(%EC%97%AC%EC%9E%90)%EC%95%84%EC%9D%B4%EB%93%A4&os=8207391&ie=utf8&key=PeopleService|title=Official Naver profile|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref> The group debuted on May 2, 2018, with their first [[extended play]] titled ''[[I Am ((G)I-dle EP)|I Am]]''.\n\n== Name ==\nIn an interview with ''The Star'', the leader of the group, [[Jeon So-yeon]], revealed that the name \"Idle\" {{small|(\uc544\uc774\ub4e4)}} came to her when she was composing the \"Idle Song\". She sent it to the company and the name was finalized after going through the company's competition.<ref>{{cite web|title=\ud604\uc7a5 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \"\ud300\uba85, \uc54c\uc544\ub4e3\uae30 \uc27d\uace0 \ubc1c\uc74c\ub3c4 \ud3b8\ud574 \uc88b\ub2e4\"|url=http://www.topstarnews.net/news/articleView.html?idxno=404594|work=TopStarNews|date=May 2, 2018|access-date=October 13, 2019|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 \"\uc6b0\ub9ac\ub9cc\uc758 \uc0c9\uacfc \uc2a4\ud0c0\uc77c \uc0dd\uacbc\uc73c\uba74 \uc88b\uaca0\ub2e4\" [\ud654\ubcf4]|url=http://www.xportsnews.com/jenter/?ac=article_view&entry_id=1000463|work=XSportsNews|date=July 24, 2018|access-date=October 13, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> However, the name received mixed reactions in South Korea and internationally because \"\uc544\uc774\ub4e4\" means \"children\" and \"idle\" in English refers to someone who avoids work.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fans aren't liking the name of Cube's new girl group|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2018/03/23/fans-arent-liking-name-cubes-new-girl-group|work=SBS Pop Asia|date=March 23, 2018|access-date=October 13, 2019|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Netizens are scratching their heads at the name of Cube Entertainment's new girl group|url=https://www.allkpop.com/article/2018/03/netizens-are-scratching-their-heads-at-the-name-of-cube-entertainments-new-girl-group|work=Allkpop|date=March 22, 2018|access-date=October 13, 2019|language=en}}</ref> The group was thus renamed (G)I-dle, with the \"I\" standing for individuality, \"\u2010\" to show that the name has been divided into two parts and \"Dle\" as the plural form of \"I\" in Korean, meaning a group of six different personalities gathered together.<ref>{{cite web|title=Let's Dance(\ub81b\uce20\ub304\uc2a4): (G)I-DLE((\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4) LATATA|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xnhlyf4I_vo|work=1theK (\uc6d0\ub354\ucf00\uc774)|date=May 4, 2018|access-date=October 13, 2019|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=[After School Club] This group has risen to be the hottest rookies, (G)I-DLE((\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4)!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uHBXlFUALKo=7m02s|work=ARIRANG K-POP|date=May 21, 2018|access-date=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n=== Pre-debut ===\n[[Jeon So-yeon|Soyeon]] was a female trainee who represented [[Cube Entertainment]] in the survival show ''[[Produce 101]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Ji-young|url=http://enews24.tving.com/news/article.asp?nsID=988275|title=[\ud504\ub85c\ub4c0\uc2a4101 \ub3d9\uc601\uc0c1] CUBE \uc5f0\uc2b5\uc0dd '\ubbf8\uccd0' vs DSP\uc5f0\uc2b5\uc0dd 'Mr.'|language=Korean|work=enews24|publisher=enews24|date=January 23, 2016}}</ref> peaking at 10th place on the fifth episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsinside.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=386115|script-title=ko:[\ud504\ub85c\ub4c0\uc2a4 101, 5\ud68c] 1\ub4f1 \uc13c\ud130 \uae40\uc138\uc815\u00b72\uc704 \uc804\uc18c\ubbf8 3\uc704 \ucd5c\uc720\uc815...61\ub4f1\uae4c\uc9c0 \uc5ce\uce58\ub77d \ub4a4\uce58\ub77d '\ud568\uaed8 \uc6b8\uc5c8\ub2e4'|language=Korean|work=News Inside|publisher=News Inside|date=February 20, 2016}}</ref> however, she did not become a member of the winning girl group, [[I.O.I]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Kim|first=Kwan-myeong|url=http://www.xportsnews.com/jenter/?ac=article_view&entry_id=709076|script-title=ko:\uc5ed\uc2dc \uc5b4\uc77c\uc804, '\ud504\ub85c\ub4c0\uc2a4101' \ucd5c\uc885 11\uc778 \uc131\uc801\ud45c|language=Korean|work=X Sports News|publisher=X Sports News|date=April 2, 2016}}</ref> Soyeon also competed in the [[Unpretty Rapstar 3|third season]] of the rap competition show ''[[Unpretty Rapstar]]'', where she finished as the second runner-up.<ref>{{cite web|last=Choi|first=Na-young|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=109&aid=0003350781|title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5]'\uc5b8\ud504\ub9ac\ud2f03', \ubbf8\ub8cc\u00b7\uc721\uc9c0\ub2f4\u00b7\ud558\uc8fc\uc5f0\u00b7\uc720\ub098\ud0b4 \ub4f1 10\uc778 \ucd9c\uc5f0.. MC \uc591\ub3d9\uadfc|language=Korean|work=OSEN|publisher=Naver|date=July 4, 2016}}</ref> She later debuted as a soloist, releasing two digital singles: \"Jelly\" and \"Idle Song\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tenasia.hankyung.com/archives/1330119|script-title=ko:'\ud504\ub4c0'\u00b7'\uc5b8\ud504\ub9ac\ud2f0' \uc804\uc18c\uc5f0, 11\uc6d4 5\uc77c \uc194\ub85c\ub85c \uc815\uc2dd \ub370\ubdd4|work=TenAsia|language=ko|date=October 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Cho Mi-yeon|Miyeon]] had previously trained under [[YG Entertainment]] between 2010 and 2015.{{cn|date=January 2020}} Soojin was a former trainee under DN Entertainment in 2015. She trained as a member of girl group Vividiva, but left before the group's debut.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.polinews.co.kr/news/article.html?no=224511|title=\uadf9\uc7a5 \uacf5\uc5f0\ud615 \uc544\uc774\ub3cc '\ube44\ube44\ub514\ubc14' \ub370\ubdd4 \uc55e\ub450\uace0 \ud2f0\uc800 \uacf5\uac1c|work=PoliNews|date=January 16, 2015|access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> [[Minnie (singer)|Minnie]] was featured in Line Friends' album ''Dance Party'', which was released in November 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.melon.com/album/detail.htm?albumId=10110671|title=Dance Party! - \uc5b4\ub9b0\uc774 \uc601\uc5b4\ub3d9\uc694|website=www.melon.com}}</ref>\n\nOn April 5, 2018, Cube Entertainment revealed the name of their upcoming girl group, (G)I-dle.<ref>{{cite web|title=\ud050\ube0c \uc0c8 \uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 '(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4' \uacf5\uc2dd \ub85c\uace0 \uacf5\uac1c! \uc804\uc18c\uc5f0 \ud3ec\ud568 \uc0c1\ubc18\uae30 \ub370\ubdd4 \ubaa9\ud45c|url=http://enews.imbc.com/News/RetrieveNewsInfo/230786|work=eNews|date=April 5, 2018|access-date=October 13, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> Before their debut date, Cube revealed the members to the public through ''Dingo Music's'' dance busking at [[Hongdae, Seoul]].<ref>{{cite web|title=WATCH: Cube Entertainment's new girl group dance busk to BTS, CL & 4Minute|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2018/04/16/watch-cube-entertainments-new-girl-group-dance-busk-bts-cl-4minute|work=SBS Pop Asia|date=April 16, 2018|access-date=October 13, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> The busking performance video exceeded two million views on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web|title=[\ud604\uc7a5S] \"\ucf58\uc149\ud2b8\ub294 \uac1c\uc131\"\u2026'\ub370\ubdd4' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ubaa9\ud45c\ub294 \uc2e0\uc778\uc0c1|url=http://www.spotvnews.co.kr/?mod=news&act=articleView&idxno=211312|work=SpotTvNews|author=Jang Woo-young|date=May 2, 2018|access-date=October 13, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018: Debut and \"Hann (Alone)\" ===\n[[File:(G)I-DLE at 'Latata' Showcase Photo Time on May 2, 2018 (5).png|thumbnail|right|(G)I-dle in May 2018]]\n(G)I-dle released their debut EP, ''[[I Am ((G)I-dle EP)|I Am]],'' on May 2, 2018 with the lead single \"[[Latata]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spotvnews.co.kr/?mod=news&act=articleView&idxno=211312|title=[\ud604\uc7a5S] \"\ucf58\uc149\ud2b8\ub294 \uac1c\uc131\"\u2026'\ub370\ubdd4' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ubaa9\ud45c\ub294 \uc2e0\uc778\uc0c1|work=Spotv News|language=ko|date=May 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://pop.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=201805021050289015290_1|title='\ub370\ubdd4' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ud0c0\uc774\ud2c0\uace1 'LATATA' MV \ud2f0\uc800 \uc601\uc0c1 \uacf5\uac1c|work=Herald Pop|language=ko|date=May 5, 2018}}</ref> The video for \"Latata\" exceeded 5.9 million views within the first week.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=311&aid=0000850998|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ub370\ubdd4\uace1 'LATATA' MV \uacf5\uac1c \uc774\ud2c0\ub9cc\uc5d0 220\ub9cc\ubdf0 \ub3cc\ud30c|work=xsportsnews|language=ko|date=May 4, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mnews.joins.com/article/22615079|title=Can They Be Next BLACKPINK? \"Hot Rookie\" (G)I-DLE Topped K-Pop Charts In the Week of Debut|date=May 11, 2018|work=JoongAng Ilbo|access-date=September 24, 2018|language=ko-KR}}</ref> The EP debuted at number 13 on the [[Gaon Album Chart]] issued on May 10.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/album.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=&targetTime=18&hitYear=2018&termGbn=week|title=2018\ub144 18\uc8fc\ucc28 Album Chart|work=[[Gaon Music Chart]]|language=ko|date=May 10, 2018}}</ref> ''I Am'' also debuted at number seven and peaked at number five on ''[[Billboard charts|Billboard]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s World Albums chart on May 9.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/world-albums/2018-05-19|title=World Albums: Top World Albums Chart|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|language=en|date=May 19, 2018}}</ref> A week after release, \"Latata\" debuted at number 35 on [[Gaon Digital Chart]] on May 17.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=ALL&targetTime=19&hitYear=2018&termGbn=week|title=2018\ub144 19\uc8fc\ucc28 Digital Chart|work=[[Gaon Music Chart]]|language=ko|date=May 17, 2018}}</ref> (G)I-dle received their first-ever [[Music programs of South Korea#Chart Systems|music show win]] on [[SBS MTV]]'s ''[[The Show (South Korean TV series)|The Show]]'' on May 22, twenty days after their debut.<ref name=\"latata1stwin\">{{Cite news|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=109&aid=0003787230|title='\ub354\uc1fc' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uccab 1\uc704 '\ub208\ubb3c'..\uc5d4\ud50c\ub77c\uc789 \ucef4\ubc31\u00b7NCT \uc81c\ub178X\uae40\uc6a9\uad6d \uc0c8 MC[\uc885\ud569] |work=Osen|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsfreezone.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=62930|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \u7f8e \ub274\uc695 \ud0c0\uc784\uc2a4\ud018\uc5b4 \uc625\uc678 \uc804\uad11\ud310 \uc7a5\uc2dd...'\uad34\ubb3c\uc2e0\uc778\uc758 \uc704\uc5c4'|work=Newsfree zone|publisher=Lee Dae-woong|date=June 4, 2018|access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref> On June 5, they made their debut on ''Billboard'''s Social 50 Chart, charting at number 36.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/social-50|title= Billboard's Social 50 |date=June 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn June, a survey was carried out among thirty-five participants in the music industry where (G)I-dle was voted the Next Generation of K-pop category with 39 points overall.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sportsseoul.com/news/read/649836|title=[\ucc3d\uac04\ud2b9\uc9d1 \uac00\uc694\uc124\ubb38\u2461]\ucd5c\uace0 \uc194\ub85c GD\u00b7\uc544\uc774\uc720, \uae30\ub300\uc8fc \uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ucd5c\uace0 \ub9e4\ub2c8\uc9c0\uba3c\ud2b8 SM \uc5d4\ud130|publisher=SportsSeoul|author=Hong Seung-han|date=June 22, 2018|access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref> On August 6, (G)I-dle held a small concert and recorded a flash-mob performance of \"Latata\" in [[Times Square]] and [[Washington Square Park]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.entertain.naver.com/read?oid=382&aid=0000665891&l|script-title=ko:'\ucef4\ubc31' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ub274\uc695 \ud0c0\uc784\uc2a4\ud018\uc5b4 \ud50c\ub798\uc2dc\ubab9 \uc778\uc99d\uc0f7|website=SportsDonga|language=korean|access-date=August 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.entertain.naver.com/read?oid=079&aid=0003132612&l|script-title=ko:(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ub274\uc695 \ud0c0\uc784\uc2a4\ud018\uc5b4 \ud50c\ub798\uc2dc\ubab9 \uc601\uc0c1 \uacf5\uac1c|language=korean|access-date=August 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/columns/k-town/8470655/g-i-dle-in-new-york-interview-hann-alone-debut-goals|title=(G)I-dle Discuss New Single 'Hann (Alone)' & Debut-Year Goals During First U.S. Visit: Exclusive|website=Billboard|access-date=August 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn August 14, (G)I-dle's first digital single, \"[[Hann (Alone)]]\", was released.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tvreport.co.kr/?c=news&m=newsview&idx=1073007|script-title=ko:[\ubba4\uc9c1@\ub9ac\ud3ff]\uc5f4\uc560\uc124 \ubd88\uad6c \ucef4\ubc31\uac15\ud589...(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uad00\uc2ec\uc77c\uae4c \ubb34\ub9ac\uc77c\uae4c|website=TV Report|language=korean|access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://m.mydaily.co.kr/new/read.php?newsid=201808091331722903|script-title=ko:(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc774\ubc88\uc5d4 \uc131\uc219\ud568\uc73c\ub85c \uc2b9\ubd80\uc218|website=My Daily|language=korean|access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> Within 24 hours, the music video surpassed 4.9 million views on YouTube.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCtCiO5t2voB14CmZKTkIzPQ/search?query=(%EC%97%AC%EC%9E%90)%EC%95%84%EC%9D%B4%EB%93%A4|title=Dingo Music Search_\uc5ec\uc790(\uc544\uc774\ub4e4)|last=|first=|date=|website=YouTube|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=June 9, 2018}}</ref> \"Hann\" topped domestic music charts including Bugs, [[Genie Music|Genie]] and Olleh Music on August 16<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.entertain.naver.com/read?oid=112&aid=0003061935|script-title=ko:[\ud31d\uc5c5\ubba4\uc9c1](\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 '\ud55c', \uc74c\uc6d0\ucc28\ud2b8 3\uacf3 1\uc704...\uc62c\ud574\uc758 \ud56b\ub8e8\ud0a4 |website=Heraldpop|language=korean|access-date=August 16, 2018}}</ref> and reached a new peak on Billboard's World Digital Song Sales chart where they debut at No. 2.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/columns/k-town/8472205/g-i-dle-hann-alone-new-peak-world-digital-song-sales-chart|title= (G)I-dle Hit New Peak on World Digital Song Sales Chart With 'Hann (Alone)'|date=August 28, 2018}}</ref> They received their first music show win on [[Show Champion]] on August 29 for \"Hann\".<ref name=\"SPOTVNEWS:\ubba4\uc9c1 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, '\ud55c'\uc73c\ub85c 1\uc704...\ud655\uc2e4\ud788 \uc99d\uba85\ud55c \uc2e4\ub825\">{{Cite news|url=http://m.spotvnews.co.kr/?mod=news&act=articleView&idxno=233916#Redyho|script-title=ko:[\ubba4\uc9c1] (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, '\ud55c'\uc73c\ub85c 1\uc704...\ud655\uc2e4\ud788 \uc99d\uba85\ud55c \uc2e4\ub825|work=SportsTvNews|access-date=August 30, 2018|language=ko}}</ref> In September, the group made their first appearance at [[KCON (music festival)|KCON]] in [[Thailand]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thairath.co.th/entertain/inter/1387954|script-title=th:ko\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e38\u0e01\u0e08\u0e19\u0e44\u0e21\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e22\u0e32\u0e01\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e49\u0e08\u0e1a! KCON 2018 THAILAND \u0e08\u0e31\u0e14\u0e40\u0e15\u0e47\u0e21\u0e2d\u0e34\u0e21\u0e41\u0e1e\u0e47\u0e04\u0e41\u0e17\u0e1a\u0e41\u0e15\u0e01|work=Thai Rath|access-date=November 7, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the rest of 2018, (G)I-dle earned several rookie awards at major Korean year-end music award shows, including the [[Asia Artist Awards]], [[Gaon Chart Music Awards]], [[Genie Music Awards]], [[Golden Disc Awards]], Korea Popular Music Awards and [[Melon Music Awards]].<ref name=\"AAA\">{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=109&aid=0003912978|accessdate=November 29, 2018|work=OSEN|date=November 28, 2018|title=[2018 AAA] \uc544\uc774\uc988\uc6d0\u00b7\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub808\uc774\ud0a4\uc988\u00b7(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4\u00b7\ub354\ubcf4\uc774\uc988, \uc2e0\uc778\uc0c1 \uc218\uc0c1|language=ko}}</ref><ref name=\"GMA\">{{cite web|url=http://m.stardailynews.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=221181|title=[S\ud3ec\ud1a0] (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, '\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 \uc0c1 \ubc1b\uc558\uc2b5\ub2c8\ub2e4~' (2018 MGA \uc9c0\ub2c8\ubba4\uc9c1\uc5b4\uc6cc\ub4dc)|date=November 7, 2018|website=Stardailynews|language=ko}}</ref><ref name=\"GDA\">{{cite web|url=https://m.entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=312&aid=0000365606|script-title=ko:[\uc81c33\ud68c \uace8\ub4e0\ub514\uc2a4\ud06c\uc5b4\uc6cc\uc988] (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc2e0\uc778\uc0c1 \uc218\uc0c1\u2026\"\ub354 \ud070 \uae30\uc068 \ub4dc\ub9ac\uaca0\ub2e4\"|date=January 5, 2019|language=ko}}</ref><ref name=\"KPMA\">{{cite web|url=https://m.entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=009&aid=0004275509|title=[2018 KPMA]\ub354\ubcf4\uc774\uc988-(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ub0a8\ub140 \uc2e0\uc778\uc0c1 '\ucf8c\uac70' |date=December 20, 2018|language=ko}}</ref><ref name=\"MMA\">{{cite web|url=https://m.entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=609&aid=0000024849|script-title=ko:(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc2e0\uc778\uc0c1 \uc218\uc0c1 \"\uc18c\uac10 \uc900\ube44 \ubabb\ud588\ub294\ub370\"[2018 \uba5c\ub860\ubba4\uc9c1\uc5b4\uc6cc\ub4dc]|date=December 1, 2018|website=Newsen|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019: ''I Made'', \"Uh-Oh\", Japanese debut and ''Queendom''===\n[[File:0226 \ubbf8\uc5f0X\ubbfc\ub2c8X\uc218\uc9c4X\uc18c\uc5f0X\uc6b0\uae30X\uc288\ud654 \ub9e4\ub825\ub118\uce58\ub294 \ud3ec\ud1a0\ud0c0\uc784 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 \ubbf8\ub2c82\uc9d1 \uc1fc\ucf00\uc774\uc2a4.png|thumbnail|left|(G)I-dle at 'I Made' showcase in February 2019]]\n(G)I-dle released their second EP, ''[[I Made]]'', on  February 26, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=109&aid=0003950274|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, 26\uc77c \ucef4\ubc31 \ud655\uc815...'\ub77c\ud0c0\ud0c0'\u2192'\ud55c' \ub300\uc138 \ud589\ubcf4 \uc787\ub294\ub2e4 [\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5]|website=Osen|access-date=February 11, 2019}}</ref> The EP contains five songs, including the lead single \"[[Senorita ((G)I-dle song)|Senorita]]\", written and composed by member Soyeon and Big Sancho.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=396&aid=0000503332|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc804\uc18c\uc5f0 \uc790\uc791\uace1 'Senorita'\ub85c \ucef4\ubc31\u2026'\uc804\uace1 \uc790\uc791\uace1' \ub208\uae38|website=Osen|access-date=February 14, 2019}}</ref> On June 26, (G)I-dle released their second digital single, \"[[Uh-Oh ((G)I-dle song)|Uh-Oh]]\".<ref>{{Citation|title='Uh Oh(\uc5b4\uc624)' \ucef4\ubc31 \uc1fc\ucf00\uc774\uc2a4\uc11c 90\ub144\ub300 '\ub274\ud2b8\ub85c' \uac10\uc131 \ubf50\ub0b8 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4|url=https://www.insight.co.kr/news/234111|publisher=Insight Korea|date=June 26, 2019|accessdate=July 13, 2019}}</ref> The song ranked number 22 on [[NetEase Music|NetEase Cloud Music China]] for the first half of 2019, making them the only K-pop group to chart on it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.stardailynews.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=247948|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc911\uad6d \uc655\uc774\ubba4\uc9c1 '2019 \uc0c1\ubc18\uae30 TOP50' 22\uc704 \ub7ad\ud06c... K-POP \uc544\ud2f0\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub85c\uc11c\ub294 \uc720\uc77c|website=Star Daily News|date=July 11, 2019|access-date=July 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July, (G)I-dle held their first U.S. performance during the annual KCON convention and music festival at [[Javits Center]], [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/international/8519446/gi-dle-play-first-best-last-worst|title=(G)I-dle Reveal Dream Collaborators in 'First, Best, Last, Worst' Game: Watch|date=July 11, 2019|author= Tamar Herman|magazine=Billboard}}</ref> They later held a live showcase at the [[Akasaka Blitz|Mainabi Blitz Akasaka]] on July 23.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.excite.co.jp/news/article/E1558329668075/|title=(G)I-DLE\u30017\u6708\u306b\u300eLATATA\u300f\u3067\u65e5\u672c\u30c7\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc\u6c7a\u5b9a&\u30b7\u30e7\u30fc\u30b1\u30fc\u30b9\u3082\u958b\u50ac|date=May 20, 2019|publisher=Excite Japan}}</ref> The showcase sold over 1,000 tickets with an attendance of 1,500 people. It was reported that around 15,000 applied to attend but due to the capacity limit of the venue, some could not make it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mdpr.jp/k-enta/detail/1853949|title=(G)I-DLE\u3001\u65e5\u672c\u521d\u30e9\u30a4\u30d6\u3067\u30c7\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc\u66f2\u300cLATATA\u300d\u521d\u62ab\u9732\uff1c\u30bb\u30c3\u30c8\u30ea\u30b9\u30c8\uff1e|date=July 24, 2019|publisher=Model Press Japan}}</ref> On July 31, (G)I-dle debuted in the Japanese market with the release of their EP ''[[Latata (EP)|Latata]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sp.universal-music.co.jp/g-i-dle/latata/|title=((G)i-dle Latata Japanese single release|publisher=Universal Music Japan}}</ref> On August 19, (G)I-dle and makeup brand ''Kate'' collaborated to release a spin-off music video of \"Latata (Japanese ver.)\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.universal-music.co.jp/g-i-dle/news/2019-08-19/|title=LATATA \u30af\u30e9\u30c3\u30b7\u30e5\u30c0\u30a4\u30e4\u30e2\u30f3\u30c9\u30a2\u30a4\u30baver.\u300d\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30c3\u30af\u30d3\u30c7\u30aa\u516c\u958b|language=ja|publisher=Universal Music Japan}}</ref>\n\n(G)I-dle subsequently participated in a reality girl group survival show created by [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]], ''[[Queendom (TV series)|Queendom]]''.<ref name=\"Queendom\">{{cite web|title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5] \ub9c8\ub9c8\ubb34\u00b7AOA\u2192\ub7ec\ube14\ub9ac\uc988\u00b7\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 \uc608\ub2a5 '\ud038\ub364' \ucd9c\uc5f0|url=http://m.isplus.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?total_id=23532491&cloc=#RedyAi|work=JTBC|date=July 22, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> In the first preliminary round, (G)I-dle finished first place after performing \"Latata\" reimagined with a concept of [[shamanism]].<ref>{{cite web|title='\ud038\ub364' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc8fc\uc220\uc0ac \ucf58\uc149\ud2b8 'LATATA'\ub85c \ubb34\ub300 \uc555\ub3c4|url=http://www.newstomato.com/ReadNews.aspx?no=918699|work=News Tomato|date=September 6, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> The introduction of the performance, Minnie's Thai \"enchantment\", was well received and became a hot topic among both Korean and Thai fans.<ref>{{cite web|title=\ubd89\uc740 \ub808\uc774\uc800\uc640 \ubbfc\ub2c8\uc758 \ubabd\ud658\uc801\uc778 \ud0dc\uad6d\uc5b4 \uc8fc\ubb38\uc73c\ub85c\u2026 \"\ud038\ub364\"|url=http://www.insightkorea.co.kr//news/articleView.html?idxno=57330|work=Insight Korea|date=September 11, 2019|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=QUEENDOM: (G)I-DLE \u0e40\u0e25\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e01\u0e04\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e40\u0e0b\u0e1b\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e2d\u0e1c\u0e35\u0e2a\u0e23\u0e49\u0e32\u0e07\u0e42\u0e0a\u0e27\u0e4c\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e48\u0e40\u0e1e\u0e25\u0e07 LATATA|url=http://www.hallyukstar.com/2019/09/05/gi-dle-queendom-latata/|work=HallyuKStar|date=September 5, 2019|language=thai}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=(G)I-DLE \u0e23\u0e38\u0e01\u0e01\u0e35\u0e49\u0e40\u0e01\u0e34\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e25\u0e01\u0e23\u0e38\u0e4a\u0e1b\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e14\u0e1b\u0e31\u0e07\u0e17\u0e35\u0e48\u0e23\u0e38\u0e48\u0e19\u0e1e\u0e35\u0e48\u0e43\u0e19\u0e27\u0e07\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e22\u0e31\u0e07\u0e22\u0e01\u0e19\u0e34\u0e49\u0e27\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e49 \u0e2d\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e2d\u0e22\u0e32\u0e01\u0e42\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e42\u0e21\u0e15\u0e43\u0e19\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22 (\u0e21\u0e35\u0e1a\u0e17\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e21\u0e20\u0e32\u0e29\u0e13\u0e4c)|url=https://sudsapda.com/top-lists/179971.html|work=Sudsapda|date=October 5, 2019|language=thai}}</ref> In the second preliminary round (G)I-dle reinterpreted [[2ne1]]'s [[Fire (2NE1 song)|Fire]], finishing in last place.<ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, 2NE1 \u2018Fire\u2019 \ucee4\ubc84..\ubc15\ubd04 \ub208\ubb3c (\ud038\ub364)|url=http://sports.mk.co.kr/view.php?year=2019&no=747487|work=MK Sports|date=September 19, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> At the end of September, they held their first fan meeting, ''Welcome to the Neverland,'' at Yes24 Live Hall in Seoul.<ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uccab \uacf5\uc2dd \ud32c\ud074\ub7fd \ucc3d\ub2e8\uc2dd \uc131\ub8cc\u2026 \uac10\ub3d9\uc73c\ub85c \ucc44\uc6b4 180\ubd84|url=http://enews.imbc.com/News/RetrieveNewsInfo/266800|work=iMBC|date=September 23, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> Tickets to the show were sold out in two minutes.<ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uad6d\ub0b4 \uccab \ud32c\ud074\ub7fd \ucc3d\ub2e8\uc2dd '\uc6f0\ucef4 \ud22c \ub124\ubc84\ub79c\ub4dc' \uc804\uc11d\ub9e4\uc9c4|url=http://www.etnews.com/20190823000082|work=ETNews|date=August 23, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n[[File:(G)I-DLE at Dream Concert on May 18, 2019.png|thumbnail|right|(G)I-dle in May 2019]]\nOn October 4, (G)I-dle performed as first-time main headliner at the [[Spotify]] On Stage Jakarta. They were one of the six acts including [[Rich Brian]], [[Ateez]], and more.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rich Brian, (G)I-DLE, ATEEZ, and More Delighted Thousands of Fans Live at Spotify On Stage Jakarta|url=https://newsroom.spotify.com/2019-10-07/rich-brian-gi-dle-ateez-and-more-delighted-thousands-of-fans-live-at-spotify-on-stage-jakarta/|work=Spotify News|date=October 7, 2019}}</ref> On October 5, the group appeared on [[Immortal Songs: Singing the Legend|Immortal Songs 2]], a [[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS]]'s reality television singing competition. This marks the group's first appearance on the program.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018\ubd88\ud6c4\uc758 \uba85\uace1\u2019 (\uc5ec\uc790) \uc544\uc774\ub4e4 \u201c\ub370\ubdd4\uace1 \u2018LATATA\u2019, \uac1c\ucf58 \ubcf4\uace0 \uc601\uac10 \uc5bb\uc5b4\u201d|url=https://sports.donga.com/3/all/20191005/97740812/1|work=Sports DOnga|date=October 5, 2019}}</ref> They performed a rendition of [[Koyote]]'s Sad Dream as a part of the group's 20th anniversary.<ref>{{cite web|title='\ubd88\ud6c4\uc758 \uba85\uace1' (\uc5ec\uc790) \uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ucf54\uc694\ud0dc '\ube44\ubabd'\uc73c\ub85c \ub9e4\ud639\uc801\uc778 \ubb34\ub300 [\uc804\uc77c\uc57c\ud654]|url=http://www.xportsnews.com/?ac=article_view&entry_id=1178602|work=XSPortsNews|date=October 6, 2019}}</ref> (G)I-dle performed \"[[I Made#Singles|Put It Straight\" (Nightmare Version)]] for Queendom's \"Fan-dora's Box\" round.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"\ubbf8\ucce4\ub2e4\" \ub9d0 \ubc16\uc5d0 \uc548 \ub098\uc624\ub294 \uc5b4\uc81c\uc790 \ud038\ub364 \uc5ed\ub300\uae09 \ubb34\ub300 \uc5f0\ucd9c (\uc601\uc0c1)|url=https://www.wikitree.co.kr/main/news_view.php?id=473171|work=WikiTree|date=October 18, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> The stage performance reached a million views after 14 hours of release, placing fourth in the round.<ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, '\ud038\ub364' \uacbd\uc5f0\uace1 '\uc2eb\ub2e4\uace0 \ub9d0\ud574' \uc601\uc0c1 1000\ub9cc\ubdf0 \ub3cc\ud30c|url=http://www.etnews.com/20191018000220|work=Electronic Newspaper|author=Dong Sun Park|date=October 18, 2019|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title='\ud038\ub364' \uc624\ub9c8\uc774\uac78 3\ucc28 \uc0ac\uc804 \uacbd\uc5f0 1\uc704 \ucc28\uc9c0|url=http://www.ccreview.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=211097|work=Chungcheong Reviews|author=Kwon Young-suk|date=October 24, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> On October 25, (G)I-dle released \"[[Lion ((G)I-dle song)|Lion]]\" as part of ''[[Queendom Final Comeback]]'' EP.<ref>{{cite web|title=[\ud22c\ub370\uc774IS] '\ud038\ub364' AOA\u00b7\ub9c8\ub9c8\ubb34\u2192\uc624\ub9c8\uc774\uac78\u00b7\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ub3d9\uc2dc \uc74c\uc6d0\ubc1c\ub9e4|url=http://isplus.live.joins.com/news/article/article.asp?total_id=23614772&cloc=|work=Daily Sports|author=Hwang Ji Young|date=October 25, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> As of November 2019, the live performances of \"Latata\" and \"Fire\" have surpassed 11 and 13 million views, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"\ub9c8\ub9c8\ubb34 \uc774\ub984\uac12, (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 \ubc1c\uacac\"\u2026'\ud038\ub364', \ub450 \ub2ec \ub3d9\uc548 \uc5bb\uc740 \uac83 [\uc885\ud569]|url=http://osen.mt.co.kr/article/G1111253078|publisher=OSEN|date=November 1, 2019}}</ref> (G)I-dle finished the show in third place.<ref>{{cite web|title='\uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 \ucef4\ubc31 \uc804\uc7c1' \ud038\ub364 \ucd5c\uc885 \uc21c\uc704\ub294? \"1\uc704 \ub9c8\ub9c8\ubb34, 2\uc704 \uc624\ub9c8\uc774\uac78\u2026\"|url=http://www.segye.com/newsView/20191101504352?OutUrl=naver|publisher=Segye|date=November 1, 2019}}</ref> \"Lion\" became a [[sleeper hit]] after gaining popularity on their stage concept of ''The Queen's Royal Welcome'', re-entering the real-time charts of various music sites.<ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \u2018\ud038\ub364\u2019 \ud6a8\uacfc \ud1a1\ud1a1\u2026\u2018LION\u2019 \ubb34\ub300 \uc720\ud29c\ube0c \uc870\ud68c\uc218 \uae09\ub4f1|trans-title=(G)I-dle 'Queendom' effect 'LION' stage YouTube views soar|url=http://www.sportsworldi.com/newsView/20191101506834|publisher=Sports World|author=Jung Ga-young|date=November 1, 2019}}</ref>  A music video for it was released on November 4.<ref>{{cite web|title=\n\u2018\ud038\ub364\u2019 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \u2018\ub77c\uc774\uc5b8\u2019 \ubba4\uc9c1\ube44\ub514\uc624 \uc804\uaca9 \uacf5\uac1c|url=http://www.xportsnews.com/?ac=article_view&entry_id=1192529|publisher=XportsNews|date=November 4, 2019}}</ref> The video surpassed 5 million views in two days.<ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 'LION' \ubba4\uc9c1\ube44\ub514\uc624, \uacf5\uac1c \uc774\ud2c0 \ub9cc\uc5d0 500\ub9cc \ubdf0 \ub3cc\ud30c|url=https://www.sedaily.com/NewsView/1VQOIW8YYX|author=Kim Joo Won|publisher=Seoul Economy|date=November 5, 2019}}</ref> The song debuted at number 13 on the World Digital Song Sales and peaked at number 5.<ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 'LION', \u7f8e \ube4c\ubcf4\ub4dc \uc6d4\ub4dc \ub514\uc9c0\ud138 \uc1a1 \uc138\uc77c\uc988 \ucc28\ud2b8 5\uc704|trans-title=(G)I-DLE's LION ranked 5th on the Billboard World Digital Song Sales Chart|url=http://news.wowtv.co.kr/NewsCenter/News/Read?articleId=A201911130389&t=NN|website=Korea Economic TV|date=November 13, 2019}}</ref> Simultaneously, the single rose eighty-nine spots to number 19 on the [[Gaon Digital Chart]] and topped China's [[QQ Music]] Korean Song chart for two consecutive weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=ALL&targetTime=45&hitYear=2019&termGbn=week|title=Digital Chart \u2013 Week 45 of 2019|website=Gaon Chart|language=ko|accessdate=November 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xportsnews.com/?ac=article_view&entry_id=1197736|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \u4e2d QQ\ubba4\uc9c1 \ud55c\uad6d\uac00\uc694 \ucc28\ud2b8 2\uc8fc \uc5f0\uc18d 1\uc704\u2026\uae00\ub85c\ubc8c \ub300\uc138 \uc785\uc99d|author=Lee Deok-haeng|website=XSportsNews|language=ko|date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> On December 21, (G)I-dle performed their hit singles at the 2020 Tainan Christmas & New Year Eve Party at [[Tainan|Tainan City]], [[Taiwan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kstarhk.com/9504/\u53f0\u7063\u6f14\u5531\u6703-\uff08g\uff09i-dle\u58d3\u8ef8\u6f14\u51fa\u300c2020\u81fa\u5357\u597dyoung\u8036\u8a95\u8de8\u5e74\u300d/|title=[\u53f0\u7063\u6f14\u5531\u6703] \uff08G\uff09I-DLE\u58d3\u8ef8\u6f14\u51fa\u300c2020\u81fa\u5357\u597dyoung\u8036\u8a95\u8de8\u5e74\u300d\u6f14\u5531\u6703\u71b1HIGH\u767b\u5834(191221)|trans-title=[Taiwan Concert] (G) I-DLE Finale Performs \"2020 Tainan Good Young New Year's Eve\" Concert Hit High (191221)|website=K-Star HK|date=December 22, 2019}}</ref> Their stage was recorded the highest tide of the event of an appearance of 80,000 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.secjie.com.tw/newsview_3713.html|title=\u53f0\u5357\u597dyoung\u8036\u8a95\u8de8\u5e74\u6f14\u5531\u6703\u5168\u5834\u55e8\u7ffb\u5929|language=tw|date=December 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2020: I-Land tour and ''I Trust''===\nOn January 28, 2020, the group announced their first world tour, titled \"I-Land: Who Am I\", which would span 32 different cities around the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uae00\ub85c\ubc8c \ud32c \ub9cc\ub09c\ub2e4\u2026\uc138\uacc4 32\uac1c \ub3c4\uc2dc\uc11c \uccab \uc6d4\ub4dc\ud22c\uc5b4|trans-title=(G)I-DLE meet global fan\u2026 First World Tour in 32 Cities of the World|url=https://www.edaily.co.kr/news/read?newsId=01115206625642640&mediaCodeNo=258|website=EDaily|date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Later, it was announced their commenced show in Bangkok and new album release project in mid-March was postponed in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus outbreak]] and to ensure the safety and health of the artist, fans, and staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mksports.co.kr/view/2020/153119/|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uccab \uc6d4\ub4dc\ud22c\uc5b4 \ubc29\ucf55 \uacf5\uc5f0 \uc77c\uc815 \uc5f0\uae30\u2026\u201c\ucf54\ub85c\ub09819 \ud655\uc0b0 \uc6b0\ub824\u201d|trans-title=(G)I-dle postponed their first World Tour Bangkok show\u2026 \"Concern Spreading Corona 19\"|work=MK Sports|author=Kim Na-young|date=February 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsseoul.com/news/read/888880|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc6d4\ub4dc\ud22c\uc5b4\u00b73\uc6d4 \uc0c8 \uc568\ubc94 \ubc1c\ub9e4 \ud504\ub85c\uc81d\ud2b8 \uc7a0\uc815 \uc5f0\uae30[\uacf5\uc2dd]|trans-title=(G)I-dle World Tour, March New album release project tentatively postponed [Official]|work=Spots Seoul|author=Choi Jin-sil|date=February 28, 2020|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, 2020, Cube Entertainment announced that (G)I-dle would be making a comeback with an extended play in early April. It was reported that they have already completed their album jacket photoshoot, filming of the music video and are in the final stages of comeback preparations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news1.kr/articles/?3878475|title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5] (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, 3\uc6d4 \uc911\uc21c\u21924\uc6d4 \ucd08 \ucef4\ubc31 \ud655\uc815\u2026MV \ucd2c\uc601 \uc644\ub8cc|trans-title=(G)I-dle mid-March \u2192 early comeback in early April\u2026 MV shooting completed|work=News1|author=Kim Min-ji|date= March 19, 2020}}</ref> Their third EP, ''[[I Trust]]'', is scheduled to release on April 6 with \"[[Oh My God ((G)I-dle song)|Oh My God]]\" as its lead single.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.khan.co.kr/entertainment/sk_index.html?art_id=202003240739003&sec_id=540101&pt=nv|title=[\uacf5\uc2dd] (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc138 \ubc88\uc9f8 \ubbf8\ub2c8\uc568\ubc94 \u2018I trust\u2019\ub85c 9\uac1c\uc6d4 \ub9cc\uc5d0 \ucef4\ubc31\u20264\uc6d4 6\uc77c \ubc1c\ub9e4 \ud655\uc815|trans-title=[Official] (G)I-DLE comeback in 9 months with third mini album 'I trust'\u2026 April 6 release confirmed|work=KyungHyang Newspaper|author=Yoo In-sun|date=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbnnews.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=382217|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc804\uc18c\uc5f0 \uc790\uc791\uace1 'Oh my god'\uc73c\ub85c \ucef4\ubc31|trans-title=[Official] (G)I-DLE comeback with Jeon So-yeon's own song \"Oh My God\"|work=NBN News|author=Hong Seung-hoon|date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, 2020, (G)I-dle was announced as part of the lineup of the 2020 [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] Stream Aid, scheduled for March 28. The livestream is a 12-hour charity livestream concert aiming to raise money for COVID-19 relief. They are the first female K-pop group to participate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.twitch.tv/en/2020/03/26/twitch-stream-aid-go-live-to-save-lives-on-328/|title=Twitch Stream Aid: Go live to save lives on 3/28|publisher=[[Twitch (service)|Twitch]]|date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2020/03/27/you-can-watch-monsta-x-and-gi-dle-twitch-stream-aid-weekend|title=You can watch MONSTA X and (G)I-DLE in Twitch Stream Aid this weekend|publisher=SBS PopAsia|date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Members ==\n* [[Cho Mi-yeon|Miyeon]] (\ubbf8\uc5f0)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?where=nexearch&query=%EB%AF%B8%EC%97%B0&sm=ppl_cts&ie=utf8&key=PeopleService&os=8207420|title=Miyeon official 'Naver' profile}}</ref>\n* [[Minnie (singer)|Minnie]] (\ubbfc\ub2c8)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?where=nexearch&query=%EB%AF%BC%EB%8B%88&sm=ppl_cts&ie=utf8&key=PeopleService&os=8207418|title=Minnie official 'Naver' profile}}</ref>\n* Soojin (\uc218\uc9c4)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?where=nexearch&query=%EC%88%98%EC%A7%84&sm=ppl_cts&ie=utf8&key=PeopleService&os=8207416|title=Soojin official 'Naver' profile}}</ref>\n* [[Jeon So-yeon|Soyeon]] (\uc18c\uc5f0)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?where=nexearch&query=%EC%86%8C%EC%97%B0&sm=ppl_cts&ie=utf8&key=PeopleService&os=3885550|title=Soyeon official 'Naver' profile}}</ref>\n* [[Song Yuqi|Yuqi]] (\uc6b0\uae30)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?where=nexearch&query=%EC%9A%B0%EA%B8%B0&sm=ppl_cts&ie=utf8&key=PeopleService&os=8207399|title=Yuqi official 'Naver' profile}}</ref>\n* Shuhua (\uc288\ud654)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?where=nexearch&query=%EC%8A%88%ED%99%94&sm=ppl_cts&ie=utf8&key=PeopleService&os=8207395|title=Shuhua official 'Naver' profile}}</ref>\n\n== Artistry ==\n[[File:180908 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 (G)I-DLE DMC Festival.png|thumb|right|(G)I-dle in September 2018]]\n\n=== Image ===\n(G)I-dle was praised for their musicality and ambiguity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://star.ohmynews.com/NWS_Web/OhmyStar/at_pg.aspx?CNTN_CD=A0002466220&CMPT_CD=P0010|title=\ub370\ubdd4 3\uac1c\uc6d4\ucc28 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc2e0 \uc74c\uc6d0\uac15\uc790\ub85c \uc790\ub9ac\ub9e4\uae40\ud560\uae4c?|author=Son Hwa-sin|date=August 25, 2018|work=OhmyNews}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=201809051043500410|title=\u2018\uc74c\uc6d0\ucc28\ud2b8\u2192\uc74c\ubc29 1\uc704\u2019 \uc544\uc774\ub4e4, 5\uac1c\uc6d4\ucc28 \uc548\ubbff\uae30\ub294 \uad34\ubb3c\uc2e0\uc778 \ud589\ubcf4[\ubba4\uc9c1\uc640\uce58]|author=Hwang Hye-jin|date=September 5, 2018|work=Newsen}}</ref> Natalie Morin from [[Refinery29]] described them as individuals with different energies that complements each other.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3132673/gi-dle-interview-self-produced-music-soyeon/|title=Meet (G)I-dle, The Women In K-Pop Who Are Unafraid To Grab The Mic|author=Natalie Morin|date=August 1, 2019|work=[[Refinery29]]}}</ref>  She also described them as \"bold and sensual\", characteristics which she asserts sets them apart from other K-pop girl groups. ''Mor.bo'' named them as a diverse group that is unafraid to try different music styles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ismorbo.com/mor-bo-radar-5-nuevos-grupos-k-pop-que-experimentan-con-edm-hip-hop-y-rb/|title=5 nuevos grupos K-pop que experimentan con EDM, hip hop y R&B|date=August 14, 2019|work=MOR.BO}}</ref> ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]] magazine'' named the group as \"independent musicians and artists\" where girl groups' concepts typically work within a mold that was made by someone else.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elle.co.kr/article/42660|title=\ud038\ub364, \uc5ec\uc790 \uc544\uc774\ub3cc\uc758 \uc7ac\ubc1c\uacac \uc21c\uac044 \uc5ec\uc790 \uc544\uc774\ub3cc\uc758 '\uc544\ud2f0\uc2a4\ud2b8'\ub85c\uc11c\uc758 \uacbd\uc7c1\uc774 \ube5b\uc744 \ubc1c\ud558\ub294 \uc21c\uac04, \uba4b\uc9d0\uc740 \ub450 \ubc30\ub85c \ud3ed\ubc1c\ud55c\ub2e4|trans-title=5 Scenes of the Rediscovery of Female Idols.|date=October 14, 2019|work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]}}</ref>\n\nDespite being the youngest group to appear on ''Queendom'', (G)I-dle members were actively involved in their own music videos, jacket photoshoots, song arrangements, choreography, and outfits production.<ref name=\"2nd\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tvreport.co.kr/2014513|trans-title=Second year (G)I-DLE able to turn Queendom upside down|title='\ub370\ubdd4 2\ub144 \ucc28' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, '\ud038\ub364' \ub4a4\uc9d1\uc5b4\ub193\uc744 \uc218 \uc788\ub358 \uc774\uc720|author=Kim Min-ji|date=October 19, 2019|work=TvReport}}</ref>\n\n=== Musical style ===\nTaylor Glasby from [[MTV]] stated that (G)I-dle songs are steeped in their very essence \u2014 a girl's complex, internal house of mirrors that is constantly being broken, assessed, understood, and remade, where one style or sound is never enough to reflect who they are. (G)I-dle is the enticing tropical beats and coy finger snaps of \"Latata\" and the ominous, warning whistled hook of \"Hann (Alone)\". They are also the pensive harmonies and slow throb of bass on the R&B-infused ballad \"Put It Straight,\" the whimsical words painted over the house music of \"What's In Your House,\" and even the tango of \"Senorita\". Their lyrics push back, they beckon. They can be boring nonchalance or sharpening desire.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3132673/gi-dle-interview-self-produced-music-soyeon/|title=(G)I-DLE ARE 'STANDING OUT' WITH THEIR SELF-PRODUCED SOUND AND DEFINING IT ON THEIR OWN TERMS|date=July 26, 2019|website=MTV News}}</ref>\n\nKim Na-yul writing for [[Herald Corporation|Herald Pop]] described (G)I-dle's genre can only be performed by them and made a good impression on the public.<ref>{{cite web|title=[POP\ucd08\uc810]\"\ud038\ub364 \ucd5c\ub300 \uc218\ud61c\" (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, 'LION' MV \uacf5\uac1c\u2192\uc5f0\uc77c \ud654\uc81c\uc131 \u7532|url=http://pop.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=201911042216354818533_1|publisher=HeraldPop|author=Kim Na Yul|date=November 4, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Melon (online music service)|Melon]] magazine'' described (G)I-dle's music generally as \"Uniqueness is (G)I-dle's most powerful weapon.\" crossing genres from \"Latata\" (moombahton), \"Hann (Alone)\" (Eastern European rhythm), \"Senorita\" (Latin pop) and \"Uh-Oh\" (Boom bap).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.melon.com/musicstory/inform.htm?mstorySeq=9829|title=2019\ub144\uc758 K-POP \ud2b8\ub799 7|date=December 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Stage performance===\nThe group was also praised for their stage presence during performances such as [[Melon Music Awards|2018 MMA]]'s golden stage reminiscent of [[Cleopatra]], and [[2018 Mnet Asian Music Awards|2018 MAMA]]'s stage performing with dozens of female dancers to emphasize the image of women.<ref name=\"HOT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ize.co.kr/articleView.html?no=2018123100287240092|trans-title=2018 year-end awards ceremony BEST|title=2018 \uc5f0\ub9d0 \uac00\uc694\uc2dc\uc0c1\uc2dd \ubb34\ub300 BEST|author=Park Hee Ah|date=December 31, 2018|work=Ize Magazine}}</ref> It is also stated that their performance for Fan-dora's Box was \"another legendary stage\" due to the emotional acting by the members where they expressed \"anger in sadness\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=201910181351467619530_1|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, '\ud038\ub364' 3\ucc28 \uacbd\uc5f0 '\uc2eb\ub2e4\uace0 \ub9d0\ud574' \uc720\ud29c\ube0c \uc870\ud68c\uc218 100\ub9cc\ubdf0 \ub3cc\ud30c|date=October 18, 2019|work=HeraldPop|language=ko}}</ref> (G)I-dle gave their last ''Queendom'' stage, \"[[Lion ((G)I-dle song)#Live_performance|Lion]]\" with the ''Lion'' story which was narrated by Minnie, danced in golden robes ornately decorated with lion's mane and finished with a herd of lions [dancers] following (G)I-dle to the six thrones. The stage was described as \"a world-class stage\" and \"a legendary stage\".<ref>{{cite web|title='\ud038\ub364' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc601\ud654\uac19\uc740 \ud53c\ub0a0\ub808\u2026\"\uc774 \uc18c\ub140\ub294, LION\" (\uc601\uc0c1)|url=http://www.newstomato.com/ReadNews.aspx?no=930382|publisher=News Tomato|author=Kim Hee-kyung|date=November 1, 2019}}</ref> This resulted in winning  several performance awards including [[Golden Disc Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=201911271338474996408_1|work=HeraldPop|author=Kim Na-yul|date=November 27, 2019|title='2019 AAA' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, AAA \uadf8\ub974\ubd80\uc0c1 \uc218\uc0c1..\"\ub354 \uc88b\uc740 \ubaa8\uc2b5\uc73c\ub85c \ubcf4\ub2f5\"|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=202001051655489275771_1|script-title=ko:[2020 \uace8\ub4e0\ub514\uc2a4\ud06c]\uc544\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub85c\u00b7(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ubca0\uc2a4\ud2b8\ud37c\ud3ec\uba3c\uc2a4\uc0c1 \"\uc0c8\ud574 \ucd9c\ubc1c\ubd80\ud130 \uac10\uc0ac\"|date=January 5, 2020|work=HeraldPop|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tfmusicawards.com/winner_2nd_tf.html|title=WINNER 2019 THE FACT MUSIC AWARDS|work=The Fact Music Award|date=March 16, 2020|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\nThe group was recognized for its brand recognition and marketing power, having topped the \"Girl Group Brand Power Ranking\" published by the Korean Business Research Institute. In 2018, they ranked #1 for June and September.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rekorea.net/bbs/board.php?bo_table=repu4&wr_id=256|title=[\ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc\ud3c9\ud310] \uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 \ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc 2018\ub144 6\uc6d4 \ube45\ub370\uc774\ud130 \ubd84\uc11d...1\uc704 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4|publisher=Korea Reputation Research Institute|date=June 9, 2018}}</ref> Their highest brand reputation index was in September 2018.<ref name=\"\uc5ec\uc790\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 \ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc\ud3c9\ud310 1\uc704 \ub4f1\uadf9 '\ud038\ub364' \ud6a8\uacfc\">{{cite news|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/stview.php?no=2019101310271318907|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 \ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc\ud3c9\ud310 1\uc704 \ub4f1\uadf9 \"'\ud038\ub364' \ud6a8\uacfc\"|publisher=Star News|date=October 13, 2019}}</ref> (G)I-dle has been dubbed the \"monster rookie\" of 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=201805251656197111616_1|title='\ubba4\uc9c1\ubc45\ud06c' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uad34\ubb3c \uc2e0\uc778\uc758 \uc139\uc2dc+\uace0\ud639 'LATATA'|work=HeraldPop|publisher=Ko Myung-jin|date=May 25, 2018|access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://star.hankookilbo.com/News/Read/201901071602365871?did=NA&dtype=&dtypecode=&prnewsid=|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc2e0\uc778\uc0c1 5\uad00\uc655 \ub2ec\uc131...\u20192018 \uad34\ubb3c \uc2e0\uc778\u2019 \uc785\uc99d|work=Hankook Ilbo|publisher=Kim Han-na|date=January 7, 2019|access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref> [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] ranked them at the top of its list as the best new K-pop group of 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/8491744/best-new-k-pop-acts-2018|title=10 Best New K-Pop Acts of 2018|website=Billboard|date=December 29, 2018|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref> It was reported that Cube's music sales in 2018 increased by 58% to \u20a98.8 billion due to the popularity of (G)I-dle's \"Latata\" and \"Hann (\u4e00)\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.edaily.co.kr/news/read?newsId=03227526622394784&mediaCodeNo=257&OutLnkChk=Y|title=\ud050\ube0c\uc5d4\ud130 \uc9c0\ub09c\ud574 \ub9e4\ucd9c 358\uc5b5\uc6d0\u2026\uc0c1\uc7a5 \uc774\ud6c4 \ucd5c\ub300 \uc2e4\uc801 \ub2ec\uc131|trans-title=Cube Entertainment last year revenue of KRW 35.8 billion\u2026 Achieve maximum performance|work=EDaily|author=Kim Sung-hoon|date=February 27, 2019|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, (G)I-dle gained more recognition in the general public after appearing on ''[[Queendom (TV series)|Queendom]]''.<ref name=\"\uc5ec\uc790\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 \ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc\ud3c9\ud310 1\uc704 \ub4f1\uadf9 '\ud038\ub364' \ud6a8\uacfc\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://kenh14.vn/gi-dle-thong-tri-top-trending-voi-san-khau-cung-loat-than-thai-hoi-huom-kinh-di-20191018000146858.chn|title=(G)I-DLE th\u1ed1ng tr\u1ecb top trending v\u1edbi s\u00e2n kh\u1ea5u c\u00f9ng lo\u1ea1t th\u1ea7n th\u00e1i h\u01a1i h\u01b0\u1edbm kinh d\u1ecb|publisher=kenh14|author=Hoang Chi|date=October 18, 2019|language=vi}}</ref> The performance of their finale song \"Lion\" was considered as one of K-pop's biggest moments of 2019 by [[CTV News]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Somos |first1=Christy |title=These are some of K-pop's biggest moments of 2019 |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/entertainment/these-are-some-of-k-pop-s-biggest-moments-of-2019-1.4738811 |website=CTVNews |accessdate=January 6, 2020 |language=en |date=December 20, 2019}}</ref> This resulted in them topping the \"Girl Group Brand Power Ranking\" for two consecutive months, in October and November 2019, respectively.<ref name=\"2nd\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://enews24.tving.com/news/article?nsID=1331406|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, '\ud038\ub364' \uacbd\uc5f0\uace1 '\uc2eb\ub2e4\uace0 \ub9d0\ud574'\ub85c 100\ub9cc\ubdf0 \ub3cc\ud30c '\ud6c4\ub048'|author=Kim Ji-yeon|date=October 18, 2019|work=eNews24|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cnews.thebigdata.co.kr/view.php?ud=20191013100321789607d270612f_23|title=\uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 \ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc\ud3c9\ud310 10\uc6d4 \ube45\ub370\uc774\ud130 \ubd84\uc11d 1\uc704\ub294 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4... 2\uc704 \ud2b8\uc640\uc774\uc2a4 ...|author=Kim Soo-ah|date=October 13, 2019|work=The Big Data News|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvdaily.asiae.co.kr/read.php3?aid=15733474531505465010#rs|title='\ud038\ub364 \ud6a8\uacfc' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, 11\uc6d4 \uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 \ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc\ud3c9\ud310 1\uc704|author=Hwang Seo-yeon|date=November 10, 2019|work=TvDaily|language=ko}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' India included \"Lion\" in their list of the 10 Best K-Pop Music Videos of 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rollingstoneindia.com/10-best-k-pop-music-videos-of-2019/|author=Riddhi Chakraborty|date=December 30, 2019|accessdate=January 8, 2020|title=10 Best K-Pop Music Videos of 2019|work=Rolling Stone India}}</ref> The song was considered as \"one of the most visceral tracks of 2019\" and was listed number one out of 920 songs released in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=The 25 Best K-pop Songs of 2019: Critics' Picks|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/international/8547126/the-25-best-k-pop-songs-of-2019-critics-picks|publisher=Billboard|date=December 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\uacb0\uc0b0 2019 : \ucd5c\uace0\uc758 \ub178\ub798|trans-title=Closing 2019: best songs|url=http://idology.kr/12885|publisher=Idology|date=February 11, 2020}}</ref> In January 2020, (G)I-dle were voted as the Most Anticipated Singers/Groups in 2020 based on surveys that were participated by several Korean music agencies, broadcasting and program officials, composers and popular music critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news1.kr/articles/?3807390|title=[\uc2e0\ub144\ud2b9\uc9d1] \uc804\ubb38\uac00 21\uc778 \uc120\uc815, 2020 \uac00\uc7a5 \uae30\ub300\ub418\ub294 \uac00\uc218\ub294|trans-title=[New Year Special] 21 Experts, 2020 Most Expected Singers|date=January 4, 2020|work=News1|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/stview.php?no=2019123108275558313|title=\uac00\uc694 \uad00\uacc4\uc790 \uc120\uc815 2020 \ud65c\uc57d \uae30\ub300\ub418\ub294 \uadf8\ub8f9\uc740?\u2466[2020 \u2606\uc2e0\ub144\uae30\ud68d]|date=January 3, 2020|work=Star News|language=ko}}</ref> In February 2020, the group achieved number 1 in brand power with the most-interacted topics \"Lion\" and world tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rekorea.net/bbs/board.php?bo_table=repu4&wr_id=453|title=\t[\ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc\ud3c9\ud310] \uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 \ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc 2020\ub144 2\uc6d4 \ube45\ub370\uc774\ud130 \ubd84\uc11d\uacb0\uacfc...1\uc704 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, 2\uc704 \ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3, 3\uc704 \uc774\ub2ec\uc758 |date=February 9, 2020|work=Korea Reputation|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n===Guinness World Record===\n(G)I-dle achieved a new [[Guinness World Record]] with [[#Music Content Company|1theK]] record challenge ''Kkinness Challenge'' on episode 4.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1-3r-7CGOcY|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 \uc2e0\uae30\ub85d\ud83d\udc51 \ud50c\ub809\uc2a4 \ud55c \ud604\uc7a5! (\uc785.\ud2c0.\ub9c9\ud83d\ude4a) (G)I-DLE \ub07c\ub124\uc2a4\ucd0c EP.4 KKINNESS CHALLENGE LION Uh-Oh|date=March 24, 2020|publisher=1theK Originals - \uc6d0\ub354\ucf00\uc774 \uc624\ub9ac\uc9c0\ub110}}</ref> ''Kkinness Challenge'' is an 'Idol Guinness Challenge' that contains the process by which an idol group enters Kkinness Village, an athlete village designed to challenge the world record of extreme events. In the video released on March 24, 2020, the group succeeded in achieving a new world record for the \"Fastest time to hang up five T-shirts\" in 25.41 seconds; the previous record-holder was held by Kaito Kozumi in 27.93 seconds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rpm9.com/news/article.html?id=20200325090008|title='\ub07c\ub124\uc2a4\ucd0c' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uae00\ub85c\ubc8c \uc774\uc0c9 \uc2e0\uae30\ub85d\ub2ec\uc131\u2026'\uc637\uac78\uc774\uc5d0 \ud2f0\uc154\uce20 5\uc7a5 \ube68\ub9ac\uac78\uae30' \ubbf8\uc158\uc131\uacf5|trans-title='Kinness Village' (G)I-dle, Achieve Global New Record\u2026 Success of 'Five pieces of T-shirts on hangers'|author=Park Dong-sun|date=March 25, 2020|work=RPM9}}</ref> On the first attempt, member Soyeon scored 28.34 seconds, which was close to the Guinness record, but unfortunately failed. Subsequently, member Shuhua, took the challenge and recorded 26.81 seconds breaking the world record. However, Soyeon who re-challenged, recorded 25.41 seconds and breaking the previous record by Shuhua. The record will be recognized as the official world record by the world's top 3 record certification agency, Supertalent World Record, and will proceed with the official procedure for Guinness listing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.donga.com/ent/article/all/20200325/100337634/1|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uae30\ub124\uc2a4 \uc138\uacc4\uc2e0\uae30\ub85d \uacbd\uc2e0\u2192\uc6d4\ub4dc\ud074\ub798\uc2a4 \ub4f1\uadf9|trans-title=(G)I-dle, break the world record for Guinness \u2192 World Class|author=Hong Se-young|date=March 25, 2020|work=Sports Donga}}</ref>\n\n== Ambassadorship ==\n[[Seoul Capital Area|Seoul Metropolitan City]] appointed (G)I-dle as the city's goodwill ambassadors alongside [[Yura (South Korean singer)|Yura]], [[Park Jin-Hee]], and eight other nominees. They will hold the title \"City Ambassadors\" for two years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cstimes.com/?mod=news&act=articleView&idxno=291618|title=\uac78\uc2a4\ub370\uc774 \uc720\ub77c-\ubc30\uc6b0 \ubc15\uc9c4\ud76c, \uc138\uacc4\uc5d0 \uc11c\uc6b8\uc2dc \uc54c\ub9b0\ub2e4|work=CSTimes|date=December 6, 2018}}</ref> On the 10th annual Children's Diabetes Celebration Festival held at Lotte World Underground Kingdom in [[Eunpyeong District|Eunpyeong-gu]], Seoul, they were awarded as the new ambassador for Korean Children's Diabetes Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=109&aid=0004026271|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ud55c\uad6d\uc18c\uc544\ub2f9\ub1e8\uc778\ud611\ud68c \ud64d\ubcf4\ub300\uc0ac \uc704\ucd09 [\uacf5\uc2dd]|work=Osen|date=June 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Endorsements ==\nIn 2019, (G)I-dle became the first Korean girl group to endorse with Kaja, a beauty brand co-created by [[Sephora]] and Memebox to create a new form combining K-beauty and K-pop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wsobi.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=70250|title=\uc5ec\uc790\uc544\uc774\ub4e4\u2019 \uce74\uc790 \ubaa8\ub378\ub85c \uc120\uc815\u2026 K\ubdf0\ud2f0&K\ud31d \uc2dc\ub108\uc9c0 \uae30\ub300|trans-title='(G)I-dle' selected as Kaja model\u2026 Expect K Beauty & K-Pop Synergy|work=Wsobi|author=Lee Ji-eun||date=March 1, 2019|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> Through the partnership, ''To Neverland'' reality TV series and \"Senorita\" music video were released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hypebae.com/2019/2/k-pop-girl-group-gi-dle-announces-kaja-partnership-with-senorita-music-video|title=K-POP GIRL GROUP (G)I-DLE ANNOUNCES KAJA PARTNERSHIP WITH \"SENORITA\" MUSIC VIDEO|work=HypeBae|author=Teresa Lam||date=February 26, 2019|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> \n\n(G)I-dle were selected as Akiii Classic's new model in 2020 to reinforce the sensitivity of [[generation Z|Gen Z]] culture and trend pioneering the brand image.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.khan.co.kr/entertainment/sk_index.html?art_id=202003041029003&sec_id=540101&pt=nv|title=[\uacf5\uc2dd] (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \u2018\uc544\ud0a4\ud074\ub798\uc2dd\u2019 \uc0c8 \ubaa8\ub378 \ubc1c\ud0c1\u2026\ub300\uc138 \ud589\ubcf4 \uc774\uc5b4\uac04\ub2e4|work=Sports Khan|author=Yoo Ha-eun|date=March 4, 2020}}</ref> In early April 2020, (G)I-dle was revealed as a promotional model for South Korea biggest contact lens brand, LensMe. A representative from LensMe explained that the group's unique music and charismatic stage performances matched well with their 'Basic, Trendy, Easy' company image.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lens-me.com/shopinfo/LENSME_MUSE.html|title=LENS-ME WITH (G)I-DLE|publisher=LensMe|date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kgdm.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=688967|title=\uc5ec\uc790\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ucf58\ud0dd\ud2b8\ub80c\uc988 \ube0c\ub79c\ub4dc \uc804\uc18d \ubaa8\ub378\ub85c \ubc1c\ud0c1|work=Gyeonggi Provincial Daily|author=Lee Da-yeon|date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|(G)I-dle discography}}\n{{See also|List of songs recorded by (G)I-dle}}\n\n===Extended plays===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Korean releases'''\n* ''[[I Am ((G)I-dle EP)|I Am]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[I Made]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[I Trust]]'' (2020)\n{{col-2}}\n'''Japanese releases'''\n* ''[[Latata (EP)|Latata]]'' (2019)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Concerts and tours==\n\n===Headlining tours===\n* ''(G)I-dle World Tour I-Land: Who Am I Tour'' (2020)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zenithnews.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=137537|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \uc6d4\ub4dc \ud22c\uc5b4 \uac1c\ucd5c \ud655\uc815\u2026 \uae00\ub85c\ubc8c \ub300\uc138 \ud589\ubcf4|work=ZenithNews|date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Variety show ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Network\n! Ref.\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Queendom (TV series)|Queendom]]''\n| [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]]\n| <ref name=\"Queendom\" />\n|}\n\n=== Reality shows ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Episodes\n! Network\n|-\n| 2018\u2013present\n| ''(G)I-dle: I-Talk''\n| {{TBA|Ongoing}}\n| [[V Live (website)|V Live]], [[YouTube]]\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''(G)I-dle: Vlog in New York''\n| 3\n| V Live\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2019\n| ''To Neverland''\n| 6\n| [[Mnet (TV channel)|M2]], [[Naver]] TV Cast<ref>{{cite web|title=(G)I-DLE to launch their first reality show 'To Neverland' in mid-January through M2 channel with partnership cosmetics brand Kaja|url=https://m.entertain.naver.com/read?oid=609&aid=0000041465|work=Newsen|date=January 4, 2019|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4\uc758 'TO NEVERLAND' \ub9c8\uc9c0\ub9c9 \uc5d0\ud53c\uc18c\ub4dc 19\uc77c \uacf5\uac1c|url=http://news.wowtv.co.kr/NewsCenter/News/Read?articleId=A201902190133&t=NN|work=WowTv|date=February 19, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''(G)I-dle: Little but Certain Happiness (\uc18c\ud655\ud589)''\n| 4\n| V Live, YouTube\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 2020\n| ''(G)I-dle: Secret Folder (\uc720\ucd9c\uae08\uc9c0)''\n| 4 + 4 specials\n| [[1theK Originals]]<ref>{{cite web|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ud398\uc774\ud06c \ub9ac\uc5bc\ub9ac\ud2f0 '\uc720\ucd9c\uae08\uc9c0' 1\ubc88 \ud0c0\uc790\u2026\uc194\uc9c1+\uc720\ucf8c \ub9e4\ub825|url=http://www.mydaily.co.kr/new_yk/html/read.php?newsid=202001151131576690&ext=na|work=MyDaily|date=January 15, 2020|language=ko}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''#HASHTALK''\n| 12\n| YouTube\n|-\n| ''(G)I-dle <So Sweet~ Happy Valentine's Day>''\n| 1\n| [[YouTube Live]]\n|-\n| ''(G)I-dle X Star Road''\n| {{TBA|Ongoing}}\n| V Live<ref>{{cite web|title='\uc2a4\ud0c0\ub85c\ub4dc' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, '\uc624\ub9c8\uc774\uac13' \uc678\uce60 \uc218\ubc16\uc5d0 \uc5c6\ub294 \ub300\uc138\ub3cc[Oh! \uc2a4\ucf00\uce58]|url=http://osen.mt.co.kr/article/G1111334364|work=OSEN|date=April 6, 2020|language=ko}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by (G)I-dle}}\n\n(G)I-dle won their first award, the \"Female Rookie Idol of the Year\", on July 24, 2018 at Brand of the Year Awards.<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ko:(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 '\uc62c\ud574\uc758 \uc544\uc774\ub3cc\ub85c \uc120\uc815\ub410\uc5b4\uc694'|url=http://m.hankooki.com/m_sp_view.php?WM=sp&FILE_NO=c3AyMDE4MDcyNDE1MjUxNzEzNjczMC5odG0|work=Hankooki|date=July 24, 2018|language=ko}}</ref> Twenty days after debuting, on May 22, 2018, they received their first [[Music programs of South Korea#Chart Systems|music show win]] on [[SBS MTV]]'s ''[[The Show (South Korean TV series)|The Show]]'' with \"[[Latata]]\".<ref name=\"latata1stwin\"/>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|(G)I-dle}}\n* {{url|http://cafe.daum.net/cube-g-i-dle|Official Cafe}} {{in lang|ko}}\n* {{url|https://www.universal-music.co.jp/g-i-dle/|Universal Music Japan Artist}} {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{(G)I-dle}}\n{{Cube Entertainment}}\n{{Golden Disk Awards for New Artist of the Year}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gidle}}\n[[Category:(G)I-dle| ]]\n[[Category:2018 establishments in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Seoul]]\n[[Category:K-pop music groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2018]]\n[[Category:South Korean dance music groups]]\n[[Category:South Korean girl groups]]\n[[Category:Cube Entertainment artists]]\n[[Category:Melon Music Award winners]]\n", "name_user": "86.19.58.13", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/(G)I-dle"}
{"title_page": "Chris Squire", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Chris Squire\n| image               = Chris squire 1978.jpg\n| caption             = Squire in August 1977\n| image_size          =\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Christopher Russell Edward Squire\n| alias               =\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date |1948|3|4|df=yes}}\n| birth_place         = [[Kingsbury, London|Kingsbury]], London, England\n| death_date          = {{Death date and age|2015|6|27|1948|3|4|df=yes}}\n| death_place         = [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[Arizona]], U.S.\n| instrument          = Bass guitar, vocals\n| genre               = [[Progressive rock]], [[symphonic rock]], [[art rock]]\n| occupation          = Musician, singer, songwriter\n| years_active        = 1965\u20132015\n| label               = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]], [[Wounded Bird Records|Wounded Bird]], [[Sanctuary Records|Sanctuary]], Lime, Stone Ghost\n| associated_acts     = [[The Selfs]], [[the Syn]], [[Mabel Greer's Toyshop]], [[Yes (band)|Yes]], [[XYZ (UK band)|XYZ]], [[Conspiracy (band)|Conspiracy]], [[A Life Within a Day|Squackett]]\n| website             = {{URL|chrissquire.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Christopher Russell Edward Squire''' (4{{nbsp}}March 1948 \u2013 27{{nbsp}}June 2015) was an English musician, singer and songwriter best known as the bassist and a founding member of the [[progressive rock]] band [[Yes (band)|Yes]]. He was the longest-serving original member, having remained in the band until his death and appearing on every studio album released from 1969 to 2014. In 2017, he was posthumously inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] as a member of Yes.<ref name=\"rrhofyes\">{{cite web|title=Inductees: Yes|url=https://www.rockhall.com/inductees/yes|website=Rock & Roll Hall of Fame|accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nSquire was widely regarded as the dominant bassist among the English progressive rock bands, influencing peers and later generations of bassists with his incisive sound and elaborately contoured, melodic bass lines. His name was associated with his trademark instrument, the [[Rickenbacker 4001]]. From 1991 to 2000, Rickenbacker produced a limited edition signature model bass in his name, the [[Rickenbacker 4001CS|4001CS]].\n\n==Early life==\nSquire was born on 4 March 1948 in the north west London suburb of [[Kingsbury, London|Kingsbury]], to Peter and Joanne Squire.<ref name=teamrock2014/> He grew up there and in the nearby [[Queensbury, London|Queensbury]] and [[Wembley]] areas.<ref name=welch24>[[#Welch2008|Welch 2008, p. 24.]]</ref><ref name=hedges15>[[#Hedges1982|Hedges 1982, p. 15.]]</ref><ref name=teamrock2014/> His father was a cab driver and his mother a secretary for an estate agent. As a youngster Squire took a liking to [[Lena Horne]] and [[Ella Fitzgerald]] records belonging to his father, though his main interest was [[church music]].<ref name=hedges15/> At age six,<ref name=welch25>[[#Welch2008|Welch 2008, p. 25.]]</ref> he joined the church choir at St. Andrew's in Kingsbury as a [[soprano]] with [[Andrew Pryce Jackman]], a friend of his who lived nearby. The choir got to perform at [[St. Paul's cathedral]].<ref name=beggs2004/><ref name=circus1975>{{cite journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201081526/http://zenponies.com/yitp/1976/nov/nov25_76.html|url=http://zenponies.com/yitp/1976/nov/nov25_76.html|archive-date=1 December 2016|title=Chris Squire: The Survivor|date=25 November 1975|first=Scott|last=Cohen|magazine=Circus|accessdate=28 November 2019}}</ref> Their choirmaster, [[Barry Rose]], was an early influence on Squire. \"He made me realise that working at it was the way to become best at something\".<ref name=hedges15/> Squire also sang in the choir at his next school, [[Haberdashers' Aske's Boys' School]], then located in [[Hampstead]].<ref name=\"close\">Welch, Chris.: ''Close to the Edge: The Story of Yes''. (London: Omnibus Press, 1999).</ref> He played the [[harmonica]] on his way home from school.<ref name=beggs2004/>\n\nSquire did not consider a music career until the age of sixteen when the emergence of [[the Beatles]] and the [[Beat music]] boom in the early 1960s inspired him to \"be in a group that don't use music stands\". A school friend recommended Squire to take up the bass after pointing out his tall frame and large hands, thinking they were ideal for playing the instrument.<ref name=teamrock2014/><ref name=hedges15/><ref name=hedges18>[[#Hedges1982|Hedges 1982, p. 18.]]</ref><ref name=beggs2004/> Squire then purchased his first bass, a Futurama, which he described as \"very cheap, but good enough to learn on.\"<ref name=\"Soocher, Stan 1979\">Soocher, Stan: \"Squire's bass fire\", ''Circus Weekly'', 13 March 1979, 33.</ref> In 1964, on the last day before the summer holidays, Squire's headmaster suspended him and a friend for having their hair too long and they were given two shillings and sixpence to have it cut. Instead, they went home and never returned.<ref name=teamrock2014/><ref name=\"close\"/> After his mother took him to a recruitment agency and enquired for work related to music, Squire landed work selling guitars at a [[Boosey & Hawkes]] shop in [[Regent Street]].<ref name=teamrock2014/> He used the staff discount offer to purchase a new bass, a [[Rickenbacker 4001]], in 1965.<ref name=hedges18/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\nSquire's first band was [[the Selfs]], a rock and rhythm and blues band that featured Jackman on keyboards and Martin Adelman on drums. Their first public performance took place at The Graveyard, a youth club in the hall of St. Andrew's.<ref name=hedges18/> In 1965, following several personnel changes, Squire, Jackman and Adelman teamed with singer [[Steve Nardelli]], guitarist John Painter, and drummer Gunnar J\u00f6kull H\u00e1konarson to form a new group, [[the Syn]]. The group performed [[Tamla Motown]] covers before they changed direction towards [[psychedelic rock]].<ref name=teamrock2014/> After several months, Painter was replaced by guitarist [[Peter Banks]].<ref name=hedges18/> The new line-up gained a following large enough to secure a weekly residency at the [[Marquee Club]] in [[Soho]], which was followed by a recording contract with [[Deram Records]]. The band once opened for [[Jimi Hendrix]] at the venue, \"So I saw what was possible, and I just had this innate faith that I was going to make it.\"<ref name=teamrock2014/> Together they released two singles before they disbanded.<ref name=hedges18/>\n\nSquire was fond of using [[LSD]] in the 1960s; a visit to the [[UFO Club]] on the drug on Friday which lasted through Saturday, and recovery on Sunday, became a regular event until a 1967 incident where he had a bad trip on a friend's home made LSD.<ref name=teamrock2014>{{cite web|url=http://teamrock.com/feature/2014-08-13/big-generator|title=Chris Squire: the hands that built prog|date=13 August 2014|first=Mark|last=Blake|publisher=TeamRock|accessdate=30 November 2016}}</ref> When the police asked him to reveal who gave it to him, Squire pretended to be disoriented and made up a story that involved an unknown Australian he met at a [[Wimpy (restaurant)|Wimpy]] restaurant beforehand.<ref name=teamrock2014/> He recalled, \"It was the last time I ever took it, having ended up in hospital in [[Fulham]] for a couple of days not knowing who I was, or what I was, or who anybody else was.\"<ref name=hedges19>[[#Hedges1982|Hedges 1982, p. 19.]]</ref> After his discharge from hospital, Squire spent several months in his girlfriend's apartment, afraid to leave, only managing to visit the corner shop.<ref name=teamrock2014/> He spent each day practising his bass playing which resulted in his distinct style,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.al.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2013/07/post_176.html|title=Yes Q&A: Chris Squire talks LSD, 'Almost Famous,' Jimmy Page project, current tour featuring classic LPs|publisher=AL.com|first=Matt|last=Wake|date=15 July 2013|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=teamrock2014/> citing bassists [[John Entwistle]], [[Jack Bruce]], [[Larry Graham]],<ref name=\"Soocher, Stan 1979\"/> and [[Bill Wyman]] as early influences.<ref name=beggs2004>{{cite web|url=http://zenponies.com/yitp/2004/oct/oct07_04.html|title=The Day the Earth Stood Still: Chris Squire Interview|date=7 October 2004|first=Nick|last=Beggs|publisher=Kajagoogoo.com|accessdate=30 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Yes===\n[[File:Chris Squire, 1973 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|200px|upright|Squire in 1974]]\nIn September 1967, Squire joined [[Mabel Greer's Toyshop]], a psychedelic group that included [[Peter Banks]], singer Clive Bayley and drummer Bob Hagger.<ref name=welch3235>[[#Welch2008|Welch 2008, pp. 32\u201335.]]</ref> They played at the Marquee club where Jack Barrie, owner of the La Chasse drinking club a few doors down, saw them perform. \"The musicianship&nbsp;... was very good but it was obvious they weren't going anywhere\", he recalled.<ref name=welch2223>Welch, pp. 22\u201323.</ref> One evening at La Chasse, Barrie introduced Squire to [[Jon Anderson]], a worker at the bar who had not found success as the lead singer of [[The Gun (band)|The Gun]] or as a solo artist.<ref name=welch2223/> The two found they shared common musical interests including [[Simon & Garfunkel]], [[The Association]] and [[vocal harmony|vocal harmonies]]. In the following days they developed \"Sweetness\", a track later recorded for the [[Yes (Yes album)|first Yes album]].<ref name=welch24/>\n\nAs the band developed, Anderson and Squire brought in drummer [[Bill Bruford]], keyboardist [[Tony Kaye (musician)|Tony Kaye]] and Banks for rehearsals. The five agreed to drop the name Mabel Greer's Toyshop; they settled on the name Yes, originally Banks's idea.<ref name=welch3235/> The band played their first show as Yes at a youth camp in [[East Mersea]], [[Essex]] on 4 August 1968.<ref name=welch45>Welch, p. 45.</ref> Squire spoke about the band's formation: \"I couldn't get [[session musician|session work]] because most musicians hated my style. They wanted me to play something a lot more basic. We started Yes as a vehicle to develop everyone's individual styles.\"<ref>Gill, Chris. Guitar World's ''Bass Guitar'', Fall 2003 issue, p. 22.</ref> Squire developed a bass solo named \"A Bass Odyssey\".<ref name=teamrock2014/>\n\nIn August 1969, Yes released their self-titled [[Yes (Yes album)|debut album]]. Martyn Adelman, who had played drums with Squire's first group, did the album photos. Squire received writing credits on four of the album's eight tracks\u2014\"Beyond & Before\", \"Looking Around\", \"Harold Land\", and \"Sweetness\".<ref name=yes1969>{{Cite AV media notes|title=Yes|publisher=Atlantic Records|id=588 190|year=1969}}</ref>\n\nAfter Bruford left the band and was replaced by [[Alan White (Yes drummer)|Alan White]] in July 1972, Squire altered his playing to suit the change in the band's rhythm section. He felt he was \"playing too much, though I was never really sure. With Bill, the things that I did felt right ... With Alan, I found that I was able to play a bit less than before and still get my playing across\".<ref>[[#Morse1996|Morse 1996, p. 41.]]</ref>\n\nSquire described his playing on \"The Remembering (High the Memory)\" from ''[[Tales from Topographic Oceans]]'' (1973) as \"one of the nicest things I think I've ever played\".<ref>[[#Morse1996|Morse 1996, p. 47.]]</ref>\n\nSquire was the only member to play on each of their 21 studio albums released from 1969 to 2014. He was seen as one of the main forces behind the band's music, as well as being \"perhaps the most enigmatic\" group member.<ref>[[#Welch2008|Welch 2008, p. 10.]]</ref> ''[[Heaven & Earth (Yes album)|Heaven & Earth]]'' was his final studio album.<ref name=\"dies\">{{cite news|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/chris-squire-dies-yes/|work=Ultimate Classic Rock|first=Nick|last=DeRiso|date=28 June 2015|accessdate=28 June 2015|title=Yes Co-Founder Chris Squire Dies}}</ref>\n\nWhile most of the band's lyrics were written by Anderson, Squire co-wrote much of their music with guitarist [[Steve Howe (guitarist)|Steve Howe]] (with Anderson occasionally contributing). In addition, Squire and Howe would supply backing vocals in harmony with Anderson on songs such as \"[[South Side of the Sky]]\" and \"[[Close to the Edge (song)|Close to the Edge]]\".\n\nDuring the band's formative years Squire was frequently known for his lateness, a habit that Bruford often complained about. Because of this, Squire would frequently drive at unsafe speeds to get to gigs on time, once causing an accident on the way to a gig in [[West Germany]] after he fell asleep at the wheel, although nobody was injured. Later on a plaque \"The Late Chris Squire\" was written in reference to it. (Shown Below)<ref name=\"close\"/>\n\nAs Squire, along with [[Alan White (Yes drummer)|Alan White]] and [[Steve Howe (guitarist)|Steve Howe]], co-owned the \"Yes\" name at the time, the 1989 [[Anderson Bruford Wakeman Howe|ABWH]] line-up without him (which contained Anderson, Bruford, [[Rick Wakeman|Wakeman]] and Howe) could not record under that name.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/anderson-bruford-wakeman-howe/|title=Yes Minus One: The History of 'Anderson Bruford Wakeman Howe'|work=Ultimate Classic Rock|first=Jeff|last=Giles|date=20 June 2015|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref>\n[[File:Chris Squire Beacon Theatre 2013-04-09.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Squire performing with Yes in April 2013]]\nFollowing Squire's death on 27 June 2015, the band's show on 7 August of the same year marked the first Yes concert ever performed without him. Former member [[Billy Sherwood]] replaced Squire during their [[List of Yes concert tours (2000s\u201310s)|2015 North American tour]] with [[Toto (band)|Toto]] from August to September 2015, as well as their performances in November 2015, as announced when the band first revealed Squire's disease in May 2015.<ref name=\"Chris Squire to undergo treatment for Leukemia\"/><ref name=\"yesworld North American Summer Tour 2015\">{{cite web |url=http://www.yesworld.com/2015/04/yes-and-toto-2015-north-american-summer-tour/ |title=YES & Toto 2015 North American Summer Tour |date= 6 April 2015 |website=www.yesworld.com |accessdate= 11 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://yes.concerttournewshub.com/ |title=Yes & Toto 2015 Co-Headlining North American Summer Tour Schedule |date=6 April 2015 |accessdate=6 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150417034432/http://yes.concerttournewshub.com/ |archivedate=17 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2015/apr/06/yes-and-toto-teaming-up-for-tour/ |title=Yes & Toto announce joint tour |date=6 April 2015 |accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Other projects===\nSquire concentrated overwhelmingly on Yes' music over the years, producing little solo work. His first solo record was 1975's ''[[Fish Out of Water (Chris Squire album)|Fish Out of Water]]'', featuring Yes alumnus [[Bill Bruford]] on drums and [[Patrick Moraz]] on keyboards and [[The Syn]]/[[The Selfs]] alumnus Andrew Jackman also on keyboards.<ref name=\"dies\"/>\n\nIn 1981, Squire was a member of the short lived [[XYZ (UK band)|XYZ]], short for eX-Yes/Zeppelin (Squire claimed his father had come up with the name)<ref name=teamrock2014/> a group composed of White and guitarist [[Jimmy Page]]. XYZ recorded several demo tracks, but never produced anything formal, though two of the demos provided the basis for two later Yes tracks, \"Mind Drive\" and \"Can You Imagine?\"<ref name=\"32yearsago\">{{cite news|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/yes-zeppelin-supergroup-xyz/|work=Ultimate Classic Rock|title=32 Years Ago: Ex-Yes and Zeppelin Members Form Supergroup XYZ|first=Sterling|last=Whitaker|date=18 April 2013|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref> Led Zeppelin singer [[Robert Plant]] was not ready, despite Page's promises, to get involved with the band so soon after the death of Zeppelin drummer [[John Bonham]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Why The Yes And Led Zeppelin Supergroup Did Not Happen|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/why-the-yes-and-led-zeppelin-supergroup-did-not-happen-20120210|agency=Noise11|date=10 February 2012|accessdate=28 June 2015|first=Paul|last=Cashmere}}</ref> According to Squire, Zeppelin manager [[Peter Grant (music manager)|Peter Grant]] objected to the name as the \"Y\" appeared before the \"Z\" in the name. The group then \"fizzled out\".<ref name=teamrock2014/>\n\nSquire also played a role in bringing [[Trevor Rabin]] into the [[Cinema (band)|Cinema]] band project, which became the ''[[90125]]'' line-up of Yes.<ref name=\"32yearsago\"/>\n\nIn later years, Squire would join with Yes guitarist [[Billy Sherwood]] in a side project called [[Conspiracy (band)|Conspiracy]]. This band's self-titled debut album in 2000 contained the nuclei of several songs that had appeared on Yes' recent albums. Conspiracy's second album, ''The Unknown'', was released in 2003.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://somethingelsereviews.com/2013/04/03/chris-squire-and-billy-sherwood-conspiracy-live-2013/|title=Chris Squire and Billy Sherwood \u2013 Conspiracy Live (2013)|first=Nick|last=Deriso|date=3 April 2013|accessdate=28 June 2015|agency=Something Else Reviews}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2004, Squire joined a reunion of The Syn. The reformed band released the album ''[[Syndestructible]]'' in 2005 before breaking up again.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.metroactive.com/papers/cruz/02.15.06/syn-0607.html|title=Chris Squire Just Says Yes to Syn|work=Metroactive|date=February 2006|first=Bill|last=Forman}}</ref>\n\nSquire also worked on two solo projects with other former Syn collaborators [[Gerard Johnson (musician)|Gerard Johnson]], [[Jeremy Stacey]] and [[Paul Stacey]].<ref name=\"close\"/> A Christmas album, ''[[Chris Squire's Swiss Choir]]'', was released in 2007 (with Johnson, J. Stacey and [[Steve Hackett]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blog.musoscribe.com/?p=550|work=Musoscribe|title=Yes: A History of Perpetual Change|first=Bill|last=Kopp|date=5 July 2011|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref> Squire collaborated again with Hackett, formerly of the band [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]], to make the [[Squackett]] album ''[[A Life Within a Day]]'', released in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/a-life-within-a-day-mw0002344321|publisher=All Music|title=A Life Within a Day|first=Bret|last=Adams|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Illness, death, and tributes ==\n\n[[File:Chris Squire Brown Plaque with Rickenbacker 4001 bass guitar motif.jpg|thumb|Brown plaque in Warwick Street, Soho, London]]\n\nOn 19 May 2015, Yes announced that Squire had been diagnosed with [[acute erythroid leukemia]], and would take a break from performing while receiving treatment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://yesworld.com/2015/05/chris-squire-to-undergo-treatment-for-leukemia/|title=Chris Squire to undergo treatment for Leukemia|date=19 May 2015 |accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://classicrock.teamrock.com/news/2015-05-19/yes-chris-squire-has-cancer|title=Yes' Chris Squire has cancer|publisher=Classic Rock|author=Martin Kielty|date=19 May 2015|accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the late evening of 27 June 2015, Squire died from the illness, aged 67, while receiving treatment in his adopted hometown of [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[Arizona]].<ref name=discoermusicdeath/><ref name=\"dies\"/><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/chris-squire-yes-bassist-and-co-founder-dead-at-67-20150628|title=Chris Squire, Yes Bassist and Co-Founder, Dead at 67|date=28 June 2015|accessdate=28 June 2015|first=Daniel|last=Kreps|magazine=Rolling Stone}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-33306933|title=Yes bass guitarist Chris Squire dies aged 67|work=BBC News|date=28 June 2015|accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref> Yes' official [[Facebook]] page confirmed the news the next day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/yestheband/posts/1050133808331940|title=Yes (official) - It\u2019s with the heaviest of hearts and... - Facebook|work=facebook.com}}</ref> Tributes were paid by fellow musicians [[Brian May]], [[Geezer Butler]], [[Gene Simmons]] and [[Tom Morello]], as well as bandmates [[Geoff Downes]] and [[Bill Bruford]].<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.uncut.co.uk/news/brian-may-leads-tributes-to-yes-bassist-chris-squire-69333 | title= Brian May leads tributes to Yes bassist Chris Squire | work=Uncut | first=Michael | last=Bonner | date=29 June 2015 | accessdate=15 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nSquire's death was central to the song \"Fragile\" from the 2016 [[Jesu/Sun Kil Moon|collaborative debut album]] between [[Jesu (band)|Jesu]] and [[Sun Kil Moon]].  In the song, [[Mark Kozelek]] recounts his experiences as a Yes fan, particularly in light of the death of a friend, also named Christopher.  Squire was given a writing credit due to lyrics from his Yes composition \"Onward\" being quoted through backing vocals.\n\nIn April 2016 asteroid 2002 XR80 received an official permanent name from the [[International Astronomical Union]] in honor of Squire. Asteroid [http://www.minorplanetcenter.net/db_search/show_object?object_id=90125 (90125) Chrissquire] was discovered 11 December 2002 and is a main-belt asteroid with an orbital period of 4.08 years.\n\n==Style and legacy==\n[[File:Chris Squire Beacon Theatre 2013-04-09 5.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Squire with a [[Multi-neck guitar|triple-necked]] bass guitar in 2013]]\nSquire's unique tone was very clear and distinct, and his playing was noted for being aggressive,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://somethingelsereviews.com/2015/02/17/yes-beyond-and-before-yesterdays/|title=Yes, \"Beyond and Before\" from Yes (1969): YESterdays|date=17 February 2015|first=Preston|last=Frazier|agency=Something Else Reviews|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref> dynamic<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicradar.com/us/news/bass/the-60-greatest-bassists-of-all-time-279007/41|title=The 60 greatest bassists of all time|publisher=MusicRadar|date=1 December 2014|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref> and melodic.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.innerviews.org/inner/yes2.html|title=Yes: Propelling forward|work=Innerviews|date=2012|first=Anil|last=Prasad|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref> Squire's main instrument was a 1964 [[Rickenbacker]] bass (model RM1999, serial number DC127), which he bought and began playing in 1965.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fotolog.com/rickenbacker/12156931/|publisher=Fotolog|accessdate=28 June 2015|title=Rickenbacker|date=6 April 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701025000/http://www.fotolog.com/rickenbacker/12156931/|archive-date=1 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Squire mentioned in a 1979 interview with ''Circus Weekly'' that he acquired this bass while working at the [[Boosey & Hawkes]] music store in London.<ref name=\"Soocher, Stan 1979\"/> The instrument, with its warmth, was a significant part of Squire's unique sound.<ref name=\"top10\">{{cite news|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/chris-squire-yes-songs/|title=Top 10 Chris Squire Yes Songs|first=Ryan|last=Reed|work=Ultimate Classic Rock|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref> Due to its distinctive tone, which has been compared to that of a [[guitar]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/may13/articles/scarbee-rickenbacker-bass.htm|title=Scarbee Rickenbacker Bass|work=Sound on Sound|first=Nick|last=Magnus|date=May 2013|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref> it allowed the bass to take on a more \"lead\" role, which created a dynamic sound, and suited Squire perfectly.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.premierguitar.com/articles/20878-cruising-to-the-edge|title=Cruising to the Edge|first=Tessa|last=Jeffers|date=27 May 2014|accessdate=28 June 2015|work=Premier Guitar}}</ref>\n\nSquire also had a unique way of playing the bass; he played exclusively with a [[plectrum]], (usually a grey Herco \"heavy\") which he held so short, that his thumb would also strike the strings right after the pick, causing subtle [[harmonics]].<ref>Interview with Bob Birch, https://youtube.com/watch?cprcYnffK_o&t=128</ref>\nHe made frequent use of hammer-ons, pull-offs as well as alternate and tremolo picking. Aside from his aforementioned use of distortion, Squire occasionally used other effects, most notably [[Chorus effect|chorus]], [[flanger]] and [[wah-wah pedal|wah-wah]] pedals, which until then had mostly been used by guitarists.\n\nIn a 1973 interview for ''[[Guitar Player]]'' magazine, Squire recalled how he had obtained his distinctive tone at the time by rewiring his RM1999 into stereo and sending the bass and treble [[Pick up (music technology)|pick-up]]s each into a separate amplifier. By splitting the signal from his bass into dual high and low frequency outputs and then sending the low frequency output to a conventional bass [[amplifier]] and the high-frequency output to a separate lead guitar amplifier, Squire produced a tonal \"sandwich\" that added a growling, overdrive edge to the sound while retaining the Rickenbacker's powerful bass response. This gave his bass sound bright, growling higher frequencies and clean, solid bass frequencies. This technique allowed Squire to use [[harmonic distortion]] on his bass while avoiding the flat, fuzzy sound, loss of power and poor bass response that typically occurs when bass guitars are overdriven through an amplifier or put through a [[Distortion (music)|fuzz box]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Ferris |first=Leonard |date=July 1973 |title=Yes' Bassist Chris Squire |journal=[[Guitar Player]] |page=42}}</ref>\nSquire also made notable use of fret buzz, a normally undesirable condition caused by low string action, to create a further, growling edge to his playing.\n\nSquire claimed to have rewired his bass to stereo, even before Rickenbacker introduced the Rick-O-Sound feature, so he could send the output of the bass (neck) pick-up through a fuzz box, while keeping the treble (bridge) pick-up clean, because the last sounded \"horribly nasal\" when used with the fuzz effect.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bassplayer.com/article/basso-cantantecontinuo-chris/January-2009/91289 |title=Basso Cantante, Continuo Chris Squire's Singing Bass Rings Again With Yes |publisher=Bassplayer.com |accessdate=17 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707213704/http://www.bassplayer.com/article/basso-cantantecontinuo-chris/January-2009/91289 |archivedate=7 July 2011 }}</ref> He also played with a pick which contributed to the sharp attack as well as using fresh Rotosound Swing Bass strings for every show.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QxDbKssKXzEC&pg=PA136&lpg=PA136&dq=%22chris+squire%22++rotosound|title=Bass Heroes: Tom Mulhern |accessdate=17 August 2011|isbn=9780879302740|author1=Mulhern|first1=Tom|year=1993}}</ref> Squire's intricate and complex bass playing style has influenced subsequent bassists such as [[Billy Sheehan]], [[Geddy Lee]] of [[Rush (band)|Rush]], [[Steve Di Giorgio]] of [[Death (metal band)|Death]] and [[Sadus]], [[Pat Badger]] of [[Extreme (band)|Extreme]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/4eyDu4I1r9/|title=Pat Badger on Instagram: \u201cI'm deeply saddened to hear of the passing of one of my biggest influences Chris Squire. Not because I knew him personally, but because of\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram}}</ref> [[Jon Camp]] of [[Renaissance (band)|Renaissance]], [[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]] of [[Iron Maiden]], [[Les Claypool]] of [[Primus (band)|Primus]], [[John Myung]] of [[Dream Theater]] and [[Robert DeLeo]] of [[Stone Temple Pilots]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Hill |first=Gary |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/chris-squire-p5508 |title=Chris Squire |website=AllMusic |date=4 March 1948 |accessdate=17 August 2011}}</ref> [[John Deacon]] of [[Queen (band)|Queen]] was also inspired by Squire, and told Guitar Magazine that Squire was his favourite bass player.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://brianmay.com/john/gtrsep99/gtrsep99.html | title= Guitar Magazine - September 1999 | work=brianmay.com | accessdate=15 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to bass, Squire also occasionally played harmonica, piano and guitar.\n\n==Nickname==\nSquire was commonly known by his nickname, \"Fish\", and the name is associated with many of his works including his solo record, ''[[Fish Out of Water (Chris Squire album)|Fish Out of Water]]'' (1975), and the solo piece \"[[The Fish (Schindleria Praematurus)]]\" from the 1971 Yes record ''[[Fragile (Yes album)|Fragile]]''. The name has multiple origins, not least of which is the [[Heteronym (linguistics)|heteronymic]] meanings of \"bass\", describing [[Bass (sound)|low frequency sound]] or the bass guitar as well as the [[Bass (fish)|fish]]. Additionally, Squire's astrological sign was [[Pisces (astrology)|Pisces]]. Further, in the early days of Yes' career, he once accidentally flooded a hotel room in [[Oslo]], Norway, while taking a shower, and [[Bill Bruford]] gave him the nickname.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfte.org/interviews/0165_Squire.html |title=1996 Interview |publisher=Nfte.org |accessdate=17 August 2011}}</ref> On the 2007 documentary ''The Classic Artists Series 3: Yes'', Bruford says that the nickname arose because Squire spent long periods in the bathroom while they shared a house together in [[Fulham]].<ref>''The Classic Artists Series 3: Yes''.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nSquire met his first wife Nikki in 1970 at a club in London.<ref name=circus1975/> They married in 1972.<ref>{{cite web|title=Esquire|url=http://allmusic.com/artist/esquire-p17351/biography|work=All Music Guide|accessdate=28 February 2011}}</ref><ref>[[#Welch2008|Welch 2008, p. 220.]]</ref> She sang on the 1981 Christmas single \"[[Run with the Fox]]\" and also the track \"Hold Out Your Hand\" from ''[[Fish Out of Water (Chris Squire album)|Fish Out of Water]]'' (1975). In 1983, she formed Esquire, on whose first album Chris, Alan White and Trevor Horn assisted. Their family included Carmen, Chandrika and Camille Squire. The couple divorced after fifteen years of marriage.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nfte.org/interviews/ns232.html|title=Conversation with Nikki Squire|agency=Notes From the Edge|first=Paul|last=Secord|website=Nfte.org|date=May 2000|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nSquire married actress Melissa Morgan on 8 May 1993. She gave birth to their only son, Cameron in 2000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/chris-squire-fd2x3c838nh|title=Chris Squire|website=Thetimes.co.uk}}</ref> She played Brittany Norman on ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'' and later returned to the daytime programme as Agnes Sorensen.<ref>{{cite web|title=Melissa Morgan Squire is returning...|url=http://www.tvguide.com/soaps/Melissa-Morgan-Squire-56719.aspx|website=Tvguide.com|accessdate=28 February 2011|date=11 July 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://broadwayworld.com/people/Melissa_Morgan/|title=Broadway World|accessdate=28 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Goldstein|first=Toby|title=Ashley Is Back on The 'Y&rR' Scene|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2003-07-20/entertainment/0307160280_1_melchior-kelly-dorian|newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]]}}</ref> The pair divorced in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailyentertainmentnews.com/music/scotland-squire-yes-chris-squires-wife/|title=Scotland Squire: Yes Chris Squire\u2019s Wife (Bio, Wiki|website=Dailyentertainmentnews.com)|date=29 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nHis third and final marriage was to Scotland Squire, who gave birth to daughter Xilan in 2008. They resided in the [[Chelsea, London|Chelsea]] neighbourhood of London, and latterly in [[Phoenix, Arizona]].<ref name=teamrock2014/>\n\nIn the 1970s, Squire was a vegetarian for five years, before he returned to eating fish, then meat.<ref name=teamrock2014/> He also got involved with [[cocaine]] in the 1970s and early 1980s after the band [[The Eagles]], then a supporting act for Yes, introduced him to it. At some point in his life, Squire also suffered a heart attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/former-manager-and-friend-jon-brewer-remembers-chris-squire|title=Former Manager and Friend Jon Brewer Remembers Chris Squire|publisher=Louder Sound|first=Rob|last=Hughes|date=28 September 2015|accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n=== Solo singles ===\n* \"[[Run with the Fox]]\" \u2013 with Alan White 1981\n\n=== Solo albums ===\n* ''[[Fish Out of Water (Chris Squire album)|Fish Out of Water]]'' (1975)\n* ''[[Chris Squire's Swiss Choir]]'' (2007)\n\n=== With Conspiracy ===\n* ''Conspiracy'' (2000 + DVD)\n* ''The Unknown'' (2003)\n\n=== With Squackett ===\n* ''[[A Life Within a Day]]'' (2012)\n\n=== With The Syn ===\n:''see [[The Syn]]\n\n=== With Yes ===\n:''see [[Yes discography]]''\n\n=== As guest musician ===\n* 1968: [[Neat Change]] - ''[[I Lied to Aunty May]]'' (with Peter Banks on guitar, Squire plays the tambourine and performs backing vocals on this single)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Home|first=Stewart|last2=Edwards|first2=Jimmy|date=26 July 2010|title=It\u2019s an Uphill Climb to the Bottom|url=https://www.3ammagazine.com/3am/its-an-uphill-climb-to-the-bottom/|journal=3:AM Magazine|access-date=16 June 2019}}</ref>\n* 1970: [[Larry Smith (musician)|Larry \"Legs\" Smith]] - ''[[Witchi-tai-Po]]'' (with Tony Kaye on this single by a member of [[Bonzo Dog Doo Dah Band]]) \n* 1973: Rick Wakeman - ''[[The Six Wives of Henry VIII (album)|The Six Wives of Henry VIII]]'' (Steve Howe, Bill Bruford & Alan White)\n* 1973: [[Eddie Harris]] - ''[[E.H. in the U.K.]]'' (with Tony Kaye & Alan White)\n* 1977: Rick Wakeman - ''[[Rick Wakeman's Criminal Record]]'' (with Alan White)\n* 1981: [[The Buggles]] - ''[[Adventures in Modern Recording]]'' (Squire is credited only with \"sound effects\" on one piece, while the bass is played by Trevor Horn)\n* 1987: [[Esquire (band)|Esquire]] - ''Esquire'' (Chris's ex-wife Nikky Squire with Alan White, Trevor Horn & Carmen Squire, Chris's daughter)\n* 1990: [[Rock Aid Armenia]] - a single re-recording of Deep Purple's \"[[Smoke on the Water]]\" (with [[Keith Emerson]], [[Geoff Downes]], [[Ian Gillan]], [[Bruce Dickinson]], [[Paul Rodgers]], [[David Gilmour]], [[Ritchie Blackmore]], [[Tony Iommi]], [[Alex Lifeson]], [[Bryan Adams]], [[Brian May]] & [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]]), which is also included on ''The Earthquake Album''.\n* 1993: [[Rick Wakeman]] - ''[[Classical Connections 2]]'' (recorded in 1971 but published in 1991 with Steve Howe & Bill Bruford)\n* 1995: [[World Trade (band)|World Trade]] - ''Euphoria'' with Billy Sherwood, co-wrote two songs\n* 2002: [[Gov't Mule]] - ''[[The Deep End, Volume 2]]''\n* 2002: Various artists - ''[[Pigs and Pyramids - An All Star Lineup Performing the Songs of Pink Floyd]]'' (again published as ''[[Back Against the Wall]]'' from Billy Sherwood in 2005)\n* 2009: [[Steve Hackett]] - ''[[Out of the Tunnel's Mouth]]''\n* 2011: Steve Hackett - ''[[Beyond the Shrouded Horizon]]''\n* 2012: [[Billy Sherwood & The Prog Collective]] - ''The Technical Divide'' (with [[Alan Parsons]] & [[Gary Green (musician)|Gary Green]])\n* 2012: Various artists - ''Songs of the Century: An All-Star Tribute to Supertramp. Let the World Revolve'' (with Billy Sherwood & Tony Kaye)\n* 2013: Billy Sherwood & The Prog Collective - ''Epilogue'' (Shining Diamonds with Patrick Moraz, Billy Sherwood, Alan Parsons & [[Steve Stevens]])\n* 2015: Steve Hackett - ''[[Wolflight]]'' (Squire plays bass on \"Love Song to a Vampire\")\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Bibliography\n*{{Cite book|last=Hedges|first=Dan|title=Yes: An Authorized Biography|year=1982|publisher=Sidgwick & Jackson|isbn=978-0-283-98751-9|ref=Hedges1982}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Morse|first=Tim|title=Yesstories: \"Yes\" in Their Own Words|year=1996|publisher=St Martin's Press|isbn=978-0-312-14453-1|ref=Morse1996}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Welch|first=Chris|title=Close to the Edge \u2013 The Story of Yes|publisher=Omnibus Press|isbn=978-1-84772-132-7|year=2008|ref=Welch2008}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n*{{IMDb name|id=0820085}}\n\n{{Yesband|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Squire, Chris}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:English rock bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Male bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English songwriters]]\n[[Category:Singers from London]]\n[[Category:Yes (band) members]]\n[[Category:People from Kingsbury, London]]\n[[Category:Progressive rock musicians]]\n[[Category:The Syn members]]\n[[Category:XYZ (English band) members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Chris Squire\n| image               = Chris squire 1978.jpg\n| caption             = Squire in August 1977\n| image_size          =\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Christopher Russell Edward Squire\n| alias               =\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date |1948|3|4|df=yes}}\n| birth_place         = [[Kingsbury, London|Kingsbury]], London, England\n| death_date          = {{Death date and age|2015|6|27|1948|3|4|df=yes}}\n| death_place         = [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[Arizona]], U.S.\n| instrument          = Bass guitar, vocals\n| genre               = [[Progressive rock]], [[symphonic rock]], [[art rock]]\n| occupation          = Musician, singer, songwriter\n| years_active        = 1965\u20132015\n| label               = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]], [[Wounded Bird Records|Wounded Bird]], [[Sanctuary Records|Sanctuary]], Lime, Stone Ghost\n| associated_acts     = [[The Selfs]], [[the Syn]], [[Mabel Greer's Toyshop]], [[Yes (band)|Yes]], [[XYZ (UK band)|XYZ]], [[Conspiracy (band)|Conspiracy]], [[A Life Within a Day|Squackett]]\n| website             = {{URL|chrissquire.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Christopher Russell Edward Squire''' (4{{nbsp}}March 1948 \u2013 27{{nbsp}}June 2015) was an English musician, singer and songwriter best known as the bassist and a founding member of the [[progressive rock]] band [[Yes (band)|Yes]]. He was the longest-serving original member, having remained in the band until his death and appearing on every studio album released from 1969 to 2014.\n\nBorn in [[Kingsbury, London|Kingsbury]], London, Squire took an early interest in [[church music]] and sang in the local church and school choirs. After he took up the bass guitar at age sixteen, his earliest gigs were in 1964 for [[the Selfs]], which later evolved into [[the Syn]]. In 1968, Squire formed Yes with singer [[Jon Anderson]]; he would remain the band's sole bassist for the next 47 years. Squire was widely regarded as the dominant bassist among the English progressive rock bands, influencing peers and later generations of bassists with his incisive sound and elaborately contoured, melodic bass lines. His name was associated with his trademark instrument, the [[Rickenbacker 4001]].\n\nIn May 2015, Squire announced a hiatus from Yes after he was diagnosed with [[acute erythroid leukemia]], and subsequently died on 27 June at his home in [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], Arizona.<ref name=discoermusicdeath>{{Cite web|url=http://www.udiscovermusic.com/chris-squire-r-i-p|publisher=UDiscovermusic|title=Chris Squire R.I.P.|date=28 June 2015|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref> The band's first show of their tour with [[Toto (band)|Toto]] on 7 August 2015 marked the first Yes concert ever performed without Squire, with longtime friend and frequent collaborator [[Billy Sherwood]] performing in his place.<ref name=\"Chris Squire to undergo treatment for Leukemia\">{{cite web |url=http://yesworld.com/2015/05/chris-squire-to-undergo-treatment-for-leukemia/|title=Chris Squire to undergo treatment for Leukemia|date=19 May 2015 |accessdate=19 May 2015}}</ref> From 1991 to 2000, Rickenbacker produced a limited edition signature model bass in his name, the [[Rickenbacker 4001CS|4001CS]]. Squire released two solo albums, ''[[Fish Out of Water (Chris Squire album)|Fish Out of Water]]'' (1975) and ''[[Chris Squire's Swiss Choir]]'' (2007), a Christmas album. He was posthumously inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] as a member of Yes in 2017.<ref name=\"rrhofyes\">{{cite web|title=Inductees: Yes|url=https://www.rockhall.com/inductees/yes|website=Rock & Roll Hall of Fame|accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSquire was born on 4 March 1948 in the north west London suburb of [[Kingsbury, London|Kingsbury]], to Peter and Joanne Squire.<ref name=teamrock2014/> He grew up there and in the nearby [[Queensbury, London|Queensbury]] and [[Wembley]] areas.<ref name=welch24>[[#Welch2008|Welch 2008, p. 24.]]</ref><ref name=hedges15>[[#Hedges1982|Hedges 1982, p. 15.]]</ref><ref name=teamrock2014/> His father was a cab driver and his mother a secretary for an estate agent. As a youngster Squire took a liking to [[Lena Horne]] and [[Ella Fitzgerald]] records belonging to his father, though his main interest was [[church music]].<ref name=hedges15/> At age six,<ref name=welch25>[[#Welch2008|Welch 2008, p. 25.]]</ref> he joined the church choir at St. Andrew's in Kingsbury as a [[soprano]] with [[Andrew Pryce Jackman]], a friend of his who lived nearby. The choir got to perform at [[St. Paul's cathedral]].<ref name=beggs2004/><ref name=circus1975>{{cite journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201081526/http://zenponies.com/yitp/1976/nov/nov25_76.html|url=http://zenponies.com/yitp/1976/nov/nov25_76.html|archive-date=1 December 2016|title=Chris Squire: The Survivor|date=25 November 1975|first=Scott|last=Cohen|magazine=Circus|accessdate=28 November 2019}}</ref> Their choirmaster, [[Barry Rose]], was an early influence on Squire. \"He made me realise that working at it was the way to become best at something\".<ref name=hedges15/> Squire also sang in the choir at his next school, [[Haberdashers' Aske's Boys' School]], then located in [[Hampstead]].<ref name=\"close\">Welch, Chris.: ''Close to the Edge: The Story of Yes''. (London: Omnibus Press, 1999).</ref> He played the [[harmonica]] on his way home from school.<ref name=beggs2004/>\n\nSquire did not consider a music career until the age of sixteen when the emergence of [[the Beatles]] and the [[Beat music]] boom in the early 1960s inspired him to \"be in a group that don't use music stands\". A school friend recommended Squire to take up the bass after pointing out his tall frame and large hands, thinking they were ideal for playing the instrument.<ref name=teamrock2014/><ref name=hedges15/><ref name=hedges18>[[#Hedges1982|Hedges 1982, p. 18.]]</ref><ref name=beggs2004/> Squire then purchased his first bass, a Futurama, which he described as \"very cheap, but good enough to learn on.\"<ref name=\"Soocher, Stan 1979\">Soocher, Stan: \"Squire's bass fire\", ''Circus Weekly'', 13 March 1979, 33.</ref> In 1964, on the last day before the summer holidays, Squire's headmaster suspended him and a friend for having their hair too long and they were given two shillings and sixpence to have it cut. Instead, they went home and never returned.<ref name=teamrock2014/><ref name=\"close\"/> After his mother took him to a recruitment agency and enquired for work related to music, Squire landed work selling guitars at a [[Boosey & Hawkes]] shop in [[Regent Street]].<ref name=teamrock2014/> He used the staff discount offer to purchase a new bass, a [[Rickenbacker 4001]], in 1965.<ref name=hedges18/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\nSquire's first band was [[the Selfs]], a rock and rhythm and blues band that featured Jackman on keyboards and Martin Adelman on drums. Their first public performance took place at The Graveyard, a youth club in the hall of St. Andrew's.<ref name=hedges18/> In 1965, following several personnel changes, Squire, Jackman and Adelman teamed with singer [[Steve Nardelli]], guitarist John Painter, and drummer Gunnar J\u00f6kull H\u00e1konarson to form a new group, [[the Syn]]. The group performed [[Tamla Motown]] covers before they changed direction towards [[psychedelic rock]].<ref name=teamrock2014/> After several months, Painter was replaced by guitarist [[Peter Banks]].<ref name=hedges18/> The new line-up gained a following large enough to secure a weekly residency at the [[Marquee Club]] in [[Soho]], which was followed by a recording contract with [[Deram Records]]. The band once opened for [[Jimi Hendrix]] at the venue, \"So I saw what was possible, and I just had this innate faith that I was going to make it.\"<ref name=teamrock2014/> Together they released two singles before they disbanded.<ref name=hedges18/>\n\nSquire was fond of using [[LSD]] in the 1960s; a visit to the [[UFO Club]] on the drug on Friday which lasted through Saturday, and recovery on Sunday, became a regular event until a 1967 incident where he had a bad trip on a friend's home made LSD.<ref name=teamrock2014>{{cite web|url=http://teamrock.com/feature/2014-08-13/big-generator|title=Chris Squire: the hands that built prog|date=13 August 2014|first=Mark|last=Blake|publisher=TeamRock|accessdate=30 November 2016}}</ref> When the police asked him to reveal who gave it to him, Squire pretended to be disoriented and made up a story that involved an unknown Australian he met at a [[Wimpy (restaurant)|Wimpy]] restaurant beforehand.<ref name=teamrock2014/> He recalled, \"It was the last time I ever took it, having ended up in hospital in [[Fulham]] for a couple of days not knowing who I was, or what I was, or who anybody else was.\"<ref name=hedges19>[[#Hedges1982|Hedges 1982, p. 19.]]</ref> After his discharge from hospital, Squire spent several months in his girlfriend's apartment, afraid to leave, only managing to visit the corner shop.<ref name=teamrock2014/> He spent each day practising his bass playing which resulted in his distinct style,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.al.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2013/07/post_176.html|title=Yes Q&A: Chris Squire talks LSD, 'Almost Famous,' Jimmy Page project, current tour featuring classic LPs|publisher=AL.com|first=Matt|last=Wake|date=15 July 2013|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=teamrock2014/> citing bassists [[John Entwistle]], [[Jack Bruce]], [[Larry Graham]],<ref name=\"Soocher, Stan 1979\"/> and [[Bill Wyman]] as early influences.<ref name=beggs2004>{{cite web|url=http://zenponies.com/yitp/2004/oct/oct07_04.html|title=The Day the Earth Stood Still: Chris Squire Interview|date=7 October 2004|first=Nick|last=Beggs|publisher=Kajagoogoo.com|accessdate=30 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Yes===\n[[File:Chris Squire, 1973 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|200px|upright|Squire in 1974]]\nIn September 1967, Squire joined [[Mabel Greer's Toyshop]], a psychedelic group that included [[Peter Banks]], singer Clive Bayley and drummer Bob Hagger.<ref name=welch3235>[[#Welch2008|Welch 2008, pp. 32\u201335.]]</ref> They played at the Marquee club where Jack Barrie, owner of the La Chasse drinking club a few doors down, saw them perform. \"The musicianship&nbsp;... was very good but it was obvious they weren't going anywhere\", he recalled.<ref name=welch2223>Welch, pp. 22\u201323.</ref> One evening at La Chasse, Barrie introduced Squire to [[Jon Anderson]], a worker at the bar who had not found success as the lead singer of [[The Gun (band)|The Gun]] or as a solo artist.<ref name=welch2223/> The two found they shared common musical interests including [[Simon & Garfunkel]], [[The Association]] and [[vocal harmony|vocal harmonies]]. In the following days they developed \"Sweetness\", a track later recorded for the [[Yes (Yes album)|first Yes album]].<ref name=welch24/>\n\nAs the band developed, Anderson and Squire brought in drummer [[Bill Bruford]], keyboardist [[Tony Kaye (musician)|Tony Kaye]] and Banks for rehearsals. The five agreed to drop the name Mabel Greer's Toyshop; they settled on the name Yes, originally Banks's idea.<ref name=welch3235/> The band played their first show as Yes at a youth camp in [[East Mersea]], [[Essex]] on 4 August 1968.<ref name=welch45>Welch, p. 45.</ref> Squire spoke about the band's formation: \"I couldn't get [[session musician|session work]] because most musicians hated my style. They wanted me to play something a lot more basic. We started Yes as a vehicle to develop everyone's individual styles.\"<ref>Gill, Chris. Guitar World's ''Bass Guitar'', Fall 2003 issue, p. 22.</ref> Squire developed a bass solo named \"A Bass Odyssey\".<ref name=teamrock2014/>\n\nIn August 1969, Yes released their self-titled [[Yes (Yes album)|debut album]]. Martyn Adelman, who had played drums with Squire's first group, did the album photos. Squire received writing credits on four of the album's eight tracks\u2014\"Beyond & Before\", \"Looking Around\", \"Harold Land\", and \"Sweetness\".<ref name=yes1969>{{Cite AV media notes|title=Yes|publisher=Atlantic Records|id=588 190|year=1969}}</ref>\n\nAfter Bruford left the band and was replaced by [[Alan White (Yes drummer)|Alan White]] in July 1972, Squire altered his playing to suit the change in the band's rhythm section. He felt he was \"playing too much, though I was never really sure. With Bill, the things that I did felt right ... With Alan, I found that I was able to play a bit less than before and still get my playing across\".<ref>[[#Morse1996|Morse 1996, p. 41.]]</ref>\n\nSquire described his playing on \"The Remembering (High the Memory)\" from ''[[Tales from Topographic Oceans]]'' (1973) as \"one of the nicest things I think I've ever played\".<ref>[[#Morse1996|Morse 1996, p. 47.]]</ref>\n\nSquire was the only member to play on each of their 21 studio albums released from 1969 to 2014. He was seen as one of the main forces behind the band's music, as well as being \"perhaps the most enigmatic\" group member.<ref>[[#Welch2008|Welch 2008, p. 10.]]</ref> ''[[Heaven & Earth (Yes album)|Heaven & Earth]]'' was his final studio album.<ref name=\"dies\">{{cite news|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/chris-squire-dies-yes/|work=Ultimate Classic Rock|first=Nick|last=DeRiso|date=28 June 2015|accessdate=28 June 2015|title=Yes Co-Founder Chris Squire Dies}}</ref>\n\nWhile most of the band's lyrics were written by Anderson, Squire co-wrote much of their music with guitarist [[Steve Howe (guitarist)|Steve Howe]] (with Anderson occasionally contributing). In addition, Squire and Howe would supply backing vocals in harmony with Anderson on songs such as \"[[South Side of the Sky]]\" and \"[[Close to the Edge (song)|Close to the Edge]]\".\n\nDuring the band's formative years Squire was frequently known for his lateness, a habit that Bruford often complained about. Because of this, Squire would frequently drive at unsafe speeds to get to gigs on time, once causing an accident on the way to a gig in [[West Germany]] after he fell asleep at the wheel, although nobody was injured. Later on a plaque \"The Late Chris Squire\" was written in reference to it. (Shown Below)<ref name=\"close\"/>\n\nAs Squire, along with [[Alan White (Yes drummer)|Alan White]] and [[Steve Howe (guitarist)|Steve Howe]], co-owned the \"Yes\" name at the time, the 1989 [[Anderson Bruford Wakeman Howe|ABWH]] line-up without him (which contained Anderson, Bruford, [[Rick Wakeman|Wakeman]] and Howe) could not record under that name.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/anderson-bruford-wakeman-howe/|title=Yes Minus One: The History of 'Anderson Bruford Wakeman Howe'|work=Ultimate Classic Rock|first=Jeff|last=Giles|date=20 June 2015|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref>\n[[File:Chris Squire Beacon Theatre 2013-04-09.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Squire performing with Yes in April 2013]]\nFollowing Squire's death on 27 June 2015, the band's show on 7 August of the same year marked the first Yes concert ever performed without him. Former member [[Billy Sherwood]] replaced Squire during their [[List of Yes concert tours (2000s\u201310s)|2015 North American tour]] with [[Toto (band)|Toto]] from August to September 2015, as well as their performances in November 2015, as announced when the band first revealed Squire's disease in May 2015.<ref name=\"Chris Squire to undergo treatment for Leukemia\"/><ref name=\"yesworld North American Summer Tour 2015\">{{cite web |url=http://www.yesworld.com/2015/04/yes-and-toto-2015-north-american-summer-tour/ |title=YES & Toto 2015 North American Summer Tour |date= 6 April 2015 |website=www.yesworld.com |accessdate= 11 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://yes.concerttournewshub.com/ |title=Yes & Toto 2015 Co-Headlining North American Summer Tour Schedule |date=6 April 2015 |accessdate=6 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150417034432/http://yes.concerttournewshub.com/ |archivedate=17 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2015/apr/06/yes-and-toto-teaming-up-for-tour/ |title=Yes & Toto announce joint tour |date=6 April 2015 |accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Other projects===\nSquire concentrated overwhelmingly on Yes' music over the years, producing little solo work. His first solo record was 1975's ''[[Fish Out of Water (Chris Squire album)|Fish Out of Water]]'', featuring Yes alumnus [[Bill Bruford]] on drums and [[Patrick Moraz]] on keyboards and [[The Syn]]/[[The Selfs]] alumnus Andrew Jackman also on keyboards.<ref name=\"dies\"/>\n\nIn 1981, Squire was a member of the short lived [[XYZ (UK band)|XYZ]], short for eX-Yes/Zeppelin (Squire claimed his father had come up with the name)<ref name=teamrock2014/> a group composed of White and guitarist [[Jimmy Page]]. XYZ recorded several demo tracks, but never produced anything formal, though two of the demos provided the basis for two later Yes tracks, \"Mind Drive\" and \"Can You Imagine?\"<ref name=\"32yearsago\">{{cite news|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/yes-zeppelin-supergroup-xyz/|work=Ultimate Classic Rock|title=32 Years Ago: Ex-Yes and Zeppelin Members Form Supergroup XYZ|first=Sterling|last=Whitaker|date=18 April 2013|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref> Led Zeppelin singer [[Robert Plant]] was not ready, despite Page's promises, to get involved with the band so soon after the death of Zeppelin drummer [[John Bonham]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Why The Yes And Led Zeppelin Supergroup Did Not Happen|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/why-the-yes-and-led-zeppelin-supergroup-did-not-happen-20120210|agency=Noise11|date=10 February 2012|accessdate=28 June 2015|first=Paul|last=Cashmere}}</ref> According to Squire, Zeppelin manager [[Peter Grant (music manager)|Peter Grant]] objected to the name as the \"Y\" appeared before the \"Z\" in the name. The group then \"fizzled out\".<ref name=teamrock2014/>\n\nSquire also played a role in bringing [[Trevor Rabin]] into the [[Cinema (band)|Cinema]] band project, which became the ''[[90125]]'' line-up of Yes.<ref name=\"32yearsago\"/>\n\nIn later years, Squire would join with Yes guitarist [[Billy Sherwood]] in a side project called [[Conspiracy (band)|Conspiracy]]. This band's self-titled debut album in 2000 contained the nuclei of several songs that had appeared on Yes' recent albums. Conspiracy's second album, ''The Unknown'', was released in 2003.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://somethingelsereviews.com/2013/04/03/chris-squire-and-billy-sherwood-conspiracy-live-2013/|title=Chris Squire and Billy Sherwood \u2013 Conspiracy Live (2013)|first=Nick|last=Deriso|date=3 April 2013|accessdate=28 June 2015|agency=Something Else Reviews}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2004, Squire joined a reunion of The Syn. The reformed band released the album ''[[Syndestructible]]'' in 2005 before breaking up again.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.metroactive.com/papers/cruz/02.15.06/syn-0607.html|title=Chris Squire Just Says Yes to Syn|work=Metroactive|date=February 2006|first=Bill|last=Forman}}</ref>\n\nSquire also worked on two solo projects with other former Syn collaborators [[Gerard Johnson (musician)|Gerard Johnson]], [[Jeremy Stacey]] and [[Paul Stacey]].<ref name=\"close\"/> A Christmas album, ''[[Chris Squire's Swiss Choir]]'', was released in 2007 (with Johnson, J. Stacey and [[Steve Hackett]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blog.musoscribe.com/?p=550|work=Musoscribe|title=Yes: A History of Perpetual Change|first=Bill|last=Kopp|date=5 July 2011|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref> Squire collaborated again with Hackett, formerly of the band [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]], to make the [[Squackett]] album ''[[A Life Within a Day]]'', released in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/a-life-within-a-day-mw0002344321|publisher=All Music|title=A Life Within a Day|first=Bret|last=Adams|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Illness, death, and tributes ==\n\n[[File:Chris Squire Brown Plaque with Rickenbacker 4001 bass guitar motif.jpg|thumb|Brown plaque in Warwick Street, Soho, London]]\n\nOn 19 May 2015, Yes announced that Squire had been diagnosed with [[acute erythroid leukemia]], and would take a break from performing while receiving treatment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://yesworld.com/2015/05/chris-squire-to-undergo-treatment-for-leukemia/|title=Chris Squire to undergo treatment for Leukemia|date=19 May 2015 |accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://classicrock.teamrock.com/news/2015-05-19/yes-chris-squire-has-cancer|title=Yes' Chris Squire has cancer|publisher=Classic Rock|author=Martin Kielty|date=19 May 2015|accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the late evening of 27 June 2015, Squire died from the illness, aged 67, while receiving treatment in his adopted hometown of [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[Arizona]].<ref name=discoermusicdeath/><ref name=\"dies\"/><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/chris-squire-yes-bassist-and-co-founder-dead-at-67-20150628|title=Chris Squire, Yes Bassist and Co-Founder, Dead at 67|date=28 June 2015|accessdate=28 June 2015|first=Daniel|last=Kreps|magazine=Rolling Stone}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-33306933|title=Yes bass guitarist Chris Squire dies aged 67|work=BBC News|date=28 June 2015|accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref> Yes' official [[Facebook]] page confirmed the news the next day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/yestheband/posts/1050133808331940|title=Yes (official) - It\u2019s with the heaviest of hearts and... - Facebook|work=facebook.com}}</ref> Tributes were paid by fellow musicians [[Brian May]], [[Geezer Butler]], [[Gene Simmons]] and [[Tom Morello]], as well as bandmates [[Geoff Downes]] and [[Bill Bruford]].<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.uncut.co.uk/news/brian-may-leads-tributes-to-yes-bassist-chris-squire-69333 | title= Brian May leads tributes to Yes bassist Chris Squire | work=Uncut | first=Michael | last=Bonner | date=29 June 2015 | accessdate=15 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nSquire's death was central to the song \"Fragile\" from the 2016 [[Jesu/Sun Kil Moon|collaborative debut album]] between [[Jesu (band)|Jesu]] and [[Sun Kil Moon]].  In the song, [[Mark Kozelek]] recounts his experiences as a Yes fan, particularly in light of the death of a friend, also named Christopher.  Squire was given a writing credit due to lyrics from his Yes composition \"Onward\" being quoted through backing vocals.\n\nIn April 2016 asteroid 2002 XR80 received an official permanent name from the [[International Astronomical Union]] in honor of Squire. Asteroid [http://www.minorplanetcenter.net/db_search/show_object?object_id=90125 (90125) Chrissquire] was discovered 11 December 2002 and is a main-belt asteroid with an orbital period of 4.08 years.\n\n==Style and legacy==\n[[File:Chris Squire Beacon Theatre 2013-04-09 5.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Squire with a [[Multi-neck guitar|triple-necked]] bass guitar in 2013]]\nSquire's unique tone was very clear and distinct, and his playing was noted for being aggressive,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://somethingelsereviews.com/2015/02/17/yes-beyond-and-before-yesterdays/|title=Yes, \"Beyond and Before\" from Yes (1969): YESterdays|date=17 February 2015|first=Preston|last=Frazier|agency=Something Else Reviews|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref> dynamic<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicradar.com/us/news/bass/the-60-greatest-bassists-of-all-time-279007/41|title=The 60 greatest bassists of all time|publisher=MusicRadar|date=1 December 2014|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref> and melodic.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.innerviews.org/inner/yes2.html|title=Yes: Propelling forward|work=Innerviews|date=2012|first=Anil|last=Prasad|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref> Squire's main instrument was a 1964 [[Rickenbacker]] bass (model RM1999, serial number DC127), which he bought and began playing in 1965.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fotolog.com/rickenbacker/12156931/|publisher=Fotolog|accessdate=28 June 2015|title=Rickenbacker|date=6 April 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701025000/http://www.fotolog.com/rickenbacker/12156931/|archive-date=1 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Squire mentioned in a 1979 interview with ''Circus Weekly'' that he acquired this bass while working at the [[Boosey & Hawkes]] music store in London.<ref name=\"Soocher, Stan 1979\"/> The instrument, with its warmth, was a significant part of Squire's unique sound.<ref name=\"top10\">{{cite news|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/chris-squire-yes-songs/|title=Top 10 Chris Squire Yes Songs|first=Ryan|last=Reed|work=Ultimate Classic Rock|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref> Due to its distinctive tone, which has been compared to that of a [[guitar]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/may13/articles/scarbee-rickenbacker-bass.htm|title=Scarbee Rickenbacker Bass|work=Sound on Sound|first=Nick|last=Magnus|date=May 2013|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref> it allowed the bass to take on a more \"lead\" role, which created a dynamic sound, and suited Squire perfectly.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.premierguitar.com/articles/20878-cruising-to-the-edge|title=Cruising to the Edge|first=Tessa|last=Jeffers|date=27 May 2014|accessdate=28 June 2015|work=Premier Guitar}}</ref>\n\nSquire also had a unique way of playing the bass; he played exclusively with a [[plectrum]], (usually a grey Herco \"heavy\") which he held so short, that his thumb would also strike the strings right after the pick, causing subtle [[harmonics]].<ref>Interview with Bob Birch, https://youtube.com/watch?cprcYnffK_o&t=128</ref>\nHe made frequent use of hammer-ons, pull-offs as well as alternate and tremolo picking. Aside from his aforementioned use of distortion, Squire occasionally used other effects, most notably [[Chorus effect|chorus]], [[flanger]] and [[wah-wah pedal|wah-wah]] pedals, which until then had mostly been used by guitarists.\n\nIn a 1973 interview for ''[[Guitar Player]]'' magazine, Squire recalled how he had obtained his distinctive tone at the time by rewiring his RM1999 into stereo and sending the bass and treble [[Pick up (music technology)|pick-up]]s each into a separate amplifier. By splitting the signal from his bass into dual high and low frequency outputs and then sending the low frequency output to a conventional bass [[amplifier]] and the high-frequency output to a separate lead guitar amplifier, Squire produced a tonal \"sandwich\" that added a growling, overdrive edge to the sound while retaining the Rickenbacker's powerful bass response. This gave his bass sound bright, growling higher frequencies and clean, solid bass frequencies. This technique allowed Squire to use [[harmonic distortion]] on his bass while avoiding the flat, fuzzy sound, loss of power and poor bass response that typically occurs when bass guitars are overdriven through an amplifier or put through a [[Distortion (music)|fuzz box]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Ferris |first=Leonard |date=July 1973 |title=Yes' Bassist Chris Squire |journal=[[Guitar Player]] |page=42}}</ref>\nSquire also made notable use of fret buzz, a normally undesirable condition caused by low string action, to create a further, growling edge to his playing.\n\nSquire claimed to have rewired his bass to stereo, even before Rickenbacker introduced the Rick-O-Sound feature, so he could send the output of the bass (neck) pick-up through a fuzz box, while keeping the treble (bridge) pick-up clean, because the last sounded \"horribly nasal\" when used with the fuzz effect.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bassplayer.com/article/basso-cantantecontinuo-chris/January-2009/91289 |title=Basso Cantante, Continuo Chris Squire's Singing Bass Rings Again With Yes |publisher=Bassplayer.com |accessdate=17 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707213704/http://www.bassplayer.com/article/basso-cantantecontinuo-chris/January-2009/91289 |archivedate=7 July 2011 }}</ref> He also played with a pick which contributed to the sharp attack as well as using fresh Rotosound Swing Bass strings for every show.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QxDbKssKXzEC&pg=PA136&lpg=PA136&dq=%22chris+squire%22++rotosound|title=Bass Heroes: Tom Mulhern |accessdate=17 August 2011|isbn=9780879302740|author1=Mulhern|first1=Tom|year=1993}}</ref> Squire's intricate and complex bass playing style has influenced subsequent bassists such as [[Billy Sheehan]], [[Geddy Lee]] of [[Rush (band)|Rush]], [[Steve Di Giorgio]] of [[Death (metal band)|Death]] and [[Sadus]], [[Pat Badger]] of [[Extreme (band)|Extreme]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/4eyDu4I1r9/|title=Pat Badger on Instagram: \u201cI'm deeply saddened to hear of the passing of one of my biggest influences Chris Squire. Not because I knew him personally, but because of\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram}}</ref> [[Jon Camp]] of [[Renaissance (band)|Renaissance]], [[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]] of [[Iron Maiden]], [[Les Claypool]] of [[Primus (band)|Primus]], [[John Myung]] of [[Dream Theater]] and [[Robert DeLeo]] of [[Stone Temple Pilots]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Hill |first=Gary |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/chris-squire-p5508 |title=Chris Squire |website=AllMusic |date=4 March 1948 |accessdate=17 August 2011}}</ref> [[John Deacon]] of [[Queen (band)|Queen]] was also inspired by Squire, and told Guitar Magazine that Squire was his favourite bass player.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://brianmay.com/john/gtrsep99/gtrsep99.html | title= Guitar Magazine - September 1999 | work=brianmay.com | accessdate=15 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to bass, Squire also occasionally played harmonica, piano and guitar.\n\n==Nickname==\nSquire was commonly known by his nickname, \"Fish\", and the name is associated with many of his works including his solo record, ''[[Fish Out of Water (Chris Squire album)|Fish Out of Water]]'' (1975), and the solo piece \"[[The Fish (Schindleria Praematurus)]]\" from the 1971 Yes record ''[[Fragile (Yes album)|Fragile]]''. The name has multiple origins, not least of which is the [[Heteronym (linguistics)|heteronymic]] meanings of \"bass\", describing [[Bass (sound)|low frequency sound]] or the bass guitar as well as the [[Bass (fish)|fish]]. Additionally, Squire's astrological sign was [[Pisces (astrology)|Pisces]]. Further, in the early days of Yes' career, he once accidentally flooded a hotel room in [[Oslo]], Norway, while taking a shower, and [[Bill Bruford]] gave him the nickname.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfte.org/interviews/0165_Squire.html |title=1996 Interview |publisher=Nfte.org |accessdate=17 August 2011}}</ref> On the 2007 documentary ''The Classic Artists Series 3: Yes'', Bruford says that the nickname arose because Squire spent long periods in the bathroom while they shared a house together in [[Fulham]].<ref>''The Classic Artists Series 3: Yes''.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nSquire met his first wife Nikki in 1970 at a club in London.<ref name=circus1975/> They married in 1972.<ref>{{cite web|title=Esquire|url=http://allmusic.com/artist/esquire-p17351/biography|work=All Music Guide|accessdate=28 February 2011}}</ref><ref>[[#Welch2008|Welch 2008, p. 220.]]</ref> She sang on the 1981 Christmas single \"[[Run with the Fox]]\" and also the track \"Hold Out Your Hand\" from ''[[Fish Out of Water (Chris Squire album)|Fish Out of Water]]'' (1975). In 1983, she formed Esquire, on whose first album Chris, Alan White and Trevor Horn assisted. Their family included Carmen, Chandrika and Camille Squire. The couple divorced after fifteen years of marriage.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nfte.org/interviews/ns232.html|title=Conversation with Nikki Squire|agency=Notes From the Edge|first=Paul|last=Secord|website=Nfte.org|date=May 2000|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nSquire married actress Melissa Morgan on 8 May 1993. She gave birth to their only son, Cameron in 2000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/chris-squire-fd2x3c838nh|title=Chris Squire|website=Thetimes.co.uk}}</ref> She played Brittany Norman on ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'' and later returned to the daytime programme as Agnes Sorensen.<ref>{{cite web|title=Melissa Morgan Squire is returning...|url=http://www.tvguide.com/soaps/Melissa-Morgan-Squire-56719.aspx|website=Tvguide.com|accessdate=28 February 2011|date=11 July 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://broadwayworld.com/people/Melissa_Morgan/|title=Broadway World|accessdate=28 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Goldstein|first=Toby|title=Ashley Is Back on The 'Y&rR' Scene|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2003-07-20/entertainment/0307160280_1_melchior-kelly-dorian|newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]]}}</ref> The pair divorced in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailyentertainmentnews.com/music/scotland-squire-yes-chris-squires-wife/|title=Scotland Squire: Yes Chris Squire\u2019s Wife (Bio, Wiki|website=Dailyentertainmentnews.com)|date=29 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nHis third and final marriage was to Scotland Squire, who gave birth to daughter Xilan in 2008. They resided in the [[Chelsea, London|Chelsea]] neighbourhood of London, and latterly in [[Phoenix, Arizona]].<ref name=teamrock2014/>\n\nIn the 1970s, Squire was a vegetarian for five years, before he returned to eating fish, then meat.<ref name=teamrock2014/> He also got involved with [[cocaine]] in the 1970s and early 1980s after the band [[The Eagles]], then a supporting act for Yes, introduced him to it. At some point in his life, Squire also suffered a heart attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/former-manager-and-friend-jon-brewer-remembers-chris-squire|title=Former Manager and Friend Jon Brewer Remembers Chris Squire|publisher=Louder Sound|first=Rob|last=Hughes|date=28 September 2015|accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n=== Solo singles ===\n* \"[[Run with the Fox]]\" \u2013 with Alan White 1981\n\n=== Solo albums ===\n* ''[[Fish Out of Water (Chris Squire album)|Fish Out of Water]]'' (1975)\n* ''[[Chris Squire's Swiss Choir]]'' (2007)\n\n=== With Conspiracy ===\n* ''Conspiracy'' (2000 + DVD)\n* ''The Unknown'' (2003)\n\n=== With Squackett ===\n* ''[[A Life Within a Day]]'' (2012)\n\n=== With The Syn ===\n:''see [[The Syn]]\n\n=== With Yes ===\n:''see [[Yes discography]]''\n\n=== As guest musician ===\n* 1968: [[Neat Change]] - ''[[I Lied to Aunty May]]'' (with Peter Banks on guitar, Squire plays the tambourine and performs backing vocals on this single)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Home|first=Stewart|last2=Edwards|first2=Jimmy|date=26 July 2010|title=It\u2019s an Uphill Climb to the Bottom|url=https://www.3ammagazine.com/3am/its-an-uphill-climb-to-the-bottom/|journal=3:AM Magazine|access-date=16 June 2019}}</ref>\n* 1970: [[Larry Smith (musician)|Larry \"Legs\" Smith]] - ''[[Witchi-tai-Po]]'' (with Tony Kaye on this single by a member of [[Bonzo Dog Doo Dah Band]]) \n* 1973: Rick Wakeman - ''[[The Six Wives of Henry VIII (album)|The Six Wives of Henry VIII]]'' (Steve Howe, Bill Bruford & Alan White)\n* 1973: [[Eddie Harris]] - ''[[E.H. in the U.K.]]'' (with Tony Kaye & Alan White)\n* 1977: Rick Wakeman - ''[[Rick Wakeman's Criminal Record]]'' (with Alan White)\n* 1981: [[The Buggles]] - ''[[Adventures in Modern Recording]]'' (Squire is credited only with \"sound effects\" on one piece, while the bass is played by Trevor Horn)\n* 1987: [[Esquire (band)|Esquire]] - ''Esquire'' (Chris's ex-wife Nikky Squire with Alan White, Trevor Horn & Carmen Squire, Chris's daughter)\n* 1990: [[Rock Aid Armenia]] - a single re-recording of Deep Purple's \"[[Smoke on the Water]]\" (with [[Keith Emerson]], [[Geoff Downes]], [[Ian Gillan]], [[Bruce Dickinson]], [[Paul Rodgers]], [[David Gilmour]], [[Ritchie Blackmore]], [[Tony Iommi]], [[Alex Lifeson]], [[Bryan Adams]], [[Brian May]] & [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]]), which is also included on ''The Earthquake Album''.\n* 1993: [[Rick Wakeman]] - ''[[Classical Connections 2]]'' (recorded in 1971 but published in 1991 with Steve Howe & Bill Bruford)\n* 1995: [[World Trade (band)|World Trade]] - ''Euphoria'' with Billy Sherwood, co-wrote two songs\n* 2002: [[Gov't Mule]] - ''[[The Deep End, Volume 2]]''\n* 2002: Various artists - ''[[Pigs and Pyramids - An All Star Lineup Performing the Songs of Pink Floyd]]'' (again published as ''[[Back Against the Wall]]'' from Billy Sherwood in 2005)\n* 2009: [[Steve Hackett]] - ''[[Out of the Tunnel's Mouth]]''\n* 2011: Steve Hackett - ''[[Beyond the Shrouded Horizon]]''\n* 2012: [[Billy Sherwood & The Prog Collective]] - ''The Technical Divide'' (with [[Alan Parsons]] & [[Gary Green (musician)|Gary Green]])\n* 2012: Various artists - ''Songs of the Century: An All-Star Tribute to Supertramp. Let the World Revolve'' (with Billy Sherwood & Tony Kaye)\n* 2013: Billy Sherwood & The Prog Collective - ''Epilogue'' (Shining Diamonds with Patrick Moraz, Billy Sherwood, Alan Parsons & [[Steve Stevens]])\n* 2015: Steve Hackett - ''[[Wolflight]]'' (Squire plays bass on \"Love Song to a Vampire\")\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Bibliography\n*{{Cite book|last=Hedges|first=Dan|title=Yes: An Authorized Biography|year=1982|publisher=Sidgwick & Jackson|isbn=978-0-283-98751-9|ref=Hedges1982}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Morse|first=Tim|title=Yesstories: \"Yes\" in Their Own Words|year=1996|publisher=St Martin's Press|isbn=978-0-312-14453-1|ref=Morse1996}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Welch|first=Chris|title=Close to the Edge \u2013 The Story of Yes|publisher=Omnibus Press|isbn=978-1-84772-132-7|year=2008|ref=Welch2008}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n*{{IMDb name|id=0820085}}\n\n{{Yesband|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Squire, Chris}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:English rock bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Male bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English songwriters]]\n[[Category:Singers from London]]\n[[Category:Yes (band) members]]\n[[Category:People from Kingsbury, London]]\n[[Category:Progressive rock musicians]]\n[[Category:The Syn members]]\n[[Category:XYZ (English band) members]]\n", "name_user": "LJA123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed repetition.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Squire"}
{"title_page": "Paul Mariner", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=June 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Paul Mariner\n| image          = Paul Mariner 2010.jpg\n| image_size     = 220\n| caption        = Mariner as manager of [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] in 2010\n| fullname       = Paul Mariner<ref name=\"Hugman\">{{Hugman|13129|accessdate=2 April 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1953|5|22|df=y}}<ref name=\"Hugman\"/>\n| birth_place    = [[Bolton]], England<ref name=\"Hugman\"/>\n| height         = \n| position       = [[Centre forward]]\n| currentclub    = \n| youthyears1    = 1971\u20131973 | youthclubs1 = [[Chorley F.C.|Chorley]]\n| years1         = 1973\u20131976 | clubs1 = [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]]           | caps1 = 135 | goals1 = 56\n| years2         = 1976\u20131984 | clubs2 = [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]                 | caps2 = 260 | goals2 = 96\n| years3         = 1984\u20131986 | clubs3 = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]                           | caps3 = 60  | goals3 = 14\n| years4         = 1986\u20131988 | clubs4 = [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]                     | caps4 = 56  | goals4 = 9\n| years5         = 1988      | clubs5 = [[Wollongong Wolves FC|Wollongong City]]<ref>{{cite web |title=1988 season \u2013 round 14 results |first=Andrew |last=Howe |url=http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/NSL/1988/round14.htm |work=Ozfootball.net |date=9 May 1988 |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=1988 season \u2013 round 15 results |first=Andrew |last=Howe |url=http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/NSL/1988/round15.htm |work=Ozfootball.net |date=9 May 1988 |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> | caps5 = 2   | goals5 = 0\n| years6         = 1989\u20131992 | clubs6 = [[Albany Capitals]]<ref name=\"profile\">{{cite web |url=http://socceroutsider.com/bios/paul-mariner |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130104215211/http://socceroutsider.com/bios/paul-mariner |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 January 2013 |title=Paul Mariner \u2013 profile |publisher=Socceroutsider.com |accessdate=10 February 2012 }}</ref> | caps6 = 17   | goals6 = 1\n| years7         = 1992\u20131993 | clubs7 = [[San Francisco Bay Blackhawks|San Francisco Bay]]<ref name=\"profile\"/> | caps7 = 10  | goals7 = 0\n| totalcaps = 555 | totalgoals = 179\n| nationalyears1 = 1977\u20131985\n| nationalteam1  = [[England national football team|England]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 35\n| nationalgoals1 = 13\n| manageryears1  = 2003      | managerclubs1  = [[Harvard Crimson]] (assistant)\n| manageryears2  = 2004\u20132009 | managerclubs2  = [[New England Revolution]] (assistant)\n| manageryears3  = 2009\u20132010 | managerclubs3  = [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]]\n| manageryears4  = 2012\u20132013 | managerclubs4  = [[Toronto FC]]\n}}\n'''Paul Mariner''' (born 22 May 1953) is an English [[Association football|football]] [[Coach (sport)|coach]] and retired player. He was most recently the head coach and technical director at [[Major League Soccer]] club [[Toronto FC]], until his dismissal in January 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Toronto FC fires coach Paul Mariner, replaced by Ryan Nelsen|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/soccer/tfc/2013/01/07/toronto_fc_fires_coach_paul_mariner_replaced_by_ryan_nelsen.html|work=Toronto Star|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Ltd|accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nA [[centre forward]] during his playing days, Mariner began his career with [[Chorley F.C.|Chorley]]. He became a professional player in 1973 with [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]], where he scored 61 goals in 155 appearances and is considered to be one of the club's best players. He joined [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] in 1976, where he achieved domestic and European success under the guidance of [[Bobby Robson]]. He was called up to play for the [[England national football team|England national team]] during his time at [[Portman Road]], and went on to represent his country at the [[UEFA Euro 1980|1980 European Championships]] and the [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982 World Cup]]. He spent two years with [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and then [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] before finishing his career abroad. He played for clubs in Australia, the US, and [[Malta]].\n\nHe took up coaching during his time with the [[Albany Capitals]] and focused on it fully when he retired from playing. After spending time working in [[Japan]], he returned to America to coach, firstly in [[Arizona]] and then at [[Harvard University]]. He joined [[Major League Soccer]] club [[New England Revolution]] in 2004 as a member of [[Steve Nicol]]'s coaching staff. After five years in [[Massachusetts]], Mariner returned to Plymouth Argyle in 2009 as their head coach. He succeeded [[Paul Sturrock]] as the club's manager two months later before returning to his role as head coach upon the arrival of [[Peter Reid]]. In January 2011, he returned to Major League Soccer as director of player development at [[Toronto FC]].\n\nMariner is currently the [[color commentator]] for the New England Revolution of MLS. Starting in 2020, Mariner only commentates for some of the Revolution games, and shares the duty with [[Charlie Davies]]. \n\n==Playing career==\n===1970s===\n[[File:Paul Mariner cropped.jpg|thumb|upright=|Mariner during his time with Ipswich Town|155px]]\n\nMariner started his career as an [[amateur]] player at non-league club [[Chorley F.C.|Chorley]], close to his Lancashire roots and his style at the helm of their attack caught the attention of [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]], for whom he signed in 1973.\n\nSo began an impressive scoring record with the [[Devon]] club, with 56 goals in 135 appearances coming before [[Bobby Robson]], who had been personally monitoring Mariner's progress, took him to Ipswich for \u00a3220,000 with [[John Peddelty]] and [[Terry Austin (footballer)|Terry Austin]] moving in the opposite direction as part of the deal. Mariner chose Ipswich ahead of similar offers from [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Brian |last=Knight |title=Plymouth Argyle: A Complete Record 1903\u20131989 |year=1989 |publisher=Breedon Books |location=Derby |isbn=0-907969-40-2 |pages=157\u2013158}}</ref>\n\nMariner made his debut in September 1976 and quickly settled into the Ipswich side as an old-fashioned number 9 \u2013 i.e., a forward capable of taking hard tackles and rough treatment from [[Defender (football)|defender]]s but willing to give it back, while also scoring a fair share of goals. Received wisdom suggests that Mariner was only a 'target-man'-type centre forward but he scored plenty of goals with his feet and had the skill to create his own chances on the deck, rather than relying entirely on service through the centre and via the flanks.\n\nSuch was Mariner's impact that six months after joining Ipswich, he made his England debut as a [[substitute (soccer)|substitute]] in a 5\u20130 win over [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]] at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]] and played from the beginning in the following game against [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]] in the [[British Home Championship]] at [[Windsor Park]], [[Belfast]]. He impressed in both games, though didn't score and was not selected for the next six matches. During this period, Ipswich finished third in the [[Football League First Division|First Division]], with Mariner contributing ten goals from 28 games.\n\nMariner's third England cap came in the return World Cup qualifier in Luxembourg, scoring a last-minute goal in a 2\u20130 win which England really needed to win by much more in order to give themselves half a chance of qualifying for the [[Football World Cup 1978|1978 World Cup]] in Argentina. By now, Mariner had become one of a number of 'target man'-type centre forwards for England coach [[Ron Greenwood]] to select from, with the likes of [[Stuart Pearson]] and [[Bob Latchford]] also on the scene. It was Mariner, however, who would get the nod for the majority of the time.\n\nMeanwhile, at club level, Mariner was having a mixed time. He scored eleven goals in 37 appearances for Ipswich, which maintained his England aspirations but the team underperformed in the First Division and finished a lowly 18th. However, they reached the [[FA Cup]] final at Wembley where they memorably beat [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] 1\u20130. Mariner hit the woodwork with one chance and generally caused havoc to the Arsenal defence, earning him the ''Man Of The Match'' award afterwards.\n\nGreenwood decided not to select Mariner for England throughout 1979, although he enjoyed his most productive spell for Ipswich in front of goal that season, hitting 13 in 33 matches. It wasn't until 1980 that Mariner won a sixth England cap \u2013 almost exactly two years after his fifth \u2013 and he scored England's goal in a surprising 4\u20131 defeat against [[Wales national football team|Wales]] at [[Wrexham]]. He stayed in the reckoning thereafter, scoring in a 2\u20131 win over [[Australia national association football team|Australia]] in [[Sydney]] in the final game before England took to the field for the [[1980 European Football Championship|1980 European Championships]]. Mariner was named in Greenwood's squad for the tournament, despite not kicking a ball during the whole qualifying campaign.\n\nHe didn't play in the opening 1\u20131 draw versus [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] in [[Turin]] but came on as a sub in the remaining two group matches \u2013 a defeat against [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and a victory over [[Spain national football team|Spain]], which ensured England's elimination from the competition.\n\n===1980s===\nMariner maintained his England place as his Ipswich goalscoring record continued to improve \u2013 17 from 41 games had come in 1980 and Ipswich made the early running as the next season got underway. England began their qualifying campaign for the [[Football World Cup 1982|1982 World Cup]] with a conclusive 4\u20130 win over [[Norway national football team|Norway]], with Mariner scoring a superb goal with a deft turn and shot from 25 yards. He was, however, left out of the next game, which turned into a gruesome 2\u20131 defeat against [[Romania national football team|Romania]] in [[Bucharest]]. Greenwood put him back in the side a month later for a now vital match against [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]], and Mariner scored the opener in a 2\u20131 win.\n\nIpswich were challenging for three trophies as the 1981 season approached its climax, with Mariner again to the fore, scoring 13 times in 36 matches. However, they were to miss out on two domestic fronts, with [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] winning the First Division (after Ipswich failed to beat [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]) and [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] defeating Ipswich in the semi-finals of the FA Cup. But in the [[UEFA Cup]], Mariner was proving to be a real hero as glory beckoned.\n\nHe scored twice in the early rounds as Ipswich progressed to a tasty quarter final against [[AS Saint-\u00c9tienne|St \u00c9tienne]]. In the first leg in France Mariner put two away as Ipswich went 4\u20131 up, and added another as Ipswich completed the task in the second leg. After winning the semi-final, Mariner scored again in the first leg of the final against [[AZ Alkmaar]] as Ipswich coasted to a 3\u20130 lead, ultimately winning the competition 5\u20134 on [[Aggregate score|aggregate]]. Weeks later, Greenwood put him back in the England side as the World Cup qualification campaign resumed with a defeat in Switzerland, a vital victory in [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] and a shock defeat in Norway. It appeared that they may miss out on the World Cup finals for an unthinkable third tournament in a row.\n\nBut results elsewhere miraculously went their way, meaning England only needed to draw with the already qualified Hungary at Wembley in the final game to guarantee qualification. It was Mariner who scored the only goal in a 1\u20130 win, though he got it via a stumble which saw him score via a deflection rather than an actual shot on goal. But it was enough.\n\nInjuries to both [[Achilles tendon]]s restricted Mariner's football over the next few months, and he only scored eight times in 25 games for Ipswich. But in the five final England warm-up matches prior to the World Cup in Spain, he scored four times, including a stunning solo run and strike against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] at Wembley. He was named in Greenwood's squad and started the first match of the tournament, against [[France national football team|France]].\n\nEngland went into a 2\u20131 lead thanks to a brace from [[Bryan Robson]] \u2013 the first of which was one of the World Cup Finals' quickest-ever goals \u2013 before Mariner slammed home a close-range volley to complete an impressive 3\u20131 win. It was his eleventh international goal in his 22nd match \u2013 an admirable ratio of one goal every other game. It was his also his sixth consecutive scoring game for England \u2013 a feat previously achieved only by [[Jimmy Greaves]].\n\nGreenwood selected Mariner for the rest of the tournament but he didn't score again and England went out in the second phase after two disappointing goalless draws. Mariner is best remembered for dragging a devastated [[Kevin Keegan]] to his feet in support after the England captain, on as a substitute after a tournament ruined by injury problems, sank to his [[knee]]s, head in hands, missed an open goal with a header which would have sent England into the semi-finals.\n\nMariner's club boss Robson subsequently became England coach and he continued to select him as the qualification campaign for the [[1984 European Football Championship|1984 European Championships]] got underway. Mariner continued to score frequently for Ipswich, whose young and vibrant side had started to age and break-up.\n\nEngland's qualification campaign faltered, though Mariner scored in consecutive pool matches against Hungary and Luxembourg \u2013 the latter of which would prove to be his 13th and final England goal. By the time he next played for England, he was an [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] player, with the Gunners taking him from Ipswich in February 1984 for \u00a3150,000. By now Mariner was in his thirties but he still initially performed well for Arsenal, scoring seven times in the final fifteen games of the season. But age was starting to get the better of him; and he only scored nine goals in 41 games in [[1984-85 in English football|1984\u201385]].\n\nMariner won two more England caps but a sign of things to come had arrived in the shape of [[Mark Hateley]], a tall but skillful young striker exactly in the Mariner mould, while [[Gary Lineker]] and [[Peter Beardsley]] also establishing themselves as international strikers.\n\nHateley came on as a substitute for Mariner in a friendly victory over [[East Germany national football team|East Germany]] in September 1984, before Mariner picked up his 35th and final cap in a goalless draw against Romania in May 1985, a qualifier for the [[Football World Cup 1986|1986 World Cup]]. He had scored 13 times for England - the first goal coming on 12 October 1977 in a 2\u20130 win over [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]] in a [[1978 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] qualifier. His last goal for England came on 16 November 1983, also against Luxembourg, but this time in a [[UEFA Euro 1984|European Championship]] qualifier.<ref>[http://www.sporting-heroes.net/football/england/paul-mariner-9569/english-caps-1977-85_a11852/]</ref>\n\nHowever, with Hateley in the ascendancy and Mariner regularly sidelined at [[Highbury]] during the 1985\u20131986 season, Robson opted not to select him for the England squad which qualified for Mexico '86.\n\nMeanwhile, at his club Mariner was rarely on the field, only playing nine times in [[1985-86 in English football|1985\u201386]], including one match as an emergency [[centre half]]. In the summer of 1986 Arsenal's new manager [[George Graham (footballer)|George Graham]] gave Mariner a [[free transfer (soccer)|free transfer]]; in all he played 80 times for Arsenal, scoring 17 goals. He signed for [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], where he spent two seasons. In May 1989, he signed with the [[Albany Capitals]] of the [[American Soccer League (1988-1989)|American Soccer League]].<ref>''CAPITALS WILL PUT BOLTS TO THE TEST'' Boston Globe \u2013 Saturday, 27 May 1989</ref>\n\n===1990s===\nMariner returned to the Capitals in 1990 as the team now played in the [[American Professional Soccer League]], formed by the merger of the American Soccer League and [[Western Soccer League]]. He played three seasons with the Capitals, where he was named to the league's Best XI in 1990.<ref>[http://a-leaguearchive.tripod.com/1990/statsasl90.htm#Albany 1990 Albany Capitals]</ref><ref>[http://a-leaguearchive.tripod.com/1989/statsasl89.htm#Albany 1989 Albany Capitals]</ref><ref>[http://www.sover.net/~spectrum/year/1990.html#APSL The Year in American Soccer \u2013 1990]</ref><ref>[http://a-leaguearchive.tripod.com/1991/stats91.htm#Albany 1991 Albany Capitals]</ref> During his three seasons in Albany, Mariner also served as an assistant coach. In the spring of 1992, the Capitals' owner offered him the position of head coach but when he heard a rumour that the team was about to collapse, he accepted a position as a player-assistant coach with the [[San Francisco Bay Blackhawks]]. He accepted that position and soon after the Capitals announced they were ceasing operations. In the early 1990s Paul made two appearances for Byhams Dairy, a Sunday League team in Sudbury Suffolk<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jonathanvankin.com/mariner1.html |title=The Player |access-date=29 June 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306204006/http://jonathanvankin.com/mariner1.html |archive-date=6 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Coaching==\n===Early career===\nAfter retiring, Mariner worked as a football pundit for [[BBC Radio Lancashire]] for their Friday-night Non-League Hour<ref>http://www.chorleyfc.com/club-news_article.asp?Key=284{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> before setting up a management company for footballers. After a spell back in England coaching at [[Bolton School]], he returned to the States to coach youth football at S.C. Del Sol in [[Phoenix, Arizona]]. In the fall of 2003 he became an assistant coach at [[Harvard University]]. In 2004, he was hired by the [[New England Revolution]] of [[Major League Soccer]] as assistant coach to former [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] defender [[Steve Nicol]].\n\n===Plymouth Argyle===\nSpeculation about his future was rife in October 2009 when he was linked with a coaching position at one of his former clubs, [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]], abetted by his visit to [[Devon]] to promote the city's [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 World Cup]] bid and his subsequent resignation on 17 October. It was announced the following day, 18 October 2009, that he was to become the new Head Coach of [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]], with [[Paul Sturrock]] staying on as Team Manager.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mariner set for Plymouth return|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/p/plymouth_argyle/8313076.stm|accessdate=7 March 2013|publisher=BBC Sport|date=18 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 December 2009, Mariner replaced Sturrock as manager of Plymouth Argyle, following a run of poor form which left the Pilgrims second bottom in the Championship.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/plymouth_argyle/8405711.stm | work=BBC News | title=Mariner in for Sturrock at Argyle | date=10 December 2009}}</ref> He was unable to keep Plymouth up, however, and they were relegated from the Football league Championship after a six-year stay, on 19 April 2010.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/plymouth_argyle/8631377.stm | publisher=BBC Sport | title=Mariner wants to stay at Plymouth | date=20 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 May 2010, it was announced that Plymouth were to look for a new manager, however Mariner would remain as a member of the coaching staff.<ref>{{cite news |title=Plymouth Argyle to look for new manager |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/plymouth_argyle/8665627.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 May 2010 |accessdate=2 April 2017}}</ref> Mariner's tenure as manager ended when [[Peter Reid]] was hired on 24 June 2010.<ref name=\"plymouthargylesacking\">{{cite news |title=Peter Reid appointed manager of Plymouth Argyle |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/plymouth_argyle/8755830.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=24 June 2010 |accessdate=2 April 2017}}</ref> Mariner stepped down from his role at [[Home Park]] on 30 December 2010 to pursue another opportunity.<ref>{{cite news|title=Paul Mariner leaves cash-strapped Plymouth Argyle|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/p/plymouth_argyle/9328665.stm|accessdate=7 March 2013|newspaper=BBC|date=30 December 2010}}</ref> \"I have known Paul for a long time and working with him has been fantastic,\" said Argyle manager [[Peter Reid]]. \"I'm sure he will be successful in everything he does in the future. He's a great personality and someone who is a legend with the fans at this football club.\"<ref>[http://www.thisisplymouth.co.uk/news/Peter-Argyle-s-rescue/article-3053991-detail/article.html \"Peter Ridsdale in to save club as Paul Mariner walks away from Home Park\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110211232633/http://www.thisisplymouth.co.uk/news/Peter-Argyle-s-rescue/article-3053991-detail/article.html |date=11 February 2011 }}. ''[[The Herald (Plymouth)|The Plymouth Herald]]''. 31 December 2010. Retrieved 7 January 2011.</ref>\n\n===Toronto FC===\nMariner was named Director of Player Development for [[Toronto FC]] on 6 January 2011, joining new head coach [[Aron Winter]] at the club.<ref>[http://www.torontofc.ca/news/2011/01/new-management-team-announced \"New management team announced\"]. [[Toronto FC]]. 6 January 2011. Retrieved 7 January 2011.</ref>\n\nAfter starting the season with 9 straight losses, former Toronto Coach [[Aron Winter]] stepped down and Toronto named Mariner head coach on 7 June 2012.<ref name=\"torontofcjob\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/soccer/mls/torontofc/article/1207460--toronto-fc-set-to-make-major-announcement |title= Aron Winter out as Toronto FC head coach, replaced by Paul Mariner |accessdate= 7 June 2012 |publisher= |date=7 June 2012 |work=The Star |first=Daniel |last=Girard}}</ref> Mariner recorded his first victory as Toronto manager on 27 June against [[Montreal Impact]], the game ended in a 3\u20130 away win.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter/2012-06-27-mtl-v-tor/recap | title = Recap: Rampant Toronto throttle Impact 3-0 in Montreal | date = 27 June 2012 | accessdate = 28 June 2012 | publisher = mlssoccer.com}}</ref> Mariner was dismissed on 7 January 2013.<ref name=\"torontofcsacking\">{{cite news|title=Toronto FC fires coach Paul Mariner, replaced by Ryan Nelsen|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/soccer/tfc/2013/01/07/toronto_fc_fires_coach_paul_mariner_replaced_by_ryan_nelsen.html|accessdate=7 March 2013|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=7 January 2013}}</ref> Mariner was praised by former Toronto FC players [[Andrew Wiedeman]]<ref name=\"Andrew Wiedeman RedNation Online Interview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rednationonline.ca/Articles2015/RNOInterviewSeriesAndrewWiedeman.aspx |author=Vujcic, Djuradj |title=Andrew Wiedeman RedNation Online Interview |accessdate=2014-12-23 |date=2014-12-22 }}</ref> and [[Eric Hassli]].<ref name=\"Eric Hassli RedNation Online Interview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rednationonline.ca/Articles2015/RedNationInterviewSeriesEricHassli.aspx |author=Vujcic, Djuradj |title=Eric Hassli RedNation Online Interview |accessdate=2018-04-19 |date=2015-05-29 }}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[EFL Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n|-||-||-||-||-||-\n|rowspan=\"6\" valign=\"center\"|[[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]]\n|-\n|[[1973-74 in English football|1973\u201374]]\n|41||14||3||2||6||1||0||0||50||17\n|-\n|[[1974-75 in English football|1974\u201375]]\n|45||20||3||1||2||0||0||0||50||21\n|-\n|[[1975-76 in English football|1975\u201376]]\n|38||15||2||0||2||1||0||0||42||16\n|-\n|[[1976-77 in English football|1976\u201377]]\n|10||7||0||0||2||0||0||0||12||7\n|-|- style=\"font-weight:bold; background-color:#eeeeee;\"\n|Total||134||56||8||3||12||2||0||0||154||61\n|-\n|rowspan=\"10\" valign=\"center\"|[[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]\n|-\n|[[1976-77 in English football|1976\u201377]]\n|28||10||3||3||0||0||0||0||31||13\n|-\n|[[1977-78 in English football|1977\u201378]]\n|37||11||7||7||1||1||6||3||53||22\n|-\n|[[1978-79 in English football|1978\u201379]]\n|33||13||5||3||1||0||5||1||44||17\n|-\n|[[1979-80 in English football|1979\u201380]]\n|41||17||3||3||2||0||4||2||50||22\n|-\n|[[1980-81 in English football|1980\u201381]]\n|36||13||7||3||4||4||11||6||58||26\n|-\n|[[1981-82 in English football|1981\u201382]]\n|25||8||2||0||5||1||1||0||33||9\n|-\n|[[1982-83 in English football|1982\u201383]]\n|37||13||3||0||1||0||1||0||37||13\n|-\n|[[1983-84 in English football|1983\u201384]]\n|23||12||1||0||4||2||0||0||28||14\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold; background-color:#eeeeee;\"\n|Total||260||97||31||19||18||8||28||12||337||136\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\" valign=\"center\"|[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n|-\n|[[1983-84 in English football|1983\u201384]]\n|15||7||0||0||0||0||0||0||15||7\n|-\n|[[1984-85 in English football|1984\u201385]]\n|36||7||3||2||2||0||0||0||41||9\n|-\n|[[1985-86 in English football|1985\u201386]]\n|9||0||3||0||2||1||0||0||14||1\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold; background-color:#eeeeee;\"\n|Total||60||14||6||2||4||1||0||0||70||17\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold; background-color:#eeeeee;\"\n|rowspan=\"1\" valign=\"top\"|'''Career'''\n|\n|'''454'''||'''167'''||'''45'''||'''24'''||'''34'''||'''11'''||'''28'''||'''12'''||'''561'''||'''214'''\n|}\n\n<small>Other includes the UEFA Cup, UEFA Cup Winner's Cup, and FA Charity Shield.</small><ref>[http://www.greensonscreen.co.uk/gosdb-players2.asp?pid=521&scp=1,2,3,4,5,6,7 GoS: Paul Mariner]</ref><ref>[http://www.itfc.co.uk/page/SeasonsGoneByIndex/0,,10272,2,00.html Ipswich Town: Season's Gone by] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503162617/http://www.itfc.co.uk/page/SeasonsGoneByIndex/0,,10272,2,00.html |date=3 May 2009 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.sporting-heroes.net/football-heroes/displayhero_club.asp?HeroID=41829 Paul Mariner: Sporting Heroes]</ref><ref>[http://jkarlsson.netfirms.com/players/m/mariner_p/ Gunnermania: Paul Mariner] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908091744/http://jkarlsson.netfirms.com/players/m/mariner_p/ |date=8 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|7 January 2013}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Team\n!rowspan=2|From\n!rowspan=2|To\n!colspan=5|Record\n!rowspan=2|{{abbr|Ref|Reference}}\n|-\n!{{abbr|P|Matches played}}!!{{abbr|W|Matches won}}!!{{abbr|D|Matches drawn}}!!{{abbr|L|Matches lost}}!!{{abbr|Win %|Win percentage}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]]\n|align=left|10 December 2009\n|align=left|24 June 2010\n{{WDL|29|7|6|16|decimals=1}}\n|<ref name=\"plymouthargylesacking\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Managers: Paul Mariner |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/managers/manager.sd?manager_id=2180 |work=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=2 April 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[Toronto FC]]\n|align=left|7 June 2012\n|align=left|7 January 2013\n{{WDL|28|6|8|14|decimals=1}}\n|<ref name=\"torontofcjob\"/><ref name=\"torontofcsacking\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Toronto FC: Matches |url=https://int.soccerway.com/teams/canada/toronto-fc/7977/matches/ |work=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |accessdate=2 April 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n!colspan=3|Total\n{{WDLtot|57|13|14|30|decimals=1}}\n!\u2014\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===As a player===\n; Plymouth Argyle\n* [[List of winners of English Football League One and predecessors#Football League Third Division 1958-1992|Third Division]] runner up: [[1974-75 in English football|1974\u201375]]\n\n; Ipswich Town\n* [[FA Cup]]: [[FA Cup Final 1978|1977\u201378]]\n* [[UEFA Cup]]: [[1981 UEFA Cup Final|1980\u201381]]\n\n===Individual===\n* [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.#Player of the Year|Plymouth Argyle Player of the Year]]: [[1974-75 in English football|1974\u201375]], [[1974-75 in English football|1975\u201376]]\n* [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.#Team of the century|Plymouth Argyle Team of the Century]]\n* Football League First Division PFA Team of the Year: [[PFA Team of the Year (1980s)#First Division 2|1980\u201381]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Lynch |title=The Official P.F.A. Footballers Heroes |page=143}}</ref>\n* [[List of Ipswich Town F.C. Players of the Year|Ipswich Town Player of the Year]]: [[1982-83 in English football|1982\u201383]]\n*[[Ipswich Town F.C. Hall of Fame|Ipswich Town Hall of Fame]]: Inducted 2011<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.eadt.co.uk/sport/ipswich-town/sir_alf_ramsey_inducted_into_ipswich_town_hall_of_fame_1_859827 | title = Sir Alf Ramsey inducted into Ipswich Town Hall of Fame | first = Elvin | last = King | work = East Anglian Daily Times| accessdate = 21 March 2014 | date = 9 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.thefa.com/England/All-Teams/Players?p=336188 Paul Mariner] at the [[Football Association]] website\n*{{soccerbase (manager)|id=2180|name=Paul Mariner}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards\n| bg = gold\n| fg = navy\n| list1 = \n{{1980\u201381 Football League First Division PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{Plymouth Argyle F.C. Player of the Year}}\n{{Ipswich Town F.C. Player of the Year}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = England squads\n| bg = white\n| fg = #0B0B3F\n| bordercolor = #0B0B3F\n| list1 = \n{{England squad UEFA Euro 1980}}\n{{England squad 1982 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Managerial positions\n| list1 = \n{{Plymouth Argyle F.C. managers}}\n{{Toronto FC managers}}\n}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mariner, Paul}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Bolton]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n[[Category:England B international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1980 players]]\n[[Category:1982 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Chorley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Plymouth Argyle F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Ipswich Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Arsenal F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Portsmouth F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bury Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Albany Capitals players]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Bay Blackhawks players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Harvard Crimson men's soccer coaches]]\n[[Category:American Soccer League (1988\u201389) players]]\n[[Category:American Professional Soccer League coaches]]\n[[Category:American Professional Soccer League players]]\n[[Category:Plymouth Argyle F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Plymouth Argyle F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:English Football League managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Malta]]\n[[Category:National Soccer League (Australia) players]]\n[[Category:Wollongong Wolves FC players]]\n[[Category:Toronto FC coaches]]\n[[Category:New England Revolution non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer broadcasters]]\n[[Category:UEFA Cup winning players]]\n[[Category:English expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in the United States]]\n[[Category:English expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=June 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Paul Mariner\n| image          = Paul Mariner 2010.jpg\n| image_size     = 220\n| caption        = Mariner as manager of [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] in 2010\n| fullname       = Paul Mariner<ref name=\"Hugman\">{{Hugman|13129|accessdate=2 April 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1953|5|22|df=y}}<ref name=\"Hugman\"/>\n| birth_place    = [[Bolton]], England<ref name=\"Hugman\"/>\n| height         = \n| position       = [[Centre forward]]\n| currentclub    = \n| youthyears1    = 1971\u20131973 | youthclubs1 = [[Chorley F.C.|Chorley]]\n| years1         = 1973\u20131976 | clubs1 = [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]]           | caps1 = 135 | goals1 = 56\n| years2         = 1976\u20131984 | clubs2 = [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]                 | caps2 = 260 | goals2 = 96\n| years3         = 1984\u20131986 | clubs3 = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]                           | caps3 = 60  | goals3 = 14\n| years4         = 1986\u20131988 | clubs4 = [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]                     | caps4 = 56  | goals4 = 9\n| years5         = 1988      | clubs5 = [[Wollongong Wolves FC|Wollongong City]]<ref>{{cite web |title=1988 season \u2013 round 14 results |first=Andrew |last=Howe |url=http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/NSL/1988/round14.htm |work=Ozfootball.net |date=9 May 1988 |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=1988 season \u2013 round 15 results |first=Andrew |last=Howe |url=http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/NSL/1988/round15.htm |work=Ozfootball.net |date=9 May 1988 |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> | caps5 = 2   | goals5 = 0\n| years6         = 1989\u20131992 | clubs6 = [[Albany Capitals]]<ref name=\"profile\">{{cite web |url=http://socceroutsider.com/bios/paul-mariner |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130104215211/http://socceroutsider.com/bios/paul-mariner |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 January 2013 |title=Paul Mariner \u2013 profile |publisher=Socceroutsider.com |accessdate=10 February 2012 }}</ref> | caps6 = 17   | goals6 = 1\n| years7         = 1992\u20131993 | clubs7 = [[San Francisco Bay Blackhawks|San Francisco Bay]]<ref name=\"profile\"/> | caps7 = 10  | goals7 = 0\n| totalcaps = 555 | totalgoals = 179\n| nationalyears1 = 1977\u20131985\n| nationalteam1  = [[England national football team|England]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 35\n| nationalgoals1 = 13\n| manageryears1  = 2003      | managerclubs1  = [[Harvard Crimson]] (assistant)\n| manageryears2  = 2004\u20132009 | managerclubs2  = [[New England Revolution]] (assistant)\n| manageryears3  = 2009\u20132010 | managerclubs3  = [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]]\n| manageryears4  = 2012\u20132013 | managerclubs4  = [[Toronto FC]]\n}}\n'''Paul Mariner''' (born 22 May 1953) is an English [[Association football|football]] [[Coach (sport)|coach]] and retired player. He was most recently the head coach and technical director at [[Major League Soccer]] club [[Toronto FC]], until his dismissal in January 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Toronto FC fires coach Paul Mariner, replaced by Ryan Nelsen|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/soccer/tfc/2013/01/07/toronto_fc_fires_coach_paul_mariner_replaced_by_ryan_nelsen.html|work=Toronto Star|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Ltd|accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nA [[centre forward]] during his playing days, Mariner began his career with [[Chorley F.C.|Chorley]]. He became a professional player in 1973 with [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]], where he scored 61 goals in 155 appearances and is considered to be one of the club's best players. He joined [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] in 1976, where he achieved domestic and European success under the guidance of [[Bobby Robson]]. He was called up to play for the [[England national football team|England national team]] during his time at [[Portman Road]], and went on to represent his country at the [[UEFA Euro 1980|1980 European Championships]] and the [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982 World Cup]]. He spent two years with [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and then [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] before finishing his career abroad. He played for clubs in Australia, the US, and [[Malta]].\n\nHe took up coaching during his time with the [[Albany Capitals]] and focused on it fully when he retired from playing. After spending time working in [[Japan]], he returned to America to coach, firstly in [[Arizona]] and then at [[Harvard University]]. He joined [[Major League Soccer]] club [[New England Revolution]] in 2004 as a member of [[Steve Nicol]]'s coaching staff. After five years in [[Massachusetts]], Mariner returned to Plymouth Argyle in 2009 as their head coach. He succeeded [[Paul Sturrock]] as the club's manager two months later before returning to his role as head coach upon the arrival of [[Peter Reid]]. In January 2011, he returned to Major League Soccer as director of player development at [[Toronto FC]].\n\nMariner is currently the [[color commentator]] for the New England Revolution of MLS. Starting in 2020, Mariner only commentates for some of the Revolution games, and shares the duty with [[Charlie Davies]]. \n\n==Playing career==\n===1970s===\n[[File:Paul Mariner cropped.jpg|thumb|upright=|Mariner during his time with Ipswich Town|155px]]\n\nMariner started his career as an [[amateur]] player at non-league club [[Chorley F.C.|Chorley]], close to his Lancashire roots and his style at the helm of their attack caught the attention of [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]], for whom he signed in 1973.\n\nSo began an impressive scoring record with the [[Devon]] club, with 56 goals in 135 appearances coming before [[Bobby Robson]], who had been personally monitoring Mariner's progress, took him to Ipswich for \u00a3220,000 with [[John Peddelty]] and [[Terry Austin (footballer)|Terry Austin]] moving in the opposite direction as part of the deal. Mariner chose Ipswich ahead of similar offers from [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Brian |last=Knight |title=Plymouth Argyle: A Complete Record 1903\u20131989 |year=1989 |publisher=Breedon Books |location=Derby |isbn=0-907969-40-2 |pages=157\u2013158}}</ref>\n\nMariner made his debut in September 1976 and quickly settled into the Ipswich side as an old-fashioned number 9 \u2013 i.e., a forward capable of taking hard tackles and rough treatment from [[Defender (football)|defender]]s but willing to give it back, while also scoring a fair share of goals. Received wisdom suggests that Mariner was only a 'target-man'-type centre forward but he scored plenty of goals with his feet and had the skill to create his own chances on the deck, rather than relying entirely on service through the centre and via the flanks.\n\nSuch was Mariner's impact that six months after joining Ipswich, he made his England debut as a [[substitute (soccer)|substitute]] in a 5\u20130 win over [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]] at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]] and played from the beginning in the following game against [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]] in the [[British Home Championship]] at [[Windsor Park]], [[Belfast]]. He impressed in both games, though didn't score and was not selected for the next six matches. During this period, Ipswich finished third in the [[Football League First Division|First Division]], with Mariner contributing ten goals from 28 games.\n\nMariner's third England cap came in the return World Cup qualifier in Luxembourg, scoring a last-minute goal in a 2\u20130 win which England really needed to win by much more in order to give themselves half a chance of qualifying for the [[Football World Cup 1978|1978 World Cup]] in Argentina. By now, Mariner had become one of a number of 'target man'-type centre forwards for England coach [[Ron Greenwood]] to select from, with the likes of [[Stuart Pearson]] and [[Bob Latchford]] also on the scene. It was Mariner, however, who would get the nod for the majority of the time.\n\nMeanwhile, at club level, Mariner was having a mixed time. He scored eleven goals in 37 appearances for Ipswich, which maintained his England aspirations but the team underperformed in the First Division and finished a lowly 18th. However, they reached the [[FA Cup]] final at Wembley where they memorably beat [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] 1\u20130. Mariner hit the woodwork with one chance and generally caused havoc to the Arsenal defence, earning him the ''Man Of The Match'' award afterwards.\n\nGreenwood decided not to select Mariner for England throughout 1979, although he enjoyed his most productive spell for Ipswich in front of goal that season, hitting 13 in 33 matches. It wasn't until 1980 that Mariner won a sixth England cap \u2013 almost exactly two years after his fifth \u2013 and he scored England's goal in a surprising 4\u20131 defeat against [[Wales national football team|Wales]] at [[Wrexham]]. He stayed in the reckoning thereafter, scoring in a 2\u20131 win over [[Australia national association football team|Australia]] in [[Sydney]] in the final game before England took to the field for the [[1980 European Football Championship|1980 European Championships]]. Mariner was named in Greenwood's squad for the tournament, despite not kicking a ball during the whole qualifying campaign.\n\nHe didn't play in the opening 1\u20131 draw versus [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] in [[Turin]] but came on as a sub in the remaining two group matches \u2013 a defeat against [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and a victory over [[Spain national football team|Spain]], which ensured England's elimination from the competition.\n\n===1980s===\nMariner maintained his England place as his Ipswich goalscoring record continued to improve \u2013 17 from 41 games had come in 1980 and Ipswich made the early running as the next season got underway. England began their qualifying campaign for the [[Football World Cup 1982|1982 World Cup]] with a conclusive 4\u20130 win over [[Norway national football team|Norway]], with Mariner scoring a superb goal with a deft turn and shot from 25 yards. He was, however, left out of the next game, which turned into a gruesome 2\u20131 defeat against [[Romania national football team|Romania]] in [[Bucharest]]. Greenwood put him back in the side a month later for a now vital match against [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]], and Mariner scored the opener in a 2\u20131 win.\n\nIpswich were challenging for three trophies as the 1981 season approached its climax, with Mariner again to the fore, scoring 13 times in 36 matches. However, they were to miss out on two domestic fronts, with [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] winning the First Division (after Ipswich failed to beat [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]) and [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] defeating Ipswich in the semi-finals of the FA Cup. But in the [[UEFA Cup]], Mariner was proving to be a real hero as glory beckoned.\n\nHe scored twice in the early rounds as Ipswich progressed to a tasty quarter final against [[AS Saint-\u00c9tienne|St \u00c9tienne]]. In the first leg in France Mariner put two away as Ipswich went 4\u20131 up, and added another as Ipswich completed the task in the second leg. After winning the semi-final, Mariner scored again in the first leg of the final against [[AZ Alkmaar]] as Ipswich coasted to a 3\u20130 lead, ultimately winning the competition 5\u20134 on [[Aggregate score|aggregate]]. Weeks later, Greenwood put him back in the England side as the World Cup qualification campaign resumed with a defeat in Switzerland, a vital victory in [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] and a shock defeat in Norway. It appeared that they may miss out on the World Cup finals for an unthinkable third tournament in a row.\n\nBut results elsewhere miraculously went their way, meaning England only needed to draw with the already qualified Hungary at Wembley in the final game to guarantee qualification. It was Mariner who scored the only goal in a 1\u20130 win, though he got it via a stumble which saw him score via a deflection rather than an actual shot on goal. But it was enough.\n\nInjuries to both [[Achilles tendon]]s restricted Mariner's football over the next few months, and he only scored eight times in 25 games for Ipswich. But in the five final England warm-up matches prior to the World Cup in Spain, he scored four times, including a stunning solo run and strike against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] at Wembley. He was named in Greenwood's squad and started the first match of the tournament, against [[France national football team|France]].\n\nEngland went into a 2\u20131 lead thanks to a brace from [[Bryan Robson]] \u2013 the first of which was one of the World Cup Finals' quickest-ever goals \u2013 before Mariner slammed home a close-range volley to complete an impressive 3\u20131 win. It was his eleventh international goal in his 22nd match \u2013 an admirable ratio of one goal every other game. It was his also his sixth consecutive scoring game for England \u2013 a feat previously achieved only by [[Jimmy Greaves]].\n\nGreenwood selected Mariner for the rest of the tournament but he didn't score again and England went out in the second phase after two disappointing goalless draws. Mariner is best remembered for dragging a devastated [[Kevin Keegan]] to his feet in support after the England captain, on as a substitute after a tournament ruined by injury problems, sank to his [[knee]]s, head in hands, missed an open goal with a header which would have sent England into the semi-finals.\n\nMariner's club boss Robson subsequently became England coach and he continued to select him as the qualification campaign for the [[1984 European Football Championship|1984 European Championships]] got underway. Mariner continued to score frequently for Ipswich, whose young and vibrant side had started to age and break-up.\n\nEngland's qualification campaign faltered, though Mariner scored in consecutive pool matches against Hungary and Luxembourg \u2013 the latter of which would prove to be his 13th and final England goal. By the time he next played for England, he was an [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] player, with the Gunners taking him from Ipswich in February 1984 for \u00a3150,000. By now Mariner was in his thirties but he still initially performed well for Arsenal, scoring seven times in the final fifteen games of the season. But age was starting to get the better of him; and he only scored nine goals in 41 games in [[1984-85 in English football|1984\u201385]].\n\nMariner won two more England caps but a sign of things to come had arrived in the shape of [[Mark Hateley]], a tall but skillful young striker exactly in the Mariner mould, while [[Gary Lineker]] and [[Peter Beardsley]] also establishing themselves as international strikers.\n\nHateley came on as a substitute for Mariner in a friendly victory over [[East Germany national football team|East Germany]] in September 1984, before Mariner picked up his 35th and final cap in a goalless draw against Romania in May 1985, a qualifier for the [[Football World Cup 1986|1986 World Cup]]. He had scored 13 times for England - the first goal coming on 12 October 1977 in a 2\u20130 win over [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]] in a [[1978 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] qualifier. His last goal for England came on 16 November 1983, also against Luxembourg, but this time in a [[UEFA Euro 1984|European Championship]] qualifier.<ref>[http://www.sporting-heroes.net/football/england/paul-mariner-9569/english-caps-1977-85_a11852/]</ref>\n\nHowever, with Hateley in the ascendancy and Mariner regularly sidelined at [[Highbury]] during the 1985\u20131986 season, Robson opted not to select him for the England squad which qualified for Mexico '86.\n\nMeanwhile, at his club Mariner was rarely on the field, only playing nine times in [[1985-86 in English football|1985\u201386]], including one match as an emergency [[centre half]]. In the summer of 1986 Arsenal's new manager [[George Graham (footballer)|George Graham]] gave Mariner a [[free transfer (soccer)|free transfer]]; in all he played 80 times for Arsenal, scoring 17 goals. He signed for [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], where he spent two seasons. In May 1989, he signed with the [[Albany Capitals]] of the [[American Soccer League (1988-1989)|American Soccer League]].<ref>''CAPITALS WILL PUT BOLTS TO THE TEST'' Boston Globe \u2013 Saturday, 27 May 1989</ref>\n\n===1990s===\nMariner returned to the Capitals in 1990 as the team now played in the [[American Professional Soccer League]], formed by the merger of the American Soccer League and [[Western Soccer League]]. He played three seasons with the Capitals, where he was named to the league's Best XI in 1990.<ref>[http://a-leaguearchive.tripod.com/1990/statsasl90.htm#Albany 1990 Albany Capitals]</ref><ref>[http://a-leaguearchive.tripod.com/1989/statsasl89.htm#Albany 1989 Albany Capitals]</ref><ref>[http://www.sover.net/~spectrum/year/1990.html#APSL The Year in American Soccer \u2013 1990]</ref><ref>[http://a-leaguearchive.tripod.com/1991/stats91.htm#Albany 1991 Albany Capitals]</ref> During his three seasons in Albany, Mariner also served as an assistant coach. In the spring of 1992, the Capitals' owner offered him the position of head coach but when he heard a rumour that the team was about to collapse, he accepted a position as a player-assistant coach with the [[San Francisco Bay Blackhawks]]. He accepted that position and soon after the Capitals announced they were ceasing operations. In the early 90's Paul made two appearances for Byhams Dairy, a Sunday League team in Sudbury Suffolk<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jonathanvankin.com/mariner1.html |title=The Player |access-date=29 June 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306204006/http://jonathanvankin.com/mariner1.html |archive-date=6 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Coaching==\n===Early career===\nAfter retiring, Mariner worked as a football pundit for [[BBC Radio Lancashire]] for their Friday-night Non-League Hour<ref>http://www.chorleyfc.com/club-news_article.asp?Key=284{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> before setting up a management company for footballers. After a spell back in England coaching at [[Bolton School]], he returned to the States to coach youth football at S.C. Del Sol in [[Phoenix, Arizona]]. In the fall of 2003 he became an assistant coach at [[Harvard University]]. In 2004, he was hired by the [[New England Revolution]] of [[Major League Soccer]] as assistant coach to former [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] defender [[Steve Nicol]].\n\n===Plymouth Argyle===\nSpeculation about his future was rife in October 2009 when he was linked with a coaching position at one of his former clubs, [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]], abetted by his visit to [[Devon]] to promote the city's [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 World Cup]] bid and his subsequent resignation on 17 October. It was announced the following day, 18 October 2009, that he was to become the new Head Coach of [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]], with [[Paul Sturrock]] staying on as Team Manager.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mariner set for Plymouth return|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/p/plymouth_argyle/8313076.stm|accessdate=7 March 2013|publisher=BBC Sport|date=18 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 December 2009, Mariner replaced Sturrock as manager of Plymouth Argyle, following a run of poor form which left the Pilgrims second bottom in the Championship.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/plymouth_argyle/8405711.stm | work=BBC News | title=Mariner in for Sturrock at Argyle | date=10 December 2009}}</ref> He was unable to keep Plymouth up, however, and they were relegated from the Football league Championship after a six-year stay, on 19 April 2010.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/plymouth_argyle/8631377.stm | publisher=BBC Sport | title=Mariner wants to stay at Plymouth | date=20 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 May 2010, it was announced that Plymouth were to look for a new manager, however Mariner would remain as a member of the coaching staff.<ref>{{cite news |title=Plymouth Argyle to look for new manager |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/plymouth_argyle/8665627.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 May 2010 |accessdate=2 April 2017}}</ref> Mariner's tenure as manager ended when [[Peter Reid]] was hired on 24 June 2010.<ref name=\"plymouthargylesacking\">{{cite news |title=Peter Reid appointed manager of Plymouth Argyle |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/plymouth_argyle/8755830.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=24 June 2010 |accessdate=2 April 2017}}</ref> Mariner stepped down from his role at [[Home Park]] on 30 December 2010 to pursue another opportunity.<ref>{{cite news|title=Paul Mariner leaves cash-strapped Plymouth Argyle|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/p/plymouth_argyle/9328665.stm|accessdate=7 March 2013|newspaper=BBC|date=30 December 2010}}</ref> \"I have known Paul for a long time and working with him has been fantastic,\" said Argyle manager [[Peter Reid]]. \"I'm sure he will be successful in everything he does in the future. He's a great personality and someone who is a legend with the fans at this football club.\"<ref>[http://www.thisisplymouth.co.uk/news/Peter-Argyle-s-rescue/article-3053991-detail/article.html \"Peter Ridsdale in to save club as Paul Mariner walks away from Home Park\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110211232633/http://www.thisisplymouth.co.uk/news/Peter-Argyle-s-rescue/article-3053991-detail/article.html |date=11 February 2011 }}. ''[[The Herald (Plymouth)|The Plymouth Herald]]''. 31 December 2010. Retrieved 7 January 2011.</ref>\n\n===Toronto FC===\nMariner was named Director of Player Development for [[Toronto FC]] on 6 January 2011, joining new head coach [[Aron Winter]] at the club.<ref>[http://www.torontofc.ca/news/2011/01/new-management-team-announced \"New management team announced\"]. [[Toronto FC]]. 6 January 2011. Retrieved 7 January 2011.</ref>\n\nAfter starting the season with 9 straight losses, former Toronto Coach [[Aron Winter]] stepped down and Toronto named Mariner head coach on 7 June 2012.<ref name=\"torontofcjob\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/soccer/mls/torontofc/article/1207460--toronto-fc-set-to-make-major-announcement |title= Aron Winter out as Toronto FC head coach, replaced by Paul Mariner |accessdate= 7 June 2012 |publisher= |date=7 June 2012 |work=The Star |first=Daniel |last=Girard}}</ref> Mariner recorded his first victory as Toronto manager on 27 June against [[Montreal Impact]], the game ended in a 3\u20130 away win.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter/2012-06-27-mtl-v-tor/recap | title = Recap: Rampant Toronto throttle Impact 3-0 in Montreal | date = 27 June 2012 | accessdate = 28 June 2012 | publisher = mlssoccer.com}}</ref> Mariner was dismissed on 7 January 2013.<ref name=\"torontofcsacking\">{{cite news|title=Toronto FC fires coach Paul Mariner, replaced by Ryan Nelsen|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/soccer/tfc/2013/01/07/toronto_fc_fires_coach_paul_mariner_replaced_by_ryan_nelsen.html|accessdate=7 March 2013|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=7 January 2013}}</ref> Mariner was praised by former Toronto FC players [[Andrew Wiedeman]]<ref name=\"Andrew Wiedeman RedNation Online Interview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rednationonline.ca/Articles2015/RNOInterviewSeriesAndrewWiedeman.aspx |author=Vujcic, Djuradj |title=Andrew Wiedeman RedNation Online Interview |accessdate=2014-12-23 |date=2014-12-22 }}</ref> and [[Eric Hassli]].<ref name=\"Eric Hassli RedNation Online Interview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rednationonline.ca/Articles2015/RedNationInterviewSeriesEricHassli.aspx |author=Vujcic, Djuradj |title=Eric Hassli RedNation Online Interview |accessdate=2018-04-19 |date=2015-05-29 }}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[EFL Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n|-||-||-||-||-||-\n|rowspan=\"6\" valign=\"center\"|[[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]]\n|-\n|[[1973-74 in English football|1973\u201374]]\n|41||14||3||2||6||1||0||0||50||17\n|-\n|[[1974-75 in English football|1974\u201375]]\n|45||20||3||1||2||0||0||0||50||21\n|-\n|[[1975-76 in English football|1975\u201376]]\n|38||15||2||0||2||1||0||0||42||16\n|-\n|[[1976-77 in English football|1976\u201377]]\n|10||7||0||0||2||0||0||0||12||7\n|-|- style=\"font-weight:bold; background-color:#eeeeee;\"\n|Total||134||56||8||3||12||2||0||0||154||61\n|-\n|rowspan=\"10\" valign=\"center\"|[[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]\n|-\n|[[1976-77 in English football|1976\u201377]]\n|28||10||3||3||0||0||0||0||31||13\n|-\n|[[1977-78 in English football|1977\u201378]]\n|37||11||7||7||1||1||6||3||53||22\n|-\n|[[1978-79 in English football|1978\u201379]]\n|33||13||5||3||1||0||5||1||44||17\n|-\n|[[1979-80 in English football|1979\u201380]]\n|41||17||3||3||2||0||4||2||50||22\n|-\n|[[1980-81 in English football|1980\u201381]]\n|36||13||7||3||4||4||11||6||58||26\n|-\n|[[1981-82 in English football|1981\u201382]]\n|25||8||2||0||5||1||1||0||33||9\n|-\n|[[1982-83 in English football|1982\u201383]]\n|37||13||3||0||1||0||1||0||37||13\n|-\n|[[1983-84 in English football|1983\u201384]]\n|23||12||1||0||4||2||0||0||28||14\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold; background-color:#eeeeee;\"\n|Total||260||97||31||19||18||8||28||12||337||136\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\" valign=\"center\"|[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n|-\n|[[1983-84 in English football|1983\u201384]]\n|15||7||0||0||0||0||0||0||15||7\n|-\n|[[1984-85 in English football|1984\u201385]]\n|36||7||3||2||2||0||0||0||41||9\n|-\n|[[1985-86 in English football|1985\u201386]]\n|9||0||3||0||2||1||0||0||14||1\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold; background-color:#eeeeee;\"\n|Total||60||14||6||2||4||1||0||0||70||17\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold; background-color:#eeeeee;\"\n|rowspan=\"1\" valign=\"top\"|'''Career'''\n|\n|'''454'''||'''167'''||'''45'''||'''24'''||'''34'''||'''11'''||'''28'''||'''12'''||'''561'''||'''214'''\n|}\n\n<small>Other includes the UEFA Cup, UEFA Cup Winner's Cup, and FA Charity Shield.</small><ref>[http://www.greensonscreen.co.uk/gosdb-players2.asp?pid=521&scp=1,2,3,4,5,6,7 GoS: Paul Mariner]</ref><ref>[http://www.itfc.co.uk/page/SeasonsGoneByIndex/0,,10272,2,00.html Ipswich Town: Season's Gone by] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503162617/http://www.itfc.co.uk/page/SeasonsGoneByIndex/0,,10272,2,00.html |date=3 May 2009 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.sporting-heroes.net/football-heroes/displayhero_club.asp?HeroID=41829 Paul Mariner: Sporting Heroes]</ref><ref>[http://jkarlsson.netfirms.com/players/m/mariner_p/ Gunnermania: Paul Mariner] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908091744/http://jkarlsson.netfirms.com/players/m/mariner_p/ |date=8 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|7 January 2013}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Team\n!rowspan=2|From\n!rowspan=2|To\n!colspan=5|Record\n!rowspan=2|{{abbr|Ref|Reference}}\n|-\n!{{abbr|P|Matches played}}!!{{abbr|W|Matches won}}!!{{abbr|D|Matches drawn}}!!{{abbr|L|Matches lost}}!!{{abbr|Win %|Win percentage}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]]\n|align=left|10 December 2009\n|align=left|24 June 2010\n{{WDL|29|7|6|16|decimals=1}}\n|<ref name=\"plymouthargylesacking\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Managers: Paul Mariner |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/managers/manager.sd?manager_id=2180 |work=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=2 April 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[Toronto FC]]\n|align=left|7 June 2012\n|align=left|7 January 2013\n{{WDL|28|6|8|14|decimals=1}}\n|<ref name=\"torontofcjob\"/><ref name=\"torontofcsacking\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Toronto FC: Matches |url=https://int.soccerway.com/teams/canada/toronto-fc/7977/matches/ |work=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |accessdate=2 April 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n!colspan=3|Total\n{{WDLtot|57|13|14|30|decimals=1}}\n!\u2014\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===As a player===\n; Plymouth Argyle\n* [[List of winners of English Football League One and predecessors#Football League Third Division 1958-1992|Third Division]] runner up: [[1974-75 in English football|1974\u201375]]\n\n; Ipswich Town\n* [[FA Cup]]: [[FA Cup Final 1978|1977\u201378]]\n* [[UEFA Cup]]: [[1981 UEFA Cup Final|1980\u201381]]\n\n===Individual===\n* [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.#Player of the Year|Plymouth Argyle Player of the Year]]: [[1974-75 in English football|1974\u201375]], [[1974-75 in English football|1975\u201376]]\n* [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.#Team of the century|Plymouth Argyle Team of the Century]]\n* Football League First Division PFA Team of the Year: [[PFA Team of the Year (1980s)#First Division 2|1980\u201381]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Lynch |title=The Official P.F.A. Footballers Heroes |page=143}}</ref>\n* [[List of Ipswich Town F.C. Players of the Year|Ipswich Town Player of the Year]]: [[1982-83 in English football|1982\u201383]]\n*[[Ipswich Town F.C. Hall of Fame|Ipswich Town Hall of Fame]]: Inducted 2011<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.eadt.co.uk/sport/ipswich-town/sir_alf_ramsey_inducted_into_ipswich_town_hall_of_fame_1_859827 | title = Sir Alf Ramsey inducted into Ipswich Town Hall of Fame | first = Elvin | last = King | work = East Anglian Daily Times| accessdate = 21 March 2014 | date = 9 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.thefa.com/England/All-Teams/Players?p=336188 Paul Mariner] at the [[Football Association]] website\n*{{soccerbase (manager)|id=2180|name=Paul Mariner}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards\n| bg = gold\n| fg = navy\n| list1 = \n{{1980\u201381 Football League First Division PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{Plymouth Argyle F.C. Player of the Year}}\n{{Ipswich Town F.C. Player of the Year}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = England squads\n| bg = white\n| fg = #0B0B3F\n| bordercolor = #0B0B3F\n| list1 = \n{{England squad UEFA Euro 1980}}\n{{England squad 1982 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Managerial positions\n| list1 = \n{{Plymouth Argyle F.C. managers}}\n{{Toronto FC managers}}\n}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mariner, Paul}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Bolton]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n[[Category:England B international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1980 players]]\n[[Category:1982 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Chorley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Plymouth Argyle F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Ipswich T